INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (1,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','What is nutrition?','The process of expelling waste from the body','The process by which organisms obtain and utilise food for nutrients from the external environment','The process of converting glucose to energy in cells','The process of transporting nutrients in the blood','B',1,0,0,1),(2,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','In amoeba, where does digestion of food take place?','In the body cavity by extracellular enzymes','In the extracellular fluid surrounding the cell','Inside the food vacuole (intracellular digestion)','In the nucleus of the amoeba','C',1,0,0,1),(3,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','Intracellular digestion refers to digestion that takes place:','In the stomach of multicellular organisms','Inside the cell, within food vacuoles','In the extracellular fluid','In the body cavity using secreted enzymes','B',2,0,0,2),(4,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','Hydra uses tentacles to:','Digest food inside the body cavity by producing enzymes','Paralyse prey and carry it inside the mouth','Absorb nutrients directly from the surrounding water','Perform photosynthesis','B',2,0,0,2),(5,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','In hydra, initial digestion in the body cavity using enzymes secreted by the inner wall cells is called:','Intracellular digestion','Extracellular digestion','Mechanical digestion','Peristaltic digestion','B',3,0,0,3),(6,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','Which stage of nutrition specifically involves breaking complex food into simple absorbable forms?','Ingestion','Assimilation','Digestion','Egestion','C',3,0,0,3),(7,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','Compared to amoeba, what advancement in digestion does hydra show?','Hydra performs only intracellular digestion like amoeba','Hydra performs both extracellular digestion in the body cavity AND intracellular digestion, while amoeba only performs intracellular digestion','Hydra performs only extracellular digestion, while amoeba performs both types','Both amoeba and hydra perform only extracellular digestion','B',4,0,0,4),(8,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','In amoeba, food is engulfed into the cell using:','Tentacles','Pseudopodia','A mouth and oesophagus','Active transport only','B',4,0,0,4),(9,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','Extracellular digestion in hydra''s body cavity produces partially digested food, which then enters cells for intracellular completion. What advantage does this sequential process provide?','It is slower and requires fewer enzymes, making it more economical','It allows more efficient digestion of complex food by combining the benefits of extracellular and intracellular digestion','It eliminates the need for enzymes entirely','It allows hydra to feed on sunlight instead of prey','B',5,0,0,5),(10,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestive System','The chapter states that ''nutritional processes become more complex as organisms become more complex in structure.'' What structural feature of most cells in multicellular organisms explains why they need a dedicated digestive system?','All cells in multicellular organisms can absorb nutrients directly from the environment','Most cells in multicellular organisms are not in direct contact with the external environment and require a specialised system to deliver nutrients','Unicellular organisms require more complex digestion than multicellular ones','Multicellular organisms rely entirely on photosynthesis for nutrients','B',5,0,0,5),(11,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Which substance forms the outer covering of the tooth and is the hardest substance in the human body?','Dentine','Cementum','Enamel','Pulp','C',1,0,0,1),(12,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Which enzyme in saliva begins the digestion of starch in the mouth?','Pepsin','Trypsin','Lipase','Salivary amylase','D',1,0,0,1),(13,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','What is peristalsis?','The secretion of bile from the liver','The absorption of nutrients through villi','Strong muscular contractions that move food through the digestive tract','The breakdown of proteins by enzymes','C',1,0,0,1),(14,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','During swallowing, the epiglottis functions to:','Push food into the mouth using the tongue','Mix saliva with food in the pharynx','Close the trachea to prevent food from entering','Secrete enzymes for chemical digestion','C',1,0,0,1),(15,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Proteins are partially digested by which enzyme in the stomach?','Salivary amylase','Lipase','Pepsin','Trypsin','C',2,0,0,2),(16,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Bile is produced by which organ?','Pancreas','Stomach','Small intestine','Liver','D',2,0,0,2),(17,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Does bile contain digestive enzymes?','Yes, it contains salivary amylase','Yes, it contains pepsin and lipase','No, enzymes are absent in bile; it converts fat into small particles and regulates pH','No, bile contains only water and salts','C',2,0,0,2),(18,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Which enzyme produced by the pancreas partially digests starch?','Pepsin','Trypsin','Pancreatic amylase','Carbohydrase','C',2,0,0,2),(19,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','The innermost part of the tooth containing soft connective tissue, blood vessels, and nerves is called:','Enamel','Dentine','Cementum','Pulp cavity','D',3,0,0,3),(20,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','In which organ does the absorption of remaining water and salts take place after the small intestine?','Oesophagus','Stomach','Large intestine','Pancreas','C',3,0,0,3),(21,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Which vitamins are produced by bacteria in the large intestine?','Vitamin A and Vitamin C','Vitamin D and Vitamin E','Vitamin K and B complex','Vitamin B12 only','C',3,0,0,3),(22,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Which of the following is correctly matched: organ — its role in digestion?','Stomach — hydrochloric acid destroys germs and regulates pH','Liver — produces enzymes that directly digest proteins','Pancreas — stores bile for release into the small intestine','Small intestine — produces hydrochloric acid','A',3,0,0,3),(23,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','During swallowing, which structure prevents food from entering the nasal cavity?','Epiglottis','Tongue','Uvula','Palate','C',4,0,0,4),(24,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Which enzyme from the pancreas COMPLETELY digests lipids into fatty acid and glycerol?','Trypsin','Pancreatic amylase','Pepsin','Lipase','D',4,0,0,4),(25,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','The chapter states that digestion in humans is ''completely extracellular.'' This means:','Digestion takes place inside each individual cell','All digestion occurs outside the cells, in the lumen of the digestive tract','Only extracellular fluid participates in digestion','Digestion occurs on the outer surface of the body','B',4,0,0,4),(26,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Mechanical digestion in the small intestine involves peristalsis AND segmentation. What does segmentation contribute that peristalsis does not?','Segmentation moves food towards the large intestine','Segmentation mixes food with digestive juices by constricting and relaxing segments of the intestine','Segmentation adds bile to the food','Segmentation absorbs nutrients directly','B',4,0,0,4),(27,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','In cows, undigested food stored in the rumen returns to the mouth for ''rumination'' (chewing cud). Based on the chapter, why does this improve digestion?','Rumination adds more bile to the food','Re-chewing breaks down cellulose and hemicellulose more thoroughly before re-entering the digestive chambers','Rumination introduces enzymes from the liver','Rumination increases salivary amylase production','B',5,0,0,5),(28,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Enamel is described as non-living. What is the most important practical implication of this property for dental health?','Non-living enamel can regenerate quickly after being damaged','Non-living enamel is harder than all other body tissues','Non-living enamel cannot repair itself once damaged, making protection from decay critically important','Non-living enamel is less important than dentine for tooth function','C',5,0,0,5),(29,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Carbohydrases in the intestinal juice convert complex carbohydrates into glucose, fructose, and galactose. Which statement about the digestion of carbohydrates in the full digestive tract is correct?','Carbohydrate digestion begins in the mouth with salivary amylase and is completed in the small intestine by carbohydrases','Carbohydrate digestion begins and ends in the stomach','Carbohydrate digestion begins in the pancreas only','Carbohydrate digestion takes place only in the large intestine','A',5,0,0,5),(30,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Digestion','Proteins are digested by pepsin in the stomach (partially), by trypsin from the pancreas (partially), and by proteases in the small intestine (completely, into amino acids). What does this multi-step process illustrate?','Chemical digestion of proteins is completed entirely in the stomach','Trypsin and proteases are the same enzyme','Chemical digestion involves a sequential multi-enzyme process with each stage breaking proteins down further until amino acids are formed','All protein digestion takes place in the large intestine','C',5,0,0,5),(31,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','What are the finger-like projections found throughout the inner wall of the small intestine called?','Lacteals','Cilia','Villi','Microvilli','C',1,0,0,1),(32,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','The lacteal is described as:','A type of blood capillary that absorbs glucose in the villus','A branch of the lymph vessel present in the villus','An enzyme produced by the intestinal wall','The outer epithelial covering of the villus','B',1,0,0,1),(33,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','The small intestine is approximately how long?','1 metre','3 metres','6 metres','10 metres','C',2,0,0,2),(34,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','Which nutrients are absorbed into the blood capillaries of the villus?','Fatty acids and glycerol','Glucose, fructose, galactose and amino acids','Vitamins K and B complex only','Water and minerals only','B',2,0,0,2),(35,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','Which substances are absorbed into the lacteal of the villus?','Glucose and amino acids','Sodium and potassium ions','Fatty acids and glycerol','Fructose and galactose','C',2,0,0,2),(36,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','Why are villi important for nutrient absorption in the small intestine?','They produce digestive enzymes for chemical digestion','They increase the surface area of absorption in the small intestine by many folds','They temporarily store nutrients before releasing them into the blood','They control the pH of the small intestine','B',3,0,0,3),(37,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','The single-layered epithelial cells of the villus serve as:','Enzyme-secreting cells that produce intestinal juice','The primary surface for the absorption of nutrients','Lymph-producing cells that feed the lacteal','Hormone-secreting cells that control digestion','B',3,0,0,3),(38,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','Why do fatty acids and glycerol take a different route from glucose and amino acids after absorption?','Fatty acids are too large to enter blood capillaries and can only enter the lacteal (lymph vessel)','Glucose and amino acids must travel through the lymph first','Fatty acids are absorbed in the large intestine, not the small intestine','All nutrients travel through the same route from the villus','A',4,0,0,4),(39,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','Bile and pancreatic juice reach the duodenum. How do they support the completion of digestion?','They provide mechanical digestion by churning food','Bile emulsifies fats and regulates pH, while pancreatic juice provides enzymes for further digestion of starch, proteins, and lipids','They absorb nutrients directly from the food','They produce glucose for immediate energy use','B',4,0,0,4),(40,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','The small intestine is 6 metres long and 2.5 cm in diameter. How does this length benefit absorption?','A longer tube enables food to pass through faster, reducing digestion time','A longer tube provides more surface area with more villi, and slows movement, allowing more time for digestion and absorption','Length is only important for mechanical digestion, not absorption','Length allows more bile to be produced','B',4,0,0,4),(41,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','If a person''s large intestine cannot reabsorb water, what is the most likely consequence?','Protein digestion would fail completely','Dehydration could occur due to inability to reabsorb remaining water from undigested material','Bile production would cease immediately','All nutrient absorption would stop','B',5,0,0,5),(42,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Absorption of Nutrients','A student says ''all nutrients absorbed in the small intestine go directly to the heart.'' Based on villus structure and the chapter, why is this incorrect?','Glucose and amino acids go to the heart while fatty acids go to the kidneys','All nutrients go through the liver via the portal vein before reaching the heart','Fatty acids and glycerol enter the lacteal (lymph vessel) and travel via the lymphatic system before eventually reaching the heart, not through the portal vein to the liver','All nutrients bypass the heart and go directly to the brain','C',5,0,0,5),(43,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','What percentage of blood is made up of plasma?','45%','25%','55%','65%','C',1,0,0,1),(44,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Platelets function in:','Carrying oxygen to tissues','Producing antibodies against pathogens','Transporting nutrients from the intestine','Blood clotting','D',1,0,0,1),(45,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Which protein in blood plasma is responsible for blood clotting?','Albumin','Globulin','Fibrinogen','Haemoglobin','C',2,0,0,2),(46,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','How is tissue fluid formed?','From lymph entering blood capillaries','When the fluid part of blood oozes into intercellular spaces through minute pores in the capillary wall','From secretions of the large intestinal wall','Directly produced by the liver as a secretion','B',2,0,0,2),(47,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Lymph differs from blood in that lymph does NOT contain:','Water','Vitamins and minerals','Red blood cells and large protein molecules','Simple components from fat digestion','C',2,0,0,2),(48,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Which blood vessels carry blood from the heart to organs and have thick, elastic walls with high-pressure flow?','Veins','Capillaries','Arteries','Lymph vessels','C',3,0,0,3),(49,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Which blood vessel has walls made of a single layer of cells with minute pores, allowing exchange of substances?','Artery','Vein','Venacava','Capillary','D',3,0,0,3),(50,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Valves in veins serve to:','Speed up blood flow toward organs','Prevent backflow of blood and ensure one-directional flow toward the heart','Reduce blood pressure in all vessels','Allow blood to flow away from the heart','B',3,0,0,3),(51,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Which of the following is NOT part of the lymphatic system as described in the chapter?','Lymph nodes','Spleen','Thymus gland','Pancreas','D',4,0,0,4),(52,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Nutrients absorbed from the small intestine are carried to the liver by the hepatic portal vein before reaching the heart. What type of vein is the hepatic portal vein?','A pulmonary vein that carries oxygenated blood','A portal vein — a vein that carries blood from organ to organ rather than directly to the heart','A systemic vein that carries deoxygenated blood from all organs','A vein that carries blood from the lungs to the heart','B',4,0,0,4),(53,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Capillaries have minute pores in their walls. Why is this structural feature essential for the transport function of blood?','Pores increase blood pressure inside capillaries','Pores allow the exchange of substances between blood and cells via tissue fluid, enabling nutrients to reach cells and waste to enter the blood','Pores prevent blood cells from escaping','Pores reduce the speed of blood flow to zero','B',5,0,0,5),(54,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Structure of Blood','Blood flows at high pressure and speed in arteries but low pressure and speed in capillaries. Why does lower speed in capillaries benefit nutrient and gas exchange?','High speed in capillaries forces nutrients into cells more effectively','Low speed in capillaries allows more time for exchange of substances between blood and surrounding cells through tissue fluid','Low speed in capillaries prevents any leakage of fluid','High pressure in arteries is directly responsible for capillary exchange','B',5,0,0,5),(55,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','The heart is situated slightly tilted to the left in which body cavity?','Abdominal cavity','Pelvic cavity','Thoracic cavity','Cranial cavity','C',1,0,0,1),(56,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','How many chambers does the human heart have?','Two','Three','Four','Five','C',1,0,0,1),(57,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','The double-layered membrane that covers the heart is called:','Pleura','Pericardium','Peritoneum','Myocardium','B',1,0,0,1),(58,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','What is the SA node in the heart?','The valve between the right atrium and right ventricle','The node in the wall of the right atrium that produces electrical impulses for heart contraction (Pacemaker)','The fluid that protects the heart from external shocks','The blood vessel that carries blood to the lungs','B',1,0,0,1),(59,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','What is an Electrocardiogram (ECG)?','A device that measures blood pressure in arteries','A graphical representation of the electrical waves felt in the walls of the heart when it beats','A machine that pumps blood artificially during surgery','A test that measures oxygen saturation in the blood','B',1,0,0,1),(60,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','The normal blood pressure of a healthy person is:','80/120 mmHg','100/60 mmHg','120/80 mmHg','140/90 mmHg','C',1,0,0,1),(61,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','Blood returning from the lungs (rich in oxygen) enters which chamber of the heart?','Right atrium','Right ventricle','Left atrium','Left ventricle','C',2,0,0,2),(62,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','The valve between the left atrium and left ventricle is called:','Tricuspid valve','Semilunar valve','Aortic valve','Bicuspid valve','D',2,0,0,2),(63,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','During ventricular systole, blood from the LEFT ventricle is pumped into:','Pulmonary artery','Venacava','Aorta','Pulmonary vein','C',2,0,0,2),(64,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','One complete cardiac cycle takes how long?','0.4 seconds','0.6 seconds','0.8 seconds','1.0 seconds','C',2,0,0,2),(65,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','Blood pressure measured when the heart contracts is called:','Diastolic pressure','Systolic pressure','Pulse pressure','Hypotension','B',2,0,0,2),(66,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','What is pulse?','The sound produced by heart valves closing','The rhythmic expansion and contraction of the arterial wall caused by the contraction of the left ventricle and the elasticity of arterial walls','The rate of breathing per minute','The electrical impulse produced by the SA node','B',3,0,0,3),(67,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','Pulmonary circulation begins from which heart chamber?','Left ventricle','Left atrium','Right atrium','Right ventricle','D',3,0,0,3),(68,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','Systemic circulation begins from which chamber and ends in which chamber?','Right ventricle; left atrium','Left ventricle; right atrium','Right atrium; left ventricle','Left atrium; right ventricle','B',3,0,0,3),(69,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','What is the function of pericardial fluid?','To carry oxygen directly to the heart muscle','To produce electrical impulses for heart contraction','To protect the heart from external shocks and reduce friction between the pericardial membrane layers','To regulate the heart rate by sending signals','C',3,0,0,3),(70,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','Blood from different parts of the body (deoxygenated, rich in CO2 and nutrients) enters which heart chamber through the venacavae?','Left atrium','Left ventricle','Right atrium','Right ventricle','C',3,0,0,3),(71,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','What are the three phases of one cardiac cycle?','Inspiration, expiration, and pause','Systole, diastole, and hypotension','Filling, pumping, and emptying of ventricles only','Atrial systole, ventricular systole, and joint diastole','D',3,0,0,3),(72,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','Joint diastole (the return of all four chambers to normal state) occurs:','During atrial systole when blood enters the ventricles','During ventricular systole when blood is pumped out','After the ventricles have pumped blood into blood vessels, when all four chambers relax simultaneously','Only when blood pressure reaches exactly 80 mmHg','C',3,0,0,3),(73,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','Since the same blood passes through the heart twice in one circuit, the circulation in humans is called double circulation. What is the advantage of this arrangement?','Double circulation slows the heart rate, reducing energy use','Double circulation ensures oxygenated blood from the lungs is kept separate from deoxygenated blood, maintaining high oxygen pressure for delivery to body tissues','Double circulation means more blood is produced in the body','Double circulation prevents blood from reaching some organs','B',4,0,0,4),(74,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','The blood pressure reading 120/80 mmHg correctly represents:','Pulse rate at rest and after exercise','Systolic pressure (120 mmHg when heart contracts) and diastolic pressure (80 mmHg when heart relaxes)','Heart rate per minute and pulse rate respectively','Oxygen level and CO2 level in blood','B',4,0,0,4),(75,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','When ventricles contract, blood does not flow back into the atria. Which structural feature prevents this backflow?','Semilunar valves close the aorta','The SA node sends a signal to prevent backflow','The valves between the atria and ventricles close when ventricles contract, ensuring one-directional flow','The elastic walls of the aorta prevent backflow by their recoil','C',4,0,0,4),(76,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Heart','During atrial systole, blood from the RIGHT atrium enters which chamber?','Left ventricle','Right ventricle','Left atrium','Pulmonary artery','B',4,0,0,4),(77,'Kerala',9,'English','Biolo