irectly damages the SA node, disrupting the cardiac cycle','Fatty food causes deposition of fat only in veins, reducing blood return to the heart','B',5,0,0,5),(90,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Health of Heart','A patient with atherosclerosis has reduced blood flow to the heart muscle through the coronary artery. If a blood clot forms in this artery, what does the chapter predict?','The liver would stop producing bile','Coronary thrombosis results, which can cause a heart attack due to blocked blood supply to the heart muscle','Pulmonary circulation would stop entirely','Blood pressure drops permanently to zero','B',5,0,0,5),(91,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','Which vascular tissue in plants transports water and salts?','Phloem','Xylem','Epidermis','Stomata','B',1,0,0,1),(92,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','Which vascular tissue in plants transports food (sucrose produced in leaves)?','Xylem','Tracheid','Phloem','Vessel','C',1,0,0,1),(93,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','In xylem, vessel cells are dead. What structural feature makes them ideal for water transport?','They have thick cross walls that divide the vessels into segments','The cross walls have disintegrated, making them look like long continuous pipes','They are living and actively pump water upward','They contain chlorophyll to provide energy for water transport','B',2,0,0,2),(94,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','The loss of water vapour from leaves through stomata is called:','Osmosis','Diffusion','Transpiration','Evaporation','C',2,0,0,2),(95,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','How does the entry of sucrose into sieve tubes create a pressure that moves food through phloem?','Sucrose lowers water concentration in sieve tubes, causing water to enter by osmosis from adjacent xylem, increasing turgor pressure that pushes sucrose along','Sucrose activates active transport proteins that pump food downward','Sucrose reacts with oxygen to generate gas pressure inside sieve tubes','Sucrose attracts minerals from the soil, creating a pulling force','A',3,0,0,3),(96,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','Which combination of forces helps water rise through xylem from roots to leaves?','Root pressure only','Transpiration pull, cohesion and adhesion of water molecules, and root pressure','Active transport alone','Osmosis in root cells only','B',4,0,0,4),(97,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','Water enters root cells and moves into xylem before rising upward. Which process allows water to enter root cells from the soil?','Active transport requiring ATP','Osmosis, since root cells have lower water concentration than the surrounding soil water','Transpiration pulling water directly from the soil','Diffusion of water through the cell wall only','B',4,0,0,4),(98,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion and Transport of Nutrients',2,'Transport in Plants','The entry of sucrose from leaf cells into sieve tubes requires energy. Once in the sieve tubes, what drives the long-distance transport of sucrose to other plant parts?','Simple diffusion of sucrose molecules down their concentration gradient in sieve tubes','High turgor pressure created when water enters sieve tubes (due to high sucrose concentration) pushes sucrose along the phloem','Root pressure acts upward through phloem like it does in xylem','Transpiration pull in phloem, identical to xylem','B',5,0,0,5),(99,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'2','Digestion a