ust stay inside RBCs','The chapter does not state that haemoglobin is inside RBCs','Proteins are small enough to pass through the capillary wall easily','Haemoglobin dissolves freely in plasma for efficient oxygen transport','A',5,0,0,5),(130,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Gaseous Exchange','During alveolar exchange, O2 diffuses into blood while CO2 diffuses out simultaneously. Which structural feature of the alveolar capillary makes both exchanges possible at the same time?','The capillary wall is thick, preventing mixing of gases','The single-cell-layer alveolar wall and capillary wall are extremely thin, moist, and highly permeable — allowing both O2 and CO2 to diffuse in their respective directions simultaneously','Special pumps in the alveolar wall handle O2 and CO2 separately','O2 and CO2 exchange occurs at different times of the cardiac cycle','B',5,0,0,5),(131,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','The first phase of cellular respiration, glycolysis, takes place in the:','Mitochondria','Nucleus','Cytoplasm','Chloroplast','C',1,0,0,1),(132,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','The second phase of cellular respiration (Krebs cycle) takes place in the:','Cytoplasm','Mitochondria','Nucleus','Cell membrane','B',1,0,0,1),(133,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','Respiration that takes place without using oxygen is called:','Aerobic respiration','Anaerobic respiration','Cellular respiration','Krebs cycle','B',1,0,0,1),(134,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','How many ATP molecules are produced during glycolysis?','28','30','38','2','D',2,0,0,2),(135,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','How many ATP molecules are produced in the Krebs cycle?','2','28','38','10','B',2,0,0,2),(136,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','In anaerobic respiration, yeast breaks down glucose and produces:','Lactic acid only','Alcohol and CO2','Water and oxygen','Pyruvic acid and water','B',2,0,0,2),(137,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','During glycolysis, glucose is converted to:','Carbon dioxide and water','Lactic acid directly','Pyruvic acid','Alcohol','C',3,0,0,3),(138,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','In Lactobacillus bacteria, anaerobic respiration converts pyruvic acid into:','Alcohol and CO2','Lactic acid','Water and oxygen','Carbon dioxide and water','B',3,0,0,3),(139,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','Which scientist discovered the chemical processes in the Krebs cycle and shared the Nobel Prize for Medicine in 1953?','Melvin Calvin','Antoine Lavoisier','Hans Adolf Krebs','Fritz Lipmann alone','C',3,0,0,3),(140,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','The complete equation for aerobic cellular respiration shows glucose + _____ → _____ + _____ + 30 ATP. What fills the blanks correctly?','Glucose + nitrogen → ammonia + water + 30 ATP','Glucose + oxygen → carbon dioxide + water + 30 ATP','Glucose + CO2 → oxygen + starch + 30 ATP','Glucose + water → lactic acid + CO2 + 30 ATP','B',4,0,0,4),(141,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','Glycolysis requires no oxygen, while the Krebs cycle requires oxygen. What does this reveal about the location where oxygen is consumed in cellular respiration?','Oxygen is consumed only in the cytoplasm during glycolysis','Oxygen is consumed in the mitochondria during the Krebs cycle, not in the cytoplasm during glycolysis','Oxygen is consumed equally in both phases','Oxygen is not consumed during cellular respiration at all','B',4,0,0,4),(142,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','Yeast is added to bread dough to make it rise (leaven). Based on the chapter''s description of anaerobic respiration in yeast, what causes the dough to rise?','Yeast produces lactic acid, which is acidic and swells the dough','Yeast performs aerobic respiration that generates heat, causing the dough to expand','Yeast performs anaerobic respiration producing CO2 gas, which creates bubbles that cause the dough to rise','Yeast produces alcohol that dissolves the gluten in the dough','C',4,0,0,4),(143,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','Aerobic respiration produces 30 ATP while anaerobic respiration produces only 2 ATP. What does this comparison indicate about the two processes?','Anaerobic respiration is more efficient because it requires no oxygen','Aerobic respiration is far more efficient in energy extraction from glucose because it completely oxidises glucose using oxygen, while anaerobic respiration only partially breaks down glucose','Both processes produce the same total energy; ATP counts only differ due to different temperature conditions','Anaerobic respiration is preferred by all organisms for its speed','B',5,0,0,5),(144,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','Curd is prepared by adding Lactobacillus bacteria to milk. Based on the chapter, what process do these bacteria use and what product causes milk to turn into curd?','Aerobic respiration; bacteria produce CO2 which acidifies milk','Anaerobic respiration; Lactobacillus produces lactic acid from pyruvic acid, which causes milk proteins to coagulate into curd','Aerobic respiration; bacteria produce alcohol that coagulates milk','Anaerobic respiration; Lactobacillus produces alcohol and CO2 that coagulate milk','B',5,0,0,5),(145,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Cellular Respiration','The chapter asks students to compare photosynthesis and cellular respiration. Which statement correctly identifies a key difference between the two processes?','Both processes produce ATP and take place in mitochondria','Photosynthesis builds glucose using CO2, water, and light energy (anabolism), while respiration breaks down glucose using O2 to release energy as ATP (catabolism)','Both processes require oxygen and release CO2','Respiration is an anabolic process like photosynthesis but takes place in the cytoplasm','B',5,0,0,5),(146,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','In amoeba, gaseous exchange takes place through:','Gills','Skin','Cell membrane','Stomata','C',1,0,0,1),(147,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','Fish exchange gases through:','Skin','Lungs','Gills','Stomata','C',1,0,0,1),(148,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','Earthworms exchange gases through:','Lungs','Gills','Their skin','Stomata on their body surface','C',2,0,0,2),(149,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','In plants, gaseous exchange takes place through stomata, lenticels, and root cells. Stomata are found on:','Roots only','The surface of leaves and young stem','Mature stem and roots','Flowers only','B',2,0,0,2),(150,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','Lenticels on the surface of mature stems allow:','Water absorption from the atmosphere','Gaseous exchange between the internal tissues and the atmosphere','Food to be transported from leaves to roots','Mineral absorption from the soil','B',3,0,0,3),(151,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','In plants during the day, stomata remain open and photosynthesis and respiration occur simultaneously. What happens to the O2 produced by photosynthesis?','All O2 is released into the atmosphere','O2 produced is used for respiration and excess O2 is expelled','O2 is converted back to CO2 immediately','O2 is stored in the vacuole','B',3,0,0,3),(152,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','The chapter states that cellular respiration in plants is similar to that in humans. How do plants differ in terms of gas exchange compared to humans?','Plants have no gas exchange at all','Plants use the same Krebs cycle and glycolysis but lack a dedicated respiratory system; instead they use stomata, lenticels, and root cells for gaseous exchange','Plants have lungs inside their stems','Plants rely entirely on photosynthesis and do not respire','B',4,0,0,4),(153,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','At night, stomata close. How do plants exchange respiratory gases in the dark?','Respiration stops completely at night in plants','Gaseous exchange continues through diffusion at night even with closed stomata','Plants absorb oxygen from the soil through roots only at night','Plants switch to anaerobic respiration at night','B',4,0,0,4),(154,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','During the day, CO2 produced by plant respiration is used for photosynthesis and insufficient CO2 is received from the atmosphere. What does this cycling of CO2 within the plant demonstrate?','Plants do not need CO2 from the atmosphere at all','Within a plant cell during high photosynthesis rates, CO2 from respiration is recycled as a raw material for photosynthesis, reducing the net CO2 taken from the atmosphere','Photosynthesis and respiration are completely separate processes with no overlap','CO2 is produced by photosynthesis and consumed by respiration only','B',5,0,0,5),(155,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Respiration in Other Organisms','Amoeba uses its cell membrane for gas exchange, earthworm uses its skin, fish uses gills, and humans use lungs with alveoli. What trend in respiratory surface complexity matches the complexity of the organism?','Simpler organisms have more complex respiratory surfaces','As organisms become more complex and larger, they develop specialised, larger-surface-area respiratory structures to meet higher oxygen demands','All organisms use the same type of respiratory surface regardless of complexity','More complex organisms have smaller respiratory surfaces to conserve energy','B',5,0,0,5),(156,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The process of removal of waste materials from the body is called:','Digestion','Excretion','Respiration','Assimilation','B',1,0,0,1),(157,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','In which organ is urea synthesised?','Kidney','Skin','Liver','Lung','C',1,0,0,1),(158,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The basic structural and functional units of the kidney are called:','Alveoli','Villi','Glomeruli','Nephrons','D',1,0,0,1),(159,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The double-walled cup-shaped structure at one end of the nephron is called:','Glomerulus','Bowman''s capsule','Collecting duct','Renal tubule','B',1,0,0,1),(160,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','How many nephrons are present in each kidney (approximately)?','12,000','12 lakh','12 crore','12,00,000 (same as 12 lakh)','B',1,0,0,1),(161,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','Urea is formed from ammonia by the reaction: ammonia + CO2 + H2O → urea. Ammonia itself is formed from the metabolism of:','Carbohydrates','Lipids','Proteins','Nucleic acids','C',2,0,0,2),(162,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The network of minute capillaries present inside the Bowman''s capsule is called:','Collecting duct','Renal tubule','Glomerulus','Pelvis','C',2,0,0,2),(163,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The presence of glucose in urine may indicate:','Kidney stone','Jaundice','Diabetes','Urinary tract infection','C',2,0,0,2),(164,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The presence of bilirubin in urine indicates which condition?','Diabetes','Kidney stone','Urinary tract infection','Jaundice','D',2,0,0,2),(165,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','During ultrafiltration in the glomerulus, a fluid called glomerular filtrate is formed. What drives this filtration?','Active transport by nephron cells','High pressure in the glomerulus due to the difference in diameters of the afferent and efferent vessels','Osmosis through the Bowman''s capsule','Enzyme action in the renal tubule','B',3,0,0,3),(166,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The glomerular filtrate contains which of the following?','Only urea and uric acid','Water, glucose, amino acids, ions, vitamins, urea, uric acid, and creatinine','Only blood cells and proteins','Only water and salts','B',3,0,0,3),(167,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','Why are glucose and amino acids NOT present in normal urine even though they appear in the glomerular filtrate?','They are too large to be filtered in the first place','They are reabsorbed from the renal tubules back into the blood during reabsorption','They are broken down by enzymes in the collecting duct','They evaporate from the renal tubules','B',3,0,0,3),(168,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','Urine travels from the nephron to the pelvis through the collecting duct, then to the urinary bladder via the:','Renal artery','Urethra','Ureter','Renal vein','C',3,0,0,3),(169,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The chapter lists four excretory organs. Which of the following correctly pairs an organ with its excretory function?','Kidney — synthesises urea from ammonia','Liver — excretes water and salts through urine','Lungs — eliminate CO2 as a respiratory excretory product','Skin — produces bile pigments for excretion','C',3,0,0,3),(170,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The three processes that convert glomerular filtrate into final urine are:','Filtration, absorption, and digestion','Ultrafiltration, reabsorption, and secretion','Osmosis, diffusion, and active transport only','Excretion, ingestion, and metabolism','B',2,0,0,2),(171,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','During secretion (the third step of urine formation), excess components retained in the blood are secreted into the renal tubules. What is the purpose of this step?','To add more glucose into the filtrate for energy','To ensure that excess substances not filtered out in the glomerulus are added to the urine for removal','To reabsorb urea back into the blood','To convert ammonia to urea inside the tubule','B',4,0,0,4),(172,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The presence of calcium oxalate crystals in urine indicates:','Diabetes','Urinary tract infection','Kidney stone','Anaemia','C',4,0,0,4),(173,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','Why is it important to avoid holding urine for a long time?','Holding urine increases blood pressure permanently','Avoiding urination prevents expulsion of bacteria from the urinary tract, which may cause urinary bladder infections and serious kidney diseases','Holding urine destroys nephrons','Holding urine increases urea production in the liver','B',4,0,0,4),(174,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','Why is ammonia converted to urea in the liver before excretion?','Ammonia is too small to be filtered by the kidneys','Ammonia is toxic; converting it to the less toxic urea makes it safer to transport in the blood to the kidneys','Urea is more easily produced from CO2 than ammonia is','Ammonia can only be excreted through the skin, not the kidneys','B',4,0,0,4),(175,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The afferent vessel (carrying blood to the glomerulus) has a larger diameter than the efferent vessel (carrying blood away). How does this size difference drive ultrafiltration?','The larger afferent vessel reduces blood pressure inside the glomerulus','Blood entering through the larger afferent vessel cannot exit quickly through the narrower efferent vessel, creating high pressure inside the glomerulus that forces filtrate out','The efferent vessel carries blood at higher pressure than the afferent vessel','Both vessels are the same size; pressure is generated by the renal tubule','B',4,0,0,4),(176,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','If both kidneys stop functioning, waste materials accumulate in the blood. Based on the chapter, which process would be used to save the patient''s life?','Kidney transplantation is always performed immediately','Haemodialysis — passing blood through a dialysis unit where waste materials diffuse into dialysis fluid through a selectively permeable membrane','Increased liver production of urea to compensate','The skin would take over the excretory function entirely','B',5,0,0,5),(177,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','In haemodialysis, heparin is added to blood before it enters the dialysis unit. Based on context, why is heparin used?','To add nutrients to the blood during dialysis','To prevent blood from clotting (coagulation) while it flows through the external dialysis unit','To increase urea production during the procedure','To dissolve the selectively permeable membrane','B',5,0,0,5),(178,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','After kidney transplantation, the patient must take medicines that suppress immunity. Based on scientific reasoning, why is this necessary?','Immunity-suppressing medicines prevent infection by the donor''s bacteria','The immune system may recognise the transplanted kidney as foreign and attack it; immunity-suppressing medicines prevent this rejection','These medicines help the new kidney produce more urine','Immunity suppression prevents the patient from developing kidney stones','B',5,0,0,5),(179,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','A diabetic patient''s urine turns red when tested with Benedict''s reagent. Based on the chapter''s description of urine abnormalities, what does this indicate and why is glucose normally absent in urine?','It indicates kidney stone; glucose is normally absent because it is too large to filter','It indicates diabetes; glucose is normally absent because it is completely reabsorbed from the renal tubules during reabsorption','It indicates anaemia; glucose is normally filtered but not secreted','It indicates jaundice; glucose is normally absent because it does not enter the glomerular filtrate','B',5,0,0,5),(180,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Excretion - Urea Synthesis and Urine Formation','The chapter states that protein metabolism produces toxic ammonia, which is converted to less toxic urea in the liver. If liver function fails, what would be the most serious consequence for the kidneys and blood?','The kidneys would produce more urea to compensate for the liver''s failure','Toxic ammonia would accumulate in the blood, disrupting homeostasis, since the liver cannot convert it to the less toxic urea that kidneys can safely excrete','The kidneys would directly excrete ammonia without any liver involvement','Ammonia would be converted to urea in the skin instead','B',5,0,0,5),(181,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Which organ regulates salt and water balance and blood pressure through excretion?','Liver','Lungs','Skin','Kidney','D',1,0,0,1),(182,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The skin contributes to homeostasis by:','Regulating blood pH only','Regulating body temperature, salt, and water balance','Producing urea for excretion','Eliminating CO2 from the body','B',1,0,0,1),(183,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The lungs help maintain homeostasis by:','Regulating water and salt balance','Neutralising toxins in the blood','Eliminating CO2 and regulating O2 levels and pH','Synthesising urea from ammonia','C',1,0,0,1),(184,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Which organ neutralises toxins, regulates metabolism, and synthesises urea in order to maintain homeostasis?','Kidney','Liver','Lung','Skin','B',1,0,0,1),(185,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Which of the following is listed as an improper lifestyle factor that disrupts homeostasis?','Regular exercise and balanced diet','Alcoholism, smoking, and use of addictive drugs','Drinking sufficient water daily','Getting adequate sleep and rest','B',2,0,0,2),(186,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Excretion in amoeba takes place through which structure?','Gills','Contractile vacuole','Nephrons','Stomata','B',2,0,0,2),(187,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Plants excrete O2, CO2, and water vapour through:','Roots only','Phloem','Stomata and lenticels','Xylem','C',2,0,0,2),(188,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Plants excrete water and salts through specialised structures found on leaf margins called:','Stomata','Lenticels','Hydathodes','Villi','C',2,0,0,2),(189,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Plants store solid waste as resins and also dispose of waste by:','Excreting all waste through stomata','Dropping mature leaves and fruits, and forming heartwood','Excreting waste through hydathodes only','Converting all waste into glucose','B',3,0,0,3),(190,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The chapter says ''maintenance of homeostasis is the sign of life.'' How do the kidney and lungs together maintain pH of the internal environment?','The kidney regulates salt/water while the lungs regulate CO2 levels and O2 — both affect blood pH','The kidney produces bile to regulate pH while lungs produce enzymes','Both organs produce urea to maintain pH','Only the liver controls blood pH; kidney and lungs have no role','A',3,0,0,3),(191,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Tissue fluid regulates the composition of the surrounding cell environment. Why is maintaining the correct composition of tissue fluid important for cells?','Tissue fluid composition controls the speed of blood flow','Cells depend on correct tissue fluid composition to maintain the conditions needed for enzyme activity within the cell','Tissue fluid directly produces ATP for cells','Tissue fluid composition has no effect on metabolism','B',3,0,0,3),(192,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The chapter lists ''over nutrition and under nutrition'' as factors disrupting homeostasis. What common mechanism explains why both extremes are harmful?','Both extremes prevent the kidneys from filtering blood','Both alter the chemical composition of the internal environment, disrupting the balance needed for metabolism to function properly','Both extremes cause anaemia and breathing problems only','Both prevent excretion through the skin','B',3,0,0,3),(193,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','In haemodialysis, blood flows through tubes made of selectively permeable membrane immersed in dialysis fluid. Waste materials move from blood to dialysis fluid by which process?','Active transport of waste into the dialysis fluid','Diffusion of waste materials from blood (high concentration) into dialysis fluid (low concentration) through the selectively permeable membrane','Osmosis of waste through the membrane','Filtration under high pressure, as in the glomerulus','B',4,0,0,4),(194,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The chapter''s description of organ roles in homeostasis shows that the liver ''neutralises toxins.'' Which of the following is consistent with this role?','The liver excretes excess water and prevents dehydration','The liver converts toxic ammonia from protein metabolism into the less toxic urea, preventing ammonia accumulation that would disrupt homeostasis','The liver produces haemoglobin for oxygen transport','The liver directly eliminates CO2 from the body','B',4,0,0,4),(195,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The chapter states that ''improper use of medicines and contact with toxic substances'' can affect homeostasis. What organ would be MOST directly affected by such toxins?','The lungs, as toxins enter through breathing','The liver, since it neutralises toxins and would be burdened by processing large amounts of toxins','The kidney, since all toxins exit only through urine','The skin, since toxins exit only through sweat','B',4,0,0,4),(196,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Pollution and lack of hygiene are listed as factors affecting homeostasis. Which is the most likely pathway by which external pollution disrupts internal homeostasis?','Pollutants increase the size of the kidney','Pollutants can enter the body and alter the chemical composition of the internal environment, directly disrupting metabolic functions','Pollution only affects the external environment without entering the body','Pollution increases the amount of O2 in the atmosphere, disrupting respiration','B',4,0,0,4),(197,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The chapter describes the liver, kidney, lungs, and skin as all contributing to homeostasis through excretion. A student claims ''the kidney alone is responsible for excretion.'' Based on the chapter, what is the most accurate correction?','The student is correct; the kidney is the only excretory organ','The claim is incorrect; excretion involves multiple organs — the liver synthesises urea, the lungs expel CO2, the skin regulates temperature/salt/water, and the kidneys excrete water/salts/urea — all working together to maintain homeostasis','The student is partly correct; only the kidney and liver are involved in excretion','The student is incorrect; only the skin performs excretion','B',5,0,0,5),(198,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','The chapter ends with a call to follow a lifestyle that preserves both external and internal environments. How are external environmental pollution and internal homeostasis linked?','External pollution has no effect on internal homeostasis','A polluted external environment introduces harmful substances into the body (through air, water, food), which can disrupt the composition of the internal environment and thus impair homeostasis','Internal homeostasis only depends on diet and exercise, not the external environment','Improving the external environment worsens internal homeostasis','B',5,0,0,5),(199,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','Excretion in plants differs from animals in that plants lack a dedicated excretory system. How do plants manage their waste products effectively?','Plants do not produce any metabolic waste','Plants use multiple mechanisms including releasing gases through stomata/lenticels, secreting water and salts through hydathodes, storing waste as resins, and disposing of waste by shedding mature leaves, fruits, and forming heartwood','Plants excrete all waste through their roots into the soil','Plants convert all waste into glucose through photosynthesis','B',5,0,0,5),(200,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'3','Respiration and Excretion',3,'Homeostasis','If CO2 is not eliminated from the body in time, how would this affect homeostasis?','Excess CO2 would increase oxygen supply','CO2 accumulation would increase blood acidity (lower pH), disrupting the chemical balance of the internal environment and impairing enzyme function and metabolism','Excess CO2 would be converted to glucose by the liver','CO2 accumulation has no effect on homeostasis as it is an inert gas','B',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (201,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','What term is used for all the chemical reactions that together take place in an organism?','Metabolism','Homeostasis','Excretion','Respiration','A',1,0,0,1),(202,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Carbohydrate, protein, lipid and nucleic acid are together called:','Hormones','Biomolecules','Nutrients','Enzymes','B',1,0,0,1),(203,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Cellulose and starch are examples of which category of biomolecules?','Lipids','Proteins','Carbohydrates','Nucleic acids','C',1,0,1,1),(204,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','DNA and RNA are examples of which type of biomolecule?','Carbohydrates','Lipids','Proteins','Nucleic acids','D',1,0,0,1),(205,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Pepsin, the enzyme that partially digests proteins, is found in:','Saliva','Bile','Pancreatic juice','Gastric juice','D',2,0,0,2),(206,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Which of the following is an example of anabolism?','Protein breaking down into amino acids','Starch breaking down into glucose','Fat breaking down into fatty acids','Plants synthesising glucose using carbon dioxide and water','D',2,0,0,2),(207,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Antibodies belong to which category of biomolecules?','Carbohydrates','Lipids','Nucleic acids','Proteins','D',2,0,1,2),(208,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Which of the following is NOT 