etabolism','Since enzymes help speed up ''countless'' chemical reactions in an organism, which conclusion follows?','One enzyme performs all reactions simultaneously','Enzymes are only active in the stomach','Many different enzymes are needed, each specific to its own reaction','Enzymes replace hormones in controlling reactions','C',4,0,1,4),(216,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Which combination of elements is stated in the chapter as forming molecules for cell structure and function?','Carbon, sulphur, oxygen, sodium, and potassium','Hydrogen, nitrogen, iron, copper, and zinc','Carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus, and calcium','Carbon, nitrogen, calcium, sodium, chlorine, and iodine','C',4,0,0,4),(217,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','The chapter states there are 37 trillion cells in the human body and estimates one billion reactions per second per cell. What is the total number of reactions per second in the human body?','37 trillion','One billion','37 sextillion (37 followed by 21 zeros)','37 billion','C',5,0,1,5),(218,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Both salivary amylase and pepsin are enzymes, yet they act in different organs. What principle does this best illustrate?','All enzymes function identically regardless of location','Different enzymes are produced in different locations to perform specific functions','Enzymes are produced only in the mouth','Pepsin and salivary amylase are the same molecule','B',5,0,1,5),(219,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','A cell synthesises glucose from carbon dioxide and water. Which category does this belong to and why?','Catabolism, because CO2 is a breakdown product','Excretion, because CO2 is removed from the cell','Anabolism, because smaller molecules are combined to form a larger molecule','Catabolism, because water molecules are broken down','C',5,0,0,5),(220,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Metabolism','Why does disruption of metabolism ultimately threaten life?','Metabolism only regulates respiration; its disruption stops breathing','Metabolism encompasses all chemical reactions essential for life processes; disrupting it prevents energy production and maintenance of cell structure','Metabolism only synthesises DNA; its disruption prevents reproduction','Metabolism only regulates excretion; its disruption causes toxin buildup in the intestine','B',5,0,1,5),(221,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','What is the fluid found in the spaces between cells in animals called?','Cytoplasm','Plasma','Extracellular fluid','Lymph','C',1,0,0,1),(222,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','What is homeostasis?','The movement of water through a semi-permeable membrane','Keeping the composition of the internal environment constant','The production of hormones by endocrine glands','Transport of nutrients through the blood','B',1,0,0,1),(223,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','The internal environment of plants consists of:','Blood, lymph, and tissue fluid','Cell walls and their components, extracellular fluid, and air sacs between cells','Chloroplasts, mitochondria, and vacuoles only','Xylem, phloem, and stomata only','B',2,0,0,2),(224,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','Why must homeostasis be maintained?','For the smooth functioning of metabolism','To increase the rate of photosynthesis','To allow cells to divide more quickly','To prevent enzyme production','A',2,0,0,2),(225,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','In multicellular animals, substances from the external environment first reach which compartment before entering cells?','Cytoplasm','Nucleus','Extracellular fluid','Mitochondria','C',2,0,0,2),(226,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','In unicellular organisms like amoeba, substances from the external environment enter the cytoplasm through:','Plasmodesmata','Extracellular fluid first, then the cell membrane','The cell membrane directly','The cell wall only','C',3,0,0,3),(227,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','Plasmodesmata in plants are defined as:','Pores in the cell membrane for water transport only','Air sacs found between plant cells','Channels in the xylem for water transport','Cytoplasmic connections that connect adjacent plant cells','D',3,0,0,3),(228,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','A doctor says ''disruption of the chemical composition of the internal environment can be life-threatening.'' Which biological concept explains this?','Disruption destroys homeostasis, preventing smooth functioning of metabolism','Disruption accelerates photosynthesis beyond a safe rate','Disruption increases enzyme production dangerously','Disruption enhances active transport excessively','A',3,0,0,3),(229,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','How does the path of substances from the external environment to the cytoplasm differ between amoeba and multicellular animals?','In animals, substances go directly through the cell wall into cytoplasm','In amoeba, substances enter directly through the cell membrane; in animals, they first reach extracellular fluid before entering cells','In both, substances enter only through plasmodesmata','In both, substances are synthesised inside the cell without entering from outside','B',4,0,0,4),(230,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','In plants, substances can enter the cytoplasm through three routes. Which of the following is NOT one of them?','Through the cell wall and extracellular spaces','Through plasmodesmata connecting adjacent cells','From one cell to another through the plasma membrane','Directly through the nucleus into the cytoplasm','D',4,0,0,4),(231,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','A student says ''the internal environment of an animal is its blood.'' How would you correct this using the chapter?','The internal environment of animals is specifically the extracellular fluid found in the spaces between cells','The internal environment includes blood, lymph, and all organs together','The internal environment is only the plasma membrane','The internal environment is the same as the external environment','A',5,0,0,5),(232,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Internal Environment and Homeostasis','Why is homeostasis described as essential for the ''smooth functioning of metabolism''?','Because homeostasis only regulates reproduction of cells','Because homeostasis controls the nervous system exclusively','Because homeostasis prevents photosynthesis from occurring too fast','Because metabolism depends on stable chemical conditions in the internal environment; without homeostasis, those conditions fluctuate and metabolic reactions are disrupted','D',5,0,0,5),(233,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Another name for the cell membrane is:','Cytoplasm','Cell wall','Plasma membrane','Nuclear membrane','C',1,0,0,1),(234,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Osmosis is the movement of water molecules from a region of _____ concentration to a region of _____ concentration through a semi-permeable membrane.','Lower; higher','Higher; lower','Equal; lower','Lower; equal','B',1,0,0,1),(235,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Diffusion is the flow of molecules from a region of higher to lower concentration. Does it require energy?','Yes, it always requires ATP','Yes, it requires carrier proteins with energy','No, it does not require energy','Only for gases does it require energy','C',1,0,0,1),(236,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Which of the following substances can easily pass through the plasma membrane without special channels?','Sodium ions and potassium ions','Water, oxygen, and carbon dioxide','Glucose and amino acids','Large proteins','B',1,0,0,1),(237,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Active transport moves substances:','From higher to lower concentration without energy','From higher to lower concentration with energy','From lower to higher concentration using energy and carrier proteins','Only by osmosis','C',1,0,0,1),(238,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','The plasma membrane is described as ''selectively permeable'' because:','All substances pass through it freely','Only certain molecules can pass through it','It allows only water to pass','It prevents all molecules from entering the cell','B',1,0,0,1),(239,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','In facilitated diffusion, molecules move from higher to lower concentration. Which additional feature distinguishes it from simple diffusion?','It requires energy (ATP)','It is assisted by proteins in the plasma membrane','It moves molecules against the concentration gradient','It only applies to water molecules','B',2,0,0,2),(240,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','A cell is placed in a concentrated salt solution. Which process causes water to leave the cell?','Active transport','Facilitated diffusion','Osmosis','Simple diffusion of salt into the cell','C',2,0,0,2),(241,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Ions such as sodium and potassium can only pass through the plasma membrane via:','Simple diffusion','Osmosis','Channel proteins in the plasma membrane','Active transport only','C',2,0,0,2),(242,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','In the spinach leaf experiment, a piece placed in fresh water would:','Shrink, because water leaves by osmosis','Remain unchanged, because water does not move','Take in water, because the cell has a lower water concentration than fresh water','Absorb salt from the fresh water','C',2,0,0,2),(243,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','How does oxygen enter cells through the plasma membrane?','By active transport, since oxygen cannot diffuse','By osmosis through pores','By diffusion from higher oxygen concentration outside to lower concentration inside','By facilitated diffusion using carrier proteins only','C',2,0,0,2),(244,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','In the osmosis demonstration using a beaker with a semi-permeable membrane, water molecules move from side A (fresh water) to side B (salt water). This happens because:','Salt pulls water across by active transport','Fresh water (side A) has higher water molecule concentration than salt water (side B)','Salt water has higher water molecule concentration','The semi-permeable membrane pumps water','B',2,0,0,2),(245,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','A cell needs to move glucose from a region of higher concentration to lower concentration using membrane proteins but no energy. Which process is this?','Active transport','Osmosis','Facilitated diffusion','Simple diffusion','C',3,0,0,3),(246,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','A cell must absorb sodium ions even though their concentration is already higher inside the cell. Which process is used?','Osmosis','Simple diffusion','Facilitated diffusion','Active transport','D',3,0,0,3),(247,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','What happens to a cell placed in a solution with very low water concentration (concentrated salt solution)?','Water enters by osmosis and the cell swells','Salt moves into the cell by active transport only','Water leaves by osmosis and the cell shrinks','No change occurs since concentration is balanced','C',3,0,0,3),(248,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','The worksheet in the chapter lists processes related to movement of substances. Which process applies ONLY to water?','Diffusion','Active transport','Osmosis','Facilitated diffusion','C',3,0,0,3),(249,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Which of the following correctly describes the flow of molecules in active transport?','From higher to lower concentration, no energy needed','From lower to higher concentration, energy required, using carrier proteins','Only water molecules move against concentration gradient','Molecules move by osmosis against the gradient','B',3,0,0,3),(250,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Carrier proteins in the plasma membrane are involved in which two processes?','Osmosis and diffusion','Facilitated diffusion and active transport','Osmosis and active transport','Diffusion and osmosis','B',3,0,0,3),(251,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Among osmosis, diffusion, facilitated diffusion, and active transport, which is the ONLY process that moves molecules AGAINST the concentration gradient?','Diffusion','Osmosis','Active transport','Facilitated diffusion','C',4,0,0,4),(252,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Which of the following processes requires BOTH energy and carrier proteins?','Simple diffusion','Osmosis','Facilitated diffusion','Active transport','D',4,0,0,4),(253,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','In the spinach leaf experiment, the cell in salt solution shrinks while the one in fresh water swells. This confirms osmosis is driven by:','Active transport towards areas of higher solute concentration','Difference in water molecule concentration across the plasma membrane','Carrier protein activity triggered by salt','Temperature differences between the solutions','B',4,0,0,4),(254,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','Which pair of processes shares the feature of moving molecules from higher to lower concentration WITHOUT energy?','Active transport and osmosis','Diffusion and facilitated diffusion','Osmosis and active transport','Facilitated diffusion and active transport','B',4,0,0,4),(255,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plasma Membrane and Exchange of Substances','If a semi-permeable membrane separates fresh water (side A) from salt water (side B), which is the correct prediction?','Water moves from B to A, since salt water h