sses',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','The chapter describes the structure of the chloroplast. Which of the following correctly matches a part with its description?','Stroma – stacks of thylakoids where chlorophyll is found','Grana – stacks of thylakoids in the chloroplast','Thylakoid – the fluid part of the chloroplast','Outer membrane – the site of the dark phase of photosynthesis','B',3,0,0,3),(278,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','How does the structure of the chloroplast support the separation of the two phases of photosynthesis?','Both phases occur in grana where chlorophyll is found','The light phase occurs in the stroma and the dark phase in the grana','The light phase occurs in the grana (thylakoids) where chlorophyll captures light, while the dark phase occurs in the stroma where CO2 is fixed into glucose','Both phases occur in the outer membrane of the chloroplast','C',4,0,0,4),(279,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','Why do plants store glucose as starch rather than keeping it as glucose?','Because glucose is too large to fit in plant cells','Because glucose dissolves quickly in water while starch is insoluble, making it suitable for storage','Because starch is easier to transport through phloem than glucose','Because starch is a protein while glucose is a carbohydrate','B',4,0,0,4),(280,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','The chapter states ''photosynthesis is ultimately anabolism, it also involves catabolism.'' Which aspect of photosynthesis involves catabolism?','The formation of glucose in the dark phase','The splitting of water molecules in the light phase','The storage of glucose as starch','The absorption of carbon dioxide from the atmosphere','B',4,0,0,4),(281,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','Which zone of the ocean does NOT support photosynthesis and why?','Euphotic zone, because it has too much light','Dysphotic zone, because light is completely absent there','Aphotic zone, because the amount of sunlight available is very little','Dysphotic zone, because temperatures are too high','C',4,0,0,4),(282,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','Algae are described as obtaining nutrients through photosynthesis. How does this relate to the concept of autotrophs?','Algae are heterotrophs because they live in water','Algae are autotrophs because they synthesise their own nutrients via photosynthesis, just like land plants','Blue-green algae are heterotrophs because they are prokaryotes','Algae are neither autotrophs nor heterotrophs','B',4,0,0,4),(283,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','A plant is kept in complete darkness for 24 hours. What would you predict about photosynthesis based on the chapter?','The dark phase continues independently using stored ATP and hydrogen','Both phases stop because the dark phase depends on ATP and hydrogen produced in the light phase','Only the light phase stops; the dark phase continues with stored CO2','Photosynthesis speeds up since darkness triggers the light phase','B',5,0,0,5),(284,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','The chapter states ''plants are the foundation stones of the biosphere.'' Which argument best supports this?','Plants produce rubber and medicines used commercially','Plants are the only source of oxygen in the atmosphere','Plants are primary producers — through photosynthesis they create oxygen and nutrients that form the base of all food chains','Plants prevent global warming through transpiration','C',5,0,0,5),(285,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','Melvin Calvin won the Nobel Prize for explaining the dark phase reactions. Based on the chapter, what is the main outcome of this phase?','Splitting of water molecules to release oxygen','Production of ATP in the presence of light in the grana','Formation of glucose by combining hydrogen and carbon dioxide in the stroma','Production of chlorophyll for light absorption','C',5,0,0,5),(286,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','Kallen Pokkudan''s conservation of mangroves is significant because mangroves offer unique climate benefits. What specific benefit does the chapter highlight that ordinary forests cannot match?','Mangroves produce commercial spices and medicines','Mangroves absorb 4-5 times more CO2 than evergreen forests, making them exceptionally effective against global warming','Mangroves provide more fish wealth than open ocean','Mangroves prevent deforestation in urban areas','B',5,0,0,5),(287,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Photosynthesis and Nutrients','Nutrients produced by plants through metabolism reach herbivores through food, and herbivores are eaten by carnivores. This flow of nutrients illustrates which relationship?','All organisms are autotrophs that can photosynthesise','Plants are heterotrophs that depend on other organisms for nutrients','Plants as autotrophs are the primary producers, forming the foundation of nutrient transfer across the food chain to herbivores and then carnivores','Carnivores can directly synthesise nutrients without consuming herbivores','C',5,0,0,5),(288,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','Kerala had approximately how many hectares of mangroves in 1975?','7,000 hectares','70,000 hectares','7,00,000 hectares','7,000,000 hectares','B',1,0,0,1),(289,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','Animals that eat plants are called:','Carnivores','Decomposers','Herbivores','Autotrophs','C',1,0,0,1),(290,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','Which of the following is an ecological service provided by mangroves listed in the chapter?','Production of rubber latex','Prevention of tsunami','Providing coffee and tea beverages','Supplying pharmaceutical drugs','B',1,0,0,1),(291,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','The Euphotic zone of the ocean extends from the surface down to:','100 metres','200 metres','1000 metres','500 metres','B',2,0,0,2),(292,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','Which of the following is NOT listed in the chapter as a product of economic importance from plants?','Rubber latex','Biopesticides','Crude petroleum oil','Medicines','C',2,0,0,2),(293,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','In the Aphotic zone of the ocean (below 1000 m), photosynthesis does not occur because:','Water temperature is too high','The amount of sunlight available is very little','Water pressure is too low','Salt concentration prevents photosynthesis','B',3,0,0,3),(294,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','Why are producers in the ocean particularly important for marine life?','They build coral reefs','They are the source of oxygen and nutrients for marine food chains through photosynthesis','They filter ocean water of pollutants','They prevent plastic pollution','B',3,0,0,3),(295,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','Why are plants described as both autotrophs AND the foundation of food chains?','Because plants produce food that passes to herbivores, which are then eaten by carnivores, making plants the base of all nutrient flow','Because plants obtain nutrients from animals','Because plants are heterotrophs that depend on decomposers','Because plants only produce oxygen and no nutrients','A',4,0,0,4),(296,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','Kallen Pokkudan was called ''Kandal Pokkudan'' and planted more than one lakh mangrove saplings. He held which key view about mangrove conservation?','Mangroves should be replaced by more productive commercial crops','Mangroves must be grown in their natural habitat','Mangroves are less effective than evergreen forests in carbon absorption','Mangroves should be cultivated only in freshwater areas','B',4,0,0,4),(297,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','The UNO prediction that by 2050 ocean plastic will surpass the weight of fish stocks indicates:','Fish populations are multiplying rapidly','Plastic pollution is becoming a serious threat to marine ecosystems','Plastic helps marine organisms grow','Organisms of the Dysphotic zone are increasing in number','B',4,0,0,4),(298,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','A developer argues that destroying mangroves to build shrimp farms is justified economically. Based on the chapter''s description of mangrove services, what is the strongest ecological counter-argument?','Mangroves produce expensive timber and should be preserved for logging','Mangroves protect coastlines, support biodiversity, store large amounts of carbon (4-5x more than evergreen forests), and prevent tsunamis — ecological services far exceeding shrimp farm benefits','Mangroves prevent rainfall and should be preserved','Mangroves produce more shrimp than shrimp farms','B',5,0,0,5),(299,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','In the Aphotic zone (below 1000 m), some organisms produce light (bioluminescence). Based on the food web described in the chapter, what do Aphotic zone organisms mainly feed on?','Phytoplankton from the Euphotic zone directly','Dead remains of organisms that sink from the Dysphotic zone','Sunlight converted by bioluminescence','Plastic waste in the ocean','B',5,0,0,5),(300,'Kerala',9,'English','Biology','MCQ',1,'1','To Life Processes',1,'Plant Services and Plant Protection','The chapter mentions chemosynthesis in the Aphotic zone as a process some bacteria use. How must chemosynthesis differ from photosynthesis?','It requires sunlight just like photosynthesis but occurs at great depths','It produces sunlight rather than using it','It produces organic compounds using chemical energy rather than light energy','It is the same as photosynthesis but performed in complete darkness with the same inputs','C',5,0,0,5),(301,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronic Configuration and Stability','Atoms combine to form molecules in order to attain:','Higher atomic mass','Larger size','Greater number of protons','Stability','D',1,0,0,1),(302,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronic Configuration and Stability','Elements in which group of the periodic table are called Noble Gases or Inert Gases?','Group 1','Group 2','Group 16','Group 18','D',1,0,0,1),(303,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronic Configuration and Stability','How many electrons are present in the outermost shell of most noble gases (except helium)?','2','6','8','18','C',2,0,0,2),(304,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronic Configuration and Stability','The stable arrangement of 8 electrons in the outermost shell of an atom is called:','Duplet configuration','Ionic configuration','Covalent configuration','Octet configuration','D',2,0,0,2),(305,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronic Configur