ingle bond. Oxygen (O₂) has a double bond. Which molecule has the highest number of shared electron pairs per bond?','HCl','F₂','O₂','N₂','D',4,0,0,4),(345,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Covalent Bonding','In the electron dot diagram of water (H₂O), oxygen (Z=8, config 2,6) shares electrons with two hydrogen atoms. The bond type in H₂O is:','Two ionic bonds','Two double bonds','One triple bond','Two single covalent bonds','D',4,0,0,4),(346,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Covalent Bonding','In which of the following is ionic bonding NOT possible?','NaCl','MgO','NaF','F₂','D',4,0,0,4),(347,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Covalent Bonding','Carbon (Z=6, config 2,4) needs 4 more electrons for an octet. In methane (CH₄), it bonds with 4 hydrogen atoms. The number of covalent bonds and bond type are:','4 double bonds','1 triple bond and 1 single bond','2 double bonds','4 single bonds','D',5,0,0,5),(348,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Covalent Bonding','HF is a covalent compound. H (Z=1) and F (Z=9, config 2,7) share one electron pair. Which atom has the greater tendency to attract the shared electrons?','Hydrogen, because it is smaller','Fluorine, because it has higher electronegativity','Both atoms equally','Hydrogen, because it has only 1 proton','B',5,0,0,5),(349,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Covalent Bonding','In the formation of Cl₂, each Cl atom (Z=17, config 2,8,7) needs 1 more electron. The bond type and number of shared pairs are:','Ionic bond; 0 shared pairs','Double bond; 2 shared pairs','Triple bond; 3 shared pairs','Single bond; 1 shared pair','D',5,0,0,5),(350,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Covalent Bonding','Ethane (C₂H₆) has C-C and C-H single bonds. Ethylene (C₂H₄) has a C=C double bond. In terms of shared electron pairs, a C=C bond has __ pairs while a C-C bond has __ pairs:','1 and 2','3 and 2','1 and 1','2 and 1','D',5,0,0,5),(351,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','The electronegativity scale widely used is proposed by:','Gilbert N. Lewis','Antoine Lavoisier','John Dalton','Linus Pauling','D',1,0,0,1),(352,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','In Pauling''s electronegativity scale, which element is the most electronegative?','Chlorine','Oxygen','Nitrogen','Fluorine','D',1,0,0,1),(353,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','The electronegativity values in Pauling''s scale range from:','0 to 10','−2 to +2','−4 to +4','0 to 4','D',1,0,0,1),(354,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','If the difference in electronegativity between two elements is 1.7 or more, the bond formed is generally:','Covalent','Metallic','Polar covalent','Ionic','D',2,0,0,2),(355,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','If the difference in electronegativity between two elements is less than 1.7, the bond formed is generally:','Ionic','Metallic','Hydrogen bond','Covalent','D',2,0,0,2),(356,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','In a homodiatomic molecule like H₂, atoms attract the shared pair of electrons:','Unequally, H₂ is polar','Equally, so H₂ is non-polar','With different electronegativities','More on one side','B',2,0,0,2),(357,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','In hydrogen chloride (HCl), the chlorine atom attracts the shared electrons more. The chlorine atom develops a partial charge of:','Delta positive (δ+)','No charge','Ionic charge of −1','Delta negative (δ−)','D',3,0,0,3),(358,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','In HCl, the hydrogen atom develops which partial charge?','δ−','No charge','Ionic +1','δ+','D',3,0,0,3),(359,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','Compounds that have partial electrical charges within the molecule are called:','Non-polar compounds','Ionic compounds','Metallic compounds','Polar compounds','D',3,0,0,3),(360,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','Water is a polar molecule. Which of the following is a consequence of water''s polar nature?','Water is a gas at room temperature','Water is a poor solvent','Water has very low density','Water can dissolve many organic and inorganic compounds','D',4,0,0,4),(361,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','Carbon monoxide (CO) has an electronegativity difference of 3.44 − 2.55 = 0.89. This compound is:','Ionic','Metallic','Non-polar','Covalent','D',4,0,0,4),(362,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','Which of the following pairs has an electronegativity difference greater than 1.7 and would form an ionic compound? (EN values: Na=0.93, Cl=3.16, C=2.55, H=2.20)','C and H (diff=0.35)','H and Cl (diff=0.96)','C and Cl (diff=0.61)','Na and Cl (diff=2.23)','D',4,0,0,4),(363,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','HF, HBr, and H₂O are polar compounds. NH₃ (ammonia) is also polar. What makes a molecule polar?','Having only one type of atom','Having covalent bonds only','Having the same electronegativity in all atoms','Unequal sharing of electrons leading to partial charges','D',5,0,0,5),(364,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','In water (H₂O), oxygen has electronegativity 3.44 and hydrogen has 2.20. The difference is 1.24. According to the electronegativity rule, the bond in H₂O is:','Ionic','Non-polar covalent','Metallic','Polar covalent (difference < 1.7)','D',5,0,0,5),(365,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','In the molecule HF, fluorine has EN=3.98 and hydrogen has EN=2.20. The difference is 1.78. Which type of bond does HF have?','Non-polar covalent','Metallic','Ionic (difference ≥ 1.7)','Polar covalent (difference < 1.7)','C',5,0,0,5),(366,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Electronegativity and Polar Nature','Linus Pauling''s electronegativity scale is described as ''relative''. This means:','All elements have the same electronegativity','Values are measured in absolute energy units','Values show the tendency of atoms to attract bonded electrons relative to fluorine','Electronegativity changes with temperature','C',4,0,0,4),(367,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Ionic compounds generally conduct electricity in their:','Solid state only','Non-aqueous solutions','Aqueous and molten states','Gaseous state only','C',1,0,0,1),(368,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Covalent compounds are generally:','Soluble in water','Insoluble in organic solvents','Not conductors of electricity','Solids with high melting points','C',1,0,0,1),(369,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Ionic compounds generally have melting and boiling points that are:','Variable','Very low','Low','High','D',2,0,0,2),(370,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Covalent compounds like wax are generally soluble in:','Water','Dilute acids','Organic solvents like kerosene and CCl₄','Salt solutions','C',2,0,0,2),(371,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Sodium chloride is an ionic compound. In which of the following states does it NOT conduct electricity?','Aqueous solution','Molten state','Solid state','Both aqueous and molten states','C',3,0,0,3),(372,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Which property distinguishes an ionic compound from a covalent compound?','Ionic compounds are always gases','Covalent compounds always have high melting points','Ionic compounds conduct electricity in aqueous state; covalent compounds generally do not','Covalent compounds cannot dissolve in any solvent','C',3,0,0,3),(373,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','A student tests two compounds. Compound A dissolves in water and conducts electricity. Compound B does not dissolve in water but dissolves in kerosene. Based on the properties:','A is covalent; B is ionic','Both are covalent','A is ionic; B is covalent','Both are ionic','C',4,0,0,4),(374,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Why do ionic compounds have high melting points?','They are made of large molecules','Their covalent bonds are strong','The strong electrostatic forces between ions require high energy to break','They are insoluble in water','C',4,0,0,4),(375,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','Wax is a covalent compound with a low melting point. NaCl is ionic with a high melting point. This difference is primarily because:','Wax molecules are larger','Ionic bonds are much weaker than covalent bonds','Wax does not have electrostatic forces while NaCl has strong ionic attractions','Covalent compounds contain more atoms','C',5,0,0,5),(376,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Properties of Ionic and Covalent Compounds','A substance exists as a solid, conducts electricity when dissolved in water, and has a high melting point. It is most likely:','A covalent molecular compound','A noble gas','A transition metal','An ionic compound','D',5,0,0,5),(377,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The valency of sodium in NaCl is:','2','3','4','1','D',1,0,0,1),(378,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The valency of chlorine in NaCl is:','2','3','4','1','D',1,0,0,1),(379,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The valency of oxygen is:','1','3','4','2','D',1,0,0,1),(380,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The chemical formula of magnesium chloride is:','MgCl','Mg₂Cl','Mg₃Cl₂','MgCl₂','D',1,0,0,1),(381,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The chemical formula of aluminum oxide is:','AlO','Al₂O₃','Al₃O₂','AlO₂','B',1,0,0,1),(382,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The valency of magnesium is:','1','3','4','2','D',2,0,0,2),(383,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The valency of aluminum is:','1','2','4','3','D',2,0,0,2),(384,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The chemical formula of sodium oxide is:','NaO','Na₂O₂','NaO₂','Na₂O','D',2,0,0,2),(385,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','To write the chemical formula of a compound, the valencies of constituent elements are:','Added together','Subtracted from each other','Written as coefficients in front of symbols','Interchanged and written as subscripts','D',2,0,0,2),(386,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Valency relates to the number of electrons an atom:','Gains or loses in nuclear reactions','Gains, loses or shares during chemical bonding','Has in its nucleus','Has in total','B',2,0,0,2),(387,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Aluminum (Z=13, config 2,8,3) donates 3 electrons during bond formation. Its valency is:','1','2','4','3','D',3,0,0,3),(388,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Fluorine (Z=9, config 2,7) accepts 1 electron. Its valency is:','2','3','4','1','D',3,0,0,3),(389,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','If magnesium (valency 2) combines with fluorine (valency 1), the formula of magnesium fluoride is:','MgF','Mg₂F','Mg₃F₂','MgF₂','D',3,0,0,3),(390,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','The chemical formula for carbon dioxide (CO₂) involves carbon (valency 4) and oxygen (valency 2). After interchanging and simplifying:','C₂O₄','C₄O₂','CO₄','CO₂','D',3,0,0,3),(391,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','To write the formula of aluminium fluoride: Al has valency 3 and F has valency 1. The formula is:','AlF','Al₃F','AlF₂','AlF₃','D',3,0,0,3),(392,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Carbon (valency 4) and chlorine (valency 1) form carbontetrachloride. Applying the valency interchange method, the formula is:','C₄Cl','CCl₂','CCl','CCl₄','D',4,0,0,4),(393,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Zinc (valency 2) and bromine (valency 1) form zinc bromide. The chemical formula is:','ZnBr','Zn₂Br','Zn₂Br₃','ZnBr₂','D',4,0,0,4),(394,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Potassium (valency 1) and oxygen (valency 2) form potassium oxide. The chemical formula is:','KO','K₂O₂','KO₂','K₂O','D',4,0,0,4),(395,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Magnesium (valency 2) and fluorine (valency 1) combine. After applying the cross-multiplication rule for valencies, the formula is:','MgF','Mg₂F₂','Mg₂F','MgF₂','D',4,0,0,4),(396,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','In the formation of NaCl, sodium donates 1 electron and chlorine accepts 1 electron. In the formation of MgO, magnesium donates 2 electrons. The valency of magnesium in MgO is:','1','3','4','2','D',5,0,0,5),(397,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Element X has valency 3 and element Y has valency 2. The formula of the compound formed between X and Y after simplification is:','XY','X₂Y₃','X₃Y₂','XY₂','B',5,0,0,5),(398,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Aluminium oxide has the formula Al₂O₃. This means the valency ratio of Al to O is:','1:01','3:02','1:02','2:03','D',5,0,0,5),(399,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','A student writes the formula of calcium oxide as Ca₂O₂. The correct formula is CaO. This means the valency of calcium is:','1','3','4','2','D',5,0,0,5),(400,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'2','Chemical Bonding',5,'Valency and Chemical Formula','Element P has valency 3 and element Q has valency 2. After interchanging valencies and simplifying by the GCF, which formula is correct for the compound PQ?','P₂Q₃','P₃Q₂','PQ','P₃Q','A',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (401,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Who made the first attempt to classify elements?','Dobereiner','Newlands','Mendeleev','Lavoisier','D',1,0,0,1),(402,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Lavoisier classified about 30 known elements into:','Metals, non-metals and metalloids','Periods and groups','Solids and liquids','Metals and non-metals','D',1,0,0,1),(403,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Dobereiner formed small groups of three elements with similar properties called:','Octaves','Periods','Groups','Triads','D',1,0,0,1),(404,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','In Dobereiner''s Triads, the atomic mass of the middle element was approximately:','The sum of the first and third','Twice the first','Three times the third','The arithmetic mean of the first and third','D',1,0,0,1),(405,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Newlands'' Law of Octaves states that the properties of every eighth element is a repetition of the:','Eighth element','Seventh element','Second element','First element','D',2,0,0,2),(406,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Newlands compared his law to:','Newton''s law of gravity','Dalton''s atomic theory','Rutherford''s model','The seven notes of music','D',2,0,0,2),(407,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Mendeleev arranged elements in his periodic table in the increasing order of their:','Electronegativity','Atomic number','Valency','Atomic mass','D',2,0,0,2),(408,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Mendeleev is known as the:','Father of chemistry','Father of atomic theory','Father of the periodic table','Father of electricity','C',2,0,0,2),(409,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','How many elements were in Mendeleev''s periodic table when it was first created?','30','56','120','63','D',3,0,0,3),(410,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','One advantage of Mendeleev''s periodic table was that it could:','Explain nuclear structure','Identify isotopes','Predict properties of undiscovered elements by leaving blank spaces','Classify metalloids correctly','C',3,0,0,3),(411,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','One limitation of Newlands'' Law of Octaves was that:','It worked for all elements','Elements with higher atomic mass did not follow the rule','It did not group metals and non-metals','It ignored atomic mass','B',3,0,0,3),(412,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','One limitation of Dobereiner''s Triads was that:','The arithmetic mean rule was wrong','All elements were classified into triads','No relationship existed','Not all elements could be classified into triads','D',3,0,0,3),(413,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','A limitation of Mendeleev''s periodic table was that elements with large differences in properties were placed in the same group. Which pair is an example?','Na and K','He and Ne','Cu/Ag with Na/K','Li and Na','C',4,0,0,4),(414,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Mendeleev''s periodic table could not give proper position to which element?','Oxygen','Carbon','Nitrogen','Hydrogen','D',4,0,0,4),(415,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','In Mendeleev''s periodic table, the strict increasing order of atomic mass was not always followed. Which pair is an example?','Na and Mg','Li and Be','Cobalt (Co) and Nickel (Ni)','Ca and K','C',4,0,0,4),(416,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','One advantage of Mendeleev''s periodic table was correction of wrongly determined atomic masses. The atomic mass of beryllium was corrected from:','9 to 14','4 to 9','14 to 9','9 to 4','C',4,0,0,4),(417,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','In Newlands'' Octaves, Na appears in the 8th position after Li. Li has atomic mass 7; Na has 23. Which element appears in position 15 (8th after Na)?','Al','Si','K','Mg','C',5,0,0,5),(418,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Lavoisier classified elements into metals and non-metals but could not classify:','Noble gases','Radioactive elements','Ionic compounds','Metalloids showing properties of both metals and non-metals','D',5,0,0,5),(419,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'4','Periodic Table',7,'Early Attempts at Classification of Elements','Mendeleev''s periodic law states that properties of elements are periodic functions of their atomic masses. Moseley later modified this to atomic numbers. The key difference is that atomic number is:','The number of neutrons','The number of neutrons plus protons','Equal to atomic mass','The number of protons (uni