,0,0,4),(594,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'3','Redox Reactions and Rate of Chemical Reactions',6,'Rate of Chemical Reactions','For a reaction between two gases, increasing pressure has an effect similar to:','Decreasing temperature','Adding a negative catalyst','Increasing the surface area of solid reactants','Increasing the concentration of reactants','D',4,0,0,4),(595,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'3','Redox Reactions and Rate of Chemical Reactions',6,'Rate of Chemical Reactions','A positive catalyst increases the rate of reaction; a negative catalyst decreases it. In the storage of H₂O₂, phosphoric acid is used as a negative catalyst. If instead MnO₂ were added, it would:','Stop the reaction completely','Act as a negative catalyst','Have no effect','Increase the rate of decomposition','D',4,0,0,4),(596,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'3','Redox Reactions and Rate of Chemical Reactions',6,'Rate of Chemical Reactions','In the collision theory, for a collision to result in a chemical reaction, the colliding molecules must have:','Any amount of energy','Energy less than threshold energy','Equal energy','Energy greater than or equal to threshold energy','D',5,0,0,5),(597,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'3','Redox Reactions and Rate of Chemical Reactions',6,'Rate of Chemical Reactions','Sulphur powder reacts with cold concentrated nitric acid, but sulphur pieces do not. The key factor responsible for this difference is:','Nature of the reactant','Temperature','Concentration of acid','Surface area of sulphur','D',5,0,0,5),(598,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'3','Redox Reactions and Rate of Chemical Reactions',6,'Rate of Chemical Reactions','The reaction CaCO₃ + 2HCl → CaCl₂ + H₂O + CO₂ can be made faster by using marble powder instead of pieces AND concentrated HCl instead of dilute HCl. This exploits:','Only nature of reactants','Only surface area','Only temperature','Both surface area and concentration factors simultaneously','D',5,0,0,5),(599,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'3','Redox Reactions and Rate of Chemical Reactions',6,'Rate of Chemical Reactions','In a reaction, increasing temperature doubles the rate for every 10°C rise. If the rate at 20°C is 1 unit, what is the rate at 40°C?','2 units','6 units','8 units','4 units','D',5,0,0,5),(600,'Kerala',9,'English','Chemistry','MCQ',1,'3','Redox Reactions and Rate of Chemical Reactions',6,'Rate of Chemical Reactions','Enzymes are biological catalysts made of:','Carbohydrates','Vitamins','Lipids','Complex protein molecules','D',5,0,0,5);
