Fever','All three stanzas begin with ''I must go down to the seas again.'' How does the content of each stanza develop the central theme?','Each stanza is about a different sailor','Each stanza describes a different journey','Each stanza repeats the same idea in different words','Each stanza moves from physical sensations to the pull of freedom to the desire for fellowship and rest — building the full picture of sea life','D',4,0,0,4),(714,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Sea-Fever','The poem uses both tactile images (''wheel''s kick'') and auditory images (''wind''s song''). What is the combined effect of these different sensory images?','They immerse the reader in the full physical and sensory experience of life at sea','They make the poem seem longer than it is','They make the poem confusing','They show that Masefield was a trained scientist','A',4,0,0,4),(715,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Sea-Fever','The poem ends with the speaker looking forward to ''quiet sleep and a sweet dream when the long trick''s over.'' In the context of the entire poem, this ending suggests:','The sailor is old and wants to retire','The long trick refers to a card game','The sailor is afraid of dying at sea','After the exhilaration of the sea, rest and peace are the natural completion of the journey','D',4,0,0,4),(716,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Sea-Fever','''Sea-Fever'' begins with a strong desire (''I must'') and ends with rest (''quiet sleep''). What arc does this structure describe?','From irresistible longing through the full experience of the sea to peaceful fulfilment','From youth to old age','From boredom to excitement','From sadness to happiness','A',4,0,0,4),(717,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Sea-Fever','The speaker says ''I must go down to the seas again.'' The word ''must'' is significant. Which reading does it best support?','The desire for the sea is an inner compulsion, as inescapable as a physical need','The sailor has no personal preference but goes out of duty','The sailor is forced to go to sea by his employer','The sailor is going to sea for the first time','A',5,0,0,5),(718,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Sea-Fever','A student argues ''Sea-Fever is just about sailing.'' A more complete reading would note that the poem also expresses:','Gandhiji''s idea of non-violence','A historical account of Victorian maritime life','The difficulty of navigation without GPS','A universal human longing for freedom, adventure, and belonging — the sea standing for any irresistible calling','D',5,0,0,5),(719,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Sea-Fever','John Masefield was Poet Laureate for 37 years (1930–1967). ''Sea-Fever'' is one of his most famous poems. Which quality of the poem most explains its lasting appeal?','Its simple, musical language that makes the longing for adventure and freedom feel universal and immediate','Its use of difficult vocabulary','Its technical accuracy about sailing','Its historical documentation of Victorian sea voyages','A',5,0,0,5),(720,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Sea-Fever','The ''gull''s way and the whale''s way'' in stanza three describe the sea as belonging to birds and whales, not humans. What does the speaker''s desire to enter this non-human world reveal?','He wishes to study marine biology','He wants to hunt whales','He is afraid of other sailors','He dislikes human society and seeks escape into a primal, free world beyond human boundaries','D',5,0,0,5),(721,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','Who wrote ''The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers''?','Hugh and Colleen Gantzer','Anita Nair','Hugh Gantzer and Mahadev Desai','Gcina Mhlope','A',1,0,0,1),(722,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','In which city are the dabbawalas unique?','Mumbai','Chennai','Delhi','Kolkata','A',1,0,0,1),(723,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','In which year did the dabbawala service begin?','1870','1920','1910','1890','D',1,0,0,1),(724,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','Who was the first person to seek the services of a dabbawala?','An old Parsi lady in the suburb of Dadar','A Marathi businessman in Churchgate','A Parsi gentleman in Dadar','A British officer in Bombay','A',1,0,0,1),(725,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','How many dabbawalas ply the Western Railway, according to the passage?','3,500','2,500','1,500','5,000','A',1,0,0,1),(726,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','Churchgate station is on which railway in Mumbai?','The Central Railway','The Metro Rail','The Harbour Line','The Western Railway','D',1,0,0,1),(727,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','How much do dabbawalas charge per customer per month?','Rs. 500','Rs. 400','Rs. 300','Rs. 600','A',1,0,0,1),(728,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','What is the name of the oldest dabbawala mentioned in the passage?','Mahadu','Ramesh','Gopal','Bikaji','D',1,0,0,1),(729,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','E. L. Paulo, a satisfied customer of the dabbawalas, was the Director and Secretary of which organisation?','The Reserve Bank of India','The Bombay Stock Exchange','The Mumbai Port Trust','The Textiles Export Promotion Council','D',1,0,0,1),(730,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','How many tiffin carriers does one tray hold?','40 to 45','30 to 35','20 to 25','50 to 55','A',2,0,0,2),(731,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','How much does a fully laden tray of tiffin carriers weigh?','85 to 100 kilos','65 to 75 kilos','40 to 50 kilos','110 to 120 kilos','A',2,0,0,2),(732,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','How many changing points does the tiffin carrier system have?','Five','Four','Three','Six','A',2,0,0,2),(733,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','At what time must tiffins be delivered to offices, according to the passage?','12:00 PM','2:30 PM','2:00 PM','1:00 pm sharp, or earlier','D',2,0,0,2),(734,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','What happens if a customer''s food is not ready when the dabbawala arrives?','The dabbawala leaves but gives the customer one more chance; the next time they are removed from the list','The dabbawala leaves immediately and gives no second chance','The dabbawala waits for up to an hour','The customer pays a fine','A',2,0,0,2),(735,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','What is the distinguishing item of clothing that all dabbawalas must wear?','White caps','A blue uniform','A red apron','A green vest','A',2,0,0,2),(736,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','What information is encoded in the alpha-numerical markings on each tiffin carrier?','The customer''s name and phone number','The price and date of subscription','The weight and contents of the tiffin','The location of the flat, changing points, delivery points, and dabbawalas involved','D',2,0,0,2),(737,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','How long had E. L. Paulo been using the dabbawala service at the time of the interview?','Ten years','Seven years','Five years','Fifteen years','A',2,0,0,2),(738,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','What did the dabbawalas send Prince Charles as a present?','A tiffin carrier with Indian food','A model of the dabbawala crate','A letter describing their system','A present for his wedding','D',2,0,0,2),(739,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','Why are dabbawalas unique to Mumbai and not found in any other city, according to the passage?','Mumbai alone has the specific combination of skyrocketing land prices, a diverse workforce, and a culture of home cooking that makes the dabbawala service essential','Only Mumbai has a large Indian population','Mumbai is the only city that makes tiffin carriers','The dabbawala association has refused to expand','A',3,0,0,3),(740,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage says dabbawalas must deal ''courteously with customers and so cannot be uncouth or drunk.'' Why is this rule particularly important?','To impress foreign visitors','Because they interact daily with customers in their homes and offices, making professionalism essential for trust','Because the law requires it','Because they work near restaurants','B',3,0,0,3),(741,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage says ''Mumbai is a great magnet. It draws people from all over India, each with their own dietary foibles and taboos.'' How does this detail explain the need for dabbawalas?','People with specific dietary requirements prefer home-cooked food from their own kitchens','People from different regions cannot cook their own food','Restaurants cannot cook food from every region','Food allergies are common in Mumbai','A',3,0,0,3),(742,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','E. L. Paulo said ''In all these ten years, they have never missed.'' Why does the passage describe this as ''a great endorsement''?','As a senior executive who maintains international standards, his praise carries particular weight','Paulo lives very far from his office','Paulo is a famous person','E. L. Paulo was their first customer','A',3,0,0,3),(743,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage notes that the dabbawala system was developed by the dabbawalas themselves, not by MBAs. Why is this detail significant?','It demonstrates that practical wisdom and grassroots organisation can create a system that academic training cannot match','It proves that the dabbawalas are dishonest','It shows that MBAs are not useful','It means the system is simple and requires no intelligence','A',3,0,0,3),(744,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','A dabbawala picks up tiffins at 8:00 am and delivers them by 1:00 pm. Empty carriers are returned by 5:30 pm. What does this schedule reveal about the system?','The dabbawalas only work part-time','A precise, time-controlled workflow that leaves no room for error at any stage','The dabbawalas have plenty of free time','The system was designed for a single railway line','B',3,0,0,3),(745,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','Why does the passage describe the dabbawala crates as ''coffin-sized''?','They are used to carry dead fish','They are shaped like coffins for easy stacking','It reflects a death-related superstition among dabbawalas','A vivid, slightly dramatic comparison to help the reader visualise the large, heavy wooden crates','D',3,0,0,3),(746,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage says dabbawalas are ''festooned like multiple garlands around the necks and shoulders'' of the delivery men. This image suggests:','The dabbawalas enjoy wearing garlands','They carry tiffin carriers decoratively around their bodies, making the most of limited transport space','The dabbawalas celebrate festivals while working','The image is a criticism of poor working conditions','B',3,0,0,3),(747,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The dabbawala responds to a question about fast food eateries with ''Chhah! You can''t live on fast food.'' This response reveals:','The dabbawala is poorly educated','He dislikes all Western food','He is angry about the question','A confident dismissal: fast food cannot replace home-cooked meals, so the dabbawala service has no real competition','D',3,0,0,3),(748,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage describes the dabbawala system as ''entirely grassroots-generated.'' What does this phrase mean?','The dabbawalas grow vegetables','The system was created by ordinary working people without formal education or institutional support','The government funded the system from the beginning','The system involves agricultural produce','B',4,0,0,4),(749,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','''Their incredible efficiency has won the admiration of international business schools.'' What does this mean about the dabbawala system?','Business schools now train dabbawalas','The system is so efficient and organised that it serves as a model studied by professional management programs','Harvard University funded the dabbawalas','The dabbawalas have become professors at business schools','B',4,0,0,4),(750,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The article describes the dabbawala association as running ''a very tightly controlled, disciplined organisation.'' How do the specific rules about white caps and punctuality illustrate this?','They show the dabbawalas have military training','These rules show that every small detail — appearance and timing — is monitored and enforced, leaving no room for individual lapses','The rules were created by the government','The rules exist only to impress foreign visitors','B',4,0,0,4),(751,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage begins by saying dabbawalas are ''unique to Mumbai'' and ends with an endorsement from Prince Charles. How does the structure of the article support its central claim?','It simply lists facts in random order','It moves from explaining why the system exists, through how it works, to testimonials from users and world figures — building a comprehensive case for its uniqueness and excellence','It focuses entirely on the history of the dabbawalas','It argues that Mumbai should be India''s capital','B',4,0,0,4),(752,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The alpha-numerical coding system was developed by the dabbawalas without any formal education. Compare this to Gandhiji''s argument in ''Dreams Realised'' that real education develops character. How are these ideas related?','They are unrelated','Both texts argue that literacy is unimportant','Gandhiji would have approved of the dabbawala system because it involves food','Both show that practical wisdom, character, and discipline can achieve what formal education cannot — one through non-violence, the other through operational genius','D',4,0,0,4),(753,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage mentions that Bikaji, 74 years old, has been working for 50 years. What does this detail illustrate about the dabbawala system?','The work is physically easy, suitable for old men','The system attracts only uneducated workers','There are no retirement benefits for dabbawalas','The system provides long-term, dignified livelihood, and senior members represent its living tradition and reliability','D',4,0,0,4),(754,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The article is written by ''Hugh and Colleen Gantzer'' — a travel writing couple. How does their perspective shape the writing?','They are critical of the dabbawala system','They write from a purely statistical standpoint','They are customers of the dabbawala service','As experienced travel writers, they bring an observational, first-hand narrative — meeting the dabbawalas, watching them work, and collecting testimonials','D',4,0,0,4),(755,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage describes both the scale (two lakh customers, 5,000 dabbawalas) and the precision (alpha-numerical codes, strict timing) of the system. Why are BOTH scale and precision important to the argument?','Scale proves the dabbawalas are rich','Precision alone would work for a small system','It is precisely the combination of massive scale and flawless precision that makes the system remarkable — precision at huge scale is extraordinarily difficult','The two facts are unrelated to each other','C',4,0,0,4),(756,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','One dabbawala says ''Can your MBAs do it? Never!'' What does this confident challenge reveal about the dabbawala''s sense of identity?','He dislikes educated people','He is poorly educated and resentful','He has a strong sense of pride and confidence in his community''s achievement — knowing their practical genius surpasses formal theory','He is being rude to the authors','C',4,0,0,4),(757,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The service began with one old Parsi lady in 1890 and now has two lakh customers. What does this growth suggest about the dabbawala service?','It grew because the government supported it','It grew because fast food is bad','A genuinely useful service, built on trust and efficiency, will organically grow to serve an entire city''s needs without needing formal backing','Mumbai''s population forced the service to grow','C',5,0,0,5),(758,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','A management student argues: ''The dabbawala system should adopt GPS and digital tracking to replace alpha-numerical codes.'' Which point from the passage would best counter this argument?','GPS is not available in Mumbai','Digital technology is unreliable','The dabbawala system works perfectly without formal education or technology — adding technology would not improve a system already hailed for flawless efficiency','The dabbawalas cannot afford technology','C',5,0,0,5),(759,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The article is a piece of travel journalism embedded in a textbook. How does the interview format (direct quotations from dabbawalas) serve the article''s purpose?','It makes the article easier to write','The quotes make the dabbawalas'' voices and pride come alive, giving credibility and humanity to what could otherwise be dry statistics','It reduces the need for the authors to do research','Interviews are required by journalistic rules','B',5,0,0,5),(760,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage says ''Such a comment from a senior executive, who has to maintain international standards, is indeed a great endorsement.'' Why is E. L. Paulo''s profession specifically important as a source of endorsement?','He is a personal friend of the authors','His high standards make his praise particularly credible','He is the head of a government department','He has used the service the longest of anyone','B',5,0,0,5),(761,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','''The saga of the tiffin carriers'' is called a ''saga'' in the title. What quality of the dabbawala story justifies the use of this word?','It is a very long story','It involves many characters','Like a literary saga, it is an epic story of human organisation, persistence, and achievement spanning over a century','It has a dramatic ending','C',5,0,0,5),(762,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The unit''s title is ''Aspire and Explore.'' How does ''The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers'' fit this theme?','The dabbawalas explore Mumbai every day','The dabbawalas aspire to become educated professionals','The dabbawala story shows that aspiring to serve a community''s needs and exploring innovative solutions create a service that achieves the seemingly impossible','It fits because the authors travel to write the article','C',5,0,0,5),(763,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The dabbawala responds ''We did. Can your MBAs do it? Never! In fact, they have often asked us to explain it to them.'' What broader lesson about knowledge and expertise does this suggest?','Formal education is useless','MBAs should be retrained as dabbawalas','Practical expertise developed through experience can be superior to theoretical knowledge — and those with formal training recognise this by coming to learn','The dabbawala is simply boasting without reason','C',5,0,0,5),(764,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The passage describes Mumbai as ''The Big Apple of India.'' What does this comparison to New York''s nickname suggest about Mumbai?','Mumbai has many apple orchards','Mumbai and New York have the same population','Like New York, Mumbai is a booming city where ambitions and opportunities converge — a place of impossible dreams made real','The comparison is geographically inaccurate','C',5,0,0,5),(765,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'The Saga of the Tiffin Carriers','The article concludes ''if you want another endorsement, ask Prince (King) Charles.'' The addition of ''(King)'' in brackets reveals:','A factual error in the original text','That the article was written before Charles became king and has been updated to reflect that he is now King','That Charles lost his royal title','The authors are British','B',5,0,0,5),(766,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','Who wrote ''Waiting for Rain''?','Gcina Mhlope','Selma Lagerlof','Anita Nair','Mahadev Desai','C',1,0,0,1),(767,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','In which city does the author Anita Nair live when not in her village?','Mumbai','Chennai','Delhi','Bangalore','D',1,0,0,1),(768,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','What is the name of the author''s village in Kerala?','Kozhikode','Thiruvananthapuram','Mundakkottukurissi','Thrissur','C',1,0,0,1),(769,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','What was the first day of the month of Karkitakam mentioned in the passage?','7-Jul','17-Jul','1-Aug','21-Jun','B',1,0,0,1),(770,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','How old is the narrator''s uncle described in the passage?','75 years old','80 years old','85 years old','90 years 