English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','What musical terms does the author use to describe the different rhythms of the rain?','Tala, laya, and sruti','Vilamba kaalam, madhyama kaalam, and dhrutha kaalam','Anupallavi, pallavi, and charanam','Raga, tala, and bhava','B',2,0,0,2),(778,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The villagers told the author that the summer drought had been intense. How long had it been since they last saw such low water tables?','A decade','Almost two decades','Three decades','Five years','B',2,0,0,2),(779,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','According to the author, what contributes to the lowering of the water table and reduced rainfall?','Increased farming activity','The arrival of more guest workers','Deforestation and building concrete structures, tiling front yards, and cutting down trees','Climate change from distant countries','C',2,0,0,2),(780,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author says she was ''the only passenger on that flight who was happy with the turbulence.'' Why does this make her different from the others?','She was not afraid of flying','She was a scientist studying atmospheric conditions','Unlike the other passengers who feared turbulence, she connected it to the monsoon she had come to Kerala specifically to experience','She was seated in a safer part of the plane','C',3,0,0,3),(781,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author says ''How do you coax a monsoon to do what it ought to be doing?'' What does this question reveal?','The author is a meteorologist','The author believes prayers can bring rain','A feeling of helplessness before nature — humans can neither control nor truly predict the monsoon','The author is angry at the government','C',3,0,0,3),(782,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author describes watching the rain ''as if it were an exotic migratory bird — afraid to even sigh in pleasure, for I might frighten it away.'' What does this simile reveal?','Migratory birds are common in Kerala','She treats the arrival of rain as fragile and precious, to be appreciated silently for fear of disturbing it','She is afraid of birds','She thinks rain is like a bird because it migrates from the Maldives','B',3,0,0,3),(783,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author''s uncle, at 85, ''straddles the past and present with the same ease he does his scooter (he learnt to ride one when he was 78).'' This description shows:','Old age prevents learning new skills','The uncle has a youthful, adaptable spirit — both physically and in his memory of how the monsoon once was','Motorcycles are common in Kerala villages','The uncle is boasting about his abilities','B',3,0,0,3),(784,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author quotes her mother: ''Where has the rain gone? Has it come to you?'' What does this question reveal about the relationship between the monsoon and Kerala''s people?','Kerala people are angry with other states for taking the rain','The monsoon is a shared, deeply personal concern — its absence is felt as a loss by the community','The mother thinks rain can travel from state to state','The question shows that the mother is confused','B',3,0,0,3),(785,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','''The prodigal son has found his way home.'' The author uses this Biblical metaphor for the arriving monsoon. What does this comparison suggest?','The rain had gone to a distant place and returned after a long absence, just like the prodigal son','The author is religious','The rain is like a wayward child who caused trouble','The monsoon was never expected to return','A',3,0,0,3),(786,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author writes that the rain ''beckons me into its arms.'' This is an example of which literary device?','Simile','Onomatopoeia','Personification — rain is given the human action of beckoning with arms','Alliteration','C',3,0,0,3),(787,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author describes asking about rain as ''not a conversation filler'' but a ''genuine query.'' What does this distinction reveal about the role of the monsoon in Kerala?','Conversation fillers are rude in Kerala culture','The monsoon is not merely a weather topic but a matter of survival — affecting roofs, paths, power, and the water table','The author prefers direct communication','The author''s parents are farmers','B',4,0,0,4),(788,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The article blends personal experience (the author''s visit) with environmental observation (low water tables, concrete monstrosities). What is the effect of this combination?','It makes the article confusing','The personal dimension makes the environmental crisis emotionally immediate, while the observational detail gives it journalistic weight','The environmental facts make the personal story less interesting','The article loses focus by mixing genres','B',4,0,0,4),(789,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author mentions paying Rs 400 for a small tanker of water in Bangalore to supplement the borewell. Why does she include this detail in an article about Kerala''s monsoon?','To show that Bangalore is more expensive than Kerala','As a warning of what Kerala will face if deforestation and concrete construction continue to reduce rainfall and water tables','To prove that she is wealthy','To compare city and village life styles','B',4,0,0,4),(790,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The article uses the Kerala month ''Karkitakam'' as a reference point. On the first day of Karkitakam, only ''a minor spell of reluctant rain'' fell. Why is this significant?','Karkitakam is the driest month in Kerala','Karkitakam is the month when ''sheets of rain ought to be falling as if the end of the world was drawing near'' — its failure is a sharp sign of the monsoon''s absence','The first day of Karkitakam is a public holiday in Kerala','Karkitakam is named after the monsoon season','B',4,0,0,4),(791,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author uses Carnatic music terminology (vilamba kaalam, madhyama kaalam, dhrutha kaalam) to describe the rhythm of the rain. What is the effect of this choice?','It shows the author studied music','It makes the article difficult to understand','It is a cultural code-switching technique that connects the rain to Kerala''s classical artistic heritage — the monsoon becomes a musical performance','It is a translation error','C',4,0,0,4),(792,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The title ''Waiting for Rain'' captures both a literal and a figurative meaning. What is the figurative meaning?','The author is waiting for a storm to pass','The article is about water conservation','Waiting for rain represents a broader human yearning — for renewal, relief from drought, and the return of something deeply valued that has been absent too long','The title refers to the delay at Kochi airport','C',4,0,0,4),(793,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','Compare ''Sea-Fever'' and ''Waiting for Rain.'' Both texts describe an intense longing for a natural element. What is the key difference in HOW the longing is resolved?','In ''Sea-Fever'' the sailor never reaches the sea; in ''Waiting for Rain'' the rain never comes','In ''Sea-Fever'' the longing is hypothetical — it has not yet been fulfilled; in ''Waiting for Rain'' the rain actually arrives at 2 am','Both longing are resolved in the same way','''Sea-Fever'' is about nature, ''Waiting for Rain'' is about climate change','B',4,0,0,4),(794,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The article warns: ''Build a few more concrete monstrosities, tile some more front yards, and cut down more trees, and in a decade''s time... you will be paying for water.'' What is the rhetorical device used in this passage?','Flashback','Understatement','A direct address to the reader using second person (''you'') and a conditional warning — if-then reasoning meant to frighten the reader into action','Irony','C',5,0,0,5),(795,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','A student says ''Waiting for Rain is just a personal travel diary about a visit to Kerala.'' A more complete reading would recognise that:','The article is entirely fictional','The personal narrative is a vehicle for an urgent environmental message about the relationship between human actions and monsoon failure','The article is primarily about Carnatic music','The student is correct — it has no broader significance','B',5,0,0,5),(796,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author ends by sitting on the verandah, watching the rain, ''afraid to even sigh in pleasure, for I might frighten it away.'' The ending is effective because:','It describes a common fear of rain','It resolves all the tension of the article with a rainstorm','It captures the paradox of the monsoon experience: even when it arrives, its fragility makes the joy tentative — the anxiety of waiting does not fully end with arrival','The author is superstitious','C',5,0,0,5),(797,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The article uses transliteration when the uncle says ''kaati-kooti poova.'' What does this technique add to the article?','It makes the article difficult to read','It is a translation error from Malayalam','It evokes the authentic voice and cultural context of the uncle — the Malayalam phrase captures a nuance that no English translation could fully convey','It shows the uncle cannot speak English','C',5,0,0,5),(798,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The author visited Kerala ''to renew my acquaintance with the monsoon,'' a phrase that personifies the monsoon as an old friend. Reading the whole article, which quality of the monsoon most justifies this personification?','The monsoon is predictable like a friend','Like a person, the monsoon has moods — it delays, disappoints, makes a dramatic entrance, and ultimately arrives in the early morning like a loved one returning home','The monsoon brings gifts like a friend','Personification is used only for literary effect','B',5,0,0,5),(799,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','Three pieces in Unit III describe three different types of exploration: sea (Sea-Fever), city service (Tiffin Carriers), and return to nature (Waiting for Rain). What common value do all three share?','All three texts are about physical adventure','All three texts are written by Indian authors','All three celebrate a human need to go beyond the ordinary — whether into the sea, into an organisational challenge, or into a monsoon-soaked village — and find something essential there','All three texts are about disappointment','C',5,0,0,5),(800,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'III','Aspire and Explore',10,'Waiting for Rain','The monsoon finally arrives at 2 am, and the author says ''the magic of the monsoon resonates in me as a sense of well-being. For now, the world is a beautiful place.'' Why does she add ''for now''?','She knows the rain will become a flood','She is uncertain if the rain will last until morning','''For now'' acknowledges that the beauty is temporary — the monsoon is still unreliable, and the environmental concerns remain; the sense of well-being is precious precisely because it is fleeting','She is tired and wants to go back to sleep','C',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (801,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What colour was the school uniform worn by the narrator in ''Half a Day''?','Green','Blue','Black','Red','A',1,0,0,1),(802,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What colour was the narrator''s tarboosh (hat) in ''Half a Day''?','Red','Green','Blue','Black','A',1,0,0,1),(803,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','Who wrote the story ''Half a Day''?','Selma Lagerlof','Naguib Mahfouz','Mahadev Desai','Wislawa Szymborska','B',1,0,0,1),(804,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','How does the narrator''s father describe school in ''Half a Day''?','The factory that makes useful people out of children','A garden of knowledge','A prison for disobedient children','A fortress of learning','A',1,0,0,1),(805,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','Where was the narrator''s mother standing when he and his father left for school?','At the school gate','On the street','At the front door','At the window','D',1,0,0,1),(806,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What does the young lad from the ironing shop call the narrator at the end of the story?','Grandpa','Uncle','Sir','Father','A',1,0,0,1),(807,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What is the name of the street the narrator must cross at the end of ''Half a Day''?','Abu Khoda','Tahrir','Al-Azhar','Al-Rashid','A',1,0,0,1),(808,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What colour were the narrator''s shoes on his first day of school?','Brown','White','Red','Black','D',1,0,0,1),(809,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','Why did the narrator have mixed feelings about his new clothes on the first day of school?','The day was not a feast but his first day at school','The clothes were too tight','His mother had not chosen them','The clothes were borrowed from a friend','A',2,0,0,2),(810,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','How does the narrator describe the school building when he first sees it from a distance?','A colourful and welcoming building','A huge high-walled fortress, stern and grim','A small cottage with a friendly garden','A bright modern structure','B',2,0,0,2),(811,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','How did the narrator feel when the school gate closed behind him on the first day?','Like a stranger who had lost his way','Angry at his father','Excited to be starting school','Happy to have arrived','A',2,0,0,2),(812,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','Which of the following is NOT mentioned as part of the school''s ''rich variety''?','Drawing and painting','The music room','Playing swings and the vaulting horse','Seeing a globe of the Earth','A',2,0,0,2),(813,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What did the woman say to comfort the children on their first day at school?','''Your parents will return very soon''','''School is easy and very enjoyable''','''Stop crying or you will be punished''','''This is your new home — here too there are mothers and fathers''','D',2,0,0,2),(814,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','How did the narrator feel after submitting to school life?','A sort of contentment','Angry and resentful','Lonely and lost','Afraid of the teachers','A',2,0,0,2),(815,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What happened to the street lined with gardens when the narrator left school at the end of the day?','It was flooded','It remained the same as in the morning','It was being repaired by workers','High buildings had taken over and it surged with people','D',2,0,0,2),(816,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What was the narrator trying to do at the crossroads at the end of the story when the young lad approached him?','Find his father','Cross the street to reach his house','Buy food from a shop','Return to the school','B',2,0,0,2),(817,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The shift from ''I'' to ''we'' in the narrator''s account of school life most likely represents:','The narrator''s sense of belonging to the school community','The narrator growing confused about events','A different narrator taking over','A grammatical error in the original','A',3,0,0,3),(818,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The ending of ''Half a Day,'' where the narrator is helped across the street and called ''Grandpa,'' most strongly suggests:','A whole lifetime has passed during the narrator''s time at school','Cairo streets are too dangerous to cross alone','The narrator forgot his way home','The narrator pretended to be elderly','A',3,0,0,3),(819,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The ''dust-laden winds and unexpected accidents'' mentioned during school life best symbolise:','Bad weather conditions in Cairo','Poor maintenance of the school building','Rivalry and physical punishment at school','The real hardships and challenges of life','D',3,0,0,3),(820,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The father''s words ''Today you truly begin life'' reveal his belief that:','Home life is not real life','School is the true starting point of a person''s life journey','He dislikes staying at home','The narrator needed to be toughened up','B',3,0,0,3),(821,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','When the father uses the question tag ''I''m not punishing you, am I?'' he is primarily:','Seeking confirmation from the listener','Offering the boy a choice','Expressing strong anger','Being sarcastic','A',3,0,0,3),(822,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The narrator feels contentment at school because ''living beings are drawn to other living beings.'' This line explains why he:','Made friends and formed attachments at school','Wanted to return home','Loved the animals in the school garden','Feared the other children','A',3,0,0,3),(823,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','''I proceeded a few steps, then came to a startled halt.'' The narrator is startled because:','He discovered that the familiar street had been completely transformed','He heard a fire engine','He saw his father ahead','He realised he had left his bag at school','A',3,0,0,3),(824,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The narrator being helped across the road by a young lad who calls him ''Grandpa'' confirms that:','The narrator has grown very old','The narrator is afraid of traffic','The narrator is visiting Cairo for the first time','The narrator pretended to need help','A',3,0,0,3),(825,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','Which pair of details BEST supports the reading that the story compresses a whole lifetime into one school day?','The new clothes and the tarboosh','The gate screeching and the children crying','The street lined with gardens and the school building','The narrator going to school as a young boy and returning as someone called ''Grandpa''','D',4,0,0,4),(826,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The story begins and ends with the narrator holding another person''s hand. What comment does this circular structure make about human life?','Cairo streets require guides at all times','Human life moves from childhood dependence to a new dependence in old age','Children and old people both need companions to cross roads','Fathers and strangers behave similarly toward the narrator','B',4,0,0,4),(827,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The father''s ''Be bold. Today you truly begin life'' and the lad''s ''Grandpa, let me take you across'' together suggest that life:','Begins and ends with the guidance of others','Is full of kind strangers','Requires constant help at every stage','In Cairo is particularly difficult','A',4,0,0,4),(828,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','Naguib Mahfouz does not name the narrator or specify the city precisely. The most likely reason is:','To make the story a universal parable about all human lives','The story is based on a real person who wanted privacy','He forgot to add these details','Egyptian literary tradition does not use character names','A',4,0,0,4),(829,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','''Good God! I was in a daze. My head spun.'' In the story''s context, the narrator''s disorientation is best understood as:','A sign that the narrator is unwell','The confusion of someone who has aged a whole lifetime without realising it','A realistic reaction to noise in Cairo','The narrator being overwhelmed by a long school day','B',4,0,0,4),(830,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The narrator says ''My misgivings had had no basis.'' Which tense is used in this clause and what does it indicate?','Past perfect; the misgivings existed earlier and were resolved by the time he made this realisation','Present perfect; an ongoing state','Simple past; an action happening right now','Future perfect; an action yet to be completed','A',4,0,0,4),(831,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','In Nainika''s retelling, she writes ''He was being watched by his mother'' instead of ''My mother stood at the window watching us.'' This change from the original represents:','Passive voice, shifting focus from the doer to the action','Active voice past continuous','Simple present tense','Past perfect tense','A',4,0,0,4),(832,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The description of the school as initially ''stern and grim'' and later as having ''rich variety'' is an example of which narrative technique?','Flashback','Foreshadowing','Stream of consciousness','The narrator''s changing perspective as he overcomes fear through experience','D',4,0,0,4),(833,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The title ''Half a Day'' is ironic because:','The story actually compresses an entire lifetime into one school day','The narrator enjoyed only half the day','The school day ended at noon','Half a day is not enough time to learn anything useful','A',5,0,0,5),(834,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','What evidence from the text most directly challenges a purely realistic reading of ''Half a Day'' as a single school day?','The middle-aged man greeting him as a long-lost acquaintance and the lad calling him ''Grandpa'' — both impossible in one real day','The mother watching from the window','The school has many activities for children','The father''s advice before the school gate','A',5,0,0,5),(835,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The climax — the narrator stranded at the crossroads until a young lad helps him — works simultaneously on two levels. These are:','A social commentary on roads and a personal memory','Realistic old age needing help, and the symbolic completion of the life cycle back to the dependence of childhood','A criticism of Egyptian urban planning and an observation about kindness','The narrator''s impatience and the lad''s generosity','B',5,0,0,5),(836,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','''How could all this have happened in half a day?'' The narrator asks this with apparent bewilderment. A careful reader understands this question as:','The key question the whole story poses: ''half a day'' is a metaphor for a lifetime','Evidence that the narrator has a memory disorder','A comment about Egyptian urban development','A rhetorical question about noise pollution','A',5,0,0,5),(837,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The woman at school says ''Dry your tears and face life joyfully.'' What is the deeper irony of these words in the context of the story''s theme?','These words foreshadow the whole life the narrator is about to live, since ''school'' IS life in this story','The woman does not truly care about the children','The school day is not actually joyful','There is no irony — the advice is straightforward','A',5,0,0,5),(838,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','A student argues: ''The story is really about education and how school changes people.'' Which aspect of the story most strongly points beyond this reading to a deeper theme?','The compression of a whole human lifetime — from birth to old age — into the span of a single school day','The school activities: music, globe, games','The emphasis on new clothes and the father''s advice','The description of the school building as a fortress','A',5,0,0,5),(839,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','The compound adjective ''dust-laden'' in ''Half a Day'' is used to describe:','The narrator''s new school uniform','The winds that bring difficulty and challenge to school life','The street outside the school','The narrator''s mood when leaving school','B',5,0,0,5),(840,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Half a Day','At the start, the narrator holds his father''s hand going to school; at the end, a stranger holds his hand crossing the road. Which statement best explains the thematic significance of this parallel?','It shows that Cairo is dangerous at all ages','It shows that fathers and strangers are equally kind','It highlights the narrator''s fear throughout life','The parallel encapsulates the full arc of human life: dependence in childhood, activity in middle, dependence again in old age','D',5,0,0,5),(841,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Who wrote the speech ''Debts of Gratitude''?','Naguib Mahfouz','Selma Lagerlof','Mahadev Desai','Gcina Mhlope','B',1,0,0,1),(842,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','For what occasion was Selma Lagerlof travelling to Stockholm?','To sit an important examination','To visit her mother who was ill','To attend a literary conference','To receive the Nobel Prize in Literature','D',1,0,0,1),(843,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','In her daydream, where does Selma imagine meeting her father?','In Paradise','At a railway station','In their old home in Sweden','In a Stockholm garden','A',1,0,0,1),(844,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','In what year was Selma Lagerlof awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature?','1900','1905','1915','1909','D',1,0,0,1),(845,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','What was Selma''s father doing in the rocking chair in her daydream?','Sleeping peacefully','Knitting','Writing letters','Reading','D',1,0,0,1),(846,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma Lagerlof was the first woman to be granted a membership in which prestigious body?','The British Academy','The Royal Society of Literature','The French Academy','The Swedish Academy','D',1,0,0,1),(847,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Who is Esselde, mentioned in Selma Lagerlof''s speech?','Selma''s younger sister','Her faithful friend who opened doors when no one believed in her','Her publisher','A fellow Nobel laureate','B',1,0,0,1),(848,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','What does Selma''s father initially say when she claims to be heavily in debt?','''I will lend you whatever you need''','''This place has everything except money''','''You should ask the Academy for help''','''I am too old to help anyone now''','B',2,0,0,2),(849,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Which literary figures does Selma mention as creating her first debt to her father?','Shakespeare and Dickens','Rousseau and Victor Hugo','Bellman and Strindberg','Tegner, Runeberg, and Andersen','D',2,0,0,2),(850,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Why did Selma feel deep sorrow as she travelled to Stockholm?','She was feeling very unwell','She did not want to receive the prize','Her father was no longer alive to share her joy','She had forgotten her prepared speech','C',2,0,0,2),(851,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','''The coaches no longer seemed to run on rails and sleepers, but to glide into space.'' This line describes Selma:','Being frightened by the train''s speed','Falling deeply asleep on the train','Entering a peaceful, dreamlike state','Believing the train had broken down','C',2,0,0,2),(852,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','What debt does Selma owe to the ''poor, homeless vagabonds'' she mentions?','Money for sheltering her during travels','A published story she wrote about them','A letter of thanks she never sent','Their mischief, pranks, and songs, which inspired her writing','D',2,0,0,2),(853,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Which of the following is NOT listed as a source of Selma''s debt of gratitude in the speech?','Old men and women in small grey cottages telling stories','The animals, birds, trees, and flowers of nature','Financial support from the Swedish Academy','Her readers, both those who praised and those who criticised her','C',2,0,0,2),(854,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','''A look of wonder will come into his eyes'' when the father hears of Selma''s literary debts. This wonder is most likely because:','He did not know his daughter had become a writer','He is surprised she still remembers their childhood','He is moved to realise that the seeds of literature he planted bore such great fruit','He is confused by her indirect approach','C',2,0,0,2),(855,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','When Selma tells her father she is ''very heavily in debt,'' she is using an indirect approach. What is she really building up to?','Asking for financial help from her father','Apologising for not visiting more often','Testing whether he still remembers their past','Revealing the Nobel Prize as the ultimate, unpayable debt of gratitude','D',3,0,0,3),(856,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma says she owes gratitude to critics for their censure as well as their praise. This reveals that:','She was deeply hurt by negative reviews','Even criticism helped her grow and improve as a writer','She is being sarcastic about critics','She ignored all critical reviews of her work','B',3,0,0,3),(857,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','''They have shown that they have trust enough in me to single me out before the whole world.'' The ''they'' refers to:','Her faithful readers','Her friends and family','The Swedish Academy','The vagabonds who inspired her','C',3,0,0,3),(858,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma says nature told her ''some of their secrets.'' In the context of the speech, this most likely means:','She literally communicated with animals in the wild','Her deep contact with nature gave her inspiration and material for her writing','She studied natural science seriously','She lived alone in a forest for many years','B',3,0,0,3),(859,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Father says ''I am glad that I got you into this debt.'' What does he mean?','He is happy she owes him money','He wants her to repay the debt immediately','He regrets encouraging her interest in literature','He is pleased that introducing her to literature created such meaningful, lifelong gratitude','D',3,0,0,3),(860,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','When Selma reveals the Nobel Prize, ''every wrinkle in his face will tremble and tears will come into his eyes.'' These tears represent:','Sadness that he missed the ceremony in Stockholm','Tears of overwhelming joy and pride in his daughter','Regret that he did not support her enough','Relief that all her financial debts will now be paid','B',3,0,0,3),(861,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma says she owes debts to ''foreign lands who have worked for me.'' This most likely refers to:','Foreign governments that financially supported her','Countries she visited on literary tours','Translators and international promoters of her work','Foreign students who studied her books','C',3,0,0,3),(862,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','The train journey frames the speech by providing:','The climax of the entire speech','Comic relief from the serious theme','Historical information about Swedish trains','A real-world setting that transitions naturally into the dreamlike meeting with her father','D',4,0,0,4),(863,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma lists debts to literature, vagabonds, storytellers, nature, friends, and readers. The single idea unifying all these debts is:','They are all financial debts to be repaid','They all shaped and enriched her as a writer and human being','They are all Swedish cultural influences','They all required a formal written acknowledgement','B',4,0,0,4),(864,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma reveals her debts in deliberate order, from small to greatest. The rhetorical effect of this escalating structure is to:','List her works in chronological order','Delay the speech unnecessarily','Build suspense, ultimately arriving at the Nobel Prize as the ultimate unpayable debt','Test the patience of the audience','C',4,0,0,4),(865,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Father responds to the Nobel Prize with ''I am too happy that you have been given the Nobel Prize to worry about anything!'' This response reveals:','He does not take debts seriously at all','He is too old to think about solutions','He accepts that some debts of gratitude are too great to solve — pure joy overrides the need for resolution','He dislikes the idea of the Nobel Prize','C',4,0,0,4),(866,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','The contrast between Selma''s daydream of her father in Paradise and the actual Stockholm banquet setting reveals:','That Selma prefers dreams to reality','That Stockholm is less beautiful than Paradise','That the most meaningful imagined conversation about her achievement happens with her deceased father','That Selma was very homesick during the ceremony','C',4,0,0,4),(867,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Both ''Half a Day'' and ''Debts of Gratitude'' use an unusual narrative device. In ''Debts of Gratitude,'' the daydream allows Selma to:','Describe Swedish train travel vividly','Introduce the other Nobel laureates','Show that Selma is mentally unstable','Express gratitude to her deceased father, whom she cannot reach in reality','D',4,0,0,4),(868,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','The vagabonds taught Selma ''that there is poetry in hard rocks and black forests.'' This most directly means:','She learned geology from them','Vagabonds wrote poetry about rocks and forests','Hard rocks and black forests are typical Swedish symbols','She discovered beauty and poetic inspiration in overlooked, humble places','D',4,0,0,4),(869,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','The central irony of ''Debts of Gratitude'' is that:','Selma is wealthy but pretends to be in debt','The greatest honour of her life creates an unpayable debt — the Nobel Prize generates gratitude, not just pride','She is not truly grateful to anyone in the speech','Her father is secretly alive and in the audience','B',5,0,0,5),(870,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','A student says ''Selma''s speech is simply a thank-you to people who helped her.'' A more nuanced reading recognises that:','She is actually criticising some people','She is sad throughout the speech','The speech explores the profound idea that gratitude can be so deep it becomes an unpayable debt','The speech is really about money','C',5,0,0,5),(871,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma Lagerlof was the first woman to win the Nobel Prize in Literature, yet she does not directly mention this milestone. The most likely reason is:','She was unaware of this historical fact','The prize was awarded for a non-literary reason','She is focused on gratitude to all who made her journey possible, not on personal historic achievements','She forgot to mention it during the speech','C',5,0,0,5),(872,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','The speech ends with a toast to the Swedish Academy, having received no solution to how the debts can be repaid. This ending is best interpreted as:','Selma is angry with the Academy','A gesture of gratitude even when repayment is impossible — the debt is acknowledged, not resolved','She is disappointed by the ceremony','She is simply following a formal protocol','B',5,0,0,5),(873,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','The recurring structure of Selma revealing one debt and then surprising her father with a deeper one builds to the Nobel Prize. Which statement best explains the purpose of this structure?','It lists her works in chronological order','It tests the audience''s patience before the main point','It mirrors the actual structure of gratitude: each acknowledgement reveals more beneath it','It delays the speech unnecessarily','C',5,0,0,5),(874,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','Selma''s father says ''One may well say of this place that it has everything except money.'' ''This place'' refers to:','The Nobel ceremony hall in Stockholm','Their childhood home in Sweden','The train compartment','Paradise, where she imagines her father is resting','D',5,0,0,5),(875,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Debts of Gratitude','The speech is delivered at the Nobel Prize banquet. The audience Selma addresses — ''Your Majesties, Your Royal Highnesses, Ladies and Gentlemen'' — contrasts sharply with whom she most wants to share the honour. This contrast shows:','That she dislikes formal events','That formal recognition matters more than personal bonds','That the most meaningful recipient of the news — her father — can only be reached in imagination','That Selma is uncomfortable with royalty','C',5,0,0,5),(876,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','Who wrote the poem ''Nothing Twice''?','John Masefield','Henry Wadsworth Longfellow','T. S. Eliot','Wislawa Szymborska','D',1,0,0,1),(877,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','What is the central idea of the poem ''Nothing Twice''?','Every day is exactly the same as yesterday','Nothing in life can ever happen twice','Two people can always relive their shared experiences','Sadness is life''s main feeling','B',1,0,0,1),(878,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','What does the word ''course'' refer to in the second stanza?','A meal served at a banquet','A river''s path','Life itself, offered only once','A school subject to be repeated','C',1,0,0,1),(879,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','To what does the poet compare the feeling of hearing someone mention your name by chance?','A beautiful dream','A gift from a dear friend','A rose flung into the room, all hue and scent','A pleasant memory of childhood','C',1,0,0,1),(880,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','According to the poem, what happens to ''today''?','It leads to a better tomorrow','Today is always gone tomorrow','It comes back stronger','It gets better with each passing day','B',1,0,0,1),(881,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''We arrive here improvised / and leave without the chance to practise.'' What does ''improvised'' mean here?','Fully prepared for every event in life','Skilled and naturally talented','Following a detailed life plan','Unprepared, without prior rehearsal for life','D',2,0,0,2),(882,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''You can''t repeat the class in summer'' most clearly suggests:','Schools close in summer holidays','Life''s experiences cannot be repeated or retaken','Summer is too hot for lessons','Education demands constant effort','B',2,0,0,2),(883,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The clock in the poem most likely symbolises:','The arrival of a friend','Being late for school','The passing of time','Modern technology in daily life','C',2,0,0,2),(884,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''We''re different (we concur) / just as two drops of water are.'' Which literary device is used?','Metaphor','Personification','Alliteration','Simile','D',2,0,0,2),(885,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','Wislawa Szymborska was awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature in which year?','1990','1993','1996','2001','C',2,0,0,2),(886,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The poet says ''this course is only offered once.'' By using the metaphor of a course, she means:','Education has only one chance at success','The school has a limited number of seats','Life, like a unique course, can only be lived once with no chance to repeat','The course is too expensive to redo','C',3,0,0,3),(887,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The rose in stanza 4 creates sudden beauty; in stanza 5 it fades. This movement illustrates:','The poet''s love of flower gardens','That roses are not truly beautiful to everyone','The transience of even the most vivid emotional moments','That memory is always perfectly accurate','C',3,0,0,3),(888,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''Why do we treat the fleeting day / with so much needless fear and sorrow?'' implies the poet is urging us to:','Be afraid of each passing day','Slow down the pace of daily life','Cherish each day rather than waste it with unnecessary fear','Write in a diary every single day','C',3,0,0,3),(889,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''Nothing Twice'' repeats its title as the poem''s opening line. This choice:','Shows the poet ran out of ideas for a beginning','Fills space at the start of the poem','Emphasises the central theme through structural repetition','Creates an accidental rhyme','C',3,0,0,3),(890,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''With smiles and kisses, we prefer / to seek accord.'' This suggests that humans, despite their uniqueness:','Cannot get along with each other','Prefer to remain isolated','Naturally seek connection and harmony even in a transient world','Fear other people deeply','C',3,0,0,3),(891,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','How does ''Nothing Twice'' connect thematically to ''Half a Day''?','Both are set in the same country','Both feature school settings as the main backdrop','Both explore the irreversibility of time and the uniqueness of each moment in life','Both are about childhood friendships and their loss','C',4,0,0,4),(892,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The poem''s tone moves from matter-of-fact statements in early stanzas to a warmer ending with ''smiles and kisses.'' What does this tonal shift suggest?','The poet changes her mind halfway through','Accepting the transience of life leads to a greater appreciation of human connection','The ending is unrelated to the rest of the poem','The poet is describing two completely different topics','B',4,0,0,4),(893,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''We arrive here improvised / and leave without the chance to practise'' uses the metaphor of a performance. How does this fit the poem''s theme?','Life is like a school rehearsal that can be repeated','An unrehearsed performance perfectly captures the idea that life is unique and unrepeatable','People should rehearse for all important events','Improvised performances are always stressful','B',4,0,0,4),(894,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The poem uses the paradox that two drops of water look the same but are different. In the context of the poem, this paradox suggests:','People are all actually the same beneath the surface','Each person''s life experience is unique, even when people appear similar from the outside','Water is the best symbol for human sameness','People should be treated equally under the law','B',4,0,0,4),(895,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The poem''s regular ABAB rhyme scheme creates order, while the theme is about unique and unrepeatable moments. How do these interact?','They do not interact at all','The rhyme scheme reinforces the poem''s message of chaos','The rhyme scheme has no deliberate meaning','The stable poetic form contrasts with the message that life''s moments are fluid and unrepeatable','D',4,0,0,4),(896,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','A student says ''Nothing Twice is a sad poem because nothing can be repeated.'' A more complete reading would recognise that:','The poem is entirely sad throughout','The poem uses the irreversibility of time to argue for cherishing each moment rather than fearing its loss','The poem has no clear emotional direction','The poem is really about the beauty of roses','B',5,0,0,5),(897,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','''A rose? A rose? What could that be? / Is it a flower or a rock?'' These lines best demonstrate:','The poet cannot identify a rose','The rapid fading of an intense emotional sensation — what felt beautiful vanishes into confusion','That metaphors are always confusing to readers','The poet is testing the reader''s attention deliberately','B',5,0,0,5),(898,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','Which interpretation of ''With smiles and kisses, we prefer / to seek accord beneath our star'' is most supported by the whole poem?','The poet is describing one specific love affair','The poet is arguing against romantic relationships','Despite each person''s uniqueness and the unrepeatable nature of time, humans naturally seek love and connection','Smiles are more important than any kind of hard work','C',5,0,0,5),(899,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The poem''s final stanza is the most hopeful in the poem. Why?','It promises that time will slow down','It says tomorrow will be better than today','It suggests that even in a world of irreversible moments, humans can still find meaningful connection','It proves that nothing bad will happen','C',5,0,0,5),(900,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'I','Hours and Years',8,'Nothing Twice','The poem opens by stating ''Nothing can ever happen twice.'' A student claims this is a flaw because ''the sun rises every day.'' The poem''s best reply to this objection is:','The sun is not mentioned in the poem','The poem refers only to human events, not natural ones','The student is correct; the poem is factually wrong','No — each sunrise is experienced by a different person in a different moment, making it unique','D',5,0,0,5),(901,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Who wrote ''Dreams Realised''?','Mahadev Desai','Gcina Mhlope','Selma Lagerlof','Naguib Mahfouz','A',1,0,0,1),(902,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Who organised a reception for Gandhiji as the ''spiritual ambassador of India'' during his visit to England?','The students of Germany','The Indian community in London','The women of England','The students of France','D',1,0,0,1),(903,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','According to Gandhiji, in which two things should every nation be self-contained?','Education and defence','Technology and trade','Agriculture and industry','Cloth and food','D',1,0,0,1),(904,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','At which hall did Gandhiji address the Women''s India Council?','Victoria Hall','Oxford Union Hall','Hyde Park Hall','Morley College Hall','D',1,0,0,1),(905,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','What was Mahadev Desai''s role in relation to Mahatma Gandhi?','His personal secretary','His doctor','His lawyer','His son','A',1,0,0,1),(906,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','What is the full title of the collection from which ''Dreams Realised'' is excerpted?','The Complete Works of Gandhi','The Spirit of India','India Speaks to the World','The Nation''s Voice','D',1,0,0,1),(907,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Which celebrity is mentioned as having wanted to meet Gandhiji during his England visit?','George Bernard Shaw','Bertrand Russell','H. G. Wells','Charlie Chaplin','D',1,0,0,1),(908,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji first visited France as a student to see the Exhibition in Paris in which year?','1890','1885','1880','1895','A',1,0,0,1),(909,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','According to Gandhiji, non-violence is NOT a weapon of the weak but of:','The strongest','The young','The educated','The wealthy','A',2,0,0,2),(910,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji said that real education consists of:','Developing character','Passing examinations by reading numerous books','Packing the brain with facts and figures','Learning many foreign languages','A',2,0,0,2),(911,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','What was the first question Charlie Chaplin asked Gandhiji?','Why Gandhiji wore such simple clothes','What Gandhiji thought of Western cinema','How long Gandhiji would stay in England','Why Gandhiji was against machinery','D',2,0,0,2),(912,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji''s reaction when first told Charlie Chaplin wanted to meet him was:','He innocently asked who that distinguished person was','Refusal, as he was too busy','Excitement, as he was a great fan','He asked his secretary to arrange it immediately','A',2,0,0,2),(913,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','According to Gandhiji, what had Indian women done during the freedom struggle when organisations were declared illegal?','They helped organise secret meetings','They boycotted British goods','They sent petitions to the British government','They came to the forefront and filled the jails','D',2,0,0,2),(914,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','What does Gandhiji say about strength in the context of non-violence?','Strength of muscle is essential','Only the young can be truly strong','Both mental and physical strength are equally needed','A strong heart is an absolute necessity, not muscular strength','D',2,0,0,2),(915,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji said at the Round Table Conference: ''If I want freedom for my country... I do not want that freedom in order that I may:''','Exploit any other race upon earth or any single individual','Establish trade with Europe','Become a world leader','Build a powerful army','A',2,0,0,2),(916,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Which method did Gandhiji use to achieve independence, according to the passage?','Unwavering non-violence and non-cooperation','Diplomatic negotiations only','Violent armed resistance','Economic boycott without any non-cooperation','A',2,0,0,2),(917,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji argued for the spinning wheel by explaining that it would:','Restore employment to the six months of unemployment of India''s peasant population','Replace all machinery in India','Produce cloth for export to England','Demonstrate Indian cultural superiority','A',3,0,0,3),(918,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji told Chaplin he was against machinery not because machinery is bad, but because:','Indian workers were not skilled enough','It was an old Indian tradition to avoid machines','Machines had destroyed Indian cottage industries','Millions of Indian peasants were unemployed and the spinning wheel would restore them','D',3,0,0,3),(919,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Why was Gandhiji in England during the events described in ''Dreams Realised''?','To study English law','On a private family visit','To receive a literary award','On a diplomatic and political mission related to Indian independence','D',3,0,0,3),(920,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji said ''There is no such thing as a gift of independence from one nation to another.'' This statement means:','Independence must be earned, not given','India was not yet ready for independence','Britain was too powerful to grant independence','Independence should be delayed','A',3,0,0,3),(921,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The passage describes unlettered women who ''bore lathi blows to the head, bleeding profusely whilst standing unflinchingly.'' This detail is used to:','Demonstrate that ordinary, uneducated women were as brave as educated leaders','Show that education is necessary for bravery','Criticise the British use of violence','Suggest that Sarojini Naidu was more important than other women','A',3,0,0,3),(922,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','What was the significance of Chaplin coming ''from the people and living for the people'' to Gandhiji?','It meant Chaplin was poor like Indian peasants','It proved Chaplin was educated','It showed Chaplin was a fellow freedom fighter','It was the quality that made Gandhiji willing to meet him','D',3,0,0,3),(923,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji said ''I have come as a result of last year''s suffering.'' He meant that:','The suffering of the Indians had driven him to persist in the independence mission','He was visiting England to rest','He was ill from the suffering','He was angry with the British government','A',3,0,0,3),(924,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The passage calls the Indian women''s awakening ''miraculous.'' This word is used to mean:','Surprising and wonderful — far beyond what was expected','Planned and organised in advance','Supernatural or involving magic','Violent and sudden','A',3,0,0,3),(925,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji describes non-violence as requiring a ''strong heart'' rather than muscular strength. What does this reveal about his philosophy?','Non-violence demands a courage and endurance that is greater than physical fighting','Only soldiers can be truly non-violent','Physical fitness is unimportant in the freedom struggle','Non-violence is only for the weak','A',4,0,0,4),(926,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji says real education must develop character. How does this idea connect to his campaign for Indian independence?','Without character, non-violence becomes a ''profitless study'' — character is the foundation of the movement','Memorising facts helps in court battles','Educated people make better soldiers','Education in English schools would benefit Indians','A',4,0,0,4),(927,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji corrected ''various notions about the women of India'' at the Women''s India Council. What does this act reveal about his broader goals?','He wanted to embarrass the British','He was promoting Indian women to take jobs in England','He was responding to a personal insult','He sought to correct Western misunderstandings of India and show the full dignity of Indian people','D',4,0,0,4),(928,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Compare Gandhiji''s concept of independence — ''I am not here to beg for independence'' — with a conventional political approach. What is distinctive about his stance?','He presents independence not as a gift to be requested but as an inevitable result of self-sacrifice','He demands rights by force','He is more aggressive than conventional politicians','He is more patient than other politicians','A',4,0,0,4),(929,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The meeting between Gandhiji and Chaplin is described in detail in the passage. What is the broader significance of this meeting?','It showed that Gandhiji liked Western films','It was a publicity stunt arranged by Gandhiji''s secretary','It proved that Chaplin supported Indian independence','It demonstrated that Gandhiji''s fame had spread to the cultural world, not just the political world','D',4,0,0,4),(930,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The passage describes Gandhiji''s ''inimitable method.'' The word ''inimitable'' means it was:','So unique that it could not be imitated or replicated','Violent and aggressive','Often copied by other leaders','Taught in Indian schools','A',4,0,0,4),(931,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji addressed both political committees and women''s organisations during his England visit. What does this range of engagements reveal about his approach to the independence mission?','He was unfocused in his activities','He was following his secretary''s schedule','He was more interested in social issues than politics','He engaged every segment of society — political, cultural, and social — to build broad support','D',4,0,0,4),(932,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The phrase ''exploitation-blinded West'' suggests that Gandhiji''s visit to England was seen as:','A sign of Indian weakness','A diplomatic compromise','An attempt to copy Western culture','Bringing moral clarity to a West blinded by colonial exploitation','D',4,0,0,4),(933,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji says ''we shall continue the process of self-sacrifice until at last no Britisher will want to remain in India as a ruler.'' This strategy is based on the idea that:','Britain will eventually be forced out by military resistance','Economic collapse will drive the British out','International pressure will force Britain to leave','Sustained self-sacrifice will make British rule morally and practically untenable','D',5,0,0,5),(934,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','A student argues that Gandhiji''s opposition to machinery was backward-looking. Which evidence from the passage best counters this?','Gandhiji met Charlie Chaplin, showing openness to Western culture','Gandhiji said character is more important than knowledge','Gandhiji said cloth and food should be self-contained','Gandhiji was not opposed to all machinery but specifically to machinery that created mass unemployment among Indian peasants','D',5,0,0,5),(935,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji''s concept of independence includes the line ''I do not want that freedom in order that I may exploit any other race.'' This reveals that his concept of freedom was:','Universal — freedom without exploitation of others — not merely political self-rule','Based on revenge against the British','Purely nationalistic and focused only on India','Economic and focused on trade','A',5,0,0,5),(936,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The passage calls Gandhiji ''a healing balm to war-weary Europe.'' What makes this a particularly apt metaphor in the historical context of his 1931 visit to England?','The First World War had ended only 13 years before, and Europe was still traumatised — Gandhiji''s message of non-violence offered moral healing','England was experiencing a terrible economic recession','Gandhiji was a trained medical doctor','Europe was suffering from a disease epidemic','A',5,0,0,5),(937,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Both Gandhiji and Selma Lagerlof (in ''Debts of Gratitude'') speak about owing debts — to people and to a cause. What distinguishes Gandhiji''s sense of debt?','Gandhiji''s debt is financial and practical','Gandhiji does not mention debts in the passage','Selma''s debt is larger and more significant','Gandhiji''s debt is to suffering people and to the cause of freedom, making it a political and moral obligation rather than personal gratitude','D',5,0,0,5),(938,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The passage notes that Gandhiji was accompanied by Mahadev Desai, who later described these events. What does Desai''s role as both participant and chronicler add to the account?','Being Gandhi''s personal secretary and close observer, Desai provides an eyewitness authenticity','It adds a fictional dimension to the events','It makes the account biased and unreliable','It removes Gandhiji''s direct voice from the account','A',5,0,0,5),(939,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','Gandhiji says ''to stand the blows of your adversaries and not to retaliate is a greater form of bravery.'' In terms of argument structure, this claim:','Is a personal opinion with no logical basis','Redefines bravery, raising the moral bar — enduring without retaliation requires more courage than fighting back','Contradicts his later call for self-sacrifice','Shows that Gandhiji is afraid of physical conflict','B',5,0,0,5),(940,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Dreams Realised','The unit''s epigraph is Dr A. P. J. Abdul Kalam''s quote: ''I realise a small aim is a crime.'' How does Gandhiji''s vision of independence in ''Dreams Realised'' best illustrate this idea?','Gandhiji''s vision extended beyond Indian freedom to a world without exploitation of any race — a large, universal aim','Gandhiji aimed only to revive the spinning wheel','Gandhiji aimed only to free India from British rule','Gandhiji''s aim was small: to attend meetings in England','A',5,0,0,5),(941,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Who wrote the memoir ''The Toilet''?','Anita Nair','Gcina Mhlope','Wislawa Szymborska','Selma Lagerlof','B',1,0,0,1),(942,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','In which city does the narrator of ''The Toilet'' stay with her sister?','Johannesburg','Durban','Cape Town','Pretoria','A',1,0,0,1),(943,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Where did the narrator''s sister work?','In a hotel in Johannesburg','In Orange Grove as a domestic worker','In a clothing factory','In a school','B',1,0,0,1),(944,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','At what time did the narrator need to leave the house each morning?','By five-thirty','Five o''clock','Four o''clock','Six o''clock','A',1,0,0,1),(945,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','What time was the bus the narrator took to work?','Seven-thirty','Seven o''clock','Six-thirty','Eight o''clock','A',1,0,0,1),(946,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','From 2019, which date is recognised as National Storytelling Day in South Africa in honour of Gcina Mhlope?','16-Jun','24-Aug','27-Sep','24-Oct','D',1,0,0,1),(947,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','In the story, what does the narrator buy one Friday after becoming the ''toilet''s best customer''?','A pen','A notebook','A magazine','A dictionary','B',1,0,0,1),(948,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','What was the narrator''s English name used by the Madam at the end of the dog episode?','Nomsa','Thandi','Zanele','Irene','D',1,0,0,1),(949,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Why was the narrator locked in her sister''s room on weekdays?','She was being punished for breaking rules','She was ill and needed rest','She had no money for transport','The Madam must not see her, as the sister feared losing her job','D',2,0,0,2),(950,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','How did the narrator first discover the public toilet in the park?','Her sister told her about it','She saw it while waiting for the bus','She found it while exploring the park','She sheltered in it from heavy rain on her way to the bus stop','D',2,0,0,2),(951,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','What quality of the toilet did the narrator particularly enjoy?','It was clean and well-maintained','It was warm in winter','Its small, enclosed space gave her a sense of privacy','It had good lighting for reading','C',2,0,0,2),(952,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Why was the narrator unable to respond to the Madam''s call of ''Ireeeeeene!'' during the dog episode?','She was asleep','She was hiding behind the room','The dogs were standing in front of her with long threatening teeth — any movement felt dangerous','She did not recognise the name','C',2,0,0,2),(953,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','What did the narrator realise on the morning she found the toilet locked?','That she had lost her notebook','That she needed to find a new job','That the toilet was not hers after all','That the park was closing permanently','C',2,0,0,2),(954,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','How did the narrator respond when she found the toilet locked for the first time?','She went back to her sister''s room','She sat on a nearby bench and wrote the story anyway','She waited outside until someone opened it','She gave up writing for the day','B',2,0,0,2),(955,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator says she felt like ''hiding something from her sister.'' What was she hiding?','Money she had saved','Her visits to the public toilet and her writing notebook','A letter from a friend','Her plans to leave Johannesburg','B',2,0,0,2),(956,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','What changes did the narrator notice in the toilet one morning?','A new door had been installed','The door had been painted and a new windowpane had replaced the old broken one','The toilet seat had been replaced','Electric lighting had been added','B',2,0,0,2),(957,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator''s sister was angry after the dog incident. What had the narrator done wrong according to the sister?','She had spoken rudely to the Madam','She had entered the yard alone instead of waiting so they could walk in together','She had scared the dogs','She had let the Madam see her notebook','B',3,0,0,3),(958,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator says ''I just wanted to howl like a dog. I wished somebody would come and be my friend.'' This shows she felt:','Excited about her new writing projects','Angry at her sister for scolding her','Deeply lonely, misunderstood, and in need of emotional support','Ready to return to her home in the Eastern Cape','C',3,0,0,3),(959,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Why did the narrator begin asking herself why she had not written anything since leaving school?','Her sister told her to take up writing again','She found old school magazines in the toilet','The solitude of the toilet triggered reflection on her earlier joy in writing','Her English teacher wrote to her','C',3,0,0,3),(960,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator says ''I didn''t know anything about publishing then, and I didn''t ask myself if my stories were good enough.'' This tells us that her early writing was motivated by:','A desire for fame','Pure enjoyment of writing, without worrying about quality or publication','A need for income','Competition with her schoolmates','B',3,0,0,3),(961,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator had to leave the house before 5:30 am and return only after 6:30 pm. This routine shows:','She was very dedicated to her job','She enjoyed long walks in the city','She was forced to live a secret existence due to the racial restrictions of apartheid South Africa','She was avoiding her sister''s anger','C',3,0,0,3),(962,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator describes the toilet''s small walls as ''wonderfully close to me — it felt like it was made to fit me alone.'' What does this reveal about her situation?','She was physically very small','In her isolated and constrained life, even a tiny enclosed space felt like a gift of privacy','The toilet was custom-built for one person','She preferred small spaces generally','B',3,0,0,3),(963,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','What does the narrator mean by calling the toilet ''my toilet''?','She owned it legally','She had cleaned and maintained it','She paid rent to use it','She had claimed it emotionally as her own private creative space','D',3,0,0,3),(964,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator imagines herself ''in some big hall doing a really popular play with other young actors.'' This daydream represents:','A plan she shared with her sister','Her deep ambition to become an actress or playwright','A play she had already written','A memory from her school years','B',3,0,0,3),(965,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The public toilet in ''The Toilet'' is far from a glamorous setting, yet the narrator writes her first poems and stories there. What does this contrast suggest?','Creativity requires luxury','The narrator had no other options','Creativity can thrive in the most unlikely circumstances when a person has determination','Public toilets are common writing spaces','C',4,0,0,4),(966,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The story is set in apartheid South Africa. How does this historical context explain the narrator''s secret existence at her sister''s employer''s home?','The Madam had a personal dislike of visitors','The narrator was illegally residing in a white suburb under apartheid''s racial restrictions','The narrator had not told her sister she was coming','The employer''s dogs made visitors unwelcome','B',4,0,0,4),(967,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Both Gcina Mhlope and Selma Lagerlof (in ''Debts of Gratitude'') write about the role of early encouragement in their literary journeys. In ''The Toilet,'' who plays this role?','Her sister','Her employer at the clothing factory','The Madam','Her English teacher at school, who encouraged her first poem','D',4,0,0,4),(968,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','On the day the toilet is locked, the narrator accepts ''that the toilet was not hers after all'' and writes on the park bench anyway. What does this moment reveal about her character?','She had given up on the toilet and was moving on','She was angry at the park authorities','Her resilience: even when her private space is lost, the creative impulse cannot be stopped','She preferred writing outdoors','C',4,0,0,4),(969,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator says ''I felt my spirits really lifting as I put on my shoes outside the gate.'' What does this detail — putting on shoes outside the gate — reveal?','She was saving her shoes from rain','The shoes were too tight to wear all day','She carried her shoes to the gate to muffle the sound of her departure — a small detail revealing the constant anxiety of her hidden life','She liked walking barefoot in the mornings','C',4,0,0,4),(970,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Compare the narrator''s options: stay in the room, get a temporary job, or write. The writing emerges as the most significant because:','It earned the most money','It was the one activity she chose for herself, rooted in her own voice and inner life','Her sister approved of it','It was the most practical way to spend time','B',4,0,0,4),(971,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator mentions that she had written in school magazines but stopped after leaving school. The public toilet restores her writing. What does the toilet symbolise in her life?','A reminder of how difficult her life was','A temporary inconvenience','A symbol of the apartheid system','A space of self-determination and creative freedom in a life where she controlled almost nothing else','D',4,0,0,4),(972,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The sister''s reaction to the dog incident (''What were you doing inside in the first place?'') is harsh but understandable in context. Why?','The sister was generally unkind to the narrator','The sister feared the narrator would embarrass her at church','The sister''s job and home were at risk if the Madam discovered she was hiding her sister illegally','The sister owned the dogs and felt responsible','C',4,0,0,4),(973,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The title ''The Toilet'' is deliberately unglamorous. What is the effect of choosing such an ordinary title for a story about literary ambition?','It shows the narrator has no literary taste','It reduces the importance of the narrator''s dreams','It honestly captures the humble, unexpected origin of a major writer''s career — success from the most unlikely of beginnings','It is a mistake that the publisher should have changed','C',5,0,0,5),(974,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','A student argues: ''Mhlope became a writer because she was talented.'' A more complete reading of the memoir would add:','She became a writer by luck','Her talent was essential, but so was her determination to create a private creative space under extremely difficult conditions','She became a writer because her sister encouraged her','She became a writer because her employer gave her free time','B',5,0,0,5),(975,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The memoir ends with the narrator writing a story on a park bench after the toilet is locked. This ending is significant because:','It shows she found a better place to write','It shows she had finished with the toilet','It shows she had truly internalised writing — no longer dependent on any particular space to create','It shows she was angry at the park authorities','C',5,0,0,5),(976,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The Madam spends her days ''painting her nails, having tea with her friends, or lying in the sun by the pool.'' This description is deliberately contrasted with the narrator''s hidden, constrained existence. The contrast reveals:','That the Madam is an evil person','The narrator is jealous of the Madam''s lifestyle','The stark inequality of apartheid South Africa, where race determined access to leisure, space, and freedom','That domestic workers in South Africa had difficult lives','C',5,0,0,5),(977,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The narrator says ''I call it my toilet because that is exactly how I felt about it.'' This sense of ownership over a public space is best understood as:','An act of theft','A sign of immaturity','Emotional and creative ownership — the narrator has made this space hers through the meaning she invested in it','Legal ownership by prolonged use','C',5,0,0,5),(978,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','''The pain you feel today is the strength you have tomorrow.'' Gcina Mhlope''s life in ''The Toilet'' best illustrates this because:','She eventually earned a lot of money from her writing','Her loneliness, isolation, and hardship became the very material and driving force of her writing career','She returned home after a successful year in Johannesburg','Her sister''s anger motivated her to prove herself','B',5,0,0,5),(979,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','The memoir is told in past tense but uses phrases like ''I call it my toilet.'' What does this present-tense intrusion suggest?','The narrator forgot the correct tense','The present tense is used throughout the memoir','The emotional ownership of the toilet persists into the present — the narrator still identifies with that creative space','It is a translation error from the original language','C',5,0,0,5),(980,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'The Toilet','Both ''Half a Day'' and ''The Toilet'' feature protagonists in confined settings that symbolise something larger. In ''The Toilet,'' the public toilet symbolises primarily:','The poverty of South Africa','The narrator''s love of solitude','A private world of freedom and self-expression within a life of severe external constraints','The failure of the South African government','C',5,0,0,5),(981,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','Who wrote the poem ''Success''?','John Masefield','H. W. Longfellow','T. S. Eliot','Wislawa Szymborska','B',1,0,0,1),(982,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','According to the poem ''Success,'' what do the pyramids look like when seen nearer and better known?','A vast desert plain','Massive stone walls','Gigantic flights of stairs','Ancient temple steps','C',1,0,0,1),(983,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','According to the poem, what were great men doing while their companions slept?','Dreaming of their future','Toiling upward in the night','Resting to prepare for the next day','Reading books by candlelight','B',1,0,0,1),(984,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','In which year was Henry Wadsworth Longfellow born?','1780','1807','1820','1835','B',1,0,0,1),(985,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','''We have not wings, we cannot soar; / But we have feet to scale and climb.'' The contrast between wings and feet suggests:','Birds are faster than humans','Humans cannot fly but must achieve goals slowly through steady effort','Flight is the best way to succeed','Climbing mountains is the path to success','B',2,0,0,2),(986,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','''The cloudy summits of our time'' in the poem most likely refers to:','Literal mountains covered in clouds','The great achievements and challenges of our era','Bad weather conditions','A cloudy day in Longfellow''s life','B',2,0,0,2),(987,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','''The distant mountains... Are crossed by pathways that appear / As we to higher levels rise.'' This line means:','Mountains are easier to cross than they appear from a distance','Pathways to success become clear only as we make progress toward our goal','Mountains near the equator have more pathways','One must hire a guide to cross mountains','B',2,0,0,2),(988,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','''The heights by great men reached and kept / Were not attained by sudden flight.'' The word ''kept'' implies that:','Great men stored their achievements like treasure','Success once achieved must also be maintained through continued effort','Height is only important if it can be defended','Great men kept the knowledge of their methods secret','B',2,0,0,2),(989,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','The pyramids are described as ''wedge-like'' as they ''cleave the desert airs.'' What do the pyramids primarily represent in the poem?','Ancient Egyptian culture and religion','The vastness of desert landscapes','Monumental human achievements that seem impossible but are built step by step','The power of kings and pharaohs','C',3,0,0,3),(990,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','Why does the poet say great men toiled ''in the night''?','Night is cooler and more comfortable for work','They were afraid to work during the day','They worked when others were resting, meaning their effort was hidden and extraordinary','They preferred working without sunlight','C',3,0,0,3),(991,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','The poem moves from soaring (wings), to climbing (feet), to stairs (pyramids), to pathways (mountains). What progression does this sequence suggest?','A journey from failure to success','Different ways of travelling','Success is not a sudden leap but a gradual, step-by-step ascent through steady effort','The poem describes a real journey Longfellow took','C',3,0,0,3),(992,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','How does the poem ''Success'' connect thematically to Gcina Mhlope''s story ''The Toilet''?','Both are set in the same time period','Both describe literal climbing of stairs','Both illustrate that great achievement comes not from sudden inspiration but from quiet, persistent effort against all odds','Both texts are from South Africa','C',3,0,0,3),(993,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','The poem uses three extended images: pyramids, mountains, and great men toiling at night. What is the effect of using multiple images for the same theme?','It shows Longfellow lacked focus','Each image adds a different dimension — scale (pyramids), navigation (mountains), and human dedication (great men) — making the theme of gradual success richer','It makes the poem longer and more impressive','The images are all from Longfellow''s personal life','B',4,0,0,4),(994,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','''While their companions slept'' contrasts the great men with ordinary people. What does this contrast reveal about the nature of exceptional achievement?','Great men need less sleep','Ordinary people are lazy','Exceptional achievement requires sacrificing the rest and comfort that others take for granted','Success depends on avoiding social relationships','C',4,0,0,4),(995,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','The poem says the pyramids are ''but gigantic flights of stairs'' when seen up close. How does this apply to the theme of success?','Great goals only seem impossible from a distance — up close they resolve into manageable steps','The pyramids are the best symbols of Egyptian success','One should always study achievements closely before judging them','Success is only visible when you are already successful','A',4,0,0,4),(996,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','The poem ''Success'' belongs to the same unit as Gandhiji''s ''Dreams Realised.'' How does Longfellow''s poem connect to Gandhiji''s life as described in the passage?','Both texts are about physical climbing','Both are set in the same historical period','Gandhiji''s decades of quiet, persistent struggle is the living embodiment of Longfellow''s message: heights reached not by sudden flight but by toiling upward','Both texts discuss the importance of education','C',4,0,0,4),(997,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','The poem''s final stanza is the most personal in the poem — about specific great men rather than general images. Why does the poem end here rather than with a general conclusion?','Longfellow ran out of ideas for general images','Ending with human beings rather than objects makes the message directly applicable — it is people who do the toiling, not pyramids','The final stanza was added by a later editor','Longfellow preferred concrete details to abstract ideas','B',5,0,0,5),(998,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','A student says: ''The poem is unrealistic because not everyone who works hard succeeds.'' The poem''s best implicit response is:','The poem agrees — hard work does not guarantee success','The poem says work is always rewarded financially','The poem addresses a different question: not whether success is guaranteed, but that heights, when reached, are only ever reached by sustained effort — not luck or sudden flight','The poem disagrees and has no response to this criticism','C',5,0,0,5),(999,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','The poem ''Success'' does not name any specific great men. How does this choice affect the poem''s impact?','It makes the poem vague and less interesting','It allows the reader to fill in examples from their own experience, making the message universal rather than historical','It is a flaw that weakens the argument','It shows Longfellow did not know any great men personally','B',5,0,0,5),(1000,'Kerala',9,'English','English','MCQ',1,'II','Winds of Change',9,'Success','Reading all three texts in Unit II together — ''Dreams Realised,'' ''The Toilet,'' and ''Success'' — which statement best summarises the unit''s theme?','Great people are born, not made','Success in any field requires good luck above all else','Obstacles and difficulties are a necessary part of every important journey — there are no shortcuts to meaningful achievement','Education is the only path to success','C',5,0,0,5);
