1010,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Simplify √2 × √8:','4','√10','√16 = 4','Both A and C','D',2,0,0,2),(1011,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Using √2 ≈ 1.414, find the approximate value of 3√2:','3.414','4.243','4','3','B',2,0,0,2),(1012,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Which of the following simplifies to a rational number?','√3 × √7','√5 × √5','√2 × √7','√3 × √5','B',2,0,0,2),(1013,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Simplify √3 × √3 × √3:','3','3√3','√27 = 3√3','Both B and C','D',3,0,0,3),(1014,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','What is (2√3)²?','4√3','12','4×3=12','Both B and C','D',3,0,0,3),(1015,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Simplify √2 × √6 × √3:','√11','6','√36 = 6','Both B and C','D',3,0,0,3),(1016,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Which correctly simplifies √50?','5√2','2√5','10√5','25√2','A',3,0,0,3),(1017,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','A square has side length √5. Its area is 5. Its perimeter is:','5','4√5','20','√20','B',3,0,0,3),(1018,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Simplify 2√3 × 3√3:','6√9 = 18','18','6×3 = 18','All of the above','D',3,0,0,3),(1019,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Simplify (√2 + √3)(√2 - √3):','1','-1','√5','2-3=-1','B',4,0,0,4),(1020,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','What is (√5 + √2)²?','7','7+2√10','7+√10','7+4√10','B',4,0,0,4),(1021,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Which of the following is equal to √(a²b) where a,b>0?','a√b','ab','a²√b','√a × √b','A',4,0,0,4),(1022,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Simplify √(3) × √(27):','3','9','√81 = 9','Both B and C','D',4,0,0,4),(1023,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','The area of a rectangle is 12 and one side is 2√3. The other side is:','6/√3 = 2√3','2√3','√3','6√3','B',4,0,0,4),(1024,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Which product gives the largest result?','√2 × √3','√3 × √3','√5 × √1','√2 × √4','B',4,0,0,4),(1025,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','The proof that √x × √y = √(xy) uses: (√x × √y)² = x×y. Why does this prove √x×√y = √(xy)?','Because squaring both sides preserves the equality','Because √(xy) is the unique positive number whose square is xy','Because √x × √y is positive and (√x×√y)² = xy','Both B and C','D',5,0,0,5),(1026,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','If √a × √b = √(ab) always, then why can''t we say √(-1) × √(-1) = √((-1)×(-1)) = √1 = 1?','The rule requires a,b ≥ 0; √(-1) is not a real number','The rule only works for rational a,b','(-1)×(-1) ≠ 1','√(-1) × √(-1) = 0','A',5,0,0,5),(1027,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','Simplify (√2)³ × (√2)³:','8','4√2','2√2','16','A',5,0,0,5),(1028,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','A student says √(a×b) = √a + √b. Find a counterexample from the chapter''s content:','√(4×4) = 4 ≠ √4+√4 = 2+2 = 4 (same! no counterexample)','√(2×2) = 2 but √2+√2 = 2√2 ≠ 2','√(9×1) = 3 but √9+√1 = 3+1 = 4 ≠ 3','Both B and C are valid counterexamples','D',5,0,0,5),(1029,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','If m√a × n√b = mn√(ab), then (3√5)(4√5) =','12√10','12×5=60','7√5','12√25=60','B',5,0,0,5),(1030,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Multiplication of Irrationals','The notation p√q means p × √q. Using this, express √(p²q) in the form p√q:','√p × √q','p × √q','p²√q','p√(pq)','B',5,0,0,5),(1031,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','What is √12 ÷ √3?','√9 = 3','√15','√4 = 2','3','D',1,0,0,1),(1032,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','The rule for dividing square roots is: √x / √y =','√(x-y)','√(x/y)','√(xy)','√x - √y','B',1,0,0,1),(1033,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','What is √50 / √2?','√25 = 5','√52','√48','10','A',1,0,0,1),(1034,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Which of the following equals 1/√2?','√2/2','2/√2','√(1/2)','Both A and C','D',1,0,0,1),(1035,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','What is √(16/4)?','√16/√4 = 4/2 = 2','4','2√2','Both A and B — it equals 2','D',1,0,0,1),(1036,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify 6√10 / 2√5:','3√2','3√5','8√15','3√50','A',2,0,0,2),(1037,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','What is 1/√5, expressed with √5 in the numerator?','√5/5','5/√5','5-Jan','√5','A',2,0,0,2),(1038,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify √(x/y) × √y:','x/y','√x','x','√(xy)/y','B',2,0,0,2),(1039,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Using √2 ≈ 1.414, what is 1/√2 approximately?','0.5','0.707','1.414','2','B',2,0,0,2),(1040,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Which of the following is the simplest form of √(3/4)?','√3/2','4-Mar','√3/4','3/√4','A',2,0,0,2),(1041,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify 4√6 / √2:','4√3','2√3','4√12','4√4','A',3,0,0,3),(1042,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','The height of an equilateral triangle with side 1 is √3/2. Express this as a single fraction with √3 in the numerator:','√3/2 (already done)','1/√3','2/√3','√(3)/4','A',3,0,0,3),(1043,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify √(a²/b):','a/√b','a²/√b','a/b','√a/b','A',3,0,0,3),(1044,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','What is 3/√3?','√3','3√3','1/√3','3','A',3,0,0,3),(1045,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify (√6 × √10) / √15:','2','√4 = 2','√(60/15) = √4 = 2','All of the above','D',3,0,0,3),(1046,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Rationalise the denominator of 5/√3:','5√3/3','3-May','√15/3','5√3','A',4,0,0,4),(1047,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify (√a / √b) × (√b / √c):','√(a/c)','a/(bc)','√a/√c','Both A and C','D',4,0,0,4),(1048,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','The area of a triangle is 6√2 cm². Its base is 4√2 cm. Its height is:','3 cm','3√2 cm','6 cm','1.5 cm','A',4,0,0,4),(1049,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify √(48) / √(3):','4','√16 = 4','√(48/3) = √16 = 4','All of the above','D',4,0,0,4),(1050,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','If x = 1/√2, then 1/x =','√2','1/√2','2','√(1/2)','A',4,0,0,4),(1051,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','The chapter shows 1/√x = √x/x. This is called rationalising the denominator. The key step is multiplying numerator and denominator by:','x','1/x','√x','x²','C',5,0,0,5),(1052,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify (√2 + √3) / √6:','√2/√6 + √3/√6 = 1/√3 + 1/√2','√(2+3)/√6 = 1','(√2+√3)/√6 = √(2/6)+√(3/6) = √(1/3)+√(1/2) = 1/√3 + 1/√2','Both A and C','D',5,0,0,5),(1053,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Which is larger: √6/3 or √(2/3)? Show they are equal.','√6/3 > √(2/3)','√6/3 < √(2/3)','√6/3 = √(6/9) = √(2/3), so they are equal','Cannot compare without a calculator','C',5,0,0,5),(1054,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','The proof that √x/√y = √(x/y) mirrors the multiplication proof. The key step is: (√x/√y)² = x/y. Why does this prove √x/√y = √(x/y)?','Because √(x/y) is the unique positive number whose square is x/y, and √x/√y is positive','Because x and y are always integers','Because division reverses multiplication','Because √x > √y when x > y','A',5,0,0,5),(1055,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Division of Irrationals','Simplify and rationalise: 6 / (2√3):','3/√3 = √3','2√3','3√3/3 = √3','Both A and C','D',5,0,0,5),(1056,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Areas of Triangles','What is the formula for the are