Multiplication',15,'Areas of Triangles','Three congruent equilateral triangles are placed edge-to-edge to form a larger triangle. If each small triangle has side a, the large triangle has side:','3a','2a','√3a','Cannot be determined','B',5,0,0,5),(1096,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Areas of Triangles','An equilateral triangle has altitude h. Express its area in terms of h only (no a):','h²/√3','h²√3/3','Since a = 2h/√3, area = (√3/4)(2h/√3)² = h²/√3 = h²√3/3','All of the above','D',5,0,0,5),(1097,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Areas of Triangles','Heron''s formula for a triangle with all irrational sides can still give a rational area. Which of the following illustrates this?','Sides √2, √3, √5 always give irrational area','An equilateral triangle with side √(4/√3) gives area = 1','No irrational-sided triangle can have rational area','Both A and C','B',5,0,0,5),(1098,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Areas of Triangles','For a right triangle with legs a and b and hypotenuse c, the area by formula is ab/2, and Heron''s gives √(s(s-a)(s-b)(s-c)). These must be equal. Show that s(s-c) = ab/2 by using s=(a+b+c)/2 and c²=a²+b²: s(s-c) = (a+b+c)(b+a-c)/4. Using c²=a²+b², this simplifies to:','(a+b+c)(b+a-c)/4 = ((a+b)²-c²)/4 = (a²+2ab+b²-a²-b²)/4 = ab/2. So s(s-c) = ab/2 ✓','ab','s(s-c) = c/2','The two formulas give different results','A',5,0,0,5),(1099,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Areas of Triangles','An equilateral triangle with side a is divided by its three altitudes into 6 congruent right triangles. Each right triangle has legs a/2 and a√3/2. Its area is:','(√3/4)a²/6 = √3a²/24','(1/2)(a/2)(a√3/2) = a²√3/8','a²√3/8 = (total area)/6 since total = 6 × a²√3/8 = 3a²√3/4 ≠ (√3/4)a²','(1/2)(a/2)(a√3/2) = a²√3/8, and 6 × a²√3/8 = 3a²√3/4 (not equal to (√3/4)a²) — each right triangle area = (√3/4)a² / 6 = a²√3/24','D',5,0,0,5),(1100,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'5','Irrational Multiplication',15,'Areas of Triangles','A student uses the formula Area = (√3/4)a² for a non-equilateral triangle with all sides approximately equal to a. The result will be:','Exactly correct','An overestimate for some triangles','Only an approximation; Heron''s formula gives the exact area for any triangle','An underestimate always','C',5,0,0,5),(1101,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Which identity gives the expansion of (x+y)(u+v)?','xu + yv','xu + xv + yu + yv','xu - xv - yu + yv','x²u + y²v','B',1,0,0,1),(1102,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','How many terms appear in the expansion of (x+y)(u+v)?','2','3','4','6','C',1,0,0,1),(1103,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','What is (2+3)(4+5) using the identity (x+y)(u+v) = xu+xv+yu+yv?','35','45','40','25','B',1,0,0,1),(1104,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','In (x+y)(u+v), setting u=x and v=y gives:','(x+y)² = x² + y²','(x+y)² = x² + 2xy + y²','(x+y)² = 2xy','(x+y)² = x²y²','B',1,0,0,1),(1105,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Which product identity is used to expand (a+b)(c+d)?','(x-y)(u-v) = xu-xv-yu+yv','(x+y)(u+v) = xu+xv+yu+yv','Difference of squares','(x+y)² = x²+2xy+y²','B',1,0,0,1),(1106,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','What is (1+2)(3+4)?','10','14','21','7','C',1,0,0,1),(1107,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Use (x+y)(u+v) to compute 13 × 14 = (10+3)(10+4):','142','152','162','182','D',2,0,0,2),(1108,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Expand (x+3)(x+5):','x²+8x+15','x²+15','x²+5x+3','2x+8','A',2,0,0,2),(1109,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Which of the following equals (a+b)²?','a² + b²','a² + ab + b²','a² + 2ab + b²','2a² + 2b²','C',2,0,0,2),(1110,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Using the identity, compute 12 × 15 as (10+2)(10+5):','150','170','180','140','C',2,0,0,2),(1111,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Expand (2+√2)(3+√3):','6 + 2√3 + 3√2 + √6','6 + √6','5 + √5','6 + √(2+3)','A',2,0,0,2),(1112,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','If (x+y)(u+v) = xu+xv+yu+yv, then (1+√2)(1+√3) =','1 + √6','1 + √2 + √3 + √6','2 + √5','√(1+2)(1+3)','B',2,0,0,2),(1113,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Compute 21 × 23 using the identity (20+1)(20+3):','463','483','443','503','B',3,0,0,3),(1114,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Expand (x+4)(x+6) and identify the constant term:','10','4','24','x²','C',3,0,0,3),(1115,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Use (10+a)(10+b) to compute 17 × 18:','296','306','316','326','B',3,0,0,3),(1116,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Expand (√2+√3)(√2+√5):','2 + √10 + √6 + √15','√4 + √15','2 + √(10+6+15)','√2(√2+√5) + √3(√2+√5)','A',3,0,0,3),(1117,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Which of the following is the correct expansion of (x+y)² using the product of sums identity?','x² + y²','(x+y)(x-y) = x² - y²','x² + 2xy + y² (setting u=x, v=y in (x+y)(u+v))','x²y²','C',3,0,0,3),(1118,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Expand (a+b)(a+c) where a=10, b=7, c=3 to compute 17 × 13:','201','211','221','231','C',3,0,0,3),(1119,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Expand (2x+3)(3x+4):','6x²+17x+12','6x²+8x+12','5x²+17x+7','6x²+7x+12','A',4,0,0,4),(1120,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','(1+√2)(2+√3) = ?','2 + √6 + 2√2 + √3','3 + √5','2+√3+2√2+√6','3 + √6','C',4,0,0,4),(1121,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','If x+y = 10 and u+v = 20, and xu = 12, xv = 18, what is yu?','Not determinable from the given info alone without individual values','8','10','12','A',4,0,0,4),(1122,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Use the identity to compute 105 × 107 = (100+5)(100+7):','11225','11235','11235','11235','B',4,0,0,4),(1123,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Expand (x+√2)² and identify the middle term:','√2x','2√2 x','√2','2x','B',4,0,0,4),(1124,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','If (x+a)(x+b) = x²+7x+12, identify a and b:','a=3, b=4','a=6, b=2','a=12, b=1','a=4, b=3 (same as A)','A',4,0,0,4),(1125,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Show that (x+y)² - (x-y)² = 4xy using the product of sums and difference identities. Which step is key?','Setting u=y in (x+y)(u+v)','(x+y)² = x²+2xy+y² and (x-y)² = x²-2xy+y²; subtracting gives 4xy','Setting x=y in the identity','The cross terms cancel','B',5,0,0,5),(1126,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Using (x+y)(u+v), express (a+b+c)² as a sum. Which expansion is correct?','a²+b²+c²','a²+b²+c²+2ab+2bc+2ca','(a+b)²+c²','a²+b²+c²+ab+bc+ca','B',5,0,0,5),(1127,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','The identity (x+y)(u+v) = xu+xv+yu+yv is used to prove that multiplication distributes over addition. Which of the following best describes this property?','a(b+c) = ab + ac','(a+b)c = ac + bc','(a+b)(c+d) = ac+ad+bc+bd','All of the above are forms of the distributive property','D',5,0,0,5),(1128,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','Compute (√2+√3)²:','5','5+2√6','5+√6','√5','B',5,0,0,5),(1129,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','If (x+y)(x+y) = x²+2xy+y², what does (x+y)(x-y) equal? (Derive using the identity with u=x, v=-y)','x²+y²','x²-y²','x²-2xy+y²','2x²','B',5,0,0,5),(1130,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Product of Sums','In the identity (x+y)(u+v)=xu+xv+yu+yv, setting x=a, y=-b, u=a, v=b gives:','(a-b)(a+b) = a²+ab-ab-b² = a²-b²','a²+b²','2a²-2b²','a²-2ab+b²','A',5,0,0,5),(1131,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','What is the expansion of (x-y)(u-v)?','xu - xv - yu + yv','xu + xv + yu + yv','xu - xv + yu - yv','xu + yv','A',1,0,0,1),(1132,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','What is (5-2)(8-3)?','15','12','9','18','A',1,0,0,1),(1133,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','(x+y)(u-v) expands to:','xu + xv - yu - yv','xu - xv + yu - yv','xu - xv - yu + yv','xu + yv','B',1,0,0,1),(1134,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Which identity gives (a-b)²?','a² + 2ab + b²','a² - 2ab + b²','a² - b²','a² + b²','B',1,0,0,1),(1135,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','(a+b)(a-b) equals:','a² + b²','a² - b²','2a','(a-b)²','B',1,0,0,1),(1136,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','What is (10-3)(10-4)?','42','38','48','52','A',1,0,0,1),(1137,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Compute 97 × 95 using (100-3)(100-5):','9215','9115','9315','9415','A',2,0,0,2),(1138,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Expand (x-3)(x-5):','x²-8x+15','x²+8x+15','x²-8x-15','x²-15','A',2,0,0,2),(1139,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Compute 99² using (100-1)²:','9081','9801','9901','9991','B',2,0,0,2),(1140,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Compute 48 × 52 using the identity (50-2)(50+2):','2496','2500','2506','2404','A',2,0,0,2),(1141,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Expand (3-√2)(3+√2):','9-2=7','9+2=11','9-√4=7','6-√4','A',2,0,0,2),(1142,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Compute 103 × 97 using (100+3)(100-3):','9901','9991','10009','9809','B',2,0,0,2),(1143,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Expand (2x-3)(2x+3):','4x²-9','4x²+9','4x²-6x+9','2x²-9','A',3,0,0,3),(1144,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Compute 995² using (1000-5)²:','990025','990025','999025','990225','A',3,0,0,3),(1145,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Expand (√5-√2)(√5+√2):','3','7','√3','√7','A',3,0,0,3),(1146,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Expand (x+2)(x-5):','x²-3x-10','x²+3x-10','x²-3x+10','x²-10','A',3,0,0,3),(1147,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Which of the following equals (a-b)² + 2ab?','a²+b²','a²+2ab+b²','(a+b)²','Both B and C','D',3,0,0,3),(1148,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Compute 198 × 202 using (200-2)(200+2):','39996','40000','39996','40004','A',3,0,0,3),(1149,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Expand (2√3-√2)(2√3+√2):','10','14','12-2=10','Both A and C','D',4,0,0,4),(1150,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','If (x+y)(x-y) = 40 and x-y = 4, find x+y:','8','10','12','6','B',4,0,0,4),(1151,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Use the identity to simplify (√7+√3)(√7-√3):','4','10','√4','√10','A',4,0,0,4),(1152,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Expand (3x-2y)²:','9x²-12xy+4y²','9x²+4y²','9x²-4y²','9x²+12xy+4y²','A',4,0,0,4),(1153,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Compute 999 × 1001 using (1000-1)(1000+1):','999999','1000001','998001','999001','A',4,0,0,4),(1154,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Which identity is being used when we write 51 × 49 = (50+1)(50-1) = 2500-1 = 2499?','(x+y)(u+v)','(x+y)²','(x+y)(x-y) = x²-y²','(x-y)²','C',4,0,0,4),(1155,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Using (x+y)(x-y) = x²-y², simplify (√2+1)(√2-1) and explain the result:','0','1 (since (√2)²-1²=2-1=1), making them a ''conjugate pair''','2','√2-1','B',5,0,0,5),(1156,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','The chapter uses (x+y)(u-v) = xu - xv + yu - yv. This shows that multiplying a sum by a difference is NOT the same as (x+y)(u+v) because:','The signs of xv and yu are reversed','There are only 3 terms','The xv term disappears','The result is always negative','A',5,0,0,5),(1157,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Prove that (a+b)² - (a-b)² = 4ab. Which step is the key simplification?','(a²+2ab+b²) - (a²-2ab+b²) = 4ab ✓','Setting a=b=0','Using a²-b²=(a+b)(a-b)','Both A and C','A',5,0,0,5),(1158,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','A student computes (x-y)² as x²-y². What error did they make?','They forgot the square on y','They omitted the -2xy middle term','They should get x²+y²','The formula only works for positive x','B',5,0,0,5),(1159,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','The product (√3+√2)(√3-√2) = 3-2 = 1. This result is useful for:','Adding surds','Rationalising denominators containing √3-√2 or √3+√2','Proving √3 > √2','Finding the square of √3','B',5,0,0,5),(1160,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Multiplication with a Difference','Which of the following is a correct relationship derived from the three multiplication identities?','(x+y)² + (x-y)² = 2x² + 2y²','(x+y)² - (x-y)² = 2xy','(x+y)(x-y) = (x+y)²','(x-y)² = (x+y)² for all x,y','A',5,0,0,5),(1161,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In the calendar, the product of numbers at the diagonals of a 2×2 square differ by:','1','7','14','0','B',1,0,0,1),(1162,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In a multiplication table, the diagonal sums in a rectangular region are always:','Different','Equal','Prime','Multiples of 10','B',1,0,0,1),(1163,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','If a two-digit number has digits a (tens) and b (units), its value is:','a + b','10a + b','ab','a × b + 10','B',1,0,0,1),(1164,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','The reverse of a two-digit number with digits a and b (tens digit a) is:','10a + b','10b + a','a + b','b - a','B',1,0,0,1),(1165,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In a calendar month, adjacent dates in the same week differ by:','1','7','6','31','A',1,0,0,1),(1166,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','A two-digit number has tens digit a and units digit b. The difference between the number and its reverse is:','9(a+b)','9(a-b)','a-b','10(a-b)','B',2,0,0,2),(1167,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In a calendar 2×2 square, the four dates are a, a+1, a+7, a+8. The difference of diagonal products is:','8','7','1','14','B',2,0,0,2),(1168,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','The number 73 reversed is 37. Their difference is:','36','72','63','37','A',2,0,0,2),(1169,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In a multiplication table, the sum of the top-left and bottom-right entries of a rectangle equals:','The product of the row and column labels','The sum of top-right and bottom-left entries','Always an even number','The perimeter of the rectangle','B',2,0,0,2),(1170,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','For any two-digit number with tens digit a and units digit b, the sum of the number and its reverse is:','11(a+b)','9(a-b)','10(a+b)','11(a-b)','A',2,0,0,2),(1171,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In a calendar 2×2 square with top-left = n, show that the diagonal products differ by 7. The two products are n(n+8) and (n+1)(n+7). Their difference is:','8','7','n','14','B',3,0,0,3),(1172,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','A two-digit number is 54. Its reverse is 45. Using the identity, the difference 54-45 = 9(5-4) =:','9','18','45','1','A',3,0,0,3),(1173,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In the multiplication table, the four entries at corners of a rectangle in rows r₁, r₂ and columns c₁, c₂ are r₁c₁, r₁c₂, r₂c₁, r₂c₂. The diagonal sums r₁c₁+r₂c₂ and r₁c₂+r₂c₁ are equal because:','r₁c₁+r₂c₂ = r₁c₂+r₂c₁ (rearranging terms)','All four products are equal','The table is symmetric','Diagonal products always equal row sums','A',3,0,0,3),(1174,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','A two-digit number plus its reverse always gives a multiple of 11. If the digits are a and b, the sum is 11(a+b). Which is NOT a possible value of this sum (assuming a,b single digits ≥1)?','22','33','100','99','C',3,0,0,3),(1175,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In a 2×2 calendar square with top-left n, the diagonal products are n(n+8)=n²+8n and (n+1)(n+7)=n²+8n+7. This confirms the difference is always:','n','8n','7','Depends on n','C',3,0,0,3),(1176,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','A 3×3 calendar square has top-left = n. The nine numbers are n, n+1, n+2, n+7, n+8, n+9, n+14, n+15, n+16. The product of the diagonal corners (n and n+16) minus the product of the other diagonal corners (n+2 and n+14) equals:','8','28','-28','4','C',4,0,0,4),(1177,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','Using the digit reversal idea, if a three-digit number has digits a, b, c, its value is 100a+10b+c. The reversed number is 100c+10b+a. Their difference is:','99(a+c)','99(a-c)','9(a-c)','100(a-c)','B',4,0,0,4),(1178,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In the multiplication table rectangle with rows r₁, r₂ and columns c₁, c₂, the product of diagonal entries satisfies: r₁c₁ × r₂c₂ and r₁c₂ × r₂c₁ are:','Always different','Equal (both equal r₁r₂c₁c₂)','Always prime','Equal only when r₁=r₂','B',4,0,0,4),(1179,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','A two-digit number exceeds its reverse by 27. If the units digit is 4, what is the tens digit?','6','7','5','8','B',4,0,0,4),(1180,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','In a 2×2 calendar square, the diagonal products always differ by 7. If the top-left is 15, the two diagonal products are:','15×22=330 and 16×21=336; difference=6','15×23=345 and 16×22=352; difference=7','15×23=345 and 16×22=352 — actually they are 15×22=330 and 16×21=336, difference=6','15×22=330 and 16×21=336, difference=6 NOT 7 — wait, let me recompute: 16×21=336, 15×22=330, 336-330=6','A',4,0,0,4),(1181,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','The calendar 2×2 square diagonal product difference is always 7 because the dates in the same column differ by 7 (a week). This is captured algebraically by (n)(n+8) - (n+1)(n+7) = n²+8n - (n²+8n+7) =:','0','-7','7','n+7','B',5,0,0,5),(1182,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','The multiplication table diagonal sum property (r₁c₁ + r₂c₂ = r₁c₂ + r₂c₁) follows from which algebraic fact?','All four products are equal','r₁c₁ + r₂c₂ - r₁c₂ - r₂c₁ = r₁(c₁-c₂) - r₂(c₁-c₂) = (r₁-r₂)(c₁-c₂) which need not be zero','r₁c₁ + r₂c₂ = r₁c₂ + r₂c₁ always (both equal r₁c₁+r₂c₂ when rewritten)','Both diagonal sums equal (r₁+r₂)(c₁+c₂)/2','D',5,0,0,5),(1183,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','If a two-digit number equals twice its reverse, and the digits are a and b, the equation is 10a+b = 2(10b+a). Solving:','a=2b','8a = 19b','a = 19b/8, which only gives integer solution when b=8, a=19 (not a single digit) — so no solution exists','The equation gives a specific valid pair','C',5,0,0,5),(1184,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','Using digit algebra, if a two-digit number is ''ab'' (= 10a+b), and ''ab'' × 9 = ''ba'' × 10 - ''ab'', which manipulation confirms the identity between a number and its reverse?','The relationship only holds for specific a,b','This simplifies to 19ab = 10ba which is not generally true','This shows a relationship between (10a+b) and (10b+a)','Such a general relationship cannot be established without specific digits','C',5,0,0,5),(1185,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Number Curiosities','A 2×2 block anywhere in the multiplication table has entries: row r, columns c and c+1; rows r and r+1. The diagonal products are r×(r+1)×c×(c+1) for one diagonal and r×(r+1)×c×(c+1) for the other. This means diagonal products are:','Always different','Equal','Equal only when r=c','Equal only for even r','B',5,0,0,5),(1186,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','The product of two odd numbers is:','Even','Odd','Always prime','Always greater than 10','B',1,0,0,1),(1187,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','Which of the following products is odd?','3 × 4','5 × 6','7 × 9','8 × 11','C',1,0,0,1),(1188,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','Two numbers leave the same remainder when divided by a given number. Their product also leaves:','A different remainder','The square of that remainder (reduced appropriately)','Zero remainder','A remainder that cannot be predicted','B',1,0,0,1),(1189,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','If 7 and 13 both leave remainder 1 when divided by 6, what remainder does 7×13=91 leave when divided by 6?','0','1','2','3','B',2,0,0,2),(1190,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','An odd number can be written as 2k+1 for some integer k. The product of two odd numbers (2m+1)(2n+1) =:','4mn+1','4mn+2m+2n+1','2(2mn+m+n)+1 (odd)','Both B and C','D',2,0,0,2),(1191,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','Numbers that leave remainder 2 when divided by 5 include: 7, 12, 17, 22. Their products also leave remainder:','2','4','3','1','B',2,0,0,2),(1192,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','If a ≡ r (mod n) and b ≡ r (mod n), then ab ≡ r² (mod n). Using this, if 3 and 8 both leave remainder 3 when divided by 5, what does 3×8=24 leave when divided by 5?','3','4','2','1','B',3,0,0,3),(1193,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','An odd number squared is always odd. If n=2k+1, then n² = 4k²+4k+1 = 2(2k²+2k)+1. This number is odd because:','It ends in 1','It is of the form 2m+1','4k²+4k is even, so adding 1 gives odd','Both B and C','D',3,0,0,3),(1194,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','Numbers leaving remainder 1 when divided by 4: 5, 9, 13, 17, ... Their product 5 × 9 = 45 leaves remainder __ when divided by 4:','0','1','2','3','B',3,0,0,3),(1195,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','If two numbers a and b both leave remainder r when divided by n, then ab leaves remainder r² (mod n). The proof uses a=qn+r and b=pn+r, so ab = pqn²+rqn+rpn+r² = n(pqn+rq+rp)+r². This means ab-r² is divisible by n. Why is r² the remainder only if r² < n?','Remainders must be less than the divisor','r² is always less than n','We take the actual remainder of r² ÷ n','Both A and C','D',4,0,0,4),(1196,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','Numbers 11 and 14 leave remainders 2 and 5 when divided by 3 (11=3×3+2, 14=3×4+2). Actually both leave remainder 2. Their product 11×14=154 leaves what remainder when divided by 3?','1','2','0','4','A',4,0,0,4),(1197,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','If a ≡ 3 (mod 7) and b ≡ 3 (mod 7), then ab ≡ 9 ≡ 2 (mod 7). Numbers leaving remainder 3 when divided by 7: 10, 17, 24. What remainder does 10×17=170 leave when divided by 7?','1','2','3','4','B',4,0,0,4),(1198,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','The chapter shows odd × odd = odd using algebra. Which of the following is the most direct algebraic proof?','All odd numbers end in 1, 3, 5, 7, or 9; multiplying gives an odd digit','Write odd numbers as 2m+1 and 2n+1; product = 4mn+2m+2n+1 = 2(2mn+m+n)+1, which is odd','Odd numbers cannot be divided by 2, so their product can''t either','Both A and C','B',5,0,0,5),(1199,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','If three numbers a, b, c all leave the same remainder r when divided by n, what remainder does abc leave when divided by n?','r','r³ (mod n)','3r (mod n)','r² (mod n)','B',5,0,0,5),(1200,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'4','Multiplication Identities',14,'Special Operations','The chapter connects the ''odd × odd = odd'' rule with the general remainder rule. Which statement best describes this connection?','Odd numbers are exactly the numbers leaving remainder 1 when divided by 2; odd × odd = 1×1 = 1 (mod 2) = odd','Odd numbers are prime, so their product is prime','The general rule only works for prime divisors','Odd × odd = odd is a special case of even × even = even','A',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (1201,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Which of the following is a negative number?','0','-5','2-Jan','√4','B',1,0,0,1),(1202,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','The commutative law for addition states:','a + (b + c) = (a + b) + c','a + b = b + a','a × b = b × a (for multiplication)','a × (b + c) = ab + ac','B',1,0,0,1),(1203,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','The distributive law states:','a + b = b + a','a × (b + c) = ab + ac','a + (b + c) = (a + b) + c','a × b = b × a','B',1,0,0,1),(1204,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Which three basic laws of arithmetic are extended to negative numbers in this chapter?','BODMAS, HCF, LCM','Commutative, Associative, Distributive','Pythagoras, Heron''s, Euclid''s','Triangle inequality, AM-GM, Cauchy-Schwarz','B',1,0,0,1),(1205,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Does the commutative law hold for subtraction?','Yes, a - b = b - a always','No — for example, 5 - 3 = 2 but 3 - 5 = -2','Yes, but only for positive numbers','Yes, if a = b','B',2,0,0,2),(1206,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Using the distributive law, compute (-3)(4 + 5):','-27','27','-12','12','A',2,0,0,2),(1207,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','The associative law for multiplication states (a × b) × c = a × (b × c). Verify with a=-2, b=3, c=-4:','(−2×3)×(−4)=(−6)×(−4)=24 and −2×(3×(−4))=−2×(−12)=24 ✓','The law fails for negative numbers','Result is −24','Result is 12','A',2,0,0,2),(1208,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Compute 3 × (-4) + 3 × (-6) using the distributive law:','-30','30','-18','18','A',2,0,0,2),(1209,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Verify the distributive law with a=5, b=-3, c=-2: a(b+c) and ab+ac:','5((-3)+(-2)) = 5×(-5) = -25; 5×(-3)+5×(-2) = -15+(-10) = -25 ✓','Results differ for negative numbers','Both give 25','a(b+c) = -25 but ab+ac = 25','A',3,0,0,3),(1210,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','The commutative law a + b = b + a extends to negative numbers. Compute (-7) + 3 and 3 + (-7):','Both equal -4 ✓','-4 and 4 (not equal)','Both equal 4','10 and -10','A',3,0,0,3),(1211,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Using the associative law, compute [(-5) + 8] + (-3) and (-5) + [8 + (-3)]:','0 and 0 ✓','0 and -2','3 and 0','-6 and 6','A',3,0,0,3),(1212,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Which law is used to write (-2)(a - b) = -2a + 2b?','Commutative law','Associative law','Distributive law','Closure law','C',3,0,0,3),(1213,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Does the distributive law hold for negative numbers? Use a=-3, b=5, c=-2 to verify:','(-3)(5+(-2)) = (-3)(3) = -9; (-3)(5)+(-3)(-2) = -15+6 = -9 ✓','The law fails','Result is 9','Result is -3','A',4,0,0,4),(1214,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','The three laws (commutative, associative, distributive) are extended to include negative numbers in this chapter. This means negative numbers form what kind of algebraic structure?','They remain outside the number system','They extend the natural numbers to integers, maintaining all these laws','They violate the commutative law','They only follow the distributive law','B',4,0,0,4),(1215,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Simplify (-4)(-3) + (-4)(7) using the distributive law:','-16','16','-16','4','A',4,0,0,4),(1216,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Using distributive law: (-1)(a + b) =','a + b','#NAME?','#NAME?','a - b','C',4,0,0,4),(1217,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','The distributive law is used in this chapter to derive (-x)(-y) = xy. The key step is: (-x)(-y) + (-x)(y) = (-x)((-y)+y) = (-x)(0) = 0, so (-x)(-y) = ?','0','#NAME?','xy (since (-x)(-y) = xy by the equation above)','Cannot be determined','C',5,0,0,5),(1218,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Which statement correctly justifies why (-1) × (-1) = 1 using the distributive law?','(-1)(1 + (-1)) = (-1)(0) = 0; and (-1)(1) + (-1)(-1) = -1 + (-1)(-1) = 0; so (-1)(-1) = 1','Two negatives make a positive, by definition','(-1)×(-1) = 1 because it is the multiplicative identity','(-1)²=1 is an axiom','A',5,0,0,5),(1219,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','In extending the number system to include negatives, the chapter asserts the three laws still hold. Which of the following would be an example of the associative law for multiplication failing (it never fails):','(-2 × 3) × 5 = -30 and -2 × (3 × 5) = -30 ✓','(-2 × 3) × 5 = -30 ≠ 30 = -2 × (3×5)','The law fails for three negatives','The associative law does fail for negatives','A',5,0,0,5),(1220,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Measures and Numbers','Prove that (-a)b = -(ab) using the distributive law:','(-a)b + ab = (-a+a)b = 0 × b = 0, so (-a)b = -(ab) ✓','(-a)b = (-1)(ab) which equals -(ab) ✓','(-a)b = -(ab) is an axiom','Both A and B give correct proofs','D',5,0,0,5),(1221,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','On the number line, negative numbers are located:','To the right of zero','To the left of zero','Above zero','Below zero','B',1,0,0,1),(1222,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','What is the opposite of -7?','0','7-Jan','7','-7','C',1,0,0,1),(1223,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','On the number line, the number -3 is how many units from 0?','1','2','3','-3','C',1,0,0,1),(1224,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','Which is greater: -5 or -2?','-5','-2','They are equal','Cannot compare','B',2,0,0,2),(1225,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','A point at position -3 on a number line is at distance __ from position 5:','2','8','-8','3','B',2,0,0,2),(1226,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','The number that is 4 units to the left of -1 on the number line is:','3','-5','5','-3','B',2,0,0,2),(1227,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','The position of a number x on the number line: if x = -4 and y = 2, the midpoint between x and y is:','1','-1','3','-3','B',3,0,0,3),(1228,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','Order from least to greatest: -10, -3, 0, -7, 5:','0, -3, -7, -10, 5','-10, -7, -3, 0, 5','5, 0, -3, -7, -10','-10, -3, -7, 0, 5','B',3,0,0,3),(1229,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','A temperature drops from -3°C to -8°C. How many degrees did it drop?','5°C','11°C','-5°C','3°C','A',3,0,0,3),(1230,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','On the number line, the distance between -a and b (where a,b > 0) is:','b - a','a + b','a - b','|a - b|','B',4,0,0,4),(1231,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','A number x satisfies -5 < x < 3. How many integers satisfy this?','7','8','9','6','A',4,0,0,4),(1232,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','The number -x is positive when:','x > 0','x < 0','x = 0','x is even','B',4,0,0,4),(1233,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','On the number line, negative numbers represent positions ''before'' zero. If I stand at position p and walk to position q, the displacement is q - p. If p = 3 and q = -2, displacement =','5','-5','1','-1','B',5,0,0,5),(1234,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','The absolute value |x| gives the distance of x from 0. For x = -6: |x| = 6. For x = 4: |x| = 4. The distance between -6 and 4 on the number line equals |(-6) - 4| =','2','10','|−10| = 10 ✓','Both B and C','D',5,0,0,5),(1235,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Position and Number','If x and -x are both plotted, they are symmetric about:','The point 1','Each other','The origin (zero)','The point x/2','C',5,0,0,5),(1236,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Displacement','What is x + (-y) equal to?','x + y','x - y','#NAME?','x × (-y)','B',1,0,0,1),(1237,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Displacement','What is x - (-y) equal to?','x - y','x × y','x + y','#NAME?','C',1,0,0,1),(1238,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Displacement','Displacement from position a to position b is given by:','a + b','a - b','b - a','|a - b|','C',1,0,0,1),(1239,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Displacement','What is 5 + (-3)?','8','2','-2','-8','B',1,0,0,1),(1240,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'7','Negative Numbers',17,'Displacement','What is 4 - (-2)?','2','6','-6','-2','B',1,0,0,1),(1241,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,