nd b?','a=3, b=2','a=4, b=1','a=4, b=2','a=3, b=4','A',5,0,0,5),(1378,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Addition and Subtraction of Irrationals','A student simplifies √2 + √2 as √4 = 2. Is this correct?','Yes, because both are √2','No — √2 + √2 = 2√2, not √4','Yes, because √4 = 2 and 2√2 ≈ 2','No — √2 + √2 = √(2+2) = √4 is actually correct','B',5,0,0,5),(1379,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Addition and Subtraction of Irrationals','A student says (1+√2) + (1+√3) = 2 + √5 by ''adding the irrational parts inside the root.'' Why is this wrong?','Because 1+1≠2','Because √2 + √3 ≠ √5; you cannot add numbers inside different square roots','Because √5 < √2 + √3 is false','Because addition is not allowed with irrationals','B',5,0,0,5),(1380,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Addition and Subtraction of Irrationals','Simplify (2+3√2) + (4-3√2) + (1+2√2) - (3+2√2):','4 + 2√2','4','4 + 3√2','4 - 2√2','B',5,0,0,5),(1381,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','What does the proof in the appendix establish?','√2 is a whole number','No fraction p/q satisfies (p/q)² = 2','2 is not a perfect square among fractions','Both B and C','D',1,0,0,1),(1382,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','In the proof, what assumption is made at the start (proof by contradiction)?','√2 is irrational','√2 = p/q for some integers p, q with no common factors','2 is an irrational number','p and q are both even','B',1,0,0,1),(1383,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','If p/q is in lowest terms, what does it mean?','p and q share a common factor','p > q','p and q have no common factor other than 1','p is even and q is odd','C',1,0,0,1),(1384,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','An odd number squared is:','Even','Odd','A multiple of 4','Always greater than 100','B',1,0,0,1),(1385,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','In the proof, if (p/q)² = 2, then p² = 2q². This means p² is:','Odd','A perfect square only','Even','Equal to q','C',2,0,0,2),(1386,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','In the proof, if p² is even, then p must be:','Odd','Even','Equal to 2','A perfect square','B',2,0,0,2),(1387,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','After showing p is even (p = 2m), substituting into p² = 2q² gives 4m² = 2q², so q² =:','4m','m²','2m²','m/2','C',2,0,0,2),(1388,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','If q² = 2m², what can we conclude about q?','q is odd','q is even','q = m','q = 2','B',2,0,0,2),(1389,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','The proof shows both p and q are even. Why does this give a contradiction?','Even numbers cannot be squared','p/q was assumed to be in lowest terms, so p and q can''t both be even','Even numbers are not integers','p/q must be less than 2','B',3,0,0,3),(1390,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','The proof that √2 is irrational uses the method of:','Direct proof','Proof by induction','Proof by contradiction','Proof by example','C',3,0,0,3),(1391,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','The key parity fact used in the proof is: if n² is even, then n is even. Which of the following demonstrates this using odd numbers?','3² = 9 (odd), 5² = 25 (odd), so odd² is always odd','2² = 4 (even), 4² = 16 (even), so even² is always even','1² = 1 (odd), proving n² can be odd','Both A and C','D',3,0,0,3),(1392,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','Could the same proof method show that √3 is irrational?','No, the proof only works for √2','Yes, a similar argument shows no fraction squares to 3','No, because 3 is odd','Yes, but only for even denominators','B',3,0,0,3),(1393,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','In the proof, after establishing p = 2m and substituting: p² = (2m)² = 4m² = 2q², we get q² = 2m². The logical chain then concludes q is even. What does this contradict?','Our assumption that p is even','Our assumption that p and q have no common factor','Our assumption that 2 is an integer','Our assumption that p > q','B',4,0,0,4),(1394,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','The proof shows the assumption that √2 = p/q (in lowest terms) leads to both p and q being even. What does this mean for the original assumption?','The assumption is correct but needs modification','The assumption must be false — √2 cannot equal any fraction','We need to find a different fraction','p and q must be very large numbers','B',4,0,0,4),(1395,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','Why is it essential to assume p/q is in lowest terms at the start of the proof?','To make p and q small numbers','Because ''both even'' is only a contradiction if they were assumed to share no common factor','To ensure p > q','To make the algebra simpler','B',4,0,0,4),(1396,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','A student tries to apply the same proof to show √4 is irrational. Where does the argument break down?','4 is not an integer','The argument works and proves √4 is irrational','When p² = 4q², you get p = 2q, so p/q = 2 — a valid rational number with no contradiction','The proof requires p/q > 1','C',4,0,0,4),(1397,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','The proof relies on: ''if n² is even, then n is even.'' Which is the correct proof of this sub-claim?','Even numbers when squared give even numbers, so the converse holds','By contrapositive: if n is odd, n = 2k+1, so n² = 4k²+4k+1 = 2(2k²+2k)+1, which is odd','All squares are even','This follows directly from the definition of even','B',5,0,0,5),(1398,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','The proof shows p and q are both divisible by 2, contradicting that p/q is in lowest terms. Which logical principle is being used to conclude √2 is irrational?','Modus ponens','Reductio ad absurdum (proof by contradiction)','Mathematical induction','The well-ordering principle','B',5,0,0,5),(1399,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','If we did not require p/q to be in lowest terms in the proof, what would go wrong?','We would get p is odd instead of even','Finding that both p and q are even would not be a contradiction — they might already share factor 2','The algebra p² = 2q² would be incorrect','Nothing would go wrong; the proof still works','B',5,0,0,5),(1400,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'2','New Numbers',12,'Appendix: Proof that No Fraction Squares to 2','The proof establishes √2 ∉ ℚ (is not rational). To fully say √2 is a ''new kind of number'', what else must be true?','√2 must be negative','√2 must have a well-defined position on the number line and satisfy x² = 2','√2 must be larger than all rational numbers','√2 must equal some other irrational number','B',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (1401,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the beads problem in this chapter, there are 100 beads that are black and white, with 10 more black than white. How many black beads are there?','45','50','55','60','C',1,0,0,1),(1402,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the beads problem, if x is the number of black beads and there are 10 more black than white, which expression gives the number of white beads?','x + 10','x − 10','10 − x','x ÷ 10','B',1,0,0,1),(1403,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the table-and-chair problem in this chapter, what is the combined price of the table and chair?','10000 rupees','11000 rupees','12000 rupees','14000 rupees','B',1,0,0,1),(1404,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the two-number problem in this chapter, the larger number is 5 times the smaller. If the smaller number is x, how is the larger number expressed?','x + 5','5 + x','5x','x ÷ 5','C',1,0,0,1),(1405,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the fraction problem solved in this chapter (where adding 1 to the numerator gives 1/2), what is the numerator of the fraction?','1','2','3','4','C',1,0,0,1),(1406,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the beads problem, taking x as the number of black beads, which equation is formed?','x + x = 100','x + (x − 10) = 100','x − (x + 10) = 100','2x + 10 = 90','B',1,0,0,1),(1407,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the table-and-chair problem, if the chair costs x rupees and the total price is 11000 rupees, which expression gives the price of the table?','x − 11000','11000 + x','11000 − x','x × 11000','C',2,0,0,2),(1408,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','Two numbers have a sum of 26 and a difference of 4. Which pair of equations correctly represents this situation?','x + y = 26, x × y = 4','x + y = 26, x − y = 4','x − y = 26, x + y = 4','x × y = 26, x + y = 4','B',2,0,0,2),(1409,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the fraction problem, the condition ''adding 1 to the numerator gives 1/2'' is written as which equation?','x + 1 = y ÷ 2','(x + 1) ÷ y = 1/2','x ÷ (y + 1) = 1/2','(x + 1) ÷ (y + 1) = 1/2','B',2,0,0,2),(1410,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','Priya bought a bag and a pair of slippers for 1100 rupees. The bag costs 300 rupees more than the slippers. If x is the price of the slippers, what is the price of the bag?','x − 300','1100 − x','x + 300','300x','C',2,0,0,2),(1411,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the two-number problem, if the smaller number is x and the larger is 5x, what equation is formed from ''subtracting the smaller from the larger gives 32''?','5x + x = 32','5x − x = 32','5x × x = 32','x − 5x = 32','B',2,0,0,2),(1412,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','From the equation 4x = 32 in the two-number problem, what is the value of x (the smaller number)?','4','6','8','10','C',2,0,0,2),(1413,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the table-and-chair problem, taking the chair price as x and table price as (11000 − x), substituting into the second condition (table + 4 chairs = 14000) gives which equation?','11000 + x = 14000','11000 + 3x = 14000','11000 − 3x = 14000','11000 + 4x = 14000','B',3,0,0,3),(1414,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','From the equation y = 2(x + 1) obtained in the fraction problem, and the second condition y + 1 = 3x, which value of x is obtained?','2','3','4','5','B',3,0,0,3),(1415,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the fraction problem, the condition ''(x + 1) / y = 1/2'' means that y equals which expression?','y = (x + 1) / 2','y = 2(x + 1)','y = 2x + 1','y = x + 2','B',3,0,0,3),(1416,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','The perimeter of a rectangle is 40 cm and one side is 8 cm longer than the other. If the longer side is x cm, what is the shorter side in terms of x?','x − 8','x + 8','40 − x','8x','A',3,0,0,3),(1417,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In a class there are 4 more girls than boys. On a day when 8 boys were absent, the number of girls was twice the number of boys present. If b represents the total number of boys, which equation models this situation?','b + 4 = 2(b − 8)','b + 4 = 2b + 8','b − 4 = 2(b − 8)','b + 4 = 2(b + 8)','A',3,0,0,3),(1418,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In the chapter, the method of replacing y with an expression in x (derived from one equation) and using it in the second equation is called:','Elimination method','Substitution method','Graphical method','Trial-and-error method','B',3,0,0,3),(1419,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','Using the pair of equations x + y = 11000 and 4x + y = 14000 (where x = price of chair), what is the price of the chair?','500 rupees','750 rupees','1000 rupees','1250 rupees','C',4,0,0,4),(1420,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','A wire 3.5 metres long is cut so one piece forms a square and the other an equilateral triangle, with all sides equal in length s (in metres). Which equation models the total wire used?','4s + 3s = 35','4s + 3s = 3.5','4s + 3s = 0.35','4s = 3s','B',4,0,0,4),(1421,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','Using the equations x + y = 26 and x − y = 4, what are the values of x and y?','x = 14, y = 12','x = 15, y = 11','x = 16, y = 10','x = 13, y = 13','B',4,0,0,4),(1422,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','An object''s speed at t = 1 second is 5 m/s and at t = 5 seconds is 13 m/s. Using the formula speed = u + at, which pair of equations is correct?','u + a = 5, u + 5a = 13','u + a = 13, u + 5a = 5','u − a = 5, u − 5a = 13','u + a = 5, 5u + a = 13','A',4,0,0,4),(1423,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','A person invested 100000 rupees in two schemes at 7% and 6%. After one year the total interest was 6750 rupees. If x rupees were invested at 7%, which equation represents the interest?','0.07x + 0.06(100000 − x) = 6750','7x + 6x = 6750','0.07x + 0.06x = 6750','7x + 6(100000 − x) = 6750','A',4,0,0,4),(1424,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','Using y = 2(x + 1) and y + 1 = 3x in the fraction problem, after finding x = 3, what is the denominator y of the fraction?','6','7','8','9','C',4,0,0,4),(1425,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','A person invested 100000 rupees at 7% and 6% interest. Total interest after one year was 6750 rupees. How much was invested at 7%?','60000 rupees','65000 rupees','75000 rupees','80000 rupees','C',5,0,0,5),(1426,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','An object starts with speed u m/s and its speed at t = 1 second is 5 m/s, at t = 5 seconds is 13 m/s. What is the rate of increase of speed a (in m/s per second)?','1','2','3','4','B',5,0,0,5),(1427,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','A fraction: adding 1 to its numerator gives 1/3; adding 1 to its denominator gives 1/4. Taking the numerator as x and denominator as y, which pair of equations represents this?','(x + 1) / y = 1/3,  x / (y + 1) = 1/4','x / (y + 1) = 1/3,  (x + 1) / y = 1/4','(x + 1) / y = 1/4,  x / (y + 1) = 1/3','(x + 1) / (y + 1) = 1/3,  x / y = 1/4','A',5,0,0,5),(1428,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','A fraction has the property that adding 1 to its numerator gives 1/3 and adding 1 to its denominator gives 1/4. What is the fraction?','12-Mar','15-Apr','10-Mar','16-May','B',5,0,0,5),(1429,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','In a class, there are 4 more girls than boys. On a day when 8 boys were absent, girls were twice the boys present. How many boys are there in total?','16','18','20','24','C',5,0,0,5),(1430,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Mental Math and Algebra','A wire 3.5 metres long is cut so one piece forms a square and the other an equilateral triangle, with all sides equal. What is the side length of each shape?','0.4 m','0.5 m','0.6 m','0.7 m','B',5,0,0,5),(1431,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pens-and-notebooks problem, the price of 2 pens and 3 notebooks is 110 rupees. The price of 2 pens and 5 notebooks is 170 rupees. By how much does the second purchase exceed the first?','40 rupees','50 rupees','60 rupees','70 rupees','C',1,0,0,1),(1432,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pens-and-notebooks problem, the price increase of 60 rupees from the first to the second purchase is entirely due to how many extra notebooks?','1','2','3','4','B',1,0,0,1),(1433,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','From the pens-and-notebooks problem, what is the price of one notebook?','20 rupees','25 rupees','30 rupees','35 rupees','C',1,0,0,1),(1434,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','From the pens-and-notebooks problem, what is the price of one pen?','5 rupees','10 rupees','15 rupees','20 rupees','B',1,0,0,1),(1435,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pencils-and-pens problem (3 pencils + 4 pens = 66 rupees; 6 pencils + 3 pens = 72 rupees), which operation does the chapter perform on the first equation to make the number of pencils equal in both?','Divide it by 2','Multiply it by 2','Add it to the second equation','Subtract the second from it','B',1,0,0,1),(1436,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','Which of the following Computer Algebra Systems is mentioned in this chapter?','MATLAB','Mathematica','GeoGebra','Python','C',1,0,0,1),(1437,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pencils-and-pens problem, after multiplying the first equation by 2, the third row of the table shows 6 pencils and 8 pens costing how much?','112 rupees','122 rupees','132 rupees','142 rupees','C',1,0,0,1),(1438,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pens-and-notebooks problem with equations 2x + 3y = 110 and 2x + 5y = 170, subtracting the first from the second gives which equation?','2y = 60','4x = 60','2y = 80','y = 60','A',2,0,0,2),(1439,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pencils-and-pens problem, equations 3x + 4y = 66 and 6x + 3y = 72. After multiplying the first equation by 2, which new equation is obtained?','6x + 8y = 66','6x + 4y = 132','6x + 8y = 132','9x + 8y = 132','C',2,0,0,2),(1440,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','After establishing that 5y = 60 in the pencils-and-pens problem (y = price of a pen), what is the price of one pen?','6 rupees','10 rupees','12 rupees','15 rupees','C',2,0,0,2),(1441,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','According to the chapter''s discussion on information and solutions, how many pairs of numbers (x, y) satisfy just one equation such as x + y = 10?','Exactly one pair','Exactly two pairs','No pair','Infinitely many pairs','D',2,0,0,2),(1442,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','The chapter states that the equations x + y = 10 and x − y = 2 have exactly one solution. What is that solution?','x = 5, y = 5','x = 6, y = 4','x = 7, y = 3','x = 8, y = 2','B',2,0,0,2),(1443,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pens-and-notebooks problem, once y = 30 (price of a notebook), what is the cost of 3 notebooks?','60 rupees','75 rupees','90 rupees','100 rupees','C',2,0,0,2),(1444,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','From 3x + 4(12) = 66 in the pencils-and-pens problem, what is the price of one pencil?','4 rupees','6 rupees','8 rupees','10 rupees','B',2,0,0,2),(1445,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pens-and-notebooks problem, the price of 2 pens is found by subtracting the cost of 3 notebooks (90 rupees) from 110 rupees. What is the price of one pen?','5 rupees','8 rupees','10 rupees','15 rupees','C',3,0,0,3),(1446,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','The price of 4 pens and 3 pencils is 66 rupees; the price of 7 pens and 3 pencils is 111 rupees. What is the price of one pen?','12 rupees','13 rupees','14 rupees','15 rupees','D',3,0,0,3),(1447,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','Using the result that a pen costs 15 rupees (from 4 pens + 3 pencils = 66 rupees), what is the price of a pencil?','2 rupees','3 rupees','4 rupees','5 rupees','A',3,0,0,3),(1448,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','A rectangle has perimeter 26 cm. Another rectangle with twice the length and thrice the breadth has perimeter 62 cm. If the original length is l and breadth is b, which simplified pair of equations is correct?','l + b = 13, 2l + 3b = 31','l + b = 26, 2l + 3b = 62','l + b = 13, 3l + 2b = 31','l + b = 26, 2l + 3b = 31','A',3,0,0,3),(1449,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the ''Nothing new'' example, Ramu paid 7 rupees for a pencil and a pen, and Aju paid 28 rupees for 4 pencils and 4 pens. Why can the individual prices not be determined?','The prices were too small to measure','Both equations are mathematically equivalent and give no unique solution','One of the equations had an error','The prices cancel out when added','B',3,0,0,3),(1450,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the chapter, the GeoGebra CAS command used to solve the equations 5x + 2y = 20 and 2x + 3y = 19 is:','Compute({5x + 2y = 20, 2x + 3y = 19}, {x, y})','Solve({5x + 2y = 20, 2x + 3y = 19}, {x, y})','Find({5x + 2y = 20, 2x + 3y = 19}, {x, y})','Solve[5x + 2y = 20, 2x + 3y = 19]','B',3,0,0,3),(1451,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Two Equations','In the pencils-and-pens problem, after writing equations (1): 3x + 4y = 66 and (2): 6x + 3y = 72, the chapter labels 2 × equation (1) as equation (3). Which step follows to find the price of a pen?','Subtract equation (1) from equation (2)','Subtract equation (2) from equation (3)','Add equation (2) and equation (3)','Multiply equation (2) by 2','B',3,0,0,3),(1452,'Kerala',9,'English'