er','The product of the two numbers','The average of the two numbers','B',1,0,0,1),(1472,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','According to the general principle in this chapter, subtracting the difference from the sum of two numbers gives:','Twice the larger number','Twice the smaller number','The sum itself','Zero','B',1,0,0,1),(1473,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','In the vessel problem (5x + 2y = 20, 2x + 3y = 19), to make the x-coefficients equal (both 10), by what numbers must the two equations be multiplied respectively?','First by 2, second by 5','First by 5, second by 2','First by 3, second by 2','First by 2, second by 3','A',2,0,0,2),(1474,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','After multiplying 5x + 2y = 20 by 2 and 2x + 3y = 19 by 5, the two new equations are:','10x + 4y = 40 and 10x + 15y = 95','10x + 4y = 40 and 10x + 15y = 90','10x + 4y = 45 and 10x + 15y = 95','10x + 4y = 40 and 10x + 10y = 95','A',2,0,0,2),(1475,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','Subtracting 10x + 4y = 40 from 10x + 15y = 95 gives which equation?','11y = 45','11y = 50','11y = 55','11y = 60','C',2,0,0,2),(1476,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','From 11y = 55 in the vessel problem, what is the value of y (capacity of the big vessel)?','4','5','6','7','B',2,0,0,2),(1477,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','In the problem with equations 4x + 3y = 43 and 3x − 2y = 11, the chapter multiplies equation (1) by 3 and equation (2) by 4 to equalise x-coefficients. Which new equations result?','12x + 9y = 129 and 12x − 8y = 44','12x + 9y = 129 and 12x + 8y = 44','12x + 9y = 43 and 12x − 8y = 44','12x + 9y = 129 and 12x + 8y = 48','A',2,0,0,2),(1478,'Kerala',9,'English','Ma