hree angles of the triangle?','30°, 60°, 90°','35°, 55°, 90°','40°, 50°, 90°','45°, 45°, 90°','B',5,0,0,5),(1499,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','In the ''Math and Reality'' box, a rectangle of perimeter 10 m is needed with length 5.5 m more than breadth. Setting up the equations shows this is impossible. Why?','The perimeter value is too large','The difference (5.5 m) exceeds the half-perimeter (5 m), making the breadth negative','The two equations are identical','The system has infinitely many solutions','B',5,0,0,5),(1500,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'1','Pairs of Equations',11,'Solving by Elimination','Using the general principle from this chapter — if the sum of two numbers is S and their difference is D — which expression gives the larger number?','(S − D) / 2','(S + D) / 2','(S × D) / 2','S − D','B',5,0,0,5),(1501,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Equal Division','What does it mean for parallel lines to be ''equally spaced apart''?','They meet at infinity','The perpendicular distance between consecutive lines is the same','They are on the same side of a transversal','Their slopes add to zero','B',1,0,0,1),(1502,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Equal Division','Three equally spaced parallel lines cut a transversal. If the first segment is 5 cm, the second segment is:','10 cm','2.5 cm','5 cm','7 cm','C',1,0,0,1),(1503,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Equal Division','Equal division by parallel lines means any transversal cut by those lines is divided into:','Unequal parts','Equal parts','Parts proportional to the angles','Parts whose product equals 1','B',1,0,0,1),(1504,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Equal Division','Four equally spaced parallel lines divide a line into three equal segments each of 4 cm. The total length of the divided part is:','4 cm','8 cm','12 cm','16 cm','C',2,