ersals cross the same set of equally spaced parallel lines. On the first transversal, each segment = 3 cm; on the second, each = 5 cm. What can we conclude?','The transversals are not straight lines','The parallel lines are not equally spaced','Both transversals are divided into equal parts, just with different lengths per segment','The segments must be equal on both transversals','C',4,0,0,4),(1513,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Equal Division','The property that equally spaced parallel lines divide any transversal into equal parts is used to justify which construction technique?','Bisecting an angle','Drawing a perpendicular from a point','Dividing a line segment into n equal parts using parallel lines','Constructing an equilateral triangle','C',5,0,0,5),(1514,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Equal Division','Equal division by parallel lines applies to transversals that are not parallel to those lines. If a transversal is drawn at a 45° angle to equally spaced horizontal parallel lines, the equal division property:','Fails because the angle changes the distances','Still holds — the transversal is divided into equal segments','Only holds for perpendicular transversals','Holds only if the angle is 90°','B',5,0,0,5),(1515,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Equal Division','Equally spaced parallel lines produce equal segments on a transversal. If you add one more equally spaced parallel line, the effect on each segment of the same transversal is:','No change to existing segments','All segments are now smaller by one unit','A new equal-length segment is added','All previous segments double','C',5,0,0,5),(1516,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Unequal Division','When three or more parallel lines (not equally spaced) cut two transversals, the segments on the two transversals are in:','Equal ratio only','The same ratio','Inverse ratio','No predictable relatio