ine XY parallel to BC is drawn so that AX:XB = 3:2, what is XY?','10','12','8','6','B',4,0,0,4),(1577,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Midsection','The midpoint theorem can be proved using the parallel lines proportional division theorem. The key step is: since M and N are midpoints, AM/MB = AN/NC = 1:1, so by the converse of the triangle division theorem:','MN = BC','MN ⊥ BC','MN || BC','MN bisects BC','C',5,0,0,5),(1578,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Midsection','A quadrilateral ABCD has midpoints M, N, P, Q of sides AB, BC, CD, DA. The quadrilateral MNPQ formed is always a:','Rectangle','Rhombus','Parallelogram','Square','C',5,0,0,5),(1579,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Midsection','In triangle ABC, M and N are midpoints of AB and BC respectively. The midsection MN is parallel to AC and MN = AC/2. A student uses this to conclude triangle BMN is similar to triangle BAC. The scale factor is:','2','2-Jan','4-Jan','4','B',5,0,0,5),(1580,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Midsection','In triangle ABC, M is the midpoint of AB, N is the midpoint of AC, and P is the midpoint of BC. Which of the following is a correct statement using the midpoint theorem?','MN = MP = NP = BC/2','MN = NP = MP, all equal to half a different side','MN = BC/2, NP = AB/2, MP = AC/2','MN + NP + MP = perimeter of ABC','C',5,0,0,5),(1581,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The point where the three altitudes of a triangle meet is called the:','Centroid','Circumcentre','Orthocentre','Incentre','C',1,0,0,1),(1582,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The centroid of a triangle is the point where the three _______ meet:','Altitudes','Medians','Perpendicular bisectors','Angle bisectors','B',1,0,0,1),(1583,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The circumcentre of a triangle is equidistant from:','The three sides','The three altitudes','The three vertices','The three medians','C',1,0,0,1),(1584,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The Euler line of a triangle passes through which three points?','Three vertices','Orthocentre, centroid, and circumcentre','Midpoints of the three sides','Three angle bisector intersection points','B',1,0,0,1),(1585,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The centroid divides each median in the ratio:','1:01','1:02','2:1 (from vertex)','3:01','C',2,0,0,2),(1586,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','A median of a triangle connects:','Two midpoints of sides','A vertex to the midpoint of the opposite side','Two vertices of the triangle','A vertex to the orthocentre','B',2,0,0,2),(1587,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The centroid of a triangle lies at what fractional distance along each median from the vertex?','3-Jan','2-Jan','3-Feb','4-Mar','C',2,0,0,2),(1588,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The circumcentre of a triangle is the centre of the circle that:','Is inscribed inside the triangle','Passes through all three vertices','Passes through all three midpoints','Has the same area as the triangle','B',2,0,0,2),(1589,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','In triangle ABC, the median from A to BC has length 12 cm. The centroid G divides this median such that AG =:','4 cm','6 cm','8 cm','9 cm','C',3,0,0,3),(1590,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The orthocentre, centroid, and circumcentre are collinear. The centroid divides the segment from orthocentre to circumcentre in ratio:','1:01','2:01','1:02','3:01','B',3,0,0,3),(1591,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','For an equilateral triangle, which of the following is true?','Orthocentre and centroid are different points','Circumcentre, centroid, and orthocentre all coincide','Only the orthocentre and circumcentre coincide','The Euler line does not exist','B',3,0,0,3),(1592,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','In a right triangle, the orthocentre is located:','Inside the triangle','At the midpoint of the hypotenuse','At the right angle vertex','Outside the triangle','C',3,0,0,3),(1593,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','In triangle ABC, centroid G lies on median AD (D is midpoint of BC). If AD = 15, what is GD?','5','10','7.5','3','A',4,0,0,4),(1594,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The Euler line result for a triangle shows that the centroid G divides the segment from orthocentre H to circumcentre O in ratio HG:GO = 2:1. If HO = 9 cm, find HG:','3 cm','6 cm','4.5 cm','9 cm','B',4,0,0,4),(1595,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','A triangle has three medians, each of length 12 cm. What is the distance from the centroid to each vertex?','4 cm','6 cm','8 cm','12 cm','C',4,0,0,4),(1596,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','For an obtuse triangle, the circumcentre is located:','Inside the triangle','On the longest side','Outside the triangle','At the obtuse vertex','C',4,0,0,4),(1597,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The centroid divides each median in ratio 2:1 from the vertex. The proof of this uses the fact that the centroid is the intersection of medians. Which property of parallel lines and triangles is central to showing this ratio?','The equal division theorem','The midsection (midpoint) theorem applied to the smaller triangle formed by one median','The Euler line theorem','The circumcentre equidistance property','B',5,0,0,5),(1598,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','In triangle ABC, G is the centroid. Medians AD, BE, CF all pass through G. AG:GD = 2:1. If AD = 18, BE = 15, CF = 12, find the sum AG + BG + CG:','30','45','15','30','A',5,0,0,5),(1599,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The Euler line connects orthocentre H, centroid G, and circumcentre O in that order, with HG:GO = 2:1. Which of the following correctly describes G''s position on HO?','G is 1/3 of the way from H to O','G is 2/3 of the way from H to O','G is the midpoint of HO','G is 1/4 of the way from H to O','B',5,0,0,5),(1600,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'3','Parallel Lines',13,'Triangle Centres','The circumcentre of a triangle is equidistant from all three vertices. This means it is the centre of the circumscribed circle. For a right triangle, the circumradius equals:','Half the shortest side','Half the hypotenuse','The length of the altitude','The length of the median to the hypotenuse','B',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (1601,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Two triangles are similar if their corresponding angles are:','Supplementary','Complementary','Equal','Right angles','C',1,0,0,1),(1602,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In similar triangles, corresponding sides are:','Equal','In the same ratio','Parallel','Perpendicular','B',1,0,0,1),(1603,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','The ratio of corresponding sides of similar triangles is called the:','Perimeter','Scale factor','Area ratio','Angle sum','B',1,0,0,1),(1604,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In triangle ABC ~ triangle PQR (AA similarity), if ∠A = ∠P and ∠B = ∠Q, then ∠C equals:','∠A','∠B','∠R','90°','C',1,0,0,1),(1605,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Sides opposite equal angles in two triangles with the same angles are:','Equal','Parallel','In the same ratio (proportional)','Perpendicular','C',1,0,0,1),(1606,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','If two triangles have all three pairs of angles equal, they are called:','Congruent','Similar','Equilateral','Right','B',1,0,0,1),(1607,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF (AA). AB = 4, DE = 8. The scale factor k is:','2','4','2-Jan','8','A',2,0,0,2),(1608,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','If triangle ABC ~ triangle PQR with scale factor 3, and PQ = 6, find AB:','18','2','6','9','B',2,0,0,2),(1609,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In similar triangles with ∠A = ∠P = 60°, ∠B = ∠Q = 80°, ∠C and ∠R are each:','50°','40°','60°','80°','B',2,0,0,2),(1610,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Two triangles with the same angles have sides 3, 4, 5 and 6, 8, x. Find x:','8','10','7','12','B',2,0,0,2),(1611,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','If triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF with AB/DE = 2/3, and BC = 6, find EF:','4','9','12','6','B',2,0,0,2),(1612,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','The AA (Angle-Angle) condition states that two triangles are similar if:','Two angles of one equal two angles of the other','All three angles are 60°','Two sides are equal','The triangles have the same area','A',2,0,0,2),(1613,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF. AB = 5, BC = 7, DE = 10. Find EF:','12','14','7','5','B',3,0,0,3),(1614,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In triangle ABC, ∠A = 50°. In triangle PQR, ∠P = 50° and ∠Q = 70°. In triangle ABC, if ∠B = 70°, are the triangles similar?','No, only one angle matches','Yes, by AA (∠A=∠P, ∠B=∠Q)','Only if their sides are equal','No, we need all three angles','B',3,0,0,3),(1615,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Triangle XYZ ~ triangle PQR with scale factor k = 3/2. If PQ = 10, find XY:','15','20','5','10','A',3,0,0,3),(1616,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Two poles stand vertically. At the same time, a 2 m pole casts a shadow of 3 m, and a second pole casts a shadow of 12 m. The height of the second pole is:','6 m','8 m','10 m','18 m','B',3,0,0,3),(1617,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In triangle ABC, D is on AB and E is on AC such that DE || BC. Triangle ADE ~ triangle ABC. If AD/AB = 3/5 and BC = 20, find DE:','10','12','15','8','B',3,0,0,3),(1618,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In a right triangle, the altitude from the right angle to the hypotenuse creates two smaller triangles, each similar to the original. This is because:','They share the same base','Each small triangle has the same angles as the original (AA)','All right triangles are similar','The altitude bisects the hypotenuse','B',3,0,0,3),(1619,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF with scale factor k. If the perimeter of ABC is P₁ and of DEF is P₂, then P₁:P₂ =','k²:1','k:1','1:k','k:k','B',4,0,0,4),(1620,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In triangle ABC, the altitude from A meets BC at D. Triangle ABD ~ triangle CAD. Which angles are equal?','∠ABD = ∠CAD and ∠ADB = ∠CDA = 90°','∠ABC = ∠CAB','∠B = ∠C only','All three pairs of angles','A',4,0,0,4),(1621,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Two similar triangles have perimeters 18 and 30. The scale factor k (larger to smaller) is:','5-Mar','3-May','18/30 = 3/5','Both A and C','D',4,0,0,4),(1622,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In triangle ABC, ∠A = 40°, ∠B = 70°. A line DE is drawn such that triangle ADE ~ triangle ABC. What are ∠ADE and ∠AED?','70° and 40°','40° and 70°','∠ADE = 70° = ∠B and ∠AED = 70° = ∠C','∠ADE = ∠B = 70° and ∠AED = ∠C = 70°','C',4,0,0,4),(1623,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Triangle ABC has sides 6, 8, 10. Triangle PQR has sides 9, 12, 15. Are they similar?','No, sides are different','Yes, scale factor = 3/2 (all sides in ratio 2:3)','Only if they have the same angles','Yes, by AA','B',4,0,0,4),(1624,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In right triangle ABC with right angle at C, the altitude CD is drawn to AB. If AD = 4 and DB = 9, find CD:','6','√36 = 6','CD² = AD × DB = 36, so CD = 6','All of the above','D',4,0,0,4),(1625,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','The chapter states: ''sides opposite equal angles are in the same ratio.'' This means if ∠A = ∠P in similar triangles, then BC/QR = AC/PR = AB/PQ. Which side is BC opposite?','∠B','∠A','∠C','∠A (since BC is opposite vertex A)','D',5,0,0,5),(1626,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','AA similarity requires only two pairs of equal angles. Why is the third pair automatically equal?','Because the triangles are congruent','Because the angle sum of any triangle is 180°, so the third angle is determined','Because corresponding sides are parallel','It is not automatically equal','B',5,0,0,5),(1627,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF with AB/DE = 5/8. If BC = 10 and CA = 15, find EF and FD:','EF=16, FD=24','EF=16, FD=20','EF=6.25, FD=9.375','EF=8, FD=12','A',5,0,0,5),(1628,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Two triangles ABC and PQR are such that ∠A + ∠B = ∠P + ∠Q. Are they necessarily similar?','Yes, by AA','Not necessarily — ∠C = ∠R only; we also need ∠A=∠P or ∠B=∠Q','Yes, because ∠C = 180 - (∠A+∠B) = 180-(∠P+∠Q) = ∠R','Both A and C','C',5,0,0,5),(1629,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF with scale factor k. Which of the following is a correct statement?','AB² = k × DE²','AB/DE = BC/EF = CA/FD = k','AB + DE = k','AB = DE always','B',5,0,0,5),(1630,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Angles and Sides','In a right triangle ABC (right angle at B), the altitude BD to AC divides it into triangles ABD and BDC. Show that BD² = AD × DC using similarity:','△ABD ~ △BDC by AA (both right-angled, share ∠D), so BD/AD = DC/BD → BD² = AD×DC ✓','BD² = AB × BC by Pythagoras','BD = AD + DC','BD² = AB² + BC² - AC²','A',5,0,0,5),(1631,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','If all three pairs of corresponding sides of two triangles are in the same ratio, the triangles are similar. This is called:','AA similarity','SSS similarity','SAS similarity','RHS congruence','B',1,0,0,1),(1632,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','SSS similarity means all corresponding sides are in ratio k. What can be concluded about the angles?','All angles are 60°','All corresponding angles are equal','All angles are right angles','No conclusion about angles','B',1,0,0,1),(1633,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle ABC has sides 3, 4, 5. Triangle DEF has sides 6, 8, 10. The scale factor is:','1','2','3','10','B',1,0,0,1),(1634,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','If two triangles are similar with scale factor k=1, they are:','Similar only','Congruent','Equilateral','Isosceles','B',1,0,0,1),(1635,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','For SSS similarity, the ratio of sides must be:','1:01','The same for all three pairs of corresponding sides','An integer','Greater than 1','B',1,0,0,1),(1636,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle ABC has sides 4, 6, 8. Triangle PQR has sides 6, 9, 12. Are they similar by SSS?','No, sides differ','Yes, ratio = 2:3 for all pairs','Only if angles are equal','Yes, ratio = 3:2','B',2,0,0,2),(1637,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle with sides 5, 12, 13 and triangle with sides 10, 24, 26 — scale factor of smaller to larger:','2','2-Jan','3','5','B',2,0,0,2),(1638,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle ABC with sides 2, 3, 4 and triangle DEF with sides 6, 9, 12 are similar. Which angle of DEF equals ∠A of ABC?','∠D (side opposite to ∠A corresponds to side opposite ∠D)','∠E','∠F','Cannot determine without knowing the angles','A',2,0,0,2),(1639,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','If all sides of triangle A are twice the corresponding sides of triangle B, what is the scale factor?','4','2','2-Jan','√2','B',2,0,0,2),(1640,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle P has sides 7, 24, 25. Triangle Q has sides 14, 48, 50. By SSS similarity, what is the scale factor from P to Q?','2','2-Jan','7','3','A',2,0,0,2),(1641,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle with sides 3, 4, 5 (right triangle) and triangle with sides a, b, c. If a/3 = b/4 = c/5 = 2, find a, b, c and identify the triangle type:','6, 8, 10 — a right triangle','6, 8, 10 — not a right triangle','3, 4, 5 — same as original','6, 8, 11','A',3,0,0,3),(1642,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','By SSS similarity, if all corresponding sides are in ratio k, then corresponding angles are equal. Can we say the triangles are always congruent?','Yes, if k=1 they are congruent; otherwise only similar','Yes always','No, similar triangles are never congruent','Only for right triangles','A',3,0,0,3),(1643,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle ABC has sides AB=4, BC=6, CA=8. Triangle DEF has sides DE=6, EF=9, FD=12. The similarity is ABC ~ DEF. Find the scale factor DE/AB:','2-Mar','3-Feb','6-Apr','1','A',3,0,0,3),(1644,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Two triangles have sides in ratio 3:5:4 and 6:10:8. Which similarity condition applies?','AA','SAS','SSS (all sides in ratio 1:2)','RHS','C',3,0,0,3),(1645,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','If triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF by SSS with scale factor k=4/3, and ∠B = 55°, then ∠E =','55° × 4/3 = 73.3°','55°','90°','Cannot be determined','B',3,0,0,3),(1646,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Two triangles have sides 5, x, 13 and 10, 24, 26. For SSS similarity, find x:','10','12','13','6','B',4,0,0,4),(1647,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','SSS similarity states that if all corresponding sides are in ratio k, the triangles are similar. The converse (if similar then SSS) means:','Similar triangles always have equal sides','If two triangles are similar, then their corresponding sides are all in the same ratio k','k must equal 1 for the converse to work','The converse is not true','B',4,0,0,4),(1648,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF (SSS) with AB=6, BC=8, CA=10, DE=9, EF=12. Find FD:','12','15','10','16','B',4,0,0,4),(1649,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle P has sides 2, 3, 4 and triangle Q has sides 3, 4, 5. Are they similar?','Yes, by SSS','No — 2/3 ≠ 3/4 ≠ 4/5, so sides are not in proportion','Yes, they share a common side length','Cannot determine without angles','B',4,0,0,4),(1650,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','If all sides of triangle A are multiplied by k to get triangle B, then all angles of B equal those of A. The reason is:','Angles depend only on the ratios of sides, not their absolute lengths','Multiplying by k adds k° to each angle','Parallel sides create equal angles','Multiplying sides by k² gives equal angles','A',4,0,0,4),(1651,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','To test SSS similarity, a student checks only two side ratios and assumes the third must match. Is this correct?','Yes, if two ratios are equal, so is the third','No — all three ratios must be checked independently','Yes, for right triangles only','Yes, because the angle sum = 180° implies the third ratio','B',5,0,0,5),(1652,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','The SSS similarity test is used to prove that equilateral triangles are all similar. The reason is:','All equilateral triangles have equal angles','All equilateral triangles have sides in ratio 1:1:1 (to each other, scaling by the side length), so by SSS all are similar','Equilateral triangles are all congruent','Both A and B','D',5,0,0,5),(1653,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Can two right triangles with the same hypotenuse but different legs be similar?','Yes, always','No — if hypotenuses are equal (k=1), similarity implies congruence, requiring all sides equal','Yes, if their acute angles differ','Only if both are isoceles','B',5,0,0,5),(1654,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','The SSS similarity test and the SSS congruence test differ because:','Congruence requires k=1 (sides equal), similarity allows any k','Similarity requires more angles','Congruence applies to more triangles','SSS similarity only works for right triangles','A',5,0,0,5),(1655,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Sides and Angles','Triangle ABC has sides in ratio 1:1:√2. Triangle DEF has sides in ratio 1:1:√2 (scaled by 5). By SSS similarity, these are similar. What can be said about their angles?','45°-45°-90° for both (isosceles right triangle)','60°-60°-60°','One has 90° angle, the other does not','Cannot determine','A',5,0,0,5),(1656,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','SAS similarity requires that two triangles have:','Three equal angles','Two sides in the same ratio and the included angle equal','Two equal sides and any angle equal','All sides in ratio k','B',1,0,0,1),(1657,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In SAS similarity, the angle must be between the two sides being compared. This angle is called the:','Opposite angle','Included angle','Exterior angle','Right angle','B',1,0,0,1),(1658,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','The three similarity conditions discussed in the chapter are:','AA, SSS, SAS','AA, ASA, AAS','SSS, SAS, RHS','AA, SAS, SSA','A',1,0,0,1),(1659,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','If two sides of triangle ABC are in ratio 2:3 with two sides of triangle DEF, and the included angles are equal, which similarity condition applies?','AA','SSS','SAS','ASA','C',1,0,0,1),(1660,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In triangles ABC and DEF, AB/DE = AC/DF = 3/4 and ∠A = ∠D. By SAS similarity, triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF. Find BC if EF = 12:','9','16','12','8','A',2,0,0,2),(1661,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','Triangle ABC and triangle DEF have AB = 4, AC = 6, DE = 6, DF = 9, and ∠A = ∠D. Are they similar?','No, sides are different','Yes, AB/DE = AC/DF = 2/3, ∠A = ∠D — SAS similarity','Only by AA','Only if BC = EF','B',2,0,0,2),(1662,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In SAS similarity, two sides of one triangle are 6 and 8, and two corresponding sides of another are 9 and 12. The ratio is:','2:03','3:04','6:8 = 3:4 = 9:12 — so 3:4 ✓','Both B and C','D',2,0,0,2),(1663,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In triangle ABC, D is the midpoint of AB and E is the midpoint of AC. By SAS similarity, triangle ADE ~ triangle ABC because AD/AB = AE/AC = 1/2 and:','∠A = ∠A (common angle)','∠D = ∠B','∠E = ∠C','All three angles match','A',2,0,0,2),(1664,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','Triangle ABC has AB = 5, BC = 7, ∠B = 60°. Triangle DEF has DE = 10, EF = 14, ∠E = 60°. Are they similar by SAS?','No, sides are different','Yes, AB/DE = BC/EF = 1/2, ∠B = ∠E','Only by AA','Only by SSS','B',3,0,0,3),(1665,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In triangle PQR and triangle XYZ, PQ = 6, QR = 10, XY = 9, YZ = 15, ∠Q = ∠Y. Are they similar by SAS? Find the scale factor:','Yes, scale factor = 3/2','No, sides don''t match','Yes, scale factor = 2/3','Only by SSS','A',3,0,0,3),(1666,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','SAS similarity: AB/PQ = BC/QR = k and ∠B = ∠Q. This guarantees triangle ABC ~ triangle PQR with what additional conclusion?','∠A = ∠P and ∠C = ∠R (all angles equal)','Only the included angles are equal','The triangles are congruent','The third sides are equal','A',3,0,0,3),(1667,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','Why must the equal angle in SAS similarity be the included angle (between the two sides), not any angle?','Non-included equal angles can appear in non-similar triangles with two sides in the same ratio','Any equal angle works','The included angle must be 90°','SAS works for any two equal angles','A',3,0,0,3),(1668,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In triangle ABC and triangle ADE where D is on AB and E is on AC, if AD/AB = AE/AC = 2/5, the triangles are similar by SAS with scale factor:','2-May','5-Feb','2','5','B',4,0,0,4),(1669,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','Triangle ABC and triangle DEF: AB = 3, AC = 5, ∠A = 80°, DE = 4.5, DF = 7.5, ∠D = 80°. Find BC if EF = 9:','6','7','9','5','A',4,0,0,4),(1670,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','SAS similarity applied to two triangles with ∠A = ∠D = 90° and AB/DE = AC/DF = k is a special case called:','SAS congruence','RHS similarity (right angle-hypotenuse-side)','AA similarity','AA with right angles','D',4,0,0,4),(1671,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In triangle XYZ and triangle XPQ (P on XY, Q on XZ), XP/XY = XQ/XZ = 3/4. Are the triangles similar?','Yes, by SAS (∠X = ∠X, common angle)','No, only one angle is shared','Yes, but only by SSS','Cannot determine','A',4,0,0,4),(1672,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','SAS similarity is the ''third way'' described in the chapter. How does it differ from AA and SSS?','It requires checking more conditions','It uses a mix of side ratios and an angle, making it useful when we know two sides and their included angle','It is less reliable than AA or SSS','It only works for right triangles','B',5,0,0,5),(1673,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','In the chapter, it is shown that if two sides are scaled by k and the included angle is equal, then the third side is also scaled by k. The key step is:','Using the law of cosines to show c² = a²+b²-2ab cos C, scaling a,b by k gives c scaled by k','Using the triangle inequality','Using the area formula','Using AA similarity','A',5,0,0,5),(1674,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','Triangles ABC and DEF have AB/DE = 2, AC/DF = 2, ∠B = ∠E. Is SAS similarity applicable?','Yes, both side ratios are 2 and an angle is equal','No — the equal angle ∠B is NOT the included angle between AB and AC; it is between AB and BC','Yes, any equal angle works for SAS','No, the side ratio must be 1','B',5,0,0,5),(1675,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Third Way (SAS Similarity)','All three similarity conditions (AA, SSS, SAS) ultimately mean the triangles have equal angles and proportional sides. Which condition is most efficient to check when you know two sides and the angle between them?','AA','SSS','SAS','All are equally efficient','C',5,0,0,5),(1676,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','If two similar triangles have scale factor k, the ratio of their areas is:','k','k²','k³','2k','B',1,0,0,1),(1677,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar triangles have scale factor 3. The ratio of their areas is:','3','6','9','27','C',1,0,0,1),(1678,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','The area scale of similar figures equals the square of the linear scale factor. If sides are in ratio 1:4, areas are in ratio:','1:04','1:08','1:16','4:01','C',1,0,0,1),(1679,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar triangles have areas 9 and 25. The ratio of their corresponding sides is:','9:25','3:05','√9:√25 = 3:5','Both B and C','D',1,0,0,1),(1680,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','If triangle A ~ triangle B with scale factor k=2, and area of A = 10, then area of B =','20','40','5','80','B',1,0,0,1),(1681,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar triangles have sides in ratio 5:3. The larger has area 75. The smaller has area:','27','45','25','15','A',2,0,0,2),(1682,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Triangle ABC has area 16 and is similar to triangle DEF with area 4. The scale factor (ABC:DEF) is:','2','4','8','√2','A',2,0,0,2),(1683,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','In triangle ABC, DE || BC with AD/DB = 1/3. The area of triangle ADE compared to triangle ABC is:','1/9 since AD/AB = 1/4, (1/4)² = 1/16','1/16 since AD/AB = 1/4 and area ratio = (1/4)² = 1/16','4-Jan','3-Jan','B',2,0,0,2),(1684,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar triangles have areas 36 and 100. The ratio of their perimeters is:','6:10 = 3:5','36:100','6:10 (since side ratio = √(area ratio) = 6:10)','Both A and C','D',2,0,0,2),(1685,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Triangle P ~ triangle Q with scale factor 1/2. If area of P = 50, area of Q =','25','12.5','100','200','B',2,0,0,2),(1686,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar triangles have areas in ratio 9:16. A side of the smaller is 6. The corresponding side of the larger is:','8','12','9','10','A',3,0,0,3),(1687,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Triangle ABC has area A₁. Triangle ADE (D on AB, E on AC) has AD = AB/3. Area of ADE =','A₁/3','A₁/9','A₁/6','A₁/4','B',3,0,0,3),(1688,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','The midsection of triangle ABC (DE || BC, D midpoint of AB, E midpoint of AC) divides the triangle. Area of ADE : area of trapezoid BCED =','1:03','1:04','3:01','1:02','A',3,0,0,3),(1689,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar triangles have corresponding altitudes h₁ = 4 and h₂ = 6. The ratio of their areas is:','4:6 = 2:3','16:36 = 4:9','2:03','Both B and C expressed differently','B',3,0,0,3),(1690,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','The area of triangle DEF is 4 times the area of similar triangle ABC. The sides of DEF are how many times the sides of ABC?','4 times','2 times','8 times','16 times','B',3,0,0,3),(1691,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF. Area of ABC = 45, area of DEF = 80. A side of ABC is 9. Find the corresponding side of DEF:','12','16','9√(80/45)','Both A and C','D',4,0,0,4),(1692,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Three similar triangles have sides in ratio 1:2:3. Their areas are in ratio:','1:02:03','1:04:09','1:08:27','1:04:06','B',4,0,0,4),(1693,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','In triangle ABC, a line PQ parallel to BC has PQ/BC = 2/3. The area of triangle APQ compared to the area of the trapezoid PQCB is:','4:05','4:09','4:(9-4) = 4:5','Both A and C','D',4,0,0,4),(1694,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar triangles have areas S₁ and S₂. The ratio of any pair of corresponding sides is:','S₁/S₂','√(S₁/S₂)','(S₁/S₂)²','S₁²/S₂²','B',4,0,0,4),(1695,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','The area of triangle ABC is 20. A line DE parallel to BC divides ABC so that AD:DB = 3:2. Find the area of triangle ADE:','12','7.2','8','9.6','B',4,0,0,4),(1696,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','The area ratio of similar triangles is k². Explain why this is k² (not k³ or k):','Area is a 2-dimensional measure; scaling lengths by k scales areas by k²','Area = base × height, both scale by k, giving k × k = k²','Each dimension scales by k and area has two dimensions','All of the above','D',5,0,0,5),(1697,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','Two similar right triangles have legs (3,4) and (6,8). Their areas are 6 and 24. The area ratio is 4 = 2². The scale factor of the sides is 2. This confirms:','Area ratio = side ratio','Area ratio = (side ratio)² = 2² = 4 ✓','Area ratio = (side ratio)³','Area ratio = 2 × side ratio','B',5,0,0,5),(1698,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','If triangle ABC ~ triangle DEF with scale factor k, and the medians of ABC are m₁, m₂, m₃, then the medians of DEF are:','k × m₁, k × m₂, k × m₃','k² × m₁, k² × m₂, k² × m₃','m₁, m₂, m₃ (same length)','√k × m₁, √k × m₂, √k × m₃','A',5,0,0,5),(1699,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','A triangle with area A is similar to a triangle with area 9A. The side ratio (larger:smaller) is:','9:01','3:01','√9:1 = 3:1','Both B and C','D',5,0,0,5),(1700,'Kerala',9,'English','Maths','MCQ',1,'6','Similar Triangles',16,'Areas and Similarity','In triangle ABC, DE || BC with AD:AB = 1:n. The area of trapezoid BCED as a fraction of triangle ABC is:','1 - 1/n²','(n-1)/n','1 - (1/n)² = 1 - 1/n² = (n²-1)/n²','Both A and C','D',5,0,0,5),(1701,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','Displacement is defined as:','Total path length covered','Straight line distance between initial and final position in a definite direction','Speed multiplied by time','Rate of change of position','B',1,0,0,1),(1702,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','The SI unit of displacement is:','km','m/s','m','m/s²','C',1,0,0,1),(1703,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','Displacement is a:','Scalar quantity','Vector quantity','Neither scalar nor vector','Both scalar and vector','B',1,0,0,1),(1704,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','Distance is a:','Vector quantity','Scalar quantity','Neither scalar nor vector','Both scalar and vector','B',1,0,0,1),(1705,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','The magnitude of displacement of an object can be:','Always greater than distance','Zero or equal to or less than the distance covered','Always equal to distance','Always greater than zero','B',2,0,0,2),(1706,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','When is the magnitude of distance and displacement equal?','When an object moves in a circle','When an object moves along a straight line in the same direction','When an object returns to its starting point','When an object is stationary','B',2,0,0,2),(1707,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','A child walks 40 m eastward from B to C, then 40 m westward from C back to B. The total distance covered is:','0 m','40 m','80 m','-40 m','C',2,0,0,2),(1708,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','A child walks 40 m eastward from B to C, then 40 m westward back to B. The displacement is:','80 m','40 m','0 m','-80 m','C',2,0,0,2),(1709,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','A child starts from B, reaches D (80 m east) and returns to C (40 m east of B). The displacement is:','120 m eastward','40 m eastward','80 m eastward','0 m','B',3,0,0,3),(1710,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','A child moves from A to D and returns to A. The displacement is:','Equal to total path length','Half the total path length','Zero, since initial and final positions are the same','Negative the total path length','C',3,0,0,3),(1711,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'2','Equations of Motion',19,'Displacement and Distance','Which statement about displacement is correct?','Displacement is always positive','Displacement can be negativ