tional force between two objects depends on:','Their masses and the distance between them','Their velocity and volume','Their colour and temperature','Their shape only','A',2,0,0,2),(1807,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','If mass m₁ is tripled and mass m₂ is unchanged, and distance is unchanged, the gravitational force:','Triples','Becomes one-third','Remains unchanged','Doubles','A',2,0,0,2),(1808,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','Which scientist formulated the Universal Law of Gravitation?','Galileo Galilei','Albert Einstein','Isaac Newton','James Clerk Maxwell','C',2,0,0,2),(1809,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','Two masses of 10 kg each are placed 1 m apart. If G = 6.67 × 10⁻¹¹ N·m²/kg², the gravitational force is approximately:','6.67 × 10⁻⁹ N','6.67 × 10⁻¹¹ N','6.67 × 10⁻¹³ N','6.67 × 10⁻⁷ N','A',3,0,0,3),(1810,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','The Earth pulls the Moon with gravitational force. The Moon also pulls the Earth. Which is greater?','Earth''s pull on Moon','Moon''s pull on Earth','They are equal in magnitude','Earth''s is ten times greater','C',2,0,0,2),(1811,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','If the distance between two objects is halved, the gravitational force between them becomes:','Double','Four times','Half','One-quarter','B',3,0,0,3),(1812,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','Two spheres of masses 20 kg and 30 kg are 5 m apart. Using F = Gm₁m₂/r² (G = 6.67 × 10⁻¹¹), force is approximately:','8.0 × 10⁻¹⁰ N','4.0 × 10⁻¹⁰ N','8.0 × 10⁻⁹ N','1.6 × 10⁻⁹ N','A',3,0,0,3),(1813,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','Why does a ball thrown horizontally still fall to Earth rather than continue in a straight line?','Because air resistance pushes it down','Because Earth''s gravitational pull continuously deflects it toward Earth','Because its inertia runs out','Because the Moon''s gravity pulls it','B',3,0,0,3),(1814,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','The gravitational force keeps the Moon in its orbit around Earth. If this force disappeared, the Moon would:','Fall toward Earth immediately','Stay in orbit by inertia','Fly off in a straight-line path (tangent to orbit)','Stop moving','C',4,0,0,4),(1815,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','Two planets: Planet A has twice the mass and twice the radius of Planet B. The gravitational acceleration at the surface of Planet A compared to Planet B is:','Twice as large','Equal','Half as large','Four times as large','C',4,0,0,4),(1816,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','At what condition will the gravitational force between two objects be zero?','When one mass is zero','When distance is finite','When both masses are equal','Never — except theoretically at infinite distance or zero mass','D',4,0,0,4),(1817,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','The gravitational force between two objects is F. If both masses are doubled and distance is also doubled, the new force is:','F','2F','F/2','4F','A',4,0,0,4),(1818,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','Earth (mass 6×10²⁴ kg) and Moon (mass 7.4×10²² kg) are 3.84×10⁸ m apart. Approximate gravitational force using F=Gm₁m₂/r² (G=6.67×10⁻¹¹) is:','2.0×10²⁰ N','6.67×10¹¹ N','7.2×10²² N','8.0×10¹⁸ N','A',5,0,0,5),(1819,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'4','Gravitation',21,'Universal Law of Gravitation','Gravitational force between an apple and Earth is felt. Why does only the a