MCQ',1,'3','Laws of Motion',20,'Newton''s Third Law of Motion','Action-reaction pairs are always equal and opposite. Why don''t they cancel?','They are on the same object so they must cancel','They act on different objects, so each affects only its own object''s motion','The law is wrong','They cancel only when objects are stationary','B',4,0,0,4),(1966,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'3','Laws of Motion',20,'Newton''s Third Law of Motion','A 5 kg block on a frictionless table is pushed by 30 N. By Newton''s Third Law the block pushes back with 30 N, yet it accelerates. Why?','Newton''s Third Law doesn''t apply to accelerating objects','The block''s reaction force acts on the pusher, not on the block — so net force on block is still 30 N','The 30 N force is stronger','The table absorbs the reaction','B',4,0,0,4),(1967,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'3','Laws of Motion',20,'Newton''s Third Law of Motion','A 10 g bullet (mass=0.01 kg) is fired at 300 m/s from a 3 kg gun. Recoil speed of gun is:','1 m/s','3 m/s','10 m/s','0.3 m/s','A',5,0,0,5),(1968,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'3','Laws of Motion',20,'Newton''s Third Law of Motion','Action and reaction pairs: Earth pulls moon (A₁) and moon pulls Earth (A₂). Which is the action and which the reaction?','A₁ is action, A₂ is reaction','A₂ is action, A₁ is reaction','Either can be called action; they form a pair','A₁ is reaction, A₂ is zero','C',5,0,0,5),(1969,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'3','Laws of Motion',20,'Newton''s Third Law of Motion','Two skaters (60 kg and 40 kg) push off each other from rest. Skater A moves at 2 m/s. Speed of Skater B is:','2 m/s in same direction','3 m/s in opposite direction','2 m/s in opposite direction','4 m/s in same direction','B',5,0,0,5),(1970,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'3','Laws of Motion',20,'Newton''s Third Law of Motion','When a ball bounces off a wall, the wall exerts a force on the ball equal and opposite to the ball''s force on the 