sity:','Diamond < Glass < Water < Air','Air < Water < Glass < Diamond','Water < Air < Glass < Diamond','Air < Glass < Water < Diamond','B',3,0,0,3),(2008,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','The change in direction of light when passing from one medium to another is caused by:','Change in colour','Change in frequency','Change in the speed of light','Change in intensity','C',3,0,0,3),(2009,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','A ray of light incident normally on the surface of separation between two media:','Undergoes maximum refraction','Deviates away from normal','Does not undergo refraction','Undergoes total internal reflection','C',3,0,0,3),(2010,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','If the speed of light in medium A is greater than in medium B, which is optically denser?','Medium A','Medium B','Both are equal','Cannot be determined','B',4,0,0,4),(2011,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','Optical density and material (mass) density of a medium are:','Always the same quantity','Always proportional','Not necessarily related to each other','Always inversely proportional','C',4,0,0,4),(2012,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','Speed of light in water is 2.25 × 10^8 m/s and in glass is 2 × 10^8 m/s. Which is optically denser?','Water, because light is slower in water','Glass, because light is slower in glass','Water, because it is materially denser','Both have equal optical density','B',4,0,0,4),(2013,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','Speed of light in medium X is 2.5 × 10^8 m/s and in medium Y is 1.8 × 10^8 m/s. A ray going obliquely from X to Y will:','Bend away from normal — Y is rarer','Not deviate at all','Bend towards normal — Y is optically denser','Undergo total internal reflection','C',5,0,0,5),(2014,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','Medium A has lower material density than B, but light travels slower in A. What can we conclude?','A has lower optical density than B','Both have equal optical density','A has higher optical density than B','Material density always determines speed of light','C',5,0,0,5),(2015,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Introduction to Refraction','Two media have identical optical densities. A ray passing obliquely from one to the other will:','Bend towards the normal','Bend away from the normal','Show no deviation','Reflect completely','C',5,0,0,5),(2016,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','The refractive index of a medium is defined as the ratio of:','Speed of light in medium to speed in vacuum','Speed of light in vacuum to speed in medium','Speed in water to speed in medium','Wavelength in medium to wavelength in vacuum','B',1,0,0,1),(2017,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','If c is the speed in vacuum and v is the speed in a medium, refractive index n equals:','n = v/c','n = c × v','n = c/v','n = c − v','C',1,0,0,1),(2018,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','The refractive index of air is approximately:','0','0.5','1','2','C',1,0,0,1),(2019,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','A medium with a higher refractive index will have:','Higher speed of light','Lower speed of light','No effect on speed','Light reflected completely','B',1,0,0,1),(2020,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','Refractive index of diamond is 2.4. Speed in vacuum = 3 × 10^8 m/s. Speed of light in diamond is:','1.25 × 10^8 