ass (n=1.52) to flint glass (n=1.62). Compared to crown glass, light in flint glass:','Travels faster','Travels slower','Same speed','Twice as fast','B',4,0,0,4),(2029,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','Light from flint glass (n=1.62) to each medium at 30° incidence. Which medium gives the largest angle of refraction?','Crown glass (1.52)','Glycerine (1.47)','Water (1.33)','Sunflower oil (1.47)','C',4,0,0,4),(2030,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','A ray goes obliquely from water (n=1.33) to glycerine (n=1.47). The refracted ray will:','Bend away from normal — glycerine is rarer','Not deviate — same medium','Bend towards normal — glycerine is denser','Undergo total internal reflection','C',4,0,0,4),(2031,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','Speed of light in ethanol is less than in methanol. Which medium has a lower refractive index?','Ethanol','Methanol','Both equal','Cannot be determined','B',5,0,0,5),(2032,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','A student claims material density of oil is less than water so light travels faster in oil. Is this correct?','Yes — material density always determines speed','No — optical density determines speed in a medium','Yes — less material means less resistance','No — speed of light is same in all media','B',5,0,0,5),(2033,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refractive Index','Light enters obliquely from medium with n=1.44 to one with n=1.47. The angle of refraction compared to angle of incidence is:','Larger — second medium is rarer','Smaller — second medium is denser','Equal — both are transparent','Depends on angle of incidence only','B',5,0,0,5),(2034,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','When light enters from an optically rarer medium to a denser medium, the refracted ray:','Deviates away from the normal','Deviates towards the normal','Goes parallel to the surface','Reflects back completely','B',1,0,0,1),(2035,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','When light enters from an optically denser medium to a rarer medium, the refracted ray:','Deviates towards the normal','Deviates away from the normal','Does not deviate','Reflects completely','B',1,0,0,1),(2036,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','The angle of refraction is the angle between the refracted ray and:','The surface at the point of incidence','The normal at the point of incidence','The incident ray','The reflected ray','B',1,0,0,1),(2037,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','The incident ray, refracted ray, and the normal at the point of incidence are:','In three different planes','All on the same plane','In two different planes','Always perpendicular to each other','B',1,0,0,1),(2038,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','Light passes from air (rarer) to glass (denser) obliquely. The angle of refraction is:','Greater than angle of incidence','Equal to angle of incidence','Less than angle of incidence','Zero','C',2,0,0,2),(2039,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','Light passes from glass (denser) to air (rarer) obliquely. The angle of refraction is:','Less than angle of incidence','Equal to angle of incidence','Greater than angle of incidence','Zero','C',2,0,0,2),(2040,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','In which situation is there NO refraction when light goes from one medium to another?','When angle of incidence is 45°','When light enters normally (perpendicular to the surface)','When the two media have very different optical densities','When light travels from glass to water','B',2,0,0,2),(2041,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','Light enters from glycerine (n=1.47) to sunflower oil (n=1.47) obliquely. What happens?','Light bends towards the normal','Light bends away from the normal','Light does not deviate','Total internal reflection occurs','C',2,0,0,2),(2042,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','A ray of light travels from air to water obliquely. In which direction does the refracted ray bend?','Away from normal — angle of refraction > angle of incidence','Towards normal — angle of refraction < angle of incidence','No bending occurs','Along the surface at 90°','B',3,0,0,3),(2043,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','Light travels from kerosene (n=1.44) to turpentine oil (n=1.47) obliquely. The refracted ray will:','Bend away from normal — enters rarer medium','Bend towards normal — enters denser medium','Not deviate at all','Undergo total internal reflection','B',3,0,0,3),(2044,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','When a ray of light travels obliquely from water to air, in which direction does it deviate?','Towards the normal','Away from the normal','Parallel to the normal','It does not deviate','B',3,0,0,3),(2045,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','When light enters obliquely from air into diamond (n=2.42), the refracted ray:','Deviates away from normal — diamond is rarer','Deviates towards normal — diamond is optically denser','Does not deviate — very high refractive index','Undergoes total internal reflection','B',3,0,0,3),(2046,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Laws of Refraction','Light passes from X to Y. Angle of refraction > angle of incidence. Which is correct?','X is optically denser; Y 