ties','When a coin in an empty vessel moves out of sight and water is poured in, the coin becomes visible again because:','Water reflects light from the coin back to the eye','Light from the coin refracts at the water surface and reaches the eye','Water magnifies the coin','Water reduces material density above it','B',1,0,0,1),(2053,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','When a glass slab is placed on text in a book, the letters appear:','At their actual depth','Raised — closer to the eye — due to refraction','Lowered due to refraction','Magnified due to the glass acting as a lens','B',2,0,0,2),(2054,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','When light is incident normally on a glass slab, what occurs at each surface?','Maximum refraction','No refraction','Total internal reflection','Light is completely absorbed','B',2,0,0,2),(2055,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','The apparent depth of an object submerged in water appears:','Greater than actual depth','Less than actual depth','Equal to actual depth','Twice the actual depth','B',2,0,0,2),(2056,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','A person doing bow-fishing aims at the apparent position of a fish. To hit the fish, the person should aim:','Exactly at the apparent position','Above the apparent position','Slightly below the apparent position','To the side of the apparent position','C',3,0,0,3),(2057,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','The bottom of a pond appears elevated when viewed from a distance. This is because refraction:','Reflects light from the bottom back upward','Makes the apparent depth less than the real depth','Makes air''s refractive index greater than water''s','Causes TIR at the pond bottom','B',3,0,0,3),(2058,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','Why is it difficult to pick up a coin at the bottom of a trough by reaching in while looking from the side?','The coin is invisible due to total internal reflection','Refraction shifts the apparent position from the actual position','The trough walls absorb all light from the coin','The coin reflects light only upwards','B',3,0,0,3),(2059,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','When light passes through a glass slab at an angle, the emergent ray is:','At 90° to the original direction','Parallel to the incident ray but laterally displaced','Exactly in the same path without displacement','At a random angle depending on slab thickness','B',4,0,0,4),(2060,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','Why do letters beneath a glass slab appear raised to an observer above?','The glass acts as a convex lens magnifying upward','Light going from glass (denser) to air (rarer) bends away from normal; the eye traces the ray back in a straight line, placing the image above the actual position','The glass has a lower refractive index than air','The glass re-emits light from a higher position','B',4,0,0,4),(2061,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','In the smoke-and-water trough activity, the laser enters at an angle. At the smoke-water boundary, light entering water from smoke (like air) will:','Bend away from normal — water is rarer','Bend towards normal — water is optically denser','Not deviate — both are transparent','Undergo total internal reflection in smoke','B',4,0,0,4),(2062,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','A glass slab of thickness t is viewed from above. Apparent thickness is less than t. This upward shift occurs because:','Light bends towards normal from glass to air, pushing images deeper','Light bends away from normal from glass to air; virtual image of the bottom appears closer to the top','Light gets absorbed in the glass, reducing effective path','TIR inside the glass reduces the apparent path','B',4,0,0,4),(2063,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','In the coin-vessel activity, the observer steps back until the coin disappears. Water is added and the coin reappears. The exact refraction event that allows this is:','TIR redirects coin''s light to the eye','Refraction at the water-air surface bends the ray from the coin over the rim that previously blocked it','Water reflects the coin''s image like a mirror','Water physically raises the coin to the rim level','B',5,0,0,5),(2064,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','A fish is at actual depth d below the water surface. To an observer above, the fish appears at a depth less than d. This is because light from the fish:','Bends towards the normal from water to air, making the fish seem deeper','Bends away from normal from water to air, making the fish appear shallower than its actual depth','Does not refract because fish moves quickly','Undergoes TIR at the surface','B',5,0,0,5),(2065,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Refraction in Glass Slab and Practical Activities','People who engage in bow-fishing aim slightly below the apparent fish position. This is because refraction at the water surface makes the fish appear:','Deeper than its real position — aim above apparent position','Shallower than its real position — the fish is actually lower than it appears','At exactly its real position — no correction needed','To the side due to lateral displacement','B',5,0,0,5),(2066,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','Stars appear to twinkle because:','Stars emit light in pulses','Light from stars undergoes irregular refraction through the continuously changing atmosphere','Our eyes blink continuously','Stars are moving rapidly relative to Earth','B',1,0,0,1),(2067,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','Even after the Sun sets below the western horizon, it is still visible for some time. This is due to:','The large size of the Sun','Atmospheric refraction bending the Sun''s light towards us','The atmosphere reflecting sunlight','The Earth rotating very slowly','B',1,0,0,1),(2068,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','Stars appear as point sources of light because:','They emit very little light','They are at a much greater distance from Earth compared to planets','The atmosphere blocks most of their light','They are smaller than planets','B',1,0,0,1),(2069,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','Light from stars undergoes irregular refraction because:','The stars are very far away','Physical conditions (pressure, temperature) of atmospheric layers continuously change, altering optical density','The atmosphere has a fixed refractive index','Starlight consists of multiple colours','B',2,0,0,2),(2070,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','The Sun is visible a few seconds before it actually crosses the eastern horizon. This is because:','Reflection of sunlight by clouds','Atmospheric refraction bends the Sun''s light over the horizon towards the observer','The Moon reflects sunlight before sunrise','Temperature inversion blocks the horizon view','B',2,0,0,2),(2071,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','Unlike stars, planets do not twinkle. The main reason is that:','Planets are much brighter than stars','Planets appear as discs (not point sources) so irregular refractions from different parts average out','The atmosphere has no effect on planet light','Planets emit their own steady light','B',3,0,0,3),(2072,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','In twinkling of stars, the apparent position of the star as seen by an observer:','Is fixed and stable throughout the night','Continuously shifts due to irregular refraction in the atmosphere','Is always below the star''s actual position','Is always exactly at the star''s actual position','B',3,0,0,3),(2073,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','The optical density of the atmosphere increases going from higher altitude down to the surface. As starlight moves downward, it:','Bends away from normal at each layer','Travels in a perfectly straight line','Gradually bends towards normal entering progressively denser layers near Earth','Undergoes TIR at the troposphere','C',3,0,0,3),(2074,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','Atmospheric refraction causes the apparent position of a star to differ from its actual position. An observer sees the star:','Below its actual position — light bends away from normal in denser layers','Slightly higher than actual — light bends towards normal entering denser layers near Earth','At exactly its actual position — refractions cancel','To one side due to Earth''s rotation','B',4,0,0,4),(2075,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','The layers of atmosphere closest to Earth''s surface have continuously changing optical density because:','These layers are materially denser than upper layers','Physical conditions like pressure and temperature continuously change in these layers','The ozone layer directly changes their refractive index','Air molecules in lower layers absorb light selectively','B',4,0,0,4),(2076,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','The Sun rises about 2 minutes earlier than its actual sunrise. This occurs because:','The atmosphere absorbs and re-emits solar light with a delay','Refraction in increasingly denser atmospheric layers near the horizon bends sunlight over the horizon, making the Sun visible before it geometrically crosses it','The Sun''s gravity bends light around the Earth','The Moon reflects sunlight over the horizon','B',5,0,0,5),(2077,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Atmospheric Refraction','A student says: ''Atmospheric refraction makes the Sun visible before it crosses the horizon, so apparent sunrise is earlier than actual.'' Is this correct?','No — the Sun''s large size allows early visibility','Yes — the Sun''s light is refracted by the atmosphere making it visible before it crosses the geometric horizon','No — it is reflection from clouds not refraction','Yes — but this applies only to stars not the Sun','B',5,0,0,5),(2078,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','Total internal reflection occurs when light travels from:','Rarer medium to denser medium','Denser medium to rarer medium at an angle greater than the critical angle','Air to water','Air to glass','B',1,0,0,1),(2079,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','The critical angle for glass is:','30°','42°','45°','90°','B',1,0,0,1),(2080,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','A light ray hits the glass-air interface at 40°. The critical angle of glass is 42°. What happens?','Total internal reflection','Refraction occurs — the ray exits the glass','The ray is absorbed','The ray travels along the glass surface','B',2,0,0,2),(2081,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','Which angle of incidence will cause total internal reflection in glass (critical angle = 42°)?','40°','38°','42°','49°','D',2,0,0,2),(2082,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','In the semicircular glass slab experiment, as the angle of incidence inside glass increases, the angle of refraction:','Decreases continuously','Stays constant at 90°','Increases until it reaches 90° after which TIR occurs','Immediately becomes 90° at any angle of incidence','C',3,0,0,3),(2083,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','Light passes through decorative lamp fibres and emerges only at the tips. This happens because:','The fibre walls absorb and re-emit light at the tips','Light undergoes successive total internal reflection inside the fibre','The fibre is coated with mirror material','The fibre bends light by diffraction','B',3,0,0,3),(2084,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','Light inside glass hits the glass-air boundary at 43°. The critical angle of glass is 42°. What happens?','Refraction occurs with angle of refraction of 43°','Total internal reflection occurs since 43° exceeds the critical angle','The ray travels along the glass-air boundary','Normal refraction with angle less than 43°','B',3,0,0,3),(2085,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','In a mirage during summer, layers of air near the road are warmer and optically rarer. Light undergoes refraction followed by total internal reflection. The final image appears:','Above the actual objects','On the road surface, resembling a pool of water','To 