 Reflection','Two conditions for TIR: (1) light from denser to rarer, and (2) angle > critical angle. Condition 1 is met but angle is 38° while critical angle is 42°. What occurs?','Total internal reflection since light goes from denser to rarer','Normal refraction — only condition 1 is met not condition 2','No light passes through the surface','The light travels along the surface','B',5,0,0,5),(2091,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','Light from the bottom of an aquarium hits the water-air surface at angle greater than critical angle. An observer outside looking from the side will see:','No light at all from that region','The bottom of the aquarium appearing above the water surface due to TIR','The bottom at its actual depth','A blurred image at twice the depth','B',5,0,0,5),(2092,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Total Internal Reflection','In optical fibres, successive TIRs allow light to travel through bends without escaping. If the critical angle of core-cladding interface is 42°, for TIR to occur, light must make an angle with the core-cladding boundary that is:','Less than 42°','Exactly 42°','Greater than 42°','Exactly 90°','C',5,0,0,5),(2093,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Applications of Total Internal Reflection','Optical fibre cables (OFC) work on the principle of:','Reflection from plane mirrors','Total internal reflection','Diffraction of light','Absorption and re-emission','B',1,0,0,1),(2094,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Applications of Total Internal Reflection','Charles K. Kao was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009 for his work on:','Discovery of total internal reflection','Transmission of light through optical fibres','Invention of the laser','Discovery of the refractive index','B',1,0,0,1),(2095,'Kerala',9,'English','Physics','MCQ',1,'1','Refraction of Light',18,'Applicat