,'MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','What natural features provided natural boundaries for Greek city-states?','Rivers and plains','Hills and mountains','Deserts and forests','Seas and oceans alone','B',3,0,0,3),(2294,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','Athens was an important centre of trade in the Mediterranean. What skills did many Athenians develop as a result?','Iron smelting and metalwork','Ship building and seafaring','Elephant training for war','Silk weaving and dyeing','B',3,0,0,3),(2295,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','How did the Athenian system of government differ from modern democracy?','Athens had no elections','Athens excluded women artisans foreigners and slaves from citizenship','Athens had a king who overruled the citizens','Athens had no system of voting','B',4,0,0,4),(2296,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','In what way were the capital cities of Greek city-states strategically positioned?','They were located at river deltas for trade','They were located on high hills for defense','They were built near forests for resources','They were placed at the centre of flat plains','B',4,0,0,4),(2297,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','What common factor explains the emergence of both Mahajanapadas in India and city-states in Greece?','Both were influenced by the Persian Empire','Both emerged from the growth of settled agriculture trade and towns that required organized governance beyond tribal systems','Both were established by the same group of conquerors','Both relied entirely on slave labour','B',4,0,0,4),(2298,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','Why might the exclusion of women artisans and foreign traders from Athenian citizenship be seen as a limitation?','These groups contributed nothing to Athenian society','Democracy that excludes productive members of society is not truly representative of all people','These groups preferred not to participate in governance','Ancient laws prohibited their inclusion and this was perfectly democratic','B',5,0,0,5),(2299,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','Greek city-states were formed when villages came together for security and governance. How does this parallel the formation of Janapadas in India?','Both were formed by military conquest of villages','In both cases the need for collective governance and security led to the grouping of settlements into political units','Both were established by foreign invaders','Greek villages merged due to religion while Indian villages merged due to trade only','B',5,0,0,5),(2300,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'2','Ideas and Early States',23,'State Formation in Greece','The chapter says 6th century BCE changes in material life were reflected in the spheres of politics and philosophy also. Which best illustrates this connection?','The invention of iron tools directly caused the writing of the Vedas','Iron tools to agricultural surplus to cities to trade to new social classes to dissatisfaction with Vedic rituals to new philosophies and new polities','Philosophy led to political changes which then caused economic change','Political rulers invented new philosophies to control people','B',5,0,0,5),(2301,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Which dynasty started the practice of land grants in India?','Kushanas','Guptas','Satavahanas','Vakatakas','C',1,0,0,1),(2302,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Who founded the Gupta dynasty?','Chandragupta I','Samudragupta','Srigupta','Skandagupta','C',1,0,0,1),(2303,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','What was Indian Feudalism?','A system of land ownership where kings owned all land','A system of governance where land was granted to chiefs and Brahmins in exchange for loyalty and services','A system of trade between kingdoms','A system of dividing the empire into provinces','B',1,0,0,1),(2304,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Which ruler issued the Vakataka order granting land to Brahmins that is mentioned in the chapter?','Chandragupta II','Vindhyashakti II','Samudragupta','Skandagupta','B',1,0,0,1),(2305,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Which irrigation device mentioned in the chapter was also called Araghata?','Canal','Dam','Ghatiyantra (Persian wheel)','Reservoir','C',2,0,0,2),(2306,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Emperor Skandagupta rebuilt which famous lake mentioned in the chapter?','Mansarovar','Wular Lake','Sudarsana Lake','Dal Lake','C',2,0,0,2),(2307,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','The Gupta period falls approximately between which centuries CE?','1st century BCE to 1st century CE','4th century to 6th century CE','7th century to 9th century CE','10th century to 12th century CE','B',2,0,0,2),(2308,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Which Chinese traveller visited India during the Gupta period and is mentioned in the chapter?','Hiuen Tsang','Marco Polo','Ibn Battuta','Fa-Hien','D',2,0,0,2),(2309,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','How were the Gupta land grants different from those of the Satavahanas?','Gupta grants were for military service while Satavahana grants were religious','Gupta grants gave more tax privileges and administrative powers to the grantee than Satavahana grants','Gupta grants were only to Brahmins while Satavahana grants were to all classes','Gupta grants were in gold while Satavahana grants were in land','B',3,0,0,3),(2310,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','What was the key feature of land grant documents issued by the Vakatakas?','They were written in copper plates','They were written in Sanskrit and granted tax exemptions to Brahmins','They were given only to Buddhist monasteries','They specified the military duties of the grantee','B',3,0,0,3),(2311,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Which dynasties ruled in India after the Mauryas as mentioned in the chapter?','Pallavas and Cholas','Kushanas Guptas Shakas Vakatakas Satavahanas Cholas Cheras and Pandyas','Rajputs and Mughals','Greeks and Parthians','B',3,0,0,3),(2312,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Why was irrigation important during the Gupta period?','To create artificial rivers for transport','To increase agricultural productivity and support the growing population and state revenues','To drain swamps for new settlements','To provide water for religious rituals','B',3,0,0,3),(2313,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','The Vakataka land grant document mentions that the land was given with exemption from taxes and with administrative rights. Why was this significant?','It meant the king gained more revenue','It meant the grantee had authority over the peasants living on the land creating a new power structure','It meant the land was free from any obligations','It meant the grantee had to pay double taxes to the king','B',4,0,0,4),(2314,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','What does the date of the Vakataka land grant (355-400 CE) tell us about the time period?','It was during the decline of the Gupta empire','It was during the post-Mauryan period when regional kingdoms flourished','It was during the Harshavardhan period','It was during the Delhi Sultanate period','B',4,0,0,4),(2315,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Why did the system of land grants lead to the weakening of central authority?','Because kings ran out of land to grant','Because as land with tax and administrative rights was granted to many individuals power became decentralised','Because land grants led to wars between grantees','Because the Brahmins who received land refused to pay any taxes','B',4,0,0,4),(2316,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','How did land grants affect the peasants who lived on the granted lands?','Peasants became free landowners','Peasants came under the authority of the grantee and had to pay taxes and render services to the new landlord','Peasants were forced to move elsewhere','Peasants received protection from the Brahmins','B',4,0,0,4),(2317,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','The chapter describes Indian Feudalism as beginning with land grants. Why is this compared to European feudalism?','Both involved invaders taking control of land','Both involved land being granted in exchange for loyalty and services creating a hierarchy of lords and peasants','Both led to the rise of democracy','Both were caused by the collapse of large empires','B',5,0,0,5),(2318,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','Why did land grants increase after the Gupta period?','Because the Guptas forced their successors to give land','Because as central authority weakened regional rulers used land grants to secure loyalty from local chiefs and Brahmins','Because trade had declined making land the only source of wealth','Because Buddhist monasteries demanded land from rulers','B',5,0,0,5),(2319,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','How does Fa-Hien''s description of prosperous India under the Guptas contrast with Hiuen Tsang''s later account?','Both described a thriving prosperous India','Fa-Hien found prosperous cities and trade while Hiuen Tsang found a weakened empire with declining cities and trade after Gupta collapse','Fa-Hien found India weak while Hiuen Tsang found it prosperous','Both described India as poor and declining','B',5,0,0,5),(2320,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Land Grants','What was the long-term consequence of the Gupta practice of granting land with administrative rights to local chiefs called Samanthas?','It strengthened the Gupta central government','It created powerful local lords (Samanthas) who eventually became independent rulers leading to the fragmentation of the empire','It led to more prosperous peasants','It strengthened trade and commerce across India','B',5,0,0,5),(2321,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','What were Srenis in the context of crafts and trade?','Royal workshops set up by the king','Guilds of craftsmen and traders','Government tax collection offices','Buddhist monasteries involved in trade','B',1,0,0,1),(2322,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','Who was the Nagarasreshtin?','The chief of the army','The chief of the city merchants','The chief of the priestly class','The chief of the Buddhist Sangha','B',1,0,0,1),(2323,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','With which regions did India have external trade during the Gupta period?','Only with China','West Asia Central Asia Southeast Asia and Rome','Only with Southeast Asia','Only with Persia','B',1,0,0,1),(2324,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','What types of textiles were exported from India as mentioned in the chapter?','Silk and wool','Muslin calico and linen','Cotton and jute','Khadi and silk','B',2,0,0,2),(2325,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','The decline in external trade after the fall of the Roman Empire affected Indian economy. What does this tell us?','Indian trade was self-sufficient','Indian trade was dependent on international demand particularly from Rome','Indian trade was mainly with China not Rome','The fall of Rome helped Indian trade grow','B',2,0,0,2),(2326,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','What was the Sarthvaha?','A type of Indian coin','The chief of a merchant caravan','A tax on goods','A type of guild','B',2,0,0,2),(2327,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','What was the significance of Gupta coins mentioned in the chapter?','They were made of bronze','They are evidence of a money economy and the prosperity of the Gupta period','They were only used in temples','They were copies of Roman coins','B',3,0,0,3),(2328,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','How did Srenis (guilds) function in the economy of the Gupta period?','They were purely social organisations','They regulated production quality credit and trade providing stability to crafts and commerce','They were controlled entirely by the king','They competed with each other causing economic instability','B',3,0,0,3),(2329,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','Why did the decline of foreign trade with Rome affect the Indian economy?','India had too much gold to export','Rome was the major market for Indian luxury goods and its fall reduced demand causing economic decline','Rome was the only source of iron for India','Indian traders moved to China instead','B',3,0,0,3),(2330,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','How did the existence of guilds (Srenis) contribute to the development of Indian crafts?','By preventing new craftsmen from entering trades','By maintaining standards of production and providing mutual support to craftsmen enabling specialisation and quality','By forcing craftsmen to work for the king','By connecting Indian craftsmen directly with foreign buyers','B',4,0,0,4),(2331,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','What does the presence of Indian textiles in Roman markets tell us about the Gupta period economy?','India imported textiles from Rome','India had a surplus of quality textiles and was integrated into international trade networks','Roman textiles were popular in India','Trade between India and Rome was limited to a few luxury items','B',4,0,0,4),(2332,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','The chapter mentions both Nagarasreshtin (chief of city merchants) and Sarthvaha (chief of merchant caravans). What does the existence of these different roles suggest?','There was only one type of merchant in Gupta India','Trade had become sufficiently organised and complex to require specialised leadership for different aspects of commerce','These were honorary titles with no real function','Both titles referred to the same person','B',4,0,0,4),(2333,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','Why is the decline of Gupta coinage evidence of economic decline?','Because people stopped using money','Because a reduction in coin production indicates declining trade and royal revenue','Because coins became too heavy to carry','Because the Guptas switched to barter trade','B',5,0,0,5),(2334,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','Fa-Hien describes prosperous cities while Hiuen Tsang describes declining cities. Using the context of trade what explains this difference?','Hiuen Tsang was less observant than Fa-Hien','Fa-Hien visited during peak Gupta prosperity when trade was flourishing while Hiuen Tsang visited after the decline of the Gupta empire and the collapse of Roman trade','The cities Fa-Hien visited were different from those Hiuen Tsang visited','Hiuen Tsang visited during a natural disaster','B',5,0,0,5),(2335,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Crafts and Trade','How did the organisation of craftsmen into Srenis (guilds) support state power during the Gupta period?','Guilds directly fought wars for the king','Guilds provided organised taxation through the Nagarasreshtin gave the state a structured economy and regulated production','Guilds replaced the state in running cities','Guilds were opposed to state power','B',5,0,0,5),(2336,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','What was the term for the lowest social group that included Chandalas in the Gupta period?','Vaishyas','Sudras','Antyajas','Gahapathis','C',1,0,0,1),(2337,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','Who were Chandalas according to the chapter?','Buddhist monks who had left the Sangha','The lowest of the Antyajas who worked as graveyard keepers','Wandering merchants without a fixed home','Foreign traders who settled in India','B',1,0,0,1),(2338,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','What was an Anuloma marriage?','A marriage between people of equal social status','A marriage between a higher-caste man and a lower-caste woman','A marriage between two people of different religions','A marriage arranged by the king','B',2,0,0,2),(2339,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','The Chinese traveller Fa-Hien described how Chandalas had to strike a piece of wood when entering a city. What does this tell us?','Chandalas were welcomed into cities','Chandalas were severely discriminated against and had to announce their presence to allow upper castes to avoid them','Chandalas were musicians by profession','Chandalas were tax collectors who announced their arrival','B',2,0,0,2),(2340,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','What was the Pratiloma marriage as opposed to Anuloma marriage?','A marriage within the same caste','A marriage of a higher-caste woman with a lower-caste man which was considered unacceptable','A marriage arranged by priests','A marriage with a foreigner','B',3,0,0,3),(2341,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','How did the jati system expand during the Gupta period?','The number of jatis decreased as people moved to cities','New jatis and upajatis formed as new crafts and occupations developed fragmenting social structure further','The jati system was abolished by the Gupta rulers','Jati became based on wealth rather than birth','B',3,0,0,3),(2342,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','The Charmakarar were a group of Antyajas who worked as tanners of animal skin. Why would this occupation lead to their social exclusion?','Because leather was too expensive','Because working with animal carcasses was considered ritually impure in the Hindu caste system','Because they competed with Brahmin merchants','Because the Guptas banned their trade','B',4,0,0,4),(2343,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','How did the low status of women in the Gupta period reflect the broader social hierarchy?','Women had equal rights in the Gupta period','Women''s restricted status was part of the same hierarchical system that also oppressed lower castes emphasising purity and social control','Women had more rights than Sudras','Women''s status was independent of the caste system','B',4,0,0,4),(2344,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','Why does the chapter say new jatis and upajatis were formed during the post-Maurya period?','Because the Gupta rulers created new castes','Because as new occupations emerged in crafts and trade each occupation group tended to become an endogamous hereditary social unit','Because Buddhism influenced the creation of new social groups','Because foreign invaders introduced their own caste groups','B',5,0,0,5),(2345,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Social Life','What does Fa-Hien''s description of Chandalas having to strike wood before entering cities tell us about the relationship between text and social reality?','Fa-Hien was exaggerating','Primary sources like travel accounts provide evidence of lived social conditions that go beyond what official texts describe about the caste system','Chandalas were treated well in all Indian cities','The caste system only existed in theory not in practice','B',5,0,0,5),(2346,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','What was the Gramapati also known as in the context of Gupta village administration?','Senani','Gramadhyaksha','Purohita','Samantha','B',1,0,0,1),(2347,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','What were Samanthas in the Gupta period?','Village elders who settled disputes','Local chiefs who received land grants and owed loyalty to the king','Buddhist monks who managed villages','Tax collectors appointed by the king','B',1,0,0,1),(2348,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','What is a Prasasti?','A type of Buddhist scripture','An inscription eulogising a king or describing his achievements','A tax payment document','A land grant deed','B',1,0,0,1),(2349,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','Which is the earliest known Prasasti mentioned in the chapter?','Prayaga Prasasti','Junagarh Prasasti','Allahabad Prasasti','Mehrauli Inscription','B',2,0,0,2),(2350,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','Who wrote the Prayaga Prasasti that describes Samudragupta''s conquests?','Kautilya','Harisena','Varahamihira','Kalidasa','B',2,0,0,2),(2351,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','Who were the Gramavriddhar in the Gupta village administration?','Appointed tax collectors','Village elders who participated in local governance','Samanthas who controlled villages','Buddhist monks who served as village leaders','B',2,0,0,2),(2352,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','How did the Gupta system of local administration through Samanthas differ from the Maurya system?','The Maurya system also used Samanthas','The Maurya system had direct centralised control while the Gupta system devolved power to local chiefs (Samanthas) through land grants','The Gupta system was more centralised than the Maurya system','Both systems relied on Brahmins for local administration','B',3,0,0,3),(2353,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','What role did Prasastis play in establishing the legitimacy of Gupta rulers?','They were used to collect taxes','They were public declarations of royal power and achievements that legitimised rulers in the eyes of subjects and posterity','They were used to make treaties with foreign kingdoms','They were instructions for local administrators','B',3,0,0,3),(2354,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','How did the role of Samanthas change from being local administrators to becoming a political threat to the Gupta empire?','Samanthas remained loyal throughout','As Samanthas accumulated land tax revenues and military power through grants they became strong enough to challenge and eventually overthrow central authority','Samanthas were replaced by Brahmins as local rulers','Samanthas converted to Buddhism and stopped paying taxes','B',3,0,0,3),(2355,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','What does the Prayaga Prasasti reveal about Samudragupta''s military campaigns?','He never fought any wars','He conducted extensive military campaigns across India subjugating many kings and establishing Gupta supremacy','He only fought defensive wars','He lost all his military campaigns','B',4,0,0,4),(2356,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','How does the structure of Gupta village administration (Gramapati Gramavriddhar and Samanthas) reflect the tension between central and local power?','There was no tension as all authority came from the centre','The multiple layers of administration reflect an attempt to maintain central oversight while accommodating local power through hereditary village heads and appointed local chiefs','All administration was handled by the central government directly','The Guptas had no local administration','B',4,0,0,4),(2357,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','The Junagarh Prasasti is the earliest known Prasasti. What does the development of Prasastis as a literary form tell us about Gupta political culture?','Kings were illiterate in the Gupta period','The Guptas used Sanskrit literature as a tool of political legitimation reflecting the importance of public proclamation of royal power','Prasastis were only written by Buddhist monks','Prasastis were secret documents not meant for public reading','B',4,0,0,4),(2358,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','Why did the Gupta administrative system with Samanthas eventually lead to the empire''s fragmentation?','Because Samanthas refused to collect taxes','Because land grants with administrative rights created powerful local rulers who over generations owed diminishing loyalty to the Gupta centre','Because the Guptas ran out of land to grant','Because Buddhist influence weakened Gupta military power','B',5,0,0,5),(2359,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','What does the fact that the Gramapati was both a village administrator and represented the state''s interests at the local level tell us about Gupta governance?','The Gupta state had no interest in villages','The Gupta state attempted to integrate local governance into the imperial system by creating officials who served both local community and state needs','Village administration was completely independent of the state','The Gramapati was only a religious official','B',5,0,0,5),(2360,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'State: Central Authority and Local Power','How does the Gupta system of governance through Samanthas compare with modern federal systems?','They are identical','Both involve division of power between central and regional authorities though Samanthas had hereditary power from land grants rather than elected mandates','The Gupta system was purely monarchical with no decentralisation','Modern federal systems are based on Gupta Samantha governance','B',5,0,0,5),(2361,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Which famous caves are known for their paintings depicting scenes from royal life and epics?','Ellora Caves','Ajanta Caves','Elephanta Caves','Badami Caves','B',1,0,0,1),(2362,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Who wrote Abhijnana Sakuntala?','Sudraka','Bhartrhari','Kalidasa','Bhasa','C',1,0,0,1),(2363,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Who was Arya Bhata?','A Gupta emperor who promoted arts','A mathematician and astronomer who wrote Aryabhatiya','A poet who wrote Kumarasambhava','A philosopher of the Mimamsa school','B',1,0,0,1),(2364,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','What is the Amarakosam?','A Sanskrit grammar text','A Sanskrit dictionary or thesaurus written by Amarasimha','A mathematical treatise','A collection of Buddhist Jataka stories','B',1,0,0,1),(2365,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Which of the following is a work by Kalidasa?','Mriccha Katika','Swapnavasavadattha','Kumarasambhava','Thrikandi','C',2,0,0,2),(2366,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Who wrote Mriccha Katika?','Kalidasa','Bhartrhari','Sudraka','Bhasa','C',2,0,0,2),(2367,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','The Iron Pillar at Mehrauli belongs to which century CE?','2nd century CE','4th century CE','6th century CE','8th century CE','B',2,0,0,2),(2368,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','What language became the language of administration during the Gupta period?','Pali','Tamil','Sanskrit','Prakrit','C',2,0,0,2),(2369,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','How many systems of philosophy (Darshanas) developed in India during this period?','Four','Six','Eight','Ten','B',3,0,0,3),(2370,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Which philosopher founded the Samkhya school of philosophy?','Patanjali','Kapila','Gauthama','Kanada','B',3,0,0,3),(2371,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','The Ajanta Cave paintings depict scenes from royal life and from the Ramayana and Mahabharata. What does this tell us about Gupta culture?','The Guptas rejected Hindu traditions','Gupta culture was rich in artistic expression drawing from both courtly and religious/epic traditions','The Guptas only patronised Buddhist art','Ajanta was created during the Maurya period','B',3,0,0,3),(2372,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Who wrote Brihatsamhita an encyclopaedic work on astrology?','Arya Bhata','Varahamihira','Amarasimha','Kalidasa','B',3,0,0,3),(2373,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','The six systems of Indian philosophy each associated with a founder reflect what about Gupta intellectual culture?','Philosophy was only for Buddhist monks','Gupta India had a flourishing philosophical tradition with multiple schools exploring different aspects of knowledge and reality','All six schools agreed with each other','Philosophy was banned from Gupta courts','B',4,0,0,4),(2374,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','How does the Abhijnana Sakuntala by Kalidasa reflect the social values of the Gupta period?','It criticises the Gupta rulers','It reflects the Gupta period''s high value of Sanskrit learning courtly refinement and the social expectations around women','It promotes Buddhist values','It was written in Prakrit not Sanskrit','B',4,0,0,4),(2375,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Arya Bhata''s Aryabhatiya contains calculations related to the earth''s orbit and pi. What does this suggest about intellectual life in Gupta India?','The Guptas were only interested in religion','Gupta India had advanced scientific knowledge in astronomy and mathematics demonstrating a culture that valued empirical inquiry','Arya Bhata''s ideas were rejected during the Gupta period','Mathematics was only studied for trade purposes','B',4,0,0,4),(2376,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','Why was Sanskrit chosen as the language of administration in the Gupta period?','Because the common people spoke Sanskrit','Because Sanskrit was the prestige language of elite culture associated with religious authority and learning giving royal communications greater legitimacy','Because Pali had died out','Because Buddhist monks required Sanskrit administration','B',4,0,0,4),(2377,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','How do the Ajanta Caves demonstrate the connection between royal patronage and artistic production in the Gupta period?','The paintings were made by ordinary people','The elaborate cave paintings required significant resources and were created under royal or wealthy patronage demonstrating how power and art were connected','Monks painted the caves without any royal support','The caves predate the Gupta period by centuries','B',5,0,0,5),(2378,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','The development of six systems of philosophy (Samkhya Yoga Nyaya Vaisheshika Vedanta Mimamsa) in Gupta India shows what about the relationship between intellectual and material prosperity?','Philosophy only develops in poor societies','Material prosperity under the Guptas created conditions for intellectual flourishing as surplus wealth freed thinkers from subsistence concerns','These philosophies were developed despite Gupta poverty','The six systems were all created by the same philosopher','B',5,0,0,5),(2379,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','How does the Iron Pillar of Mehrauli serve as evidence of Gupta technological achievement?','It is evidence of Gupta military strength','It demonstrates advanced metallurgical knowledge as the pillar has resisted rust for centuries','It shows that the Guptas imported iron technology from China','It is evidence of Buddhist construction techniques','B',5,0,0,5),(2380,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'Art and Literature','The chapter describes both literary achievements (Kalidasa Sudraka Bhasa) and scientific achievements (Arya Bhata Varahamihira) in the Gupta period. What does this breadth suggest?','The Gupta period only excelled in one area','The Gupta period was a comprehensive cultural golden age with excellence across literature philosophy science and art','Scientific and literary achievements were unconnected in Gupta India','Only Brahmins contributed to these achievements','B',5,0,0,5),(2381,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What was a Brahmadeya?','A temple dedicated to Brahma','Land granted to a group of Brahmins by South Indian rulers','A Brahmin village elder','A Sanskrit school in South India','B',1,0,0,1),(2382,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What was Mahabalipuram known as during the Pallava period?','A religious centre','The port city of the Pallavas','The capital of the Pandyas','A centre of Buddhist learning','B',1,0,0,1),(2383,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What is Dravidian architecture?','The architecture of North Indian temples','The architectural style developed in South India with three main phases','The Buddhist cave architecture of South India','The Muslim architecture introduced in South India','B',1,0,0,1),(2384,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','Who wrote Matthavilasa Prahasana?','Pulakesi II','Mahendravarman I','Narasimhavarman','Rajasimha','B',1,0,0,1),(2385,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What was an Agrahara?','A type of South Indian temple','A village given entirely to Brahmins','A South Indian port city','A type of South Indian land tax','B',2,0,0,2),(2386,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What was Nagapattinam during the Pandya period?','A Brahmin settlement','The port city of the Pandyas','A temple city','A Buddhist learning centre','B',2,0,0,2),(2387,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What is Devadanam?','Land granted to Brahmins','Land granted to temples','Land given to Buddhist monasteries','Land given to military chiefs','B',2,0,0,2),(2388,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','Which site in South India has been declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site as mentioned in the chapter?','Meenakshi Temple Madurai','Srirangam Temple','Mahabalipuram','Thanjavur Temple','C',2,0,0,2),(2389,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What are the three phases of Dravidian architectural development mentioned in the chapter?','Stone brick and concrete','Rock-cut monolithic chariot and structural','Wooden cave and brick','Pallava Chola and Pandya','B',3,0,0,3),(2390,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','What is the significance of Brahmadeya grants in South Indian history?','They helped spread Islam in South India','They helped establish Brahmin social and religious authority in South India through landholding','They were used to fund wars against the Cholas','They were only symbolic with no real land transfer','B',3,0,0,3),(2391,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','How did the practice of Devadanam (land to temples) contribute to the development of South Indian temples?','It had no effect on temple development','It provided temples with an economic base allowing them to employ priests artisans and workers and develop into large institutions','Temples used the land to build new temples','Devadanam was only practiced in North India','B',3,0,0,3),(2392,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','Which kingdoms are mentioned as ruling South India in the post-Mauryan period in the chapter?','Guptas and Kushanas','Pallavas and Pandyas','Cheras and Rajputs','Vakatakas and Chalukyas','B',3,0,0,3),(2393,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','How did Mahabalipuram (Pallava port) and Nagapattinam (Pandya port) contribute to South Indian prosperity?','They were only military bases','They served as centres of maritime trade connecting South India with Southeast Asia and the wider Indian Ocean world','They were primarily religious pilgrimage sites','They were only important for internal river trade','B',4,0,0,4),(2394,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','Why was the Meenakshi Temple at Madurai significant for South Indian society?','It was built by North Indian rulers','It was a major religious centre that also served as a focal point for economic and social life in the region','It was the only temple in South India','It was built during the Gupta period','B',4,0,0,4),(2395,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','How does the development of three phases of Dravidian architecture (rock-cut to monolithic chariot to structural) reflect technological progress?','Each phase was the same as the previous','Each phase represents advancement in construction techniques from simpler rock carving to increasingly complex free-standing structural temples','The structural phase was simpler than the rock-cut phase','All three phases were developed simultaneously','B',4,0,0,4),(2396,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','Mahendravarman I wrote the Sanskrit play Matthavilasa Prahasana. What does a Pallava king writing Sanskrit literature tell us?','Pallava kings could not write Tamil','Pallava rulers were patrons of Sanskrit learning demonstrating the prestige of Sanskrit culture across the subcontinent even in Dravidian South India','Matthavilasa Prahasana was actually written by a Brahmin','Pallava kings only patronised Tamil literature','B',4,0,0,4),(2397,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','How did the South Indian system of Brahmadeya and Agrahara grants parallel the North Indian system of land grants?','They were completely different systems','Both involved giving land with tax and administrative privileges to Brahmins creating similar feudal structures across India','South Indian grants were more democratic than North Indian grants','North Indian grants went to Brahmins while South Indian grants went to temples','B',5,0,0,5),(2398,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','Why did South Indian ports like Mahabalipuram and Nagapattinam become important after the decline of Roman trade?','They had no importance after Rome declined','As Rome declined South India shifted its trading focus to Southeast Asia making South Indian ports important nodes in the emerging Indian Ocean trade network','South Indian trade with Rome increased after Roman decline','South Indian ports became important only after the medieval period','B',5,0,0,5),(2399,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','The chapter describes Dravidian architecture developing through three phases from rock-cut to structural. What does this progression tell us about the relationship between royal power and religious architecture?','Kings had no interest in temple architecture','Increasing royal power and wealth enabled more ambitious architectural projects representing royal piety and legitimacy through temple construction','The structural phase was built by ordinary people','Rock-cut architecture required more resources than structural temples','B',5,0,0,5),(2400,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'3','Land Grants and the Indian Society',24,'South India','How does the UNESCO recognition of Mahabalipuram''s heritage reflect the long-term significance of Pallava artistic achievement?','UNESCO recognition has no historical significance','The recognition confirms that Pallava architectural achievements were of outstanding universal value demonstrating the lasting global importance of South Indian cultural contributions','UNESCO recognises only modern achievements','Mahabalipuram was not actually built by the Pallavas','B',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (2401,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','Who moved the Objective Resolution in the Constituent Assembly?','B.R. Ambedkar','Jawaharlal Nehru','Sardar Patel','Rajendra Prasad','B',1,0,0,1),(2402,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','On which date was the Objective Resolution moved in the Constituent Assembly?','26-Jan-50','26-Nov-49','13-Dec-46','15-Aug-47','C',1,0,0,1),(2403,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','According to the Objective Resolution India would be declared as what type of state?','A monarchical state','A sovereign independent republic','A confederation of states','A dominion under Britain','B',1,0,0,1),(2404,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','The Objective Resolution stated that powers and authority of the sovereign independent India would be derived from where?','The Constitution alone','The people','The Parliament','The President','B',2,0,0,2),(2405,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','Which type of justice does the Objective Resolution mention as a goal for Indian citizens?','Only economic justice','Social economic and political justice','Only political justice','Only social justice','B',2,0,0,2),(2406,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','The Objective Resolution described India as a union of territories. Which territories are mentioned?','Only British Indian territories','The territories of British India Indian States and territories outside British India willing to join','Only the princely states','Only the democratic provinces','B',2,0,0,2),(2407,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','Why did the Objective Resolution specify that autonomous units would have residuary powers?','To strengthen central government','To ensure that states and units retained powers not specifically delegated to the central authority preserving federal character','To make India a confederation','To limit the powers of Parliament','B',3,0,0,3),(2408,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','The Objective Resolution promised safeguards for minorities backward and tribal areas. What principle does this reflect?','Majoritarianism','The commitment to protect vulnerable groups even within a democratic framework','Separation of religion from politics','Economic equality','B',3,0,0,3),(2409,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','How did the Objective Resolution become the Preamble to the Indian Constitution?','The Preamble replaced the Objective Resolution','The core principles of the Objective Resolution were incorporated into the Preamble giving it constitutional status','The Objective Resolution became an appendix to the Constitution','The Preamble was written by different people from those who drafted the Objective Resolution','B',3,0,0,3),(2410,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','The Objective Resolution stated India would be a republic. How does a republic differ from a constitutional monarchy?','In a republic the head of state is elected or appointed not hereditary','In a republic there is no legislature','In a republic the military controls the government','In a republic there are no fundamental rights','A',4,0,0,4),(2411,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','Why was the Objective Resolution moved on 13 December 1946 before the Constitution was drafted?','To celebrate independence','To establish the foundational principles and goals that would guide the drafting of the Constitution','To elect the President','To declare war on Pakistan','B',4,0,0,4),(2412,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','The Objective Resolution promised fundamental freedoms to all Indians. Why was it significant that this was stated at the very beginning of the Constitution-making process?','It was only a formality','It committed the framers to protecting individual rights from the outset making freedom a foundational principle of the new republic','It replaced the need for Fundamental Rights in the Constitution','It was mainly for international audiences','B',4,0,0,4),(2413,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','The Objective Resolution includes the phrase all power and authority of the sovereign independent India and its constitution shall flow from the people. Why is this principle of popular sovereignty so fundamental to democracy?','Because it prevents military coups','Because it establishes that the state''s authority derives from and is accountable to the citizens it governs','Because it means people can change the government daily','Because it gives each citizen a veto over laws','B',5,0,0,5),(2414,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','How did the Objective Resolution address the challenge of integrating princely states into India?','By ignoring the princely states','By referring to territories willing to join as part of India leaving room for negotiation while affirming India''s territorial unity','By forcing all princely states to join immediately','By allowing princely states to remain independent','B',5,0,0,5),(2415,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Objective Resolution','Nehru described the Objective Resolution as a pledge and undertaking. What does this language suggest about the moral weight given to constitution-making?','It suggests the Constitution was only a legal document','It suggests the framers saw constitution-making as a moral and historical commitment to the people of India beyond mere legal formality','It suggests the Constitution could be easily changed','It suggests Nehru was making a personal promise','B',5,0,0,5),(2416,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','On which date was the Indian Constitution adopted?','26-Jan-50','15-Aug-47','26-Nov-49','13-Dec-46','C',1,0,0,1),(2417,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','On which date did the Indian Constitution come into force?','26-Nov-49','13-Dec-46','15-Aug-47','26-Jan-50','D',1,0,0,1),(2418,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','How many articles did the original Indian Constitution have?','295','305','395','425','C',1,0,0,1),(2419,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','How many schedules did the original Indian Constitution have?','6','8','10','12','B',1,0,0,1),(2420,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','What type of legislature does the Indian Constitution establish at the central level?','Unicameral','Bicameral','Tricameral','No legislature','B',2,0,0,2),(2421,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','What are Directive Principles of State Policy (DPSP)?','Fundamental rights that can be enforced in court','Guidelines for the government to follow in policy making though not enforceable in court','Laws passed by Parliament','Fundamental duties of citizens','B',2,0,0,2),(2422,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','What does it mean that the Indian Constitution is both rigid and flexible?','The Constitution can never be changed','Some parts require a special amendment procedure (rigid) while others can be amended by ordinary majority (flexible)','The Constitution changes every year','The Constitution is rigid for states but flexible for the Centre','B',2,0,0,2),(2423,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','The Indian Constitution was drafted from 9 December 1946. How many years did it take to complete?','1 year','2 years','3 years','5 years','C',2,0,0,2),(2424,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','Why is the Indian Constitution described as the largest written constitution in the world?','Because it covers all possible laws','Because it is a comprehensive document addressing the governance of a diverse nation with detailed provisions','Because the framers wanted to show India''s importance','Because it includes the constitution of all states','B',3,0,0,3),(2425,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','What does parliamentary democracy mean in the context of the Indian Constitution?','The President holds all executive power','The executive is responsible to the legislature and derives authority from it','Parliament can override the Supreme Court','All citizens can become members of Parliament','B',3,0,0,3),(2426,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','What are Fundamental Duties in the Indian Constitution?','Rights that cannot be taken away','Obligations of citizens towards the state and society','Duties only of government officials','International obligations of India','B',3,0,0,3),(2427,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','What are Independent Constitutional Institutions mentioned in the chapter?','Institutions that are part of the central government','Bodies like the Election Commission and CAG that function independently of executive control','Private organisations given constitutional status','State governments','B',3,0,0,3),(2428,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','Why does the Indian Constitution establish an independent judiciary?','To give judges more salary','To ensure that constitutional rights are protected and disputes between citizens and the state or between states are resolved impartially','To allow judges to make new laws','To give the judiciary power over Parliament','B',4,0,0,4),(2429,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','How does the Indian Constitution balance federalism with a strong centre?','By making states completely sovereign','By dividing powers between Centre and states through three lists while giving the Centre override powers during emergencies','By abolishing states entirely','By making the Centre subservient to states','B',4,0,0,4),(2430,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','Why are Fundamental Rights described as justiciable?','Because they are very important','Because they can be enforced through the courts meaning citizens can sue the government if rights are violated','Because judges wrote them','Because they appear in the Constitution','B',4,0,0,4),(2431,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','The Constitution came into force on 26 January 1950. Why was this date chosen?','It was Nehru''s birthday','It commemorated 26 January 1930 when the Indian National Congress passed the Purna Swaraj resolution demanding complete independence','It was the birthday of B.R. Ambedkar','It was the date India joined the United Nations','B',4,0,0,4),(2432,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','The Indian Constitution has Fundamental Rights AND Directive Principles of State Policy. How do these two sets of provisions differ and complement each other?','They are the same thing','Fundamental Rights are justiciable individual protections while DPSPs are non-justiciable policy goals; together they balance individual freedom with social justice','Fundamental Rights are for the government while DPSPs are for citizens','DPSPs override Fundamental Rights','B',5,0,0,5),(2433,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','Why does the Indian Constitution need to be both rigid and flexible?','For aesthetic balance','Rigidity for core provisions protects fundamental rights and structure from hasty changes while flexibility for other provisions allows adaptation to changing needs','Rigid parts can never be changed','Flexibility means any one citizen can amend the Constitution','B',5,0,0,5),(2434,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','The Indian Constitution establishes parliamentary democracy AND federalism. How can there be tension between these two features?','There is no tension','In parliamentary democracy the Centre may dominate while federalism requires state autonomy; the Constitution manages this tension through division of powers','Parliamentary democracy and federalism are identical','Federalism means there is no central Parliament','B',5,0,0,5),(2435,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Features of the Indian Constitution','Why was it important that India established Independent Constitutional Institutions like the Election Commission?','To create more government jobs','To ensure that critical functions like elections remain free from political interference by the executive thus protecting democracy','To give the judiciary more power','Because Parliament demanded it','B',5,0,0,5),(2436,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','Which of the following is a feature of Indian Federalism mentioned in the chapter?','Dual citizenship for Centre and states','Single citizenship','No written constitution','Absence of an independent judiciary','B',1,0,0,1),(2437,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','Does India have single or dual citizenship?','Dual citizenship','Single citizenship','No citizenship system','State-level citizenship','B',1,0,0,1),(2438,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','What type of judiciary does Indian federalism require?','A separate court for each state','An independent judiciary','A judiciary controlled by the Centre','No judiciary','B',1,0,0,1),(2439,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','How is India described in the chapter in terms of its federal character?','Purely federal','Quasi-federal (federal with a strong centre)','Purely unitary','A confederation','D',1,0,0,1),(2440,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','What does a common Constitution in a federal system mean?','Each state has its own constitution','The same Constitution governs both the Centre and the states','The Constitution can be changed by any state','States can write separate constitutions','B',2,0,0,2),(2441,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','Why is the sovereignty of the Constitution important in Indian federalism?','So that Parliament can change the Constitution easily','So that neither the Centre nor the states can override the Constitution as the supreme law of the land','So that the President has the final say','So that courts cannot interpret the Constitution','B',2,0,0,2),(2442,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','What does division of powers mean in Indian federalism?','The President divides power among ministers','The Constitution assigns different subjects to the Centre and states through separate legislative lists','Power is equally shared between all citizens','The military divides power with the civilian government','B',2,0,0,2),(2443,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','The chapter describes India as quasi-federal. What does this mean?','India is half a federation','India has federal features but with a stronger Centre than in a purely federal system like the USA','India is neither federal nor unitary','India''s federation changes every year','B',2,0,0,2),(2444,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','How does a bicameral legislature support federalism in India?','By having two presidents','By having a Rajya Sabha (Council of States) that represents state interests at the central level alongside the Lok Sabha','By allowing states to have two legislatures','By giving each state an equal number of seats in Parliament','B',3,0,0,3),(2445,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','What is the difference between a federal system and a confederation?','They are the same','In a federation the central government has authority over citizens directly while in a confederation it only has authority through state governments','A federation has no constitution while a confederation does','A confederation is stronger than a federation','B',3,0,0,3),(2446,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','Why does Indian federalism have a strong centre compared to other federations?','Because the President is more powerful than in other countries','Because the framers wanted to prevent the kind of centrifugal forces that could lead to disintegration given India''s diversity and the experience of partition','Because states demanded a strong centre','Because the British demanded a strong centre','B',3,0,0,3),(2447,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','How does the Indian Constitution maintain the sovereignty of the Constitution rather than sovereignty of Parliament or states?','By making the Constitution unchangeable','Through judicial review which allows courts to strike down laws that violate the Constitution even if passed by Parliament or state legislatures','By giving the President veto power','By requiring all laws to be approved by citizens','B',3,0,0,3),(2448,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','The chapter mentions that India has a common constitution. How does this differ from countries like the USA where states have their own constitutions?','There is no difference','In India states cannot have their own constitutions meaning India has a more unified constitutional framework than the USA','Indian states can have separate constitutions if they choose','The USA does not have state constitutions','B',4,0,0,4),(2449,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','Why does single citizenship in India contrast with the USA where citizens have both national and state citizenship?','Because India is smaller than the USA','Because single citizenship reinforces national unity and prevents the development of strong state-based identities that could threaten national cohesion','Because Indian states demanded single citizenship','Because the British colonial system required single citizenship','B',4,0,0,4),(2450,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','How does the Indian Supreme Court''s role in resolving Centre-state disputes demonstrate the principle of constitutional sovereignty?','It shows the Supreme Court is more powerful than Parliament','It demonstrates that the Constitution is the ultimate arbiter of disputes showing that even the Centre cannot override constitutional provisions','It shows states can always win against the Centre','It shows the Supreme Court writes the Constitution','B',4,0,0,4),(2451,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','The Rajya Sabha in Indian Parliament represents the states. How effectively does it protect state interests compared to the US Senate where each state has equal representation?','The Rajya Sabha is identical to the US Senate','The Rajya Sabha has states represented proportionally to population while the US Senate gives equal representation to each state meaning large Indian states have more influence but small states have less protection','The Rajya Sabha gives each state equal seats','The US Senate is more powerful than India''s Rajya Sabha','B',4,0,0,4),(2452,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','Why do some scholars argue that India''s quasi-federal system undermines true federalism?','Because India has too many states','Because the Centre has override powers (through Article 356 President''s Rule emergency powers) that can suspend state governments challenging the autonomy that genuine federalism requires','Because states are too powerful in India','Because India has no written constitution','B',5,0,0,5),(2453,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','How does the concept of quasi-federalism in India reflect the historical context of its creation?','It was copied from Pakistan''s constitution','The framers responding to partition and concerns about national unity deliberately created a federation with a strong centre to ensure national integration while still respecting regional diversity','The British demanded a quasi-federal system','It was created to please small states','B',5,0,0,5),(2454,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','The chapter states that in Indian federalism there is a division of powers sovereignty of constitution single citizenship independent judiciary bicameral legislature and quasi-federal structure. How do these features work together as a system?','These features are independent of each other','These features are mutually reinforcing: divided powers define the federation; constitutional sovereignty ensures rules are followed; independent judiciary enforces them; single citizenship and bicameral legislature balance unity with state representation','Only some of these features are actually present in India','The features contradict each other','B',5,0,0,5),(2455,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Indian Federalism','Why might the strong centre in Indian federalism be justified despite the tension it creates with state autonomy?','Because the states are too small to govern themselves','Because given India''s enormous diversity in language religion and culture a weak centre could lead to fragmentation while the strong centre helps maintain the unity needed for development and democracy','Because states demanded a strong centre','Because international treaties require a strong central government','B',5,0,0,5),(2456,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','In which schedule of the Indian Constitution are the three legislative lists (Union State and Concurrent) found?','Fifth Schedule','Sixth Schedule','Seventh Schedule','Eighth Schedule','C',1,0,0,1),(2457,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','How many subjects are in the Union List originally?','66','47','97','100','C',1,0,0,1),(2458,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Which of the following is a Union List subject?','Agriculture','Local government','Defence','Marriage','C',1,0,0,1),(2459,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Which of the following is a State List subject?','Foreign affairs','Banking','Railways','Police','D',1,0,0,1),(2460,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','How many subjects are in the Concurrent List originally?','97','47','66','30','B',2,0,0,2),(2461,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Which of the following is a Concurrent List subject?','Citizenship','Defence','Education','Foreign affairs','C',2,0,0,2),(2462,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','What are Residuary Powers and who holds them in India?','Powers shared equally between Centre and states','Powers not mentioned in any list which belong to the Centre in India','Powers reserved for the Supreme Court','Powers given to the states','B',2,0,0,2),(2463,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','What is an example of a residuary power mentioned in the chapter?','Education','Cyber laws','Agriculture','Marriage','B',2,0,0,2),(2464,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','If Parliament and a state legislature both pass laws on a Concurrent List subject and they conflict which law prevails?','The state law prevails','The Central law prevails','The Supreme Court decides case by case','Both laws are invalid','B',3,0,0,3),(2465,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Why is citizenship a Union List subject rather than a State List subject?','Because states cannot make citizenship laws','Because having uniform national citizenship is essential for national unity and cannot be left to individual states','Because citizenship is too complex for states','Because the British required central control of citizenship','B',3,0,0,3),(2466,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Why is agriculture a State List subject rather than a Union List subject?','Because agriculture is not important nationally','Because agriculture is primarily a local matter that varies by region making state-level regulation more appropriate than central regulation','Because the Centre has no interest in agriculture','Because agriculture was always a state subject in British India','B',3,0,0,3),(2467,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','What is the significance of education being on the Concurrent List?','Education is not important enough for the Union List','Both Parliament and state legislatures can legislate on education allowing national standards while permitting state adaptation to local needs','Education should be only a state subject','The Centre has no role in education','B',3,0,0,3),(2468,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Why is defence a Union List subject rather than a State List or Concurrent List subject?','Because only the Centre has the resources for defence','Because national defence requires unified command and cannot be fragmented among states as it involves the sovereignty and integrity of the entire country','Because states do not have armies','Because defence was always a central subject in India','B',4,0,0,4),(2469,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','The Union List has more subjects than the State List. What does this tell us about the balance of power in Indian federalism?','States are more powerful than the Centre','The Centre has jurisdiction over more areas of governance reflecting India''s quasi-federal nature with a stronger Centre','All subjects on both lists have equal importance','The State List subjects are more important than the Union List subjects','B',4,0,0,4),(2470,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Residuary powers belong to the Centre in India but to the states in the USA. What does this difference tell us about these two federal systems?','There is no difference','It reinforces that India has a stronger centre than the USA as giving residuary powers to the Centre means any new area of legislation defaults to central control','The USA has a stronger centre than India','Residuary powers are unimportant in both countries','B',4,0,0,4),(2471,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','Why does the Concurrent List exist as a separate category rather than putting all subjects either in the Union or State List?','To create confusion','Because some subjects like education and forests need both national standards and local adaptation requiring both levels of government to be able to legislate','Because the framers ran out of space in the other lists','Because the British demanded a concurrent list','B',4,0,0,4),(2472,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','The original Union List had 97 subjects. Critics argue this makes India''s federalism more centralist than federal. How would you evaluate this criticism?','There are no valid criticisms of Indian federalism','The criticism has merit as having more subjects under central jurisdiction limits state autonomy though the division was designed to balance unity with diversity given India''s complex post-independence challenges','The Union List is too small','States have more subjects than the Centre','B',5,0,0,5),(2473,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','How does giving cyber laws as residuary powers to the Centre reflect the framers'' wisdom?','The framers knew about cyber laws in 1950','By giving residuary powers to the Centre the framers ensured that unforeseen new areas of legislation would be handled centrally preventing a vacuum in governance for issues that did not exist when the Constitution was drafted','Cyber laws were common in 1950','The framers gave residuary powers to the states','B',5,0,0,5),(2474,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','If Parliament passes a law on a Concurrent List subject that conflicts with a state law previously passed on the same subject what happens to the state law?','The state law continues to operate','The state law becomes void to the extent of the inconsistency with the Central law unless the state law had received the President''s assent','Both laws operate simultaneously','The Supreme Court must approve the Central law first','B',5,0,0,5),(2475,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Division of Powers','The Seventh Schedule with its three lists represents a constitutional solution to dividing power in a diverse nation. What are the key principles behind how subjects were allocated to different lists?','Subjects were allocated randomly','Subjects requiring national uniformity went to Union List; subjects requiring local adaptation went to State List; subjects needing both went to Concurrent List; with residuary powers at Centre to handle new areas','All important subjects went to the State List','The allocation was based on the British colonial system','B',5,0,0,5),(2476,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','What are the three organs of government mentioned in the chapter?','President Prime Minister and Parliament','Legislature Executive and Judiciary','Union List State List and Concurrent List','Lok Sabha Rajya Sabha and the President','B',1,0,0,1),(2477,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','What is the main function of the Legislature?','To implement laws','To make laws','To interpret laws','To enforce laws','B',1,0,0,1),(2478,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','What is the main function of the Judiciary?','To make laws','To implement laws','To interpret laws and resolve disputes','To collect taxes','C',1,0,0,1),(2479,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','What is the main function of the Executive?','To make laws','To implement laws made by the Legislature','To interpret the Constitution','To conduct elections','B',1,0,0,1),(2480,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','Who does Parliament (the Legislature) consist of in India?','Only the Lok Sabha','The Lok Sabha Rajya Sabha and the President','Only the Prime Minister and Cabinet','All elected representatives across India','B',1,0,0,1),(2481,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','What does the separation of powers principle prevent?','Efficient governance','Concentration of all power in one organ of government','Democratic elections','Federalism','B',2,0,0,2),(2482,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','How does the parliamentary form of government in India relate to the separation of powers?','The executive and legislature are completely separate','The executive is derived from and responsible to the legislature creating a partial fusion of powers','The judiciary controls the executive','Parliament and the Judiciary have equal powers','B',2,0,0,2),(2483,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','What is meant by checks and balances in the context of separation of powers?','Financial controls on government spending','Each organ of government has ways to limit and oversee the powers of the other organs','A system of counting votes','A military oversight mechanism','B',2,0,0,2),(2484,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','Dr. Ambedkar said that the Constitution protects Indian democracy from being surrendered by legislature and executive. How?','By giving all power to the Judiciary','By separating powers and establishing an independent judiciary that can check the actions of the other organs','By giving all power to the people through referendums','By making the Constitution impossible to amend','B',2,0,0,2),(2485,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','The Indian Parliament consists of the Lok Sabha Rajya Sabha and the President. Why is the President part of Parliament even though the President is also head of the executive?','Because the President wants to be in Parliament','Because the President''s assent is required for bills to become law making the President part of the legislative process','Because the President writes all laws','Because the Rajya Sabha elected the President','B',2,0,0,2),(2486,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','How does judicial review strengthen the separation of powers in India?','By allowing judges to make laws','By giving courts the power to strike down legislative and executive actions that violate the Constitution thus ensuring no organ exceeds its constitutional limits','By making the judiciary the most powerful organ','By preventing Parliament from passing any laws','B',3,0,0,3),(2487,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','In what way does India''s parliamentary system differ from the US presidential system in terms of separation of powers?','They are identical','In India the executive comes from the legislature and is accountable to it while in the USA the President is independently elected and not directly accountable to Congress','In India the President is directly elected','In the USA Congress and the President are from the same party','B',3,0,0,3),(2488,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','How does federalism work together with separation of powers to distribute power in India?','They are unrelated concepts','Separation of powers distributes power horizontally between organs (legislature executive judiciary) while federalism distributes power vertically between Centre and states creating a comprehensive power distribution','Federalism replaces the need for separation of powers','Separation of powers applies only at the state level','B',3,0,0,3),(2489,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','Why is an independent judiciary essential for both separation of powers and federalism to function?','Because judges need secure jobs','Because without an independent judiciary neither citizens'' rights against the executive nor states'' rights against the Centre could be effectively enforced','Because the judiciary controls Parliament','Because judges elect the President','B',3,0,0,3),(2490,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','The Constitution prevents concentration of power through both the parliamentary form and federal structure. How do these two mechanisms work together?','They contradict each other','The parliamentary form ensures executive accountability to elected representatives while federalism ensures power is distributed between Centre and states so no single entity can accumulate all power','Only the parliamentary form prevents concentration of power','Only federalism prevents concentration of power','B',3,0,0,3),(2491,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','Why does the Constitution give the Supreme Court the power to review laws passed by Parliament?','Because Supreme Court judges are more intelligent than Parliament','Because the founders recognised that a popularly elected Parliament could still violate constitutional rights and only an independent court could serve as a neutral arbiter of constitutionality','Because Parliament demanded judicial review','Because the British required judicial review','B',4,0,0,4),(2492,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','Ambedkar argued that without constitutional safeguards democracy could be surrendered by those who hold power. What historical examples support this concern?','There are no examples','History shows that elected majorities can undermine democracy through legitimate means so constitutional constraints on majority power are necessary to protect minority rights and institutional independence','Elected governments always protect democracy','Constitutional safeguards are unnecessary if elections are free','B',4,0,0,4),(2493,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','How does the doctrine of separation of powers protect individual rights?','By ensuring everyone has a job in government','By ensuring that no single person or group controls all aspects of governance preventing tyranny and creating multiple points of accountability','By giving individuals power over the government','By ensuring all laws protect individual rights','B',4,0,0,4),(2494,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','The Indian executive (Council of Ministers) is responsible to Parliament. Why does this accountability to the legislature strengthen democracy beyond what a purely separated executive provides?','Because it makes the executive weaker','Because requiring the executive to maintain the confidence of elected representatives ensures ongoing democratic accountability rather than just accountability at election time','Because it gives Parliament more power','Because the Prime Minister is more important than the President','B',4,0,0,4),(2495,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','In what ways does India''s system of power distribution through separation of powers AND federalism reflect the framers'' understanding of how power can be abused?','The framers were not concerned about power abuse','The framers understood that power must be checked at multiple levels: horizontally through separation of organs and vertically through federalism creating a system where no single actor can dominate all governance','The framers only cared about efficiency','Power distribution was imposed by the British','B',4,0,0,4),(2496,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','Dr. Ambedkar''s warning that democracy could be surrendered is particularly relevant to the relationship between the elected majority and constitutional rights. What mechanism does the Indian Constitution use to protect against this?','Regular elections every five years','Fundamental Rights that cannot be abrogated even by Parliament combined with judicial review allowing courts to strike down laws violating these rights','The President''s veto power','International oversight of Indian elections','B',5,0,0,5),(2497,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','How does the separation of powers in India reflect a tension between efficiency (which centralised authority provides) and accountability (which separated powers provide)?','There is no tension','Separation of powers reduces efficiency because each organ must work within constitutional limits but this inefficiency is the price of accountability and prevents abuse of power','Separated powers are more efficient than centralised power','Accountability and efficiency are not in tension','B',5,0,0,5),(2498,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','The chapter says the parliamentary form and federal structure prevent concentration of power. However critics note that the Central government has used Article 356 (President''s Rule) to dismiss state governments. Does this undermine the separation of powers argument?','Article 356 does not exist','Article 356 does create tension with federalism as it allows the Centre to override state governments; however the Supreme Court''s role in reviewing such actions (as in the Bommai case) shows that even central power is subject to constitutional checks','Article 356 strengthens federalism','The Supreme Court has never reviewed Article 356 cases','B',5,0,0,5),(2499,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','How does the existence of independent constitutional institutions like the Election Commission and the CAG reinforce the separation of powers beyond the traditional three organs?','These institutions have no constitutional role','They extend the principle of power separation by creating additional autonomous bodies that perform critical functions free from executive interference thus adding more checks to the power distribution system','These institutions are part of the executive','The Election Commission and CAG are part of Parliament','B',5,0,0,5),(2500,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'4','Distribution of Power in the Indian Constitution',25,'Separation of Powers','Comparing the division of powers (Centre vs states) with the separation of powers (Legislature vs Executive vs Judiciary) what fundamental principle underlies both?','Both are about giving more power to the Centre','Both reflect the same fundamental principle: that concentrated power is dangerous to democracy and that distributing power among multiple accountable actors creates better governance and protects rights','Division of powers is about territory while separation of powers is about functions with no common principle','Both systems were copied from the USA','B',5,0,0,5),(2501,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','From which languages are the roots of the word demography derived?','Latin and French','Greek demos (people) and graphein (define)','Sanskrit and Persian','Arabic and Turkish','B',1,0,0,1),(2502,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','According to UNFPA 2023 what is India''s approximate population?','100 crore','120 crore','142.86 crore','160 crore','C',1,0,0,1),(2503,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','Which institution conducts the census in India?','NITI Aayog','National Sample Organisation','Office of the Census Commissioner of India','National Institute of Population Studies','C',1,0,0,1),(2504,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','How often is the census conducted in India?','Every 5 years','Every 10 years','Every 15 years','Every 20 years','B',1,0,0,1),(2505,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','What is the difference between formal demography and social demography?','They are the same thing','Formal demography focuses on statistical data about population while social demography examines the relationship between population changes and social factors','Formal demography is older than social demography','Social demography only studies migration','B',2,0,0,2),(2506,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','According to the chapter which institution is responsible for collecting population data through the NSO?','NFHS','NIPFP','National Sample Organisation','Census Commissioner','C',2,0,0,2),(2507,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','According to UNFPA 2023 what is the approximate world population?','500 crore','600 crore','700 crore','804.5 crore','D',2,0,0,2),(2508,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','What does NFHS stand for in the context of population studies in India?','National Female Health Survey','National Family Health Survey','National Fertility and Housing Survey','National Food and Health Survey','B',2,0,0,2),(2509,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','Why is India''s census described as the largest census in the world?','Because India has the most accurate data','Because India is the world''s most populous country conducting a massive data collection exercise','Because India invented the census','Because India''s census covers more topics than any other','B',3,0,0,3),(2510,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','What is the role of NITI Aayog (formerly NIPFP) in population studies in India?','To conduct the census','To conduct research and provide policy recommendations related to population and economic planning','To register births and deaths','To manage migration of workers','B',3,0,0,3),(2511,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','How does the study of demography help governments make decisions?','It helps governments make travel plans','It provides data on population size growth distribution and characteristics enabling governments to plan for education healthcare housing and employment','It helps governments decide which languages to teach','It is only useful for historical research','B',3,0,0,3),(2512,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','The word demography combines demos (people) and graphein (define or write). What does this etymology tell us about the purpose of demography?','That demography is about writing stories about people','That demography is fundamentally about describing and writing about people in quantitative terms','That demography is a form of poetry','That demography was invented by the Greeks','B',3,0,0,3),(2513,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','Why does India need multiple institutions (NSO NFHS NITI Aayog NIPS) for population studies rather than just one?','Because each institution duplicates the others'' work','Because different aspects of population study require different methodologies and expertise with the census providing comprehensive data while NFHS provides health-focused surveys and NITI Aayog analyses policy implications','Because the government creates unnecessary institutions','Because population data is too simple for multiple institutions','B',4,0,0,4),(2514,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','India overtook China to become the world''s most populous country. What challenges does this create for governance?','No challenges as more people means more workers','Pressure on food water housing education healthcare and employment systems that must be planned using accurate demographic data','Population size has no effect on governance','India should reduce its population immediately','B',4,0,0,4),(2515,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','What distinguishes a national census from a sample survey like NFHS?','They collect identical data','A census attempts to count every person in the country while a sample survey studies a representative subset to draw conclusions about the whole population','A sample survey is more accurate than a census','A census only counts men','B',4,0,0,4),(2516,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','Why is population data collected every 10 years in India and not more frequently?','Because the government is lazy','Because a census is expensive and logistically complex requiring massive resources while 10-year intervals balance the need for updated data with practical constraints','Because population does not change frequently','Because the Constitution requires 10-year intervals','B',4,0,0,4),(2517,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','India having the world''s most populous census is described as a significant achievement. What challenges does conducting a census in a diverse country like India involve?','India''s census is simple because everyone speaks Hindi','Conducting a census in India requires working across 22 official languages hundreds of dialects diverse geographies remote areas and a population of over 1.4 billion','India''s census only covers cities','India''s census does not cover tribal areas','B',5,0,0,5),(2518,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','How does the distinction between formal demography (statistical focus) and social demography (social factors focus) reflect different approaches to understanding population?','They are identical approaches','Formal demography tells us what is happening to population through numbers while social demography asks why it is happening by examining social economic and cultural factors; together they provide a complete picture','Social demography is less scientific than formal demography','Formal demography is only useful for mathematicians','B',5,0,0,5),(2519,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','The chapter mentions that India''s population was 142.86 crore while the world''s was 804.5 crore. What percentage of the world''s population does India represent approximately?','About 10%','About 18%','About 25%','About 30%','B',5,0,0,5),(2520,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Demography Basics','Why might population data from the census be important for planning school construction in a district?','Because schools are built where census offices are','Because census data on the number of children in different age groups in each area tells planners exactly how many school seats are needed in each location','Because census data is only used for national planning','Because school construction is independent of population data','B',5,0,0,5),(2521,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','According to census data what was India''s approximate population in 1901?','100 million','238 million','300 million','500 million','B',1,0,0,1),(2522,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','According to census data what was India''s population in 2011?','800 million','1000 million','1210 million','1400 million','C',1,0,0,1),(2523,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','In which year did India''s population actually decrease compared to the previous census?','1901','1911','1921','1931','C',1,0,0,1),(2524,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','India''s population was 251 million in 1921. In which year was it lower than this?','1901','1911','1931','1941','B',1,0,0,1),(2525,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','What was the main cause of the population decline seen in the 1921 census?','A deliberate government policy','Famines diseases and epidemics that caused high death rates','Large-scale emigration from India','A drop in birth rates','B',2,0,0,2),(2526,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','What does the population data from 1901 to 2011 reveal about the overall trend?','India''s population decreased overall','India''s population grew dramatically from 238 million to 1210 million over a century','India''s population remained stable','India''s population grew only after independence','B',2,0,0,2),(2527,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','Why is 1921 called the Year of the Great Divide in Indian demographic history?','Because India was divided in 1921','Because it marks the transition from a period of stagnant or declining population to continuous rapid population growth','Because the first census was conducted in 1921','Because India''s borders were fixed in 1921','B',2,0,0,2),(2528,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','What is the significance of a census showing a decline in population compared to the previous census?','It means the census was inaccurate','It indicates that death rates exceeded birth rates suggesting crisis conditions such as famine disease or epidemics','It means people emigrated from the country','It is normal and expected','B',2,0,0,2),(2529,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','After 1921 India''s population grew rapidly. What factors contributed to this growth?','A sudden increase in immigration','Gradual decline in death rates due to improved medicine and public health while birth rates remained high','A large increase in birth rates only','The end of British rule','B',3,0,0,3),(2530,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','Why did population grow more slowly before 1921 compared to after?','Because people were less fertile before 1921','Because high death rates from disease famine and epidemics offset high birth rates while after 1921 death rates gradually fell','Because people had fewer children before 1921','Because there was more emigration before 1921','B',3,0,0,3),(2531,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','What does the pattern of population growth from 1901 to 2011 (with 1921 as the Year of the Great Divide) tell us about the relationship between population growth and development?','Population always grows at the same rate','Improvements in healthcare and food security lowered death rates faster than birth rates fell leading to rapid population growth a pattern common to developing countries','Development always reduces population growth','Population growth and development are unrelated','B',3,0,0,3),(2532,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','From 1901 to 1921 India''s population grew very slowly (from 238 million to 251 million). What does this slow growth suggest about living conditions?','Living conditions were excellent','Harsh living conditions with high death rates from disease famine and poor healthcare nearly offset the birth rate resulting in minimal net growth','People chose to have fewer children','There was significant emigration during this period','B',3,0,0,3),(2533,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','India''s population grew from 238 million in 1901 to 1210 million in 2011 - more than a fivefold increase. What are the implications of such rapid population growth for resource planning?','Population growth has no implications for resources','Such growth creates enormous demands on food water energy education and healthcare requiring sophisticated long-term planning using demographic data','India''s resources are unlimited so growth is not a problem','Population growth always leads to prosperity','B',4,0,0,4),(2534,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','The 1921 decline in India''s population coincided with global epidemics like the Spanish flu. How does this external event illustrate the relationship between global and local demographic trends?','Global events do not affect Indian demography','External events like global pandemics can dramatically affect local demographic trends showing that Indian population dynamics cannot be understood in isolation from global events','India was unaffected by the Spanish flu','Only wars affect population decline','B',4,0,0,4),(2535,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','How does the census data from 1901 to 2011 help us understand the demographic transition theory (which predicts that death rates fall before birth rates in developing countries)?','The data contradicts demographic transition theory','The data supports it: from 1901 to 1921 both birth and death rates were high; from 1921 death rates began falling while birth rates remained high leading to rapid growth','The data shows birth rates fell before death rates in India','Demographic transition theory does not apply to India','B',4,0,0,4),(2536,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','Why might policymakers be concerned if population growth continues at the rate seen from 1921 to 2011?','Because more people means more votes','Because continued rapid growth could outpace the country''s ability to provide adequate food housing healthcare education and employment for all citizens','Because population growth always leads to poverty','Because international organisations require population control','B',4,0,0,4),(2537,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','India''s population growth from 1901 to 2011 was largely driven by falling death rates rather than rising birth rates. What does this tell us about the nature of India''s demographic challenge?','India needs to increase birth rates','The demographic challenge is not that people are having too many children compared to before but that far more people are surviving creating a population growth that requires development to match','India needs to increase death rates','Population growth was caused by immigration','B',5,0,0,5),(2538,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','The census data shows population was 251 million in 1921 and 1210 million in 2011. Using the demographic transition framework what stages can we identify in this data?','Only one stage is visible','We can see the late high-stationary stage around 1921 followed by the early-expanding stage from 1921-1947 as death rates fell and then the late-expanding stage post-independence as healthcare improved further','The data shows no stages','Demographic transition does not apply to census data','B',5,0,0,5),(2539,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','Why is accurate historical population data from before independence important for understanding India''s current demographic situation?','Historical data has no relevance to current demographics','Historical data provides baseline trends that allow us to understand how and why the population grew to its current size and predict future trends','Historical data is too old to be useful','India''s demographics changed completely after independence','B',5,0,0,5),(2540,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Growth','If India''s population grew from 238 million in 1901 to 1210 million in 2011 what average decadal growth rate does this represent and what are the implications?','Exactly 10% per decade with no variation','An average of about 17% per decade though varying significantly with slow growth pre-1921 and rapid growth post-1921; this implies India experienced its most challenging population growth precisely when it was trying to develop economically','Exactly 5% per decade throughout','The growth was entirely after 1947','B',5,0,0,5),(2541,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','What is internal migration?','Migration between two different countries','Migration within the borders of one country','Migration to a neighbouring country','Temporary migration for work','B',1,0,0,1),(2542,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','What is international migration?','Migration within a country','Migration that crosses national borders','Migration from rural to urban areas','Migration for religious reasons','B',1,0,0,1),(2543,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','The chapter mentions Kerala workers going to Gulf countries. This is an example of what type of migration?','Internal migration','International migration','Rural to urban migration','Forced migration','B',1,0,0,1),(2544,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','Which famous Malayalam poet wrote about Kerala workers going to Assam during World War II?','G. Sankara Kurup','O.N.V. Kurup','Vailoppilly Sreedhara Menon','Kumaran Asan','C',1,0,0,1),(2545,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','What are push factors in migration?','Factors that attract people to a new place','Factors that drive people away from their current place of residence','Government policies encouraging migration','Natural disasters only','B',2,0,0,2),(2546,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','What are pull factors in migration?','Factors that force people to leave their home','Factors that attract people to a destination such as better income or higher social status','Government policies discouraging migration','Religious factors only','B',2,0,0,2),(2547,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','The chapter mentions better income as an example of what type of migration factor?','Push factor','Pull factor','Neutral factor','Political factor','B',2,0,0,2),(2548,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','What does the term guest workers refer to in Kerala?','Foreign tourists in Kerala','Migrant workers from other states who work in Kerala','Kerala workers going abroad','Workers employed by the government','B',2,0,0,2),(2549,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','Why did Kerala workers go to Assam during World War II as described in Vailoppilly''s poem?','For religious reasons','For employment opportunities as the war created labour demands in Assam''s industries','Due to government orders','Due to natural disasters in Kerala','B',3,0,0,3),(2550,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','What push factors might have driven Kerala workers to migrate to Gulf countries?','Excess job opportunities in Kerala','Lack of employment opportunities in Kerala despite a highly educated population pushing people to seek work abroad','High salaries in Kerala','Political instability in Kerala','B',3,0,0,3),(2551,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','How does migration affect the region that people leave?','It has no effect','It can lead to labour shortages in the source region while remittances sent back can improve living standards','It always leads to economic growth in the source region','It only affects urban areas','B',3,0,0,3),(2552,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','Why is the distinction between internal and international migration important for policy?','It has no policy implications','Internal migration is governed by domestic law while international migration involves immigration laws of other countries creating different legal frameworks and policy responses','Internal migration is always more significant than international migration','All migration is treated the same by governments','B',3,0,0,3),(2553,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','Kerala has both significant outmigration (to Gulf countries and other states) and significant inmigration (guest workers from other states). What does this dual pattern suggest about Kerala''s economy?','Kerala''s economy is completely stagnant','Kerala''s economy is complex: it lacks sufficient jobs in some sectors forcing skilled workers to migrate while having labour shortages in other sectors attracting workers from other states','Kerala has no economy','This pattern is identical to all other Indian states','B',4,0,0,4),(2554,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','How does Vailoppilly''s poem about Kerala workers going to Assam during World War II serve as a historical demographic source?','Poems cannot be demographic sources','Literary sources like this poem document migration patterns and the human experience of migration providing historical evidence of demographic trends that may not be captured in official statistics','The poem is fictional and has no demographic value','Only census data can show migration trends','B',4,0,0,4),(2555,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','Why does high social status appear as a pull factor for migration?','Because social status is not important to migrants','Because people migrate not only for economic reasons but also for social mobility and improved social standing showing that demographic behaviour is influenced by social as well as economic factors','Because social status is the only reason people migrate','Because all migrants are concerned about status','B',4,0,0,4),(2556,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','The Gulf migration from Kerala transformed Kerala''s economy through remittances. How does this illustrate the relationship between international migration and regional development?','International migration has no effect on regional development','International migration can become a major driver of regional development when remittances flow back to the source region transforming living standards and local economies','Kerala''s development was unrelated to Gulf migration','Only domestic migration affects regional development','B',4,0,0,4),(2557,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','Why might a highly educated state like Kerala experience higher rates of outmigration than less educated states?','Education reduces the desire to migrate','A highly educated population has greater awareness of opportunities abroad higher qualifications that meet international labour demands and greater financial resources to enable migration','Educated people never migrate','Education and migration are unrelated','B',5,0,0,5),(2558,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','How does the presence of guest workers in Kerala creating a reverse migration pattern complicate simple push-pull models of migration?','Simple push-pull models explain all migration','Kerala''s dual migration pattern (outmigration of skilled workers and inmigration of unskilled workers) shows that push and pull factors operate differently for different skill levels revealing the complexity of migration drivers','Push-pull models have no limitations','Migration in Kerala follows a simple single-direction pattern','B',5,0,0,5),(2559,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','The chapter mentions both economic factors (better income) and social factors (high social status) as pull factors. What does including social factors tell us about why people migrate?','People only migrate for economic reasons','Migration decisions are complex involving not just material calculations but also aspirations for social recognition and status suggesting that demographic behaviour cannot be explained by economics alone','Social factors are less important than economic factors','People never migrate for social reasons','B',5,0,0,5),(2560,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Migration','How does studying migration patterns help governments plan for regional development?','Migration data is useless for planning','Migration data identifies regions experiencing population loss (needing economic development) and regions experiencing rapid growth (needing infrastructure expansion) allowing targeted policy interventions','All regions need the same development','Migration is too unpredictable for planning purposes','B',5,0,0,5),(2561,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','How is birth rate defined?','Number of children born per hundred population','Number of live births per thousand population','Number of births per million population','Number of babies born in hospitals per year','B',1,0,0,1),(2562,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','How is death rate defined?','Number of deaths per hundred population','Number of deaths per thousand population','Number of deaths per million population','Number of accidental deaths per year','B',1,0,0,1),(2563,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','What is infant mortality rate?','Number of infants who die before age 5 per thousand','Number of infants who die within one year of birth per 1000 live births','Number of infants who die at birth per 100','Number of infants who die per year in a country','B',1,0,0,1),(2564,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','What is maternal mortality rate?','The death rate of all women per year','The number of women dying due to causes related to childbirth per thousand births','The death rate of mothers above age 40','The number of pregnant women per thousand','B',1,0,0,1),(2565,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','How is population growth calculated according to the chapter?','Birth rate plus death rate','Birth rate minus death rate','Death rate minus birth rate','Immigration rate plus birth rate','B',2,0,0,2),(2566,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','If a country has a birth rate of 25 per thousand and a death rate of 8 per thousand what is the population growth rate?','33 per thousand','17 per thousand','25 per thousand','8 per thousand','B',2,0,0,2),(2567,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','Why is infant mortality rate considered an important indicator of development?','Because all countries have high infant mortality','Because the survival of infants reflects the quality of healthcare nutrition and maternal education making it a sensitive indicator of overall development','Because infants are not important to population statistics','Because infant mortality only affects poor families','B',2,0,0,2),(2568,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','Why is maternal mortality rate an important indicator of women''s health status?','Because it measures general population health','Because it measures the risk women face in childbirth reflecting healthcare quality access to skilled birth attendants and overall gender equity in healthcare','Because it is easy to measure','Because maternal mortality only affects rural women','B',2,0,0,2),(2569,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','If a population''s birth rate is lower than its death rate what happens to the total population?','The population grows rapidly','The population declines','The population stays the same','The population migrates','B',3,0,0,3),(2570,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','Why might a country want to reduce its birth rate?','To reduce population growth and ensure resources are adequate for existing and future citizens','To eliminate children from the country','To become less populous than neighbouring countries','Because fewer people means more land','A',3,0,0,3),(2571,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','High birth rates combined with falling death rates led to rapid population growth in India after 1921. Why did death rates fall faster than birth rates?','Because the government banned having children','Because modern medicine vaccines and improved sanitation reduced death rates quickly while social norms about family size changed much more slowly','Because people stopped dying','Because birth rates fell at the same time as death rates','B',3,0,0,3),(2572,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','Why is infant mortality rate measured per 1000 live births rather than as a percentage?','Because percentages are too simple','Because infant deaths are relatively rare events and using a larger base of 1000 makes the rate a more meaningful number for comparison across populations','Because there are always exactly 1000 births','Because percentages cannot be used in demography','B',3,0,0,3),(2573,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','A country reduces its maternal mortality rate from 200 to 50 per thousand births. What does this improvement likely reflect?','Fewer women are having children','Improvements in prenatal care skilled birth attendance emergency obstetric services and women''s nutrition and health literacy','More women are dying of other causes','The census data changed','B',4,0,0,4),(2574,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','How does comparing birth rates and death rates across different Indian states tell us about regional development disparities?','All Indian states have the same birth and death rates','States with lower birth rates lower death rates and lower infant mortality rates tend to be more developed showing how demographic indicators reflect underlying development differences','Demographic indicators are not related to development','Only national-level rates are meaningful','B',4,0,0,4),(2575,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','Why might lowering infant mortality actually lead to lower birth rates in the long run?','Because parents have more infants to care for','Because when parents are confident that children will survive to adulthood they tend to have fewer children as child survival security reduces the need for many births as insurance against child death','Because infant mortality and birth rates are unrelated','Because governments force families to have fewer children','B',4,0,0,4),(2576,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','The relationship between birth rate and death rate determines population growth. Why is this simple formula insufficient to understand population dynamics?','The formula is completely sufficient','The formula captures natural increase but ignores migration which also affects population size; additionally the formula does not explain why rates are what they are requiring social economic and health analysis','The formula is too complex','Population dynamics are only determined by birth rates','B',4,0,0,4),(2577,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','India has made significant progress in reducing infant mortality from very high rates to much lower rates. What combination of factors has driven this improvement and what does it suggest about development priorities?','Only one factor caused the improvement','Improvements in child immunisation skilled birth attendance nutrition supplementation oral rehydration therapy and maternal education have all contributed suggesting that multiple simultaneous interventions are needed for demographic improvement','Infant mortality reduced on its own','Only economic growth reduced infant mortality','B',5,0,0,5),(2578,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','High maternal mortality rates in developing countries reflect complex intersections of healthcare poverty and gender inequality. How do these factors interact?','Maternal mortality is only caused by poor healthcare','Poor women have less access to skilled healthcare; gender inequality means women''s health needs are underresourced; poverty prevents transport to hospitals; together these create a compound risk that is more than the sum of individual factors','Maternal mortality is only caused by gender inequality','Maternal mortality only occurs in rural areas','B',5,0,0,5),(2579,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','A demographer studying a population finds that the birth rate has declined but the total population continues to grow rapidly. What is the most likely explanation?','The data is incorrect','Death rates have fallen even faster than birth rates so even though fewer children are being born proportionally more people are surviving creating continued population growth despite declining birth rates','The population is growing through immigration only','Birth rates cannot decline while population grows','B',5,0,0,5),(2580,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Birth Rate and Death Rate','Why might reducing infant mortality and maternal mortality be more effective demographic policies than direct attempts to reduce birth rates?','Because infant and maternal mortality reduction has nothing to do with birth rates','Because improving child survival and maternal health builds the social confidence needed for families to voluntarily choose smaller family sizes making demographic transition happen through human development rather than coercive population control','Because coercive population control is more effective','Because reducing death rates always increases birth rates','B',5,0,0,5),(2581,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','What does population density measure?','The total population of a country','The number of people per unit area (usually per square kilometre)','The health status of a population','The growth rate of a population','B',1,0,0,1),(2582,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','What is the female-male ratio in the context of population indicators?','The ratio of women workers to men workers','The number of females per 1000 males in a population','The ratio of female births to male births','The ratio of women voters to men voters','B',1,0,0,1),(2583,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','What is child sex ratio?','The overall female-male ratio in a country','The number of girls per 1000 boys in the age group 0-6 years','The ratio of children to adults','The death rate of children','B',1,0,0,1),(2584,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','What is life expectancy?','The maximum age a person can live to','The average number of years a person is expected to live based on current conditions','The age at which most people retire','The average working age of a population','B',1,0,0,1),(2585,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','What is dependency ratio?','The ratio of employed to unemployed','The ratio of the economically dependent population (children and elderly) to the working-age population','The ratio of poor to rich people','The ratio of rural to urban population','B',2,0,0,2),(2586,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','A low female-male ratio in India indicates what social problem?','Economic poverty','Gender discrimination leading to female foeticide and infanticide','High migration of women','Women living longer than men','B',2,0,0,2),(2587,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','What is age structure in the context of demography?','The height distribution of a population','The distribution of a population across different age groups','The structure of families in a society','The average age at marriage','B',2,0,0,2),(2588,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','A young age structure (with a large proportion of young people) has what implication for a country''s workforce?','It means the country will have less workers in the future','It means the country will have a large working-age population in the coming years creating a demographic dividend if jobs are available','It means the country has high infant mortality','It means the country has too many children','B',2,0,0,2),(2589,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','Why is a declining child sex ratio in India a cause for concern?','Because it means there are too many boys','Because it indicates selective elimination of girl children through sex-selective abortion or infanticide reflecting severe gender discrimination','Because having more boys than girls is natural','Because child sex ratio does not affect society','B',3,0,0,3),(2590,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','How does life expectancy serve as an indicator of overall development?','It only measures healthcare quality','Life expectancy reflects the combined impact of healthcare nutrition sanitation education and living standards making it a comprehensive indicator of human development','Life expectancy is only affected by genetics','Countries with low life expectancy are always poor','B',3,0,0,3),(2591,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','What is a demographic dividend and how can India benefit from it?','The money India receives from population growth','When a large young population enters the working age this creates potential for rapid economic growth (demographic dividend) if India can provide education skills and employment','A dividend paid to large families','India cannot benefit from any demographic dividend','B',3,0,0,3),(2592,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','A high dependency ratio has what economic implications?','A high dependency ratio means a stronger economy','A high dependency ratio means fewer workers must support more non-working people reducing savings investment and economic growth potential','A high dependency ratio is always good for the economy','Dependency ratio has no economic implications','B',3,0,0,3),(2593,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','India has a relatively young population compared to ageing countries like Japan. How does this create both an opportunity and a challenge?','Young population is always better without challenges','The opportunity is a potential demographic dividend from a large workforce; the challenge is providing education training and employment to this large young population otherwise it could create unemployment and social instability','Young population creates only opportunities','Young population creates only challenges','B',4,0,0,4),(2594,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','Why is it concerning that India''s female-male ratio is lower than 1000 (meaning fewer women than men)?','Because countries need more men than women','Because it suggests widespread gender discrimination that selectively eliminates female life from conception onwards reflecting deeply embedded patriarchal values that undermine gender equality and development','Because it is normal to have fewer women','Because it helps control population growth','B',4,0,0,4),(2595,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','How does population density vary across India and what factors explain this variation?','Population density is uniform across India','India has very high density in fertile river plains (Ganga plains UP Bihar) and low density in mountains deserts and forests reflecting the relationship between agricultural potential water availability and population concentration','All of India has the same population density','Population density is only high in cities','B',4,0,0,4),(2596,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','A state with a high life expectancy low infant mortality and balanced sex ratio can be said to have what?','An old population structure','A more developed and equitable human development profile reflecting better healthcare gender equity and overall living standards','An economically poor population','These indicators are unrelated to each other','B',4,0,0,4),(2597,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','India is transitioning from a young to a gradually ageing population as birth rates fall. What policy implications does this demographic transition have for the future?','India''s population will never age','India needs to plan for increased elderly care pension systems and healthcare for an ageing population while maximising the current demographic dividend before the working-age proportion begins to shrink','India should increase its birth rate immediately','Ageing populations always benefit economies','B',5,0,0,5),(2598,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','The child sex ratio in India has declined over decades despite economic growth. What does this tell us about the relationship between economic development and gender discrimination?','Economic development always eliminates gender discrimination','Economic development alone does not eliminate gender discrimination; in fact access to technology (sex-selective abortion) combined with son preference can make sex discrimination more effective requiring targeted social interventions beyond economic growth','Economic development has increased gender discrimination','The child sex ratio is unrelated to gender discrimination','B',5,0,0,5),(2599,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','How do the various population indicators (density sex ratio age structure life expectancy dependency ratio) work together to give a comprehensive picture of a country''s development?','Each indicator is completely independent','Together these indicators reveal the interconnected dimensions of development: density shows resource pressure; sex ratio reveals gender equity; age structure shows workforce potential; life expectancy reflects healthcare; dependency ratio shows economic burden creating a multi-dimensional development profile','Only GDP is needed to assess development','Population indicators are not related to development','B',5,0,0,5),(2600,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 1','MCQ',1,'5','Demographic Trends in India',26,'Population Indicators','Kerala has one of India''s highest female-male ratios (more women than men relative to the national average) while also having high literacy and low fertility. What does this suggest about the relationship between women''s status and demographic outcomes?','These factors are coincidental','States where women have higher status through better education and healthcare tend to have better sex ratios and lower fertility rates demonstrating that improving women''s status is one of the most effective demographic interventions','Kerala''s high female ratio is due to male emigration only','Female-male ratio is unrelated to women''s literacy or fertility','B',5,0,0,5);
