t of the Yamuna placing it inside the Ganga Plain','B',5,0,0,5),(2735,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Brahmaputra Plain','By what other names is the Brahmaputra Plain known?','Punjab Valley and Doab Valley','Assam Valley and Assam Plain','Bengal Basin and Delta Plain','Bhabar Zone and Tarai Zone','B',1,0,0,1),(2736,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Brahmaputra Plain','What is the approximate length and width of the Brahmaputra Plain?','Length 400 km, Width 150-200 km','Length 720 km, Width 60-70 km','Length 1000 km, Width 30-40 km','Length 500 km, Width 100-120 km','B',2,0,0,2),(2737,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Brahmaputra Plain','Which hills form the southern boundary of the Brahmaputra Plain?','Patkai-Naga Hills','Eastern Himalaya','Garo-Khasi-Jaintia and Mikir Hills','Shiwalik Hills','C',3,0,0,3),(2738,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Brahmaputra Plain','Which of the following rivers is NOT a tributary associated with the Brahmaputra Plain?','Teesta','Manas','Lohit','Beas','D',4,0,0,4),(2739,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Brahmaputra Plain','The Brahmaputra Plain extends from Assam state to Dubri near the Bangladesh border. What geographical feature is it particularly rich in?','Salt lakes','Ox-bow lakes from old Indus tributaries','Alluvial fans formed by mountain streams','Sandbars from ocean tides','C',4,0,0,4),(2740,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Brahmaputra Plain','A student incorrectly states that the Western Ghats form the eastern boundary of the Brahmaputra Plain. What is the correct eastern boundary?','Karakoram Range','Patkai-Naga Hills','Garo-Khasi-Jaintia Hills','Eastern Himalaya','B',5,0,0,5),(2741,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','In the Bhabar zone, rivers disappear underground due to which feature of the terrain?','Dense forest cover absorbing all water','Porous rocks and boulders through which water seeps','High evaporation in the hot season','Deep canals that divert river water','B',1,0,0,1),(2742,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','Which of the four north-south zones of the plain contains the older, higher alluvial deposits?','Khadar','Tarai','Bhangar','Bhabar','C',1,0,0,1),(2743,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','What is the approximate width of the Bhabar zone?','2-4 km','8-10 km','20-30 km','50-60 km','B',2,0,0,2),(2744,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','Which zone is described as marshy and swampy, with rivers re-emerging at the surface and supporting luxurious vegetation and wildlife?','Bhabar','Bhangar','Khadar','Tarai','D',2,0,0,2),(2745,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','In what order do you encounter the four north-south zones travelling from the Shiwaliks southward into the plain?','Tarai - Bhabar - Bhangar - Khadar','Bhabar - Tarai - Bhangar - Khadar','Bhangar - Khadar - Bhabar - Tarai','Khadar - Bhangar - Tarai - Bhabar','B',3,0,0,3),(2746,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','Khadar is described as younger alluvium deposited in lower-lying areas. Why is Khadar considered more fertile than Bhangar?','Khadar has higher salt content','Khadar is regularly renewed by fresh alluvial deposits during floods','Khadar is closer to the Himalayas','Khadar has coarser rocks that retain more water','B',3,0,0,3),(2747,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','A traveller crosses the Bhabar zone and enters the next zone southward. Which observation confirms they are now in the Tarai zone?','Rivers have vanished underground and the ground is rocky','Rivers reappear at the surface and the land is marshy with thick vegetation','The land is elevated with older, compacted alluvium','Annual flooding deposits fresh silt each year on low-lying land','B',4,0,0,4),(2748,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','Bhangar occupies higher ground than Khadar. Which explanation correctly accounts for why rivers flow through Khadar but not Bhangar areas during normal flow?','Bhangar is too saline for river water to flow through','Rivers naturally occupy lower ground (Khadar), having cut channels into the floodplain over time','Bhangar was built by wind deposition, not rivers, so rivers avoid it','Rivers avoid Bhangar because its old alluvium is too compact to erode','B',4,0,0,4),(2749,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','A student confuses Bhabar and Tarai and says ''rivers disappear in the Tarai.'' What is the correct distinction between these two zones?','Rivers disappear in both zones equally','Rivers disappear in the Bhabar due to porous boulders and re-emerge in the Tarai as springs and streams','Rivers disappear in the Tarai due to swampy soil and re-emerge in the Bhabar','Rivers disappear only in the Khadar due to sandy soil','B',5,0,0,5),(2750,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'North-South Zones (Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, Khadar)','Among Bhabar, Tarai, Bhangar, and Khadar, which zone is most suitable for large-scale agriculture and why?','Bhabar, because it is closest to mountain streams bringing fresh nutrients','Tarai, because dense vegetation indicates rich soil','Khadar, because it receives fresh fertile alluvial deposits regularly through periodic flooding','Bhangar, because elevated land avoids flood damage to crops','C',5,0,0,5),(2751,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','After which Greek letter is the delta landform named?','Alpha','Beta','Delta','Omega','C',1,0,0,1),(2752,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','What are the sinuous or winding curves formed in a river due to alluvial obstructions in its course called?','Levees','Meanders','Deltas','Alluvial fans','B',1,0,0,1),(2753,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','Natural ridges of higher ground formed along river banks due to repeated flood deposition are called:','Sandbars','Levees','Ox-bow lakes','Flood plains','B',2,0,0,2),(2754,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','How is an ox-bow lake formed?','When a river delta is cut off by the sea','When a meander loop is cut off from the main river channel','When an alluvial fan fills up with water','When a levee breaks and water floods a low area permanently','B',2,0,0,2),(2755,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','What is deposited on either side of a river during flooding to build up a flood plain?','Rocks and boulders','Salt and minerals from evaporation','Alluvium such as silt and fine sediment','Gravel from the river bed only','C',3,0,0,3),(2756,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','Which depositional landform is described as a linear feature formed by the deposition of sand, silt, or gravel in a river channel?','Meander','Levee','Sandbar','Alluvial fan','C',3,0,0,3),(2757,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','Alluvial fans form when a river enters a plain from mountains. What causes the fan shape?','The river increases velocity and erodes a wide arc','Wind spreads the river''s sediment in a fan shape','The river decreases velocity upon entering the plain, depositing material that spreads outward','Tectonic uplift pushes sediment into a fan shape','C',4,0,0,4),(2758,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','A delta is formed at the mouth of a river by distributaries. What shape does a typical delta resemble?','A crescent','A triangle','A circle','A straight line','B',4,0,0,4),(2759,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','Which two landforms are directly related as successive stages in the evolution of a river meander over time?','Alluvial fan and delta','Meander and ox-bow lake','Levee and sandbar','Riverine island and alluvial fan','B',4,0,0,4),(2760,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','Levees form as higher ground close to river banks. Why might levees paradoxically increase flood risk over long periods?','Levees lower the surrounding plain, making it flood-prone','Repeated deposition raises the river bed above the surrounding plain, so floodwater overtops levees more easily over time','Levees reduce river velocity, causing the river to dry up','Levees divert water into ox-bow lakes, overfilling them','B',5,0,0,5),(2761,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','A student argues that a delta and an alluvial fan are essentially the same landform. What is the key distinction between them?','Alluvial fans are always larger than deltas','Alluvial fans form where a river enters a plain inland (fan-shaped deposition), while deltas form at the river''s mouth where it meets a sea or lake (triangular, built by distributaries)','Deltas form in rivers, alluvial fans form only in deserts','There is no distinction; both terms describe the same feature','B',5,0,0,5),(2762,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Depositional Landforms','When a river meander''s neck is cut off, what landform is immediately created, and what does it become over centuries without active river flow?','It becomes a levee and grows higher with repeated floods','It becomes an ox-bow lake and may eventually dry up into a swamp or marshy depression','It becomes an alluvial fan and spreads outward','It becomes a sandbar and is removed by river erosion','B',5,0,0,5),(2763,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','What is the name of the hot, dry wind that blows in May-June across the northern plain?','Mistral','Sirocco','Loo','Chinook','C',1,0,0,1),(2764,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','Which months are the coldest in the Cold Season of the northern plain?','October and November','December and January','February and March','April and May','B',1,0,0,1),(2765,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','During which season does the ''October heat'' phenomenon occur in the northern plain?','Cold season','Hot season','SW Monsoon season','NE Monsoon / Retreating Monsoon season','D',1,0,0,1),(2766,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','The SW Monsoon has two branches. Which branch enters the Ganga plain through the Sundarbans?','Arabian Sea branch','Bay of Bengal branch','Laccadive Sea branch','Indian Ocean branch','B',2,0,0,2),(2767,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','In the hot season, what is the maximum temperature recorded in the western part of the plain in May?','35 degrees C','40 degrees C','48 degrees C','55 degrees C','C',2,0,0,2),(2768,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','What characterises the winds during the NE Monsoon / Retreating Monsoon season?','Moisture-laden and bring heavy rainfall','Hot and dusty from Rajasthan','Cold and moist from western Asia','Dry, moisture-less winds blowing from high pressure areas','D',2,0,0,2),(2769,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','The Bay of Bengal branch of the SW Monsoon bifurcates after entering through the Sundarbans. Where does one sub-branch go?','Directly northward into Nepal','Eastward toward the Brahmaputra valley','Southward along the eastern coast','Westward toward the Arabian Sea','B',3,0,0,3),(2770,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','Where do the two branches of the SW Monsoon finally meet over the northern plain?','Over Uttar Pradesh','Over Punjab','Over Rajasthan','Over West Bengal','B',3,0,0,3),(2771,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','Which of the following correctly lists the four climatic seasons of the northern plain in order?','Hot Season - SW Monsoon - Retreating Monsoon - Cold Season','Cold Season - SW Monsoon - Hot Season - Retreating Monsoon','Retreating Monsoon - Cold Season - Hot Season - SW Monsoon','SW Monsoon - Hot Season - Cold Season - Retreating Monsoon','A',3,0,0,3),(2772,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','Cold waves during the Cold Season originate from Western Asia. What is the approximate time span of the Cold Season in the northern plain?','October to December','Mid-November to March','January to April','December to February only','B',4,0,0,4),(2773,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','What atmospheric condition causes the SW Monsoon to be drawn into the Indian subcontinent during June-September?','High pressure over the Indian Ocean pushing winds northward','Low pressure developing over the Indian subcontinent attracting the SW Monsoon','Cold temperatures in the Himalayas pulling warm ocean air northward','The rotation of the Earth deflecting winds toward India','B',4,0,0,4),(2774,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','Dust storms occur in evenings during the hot season. Which region is the source of the Loo wind, and which two months does it typically blow?','Bay of Bengal; July and August','Rajasthan; May and June','Himalayan glaciers; December and January','Arabian Sea; October and November','B',4,0,0,4),(2775,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','A student says the Loo wind is present during the Cold Season. Why is this incorrect?','Loo is a sea breeze found only in coastal areas','Loo is a hot, dry wind that blows during May-June in the hot season, not during the cold season','Loo is a monsoon wind that blows only in July','Loo is a cold wave from Western Asia found in December-January','B',5,0,0,5),(2776,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Climate','The Bay of Bengal branch bifurcates after Sundarbans, with one sub-branch going west through the Ganga plains and eventually joining the Arabian Sea branch over Punjab. A student claims Rajasthan receives abundant monsoon rainfall because both branches meet there. What is wrong with this reasoning?','Nothing; Rajasthan receives heavy monsoon rainfall','The branches join over Punjab, not Rajasthan; moisture is largely depleted before reaching Rajasthan, making it arid','The branches never join; they remain separate throughout','Rajasthan is in the rain shadow of the Eastern Ghats','B',5,0,0,5),(2777,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','What is the most widespread type of natural vegetation in the northern plain?','Tropical Thorn Forests','Tropical Deciduous Forests','Swamp and Mangrove Forests','Coniferous Forests','B',1,0,0,1),(2778,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','The Sundarbans mangrove forest is famous for which animal?','Asiatic Lion','Snow Leopard','Royal Bengal Tiger','Indian Elephant','C',1,0,0,1),(2779,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','Tropical Thorn Forests are found in which regions of the northern plain?','Tarai and Bhabar zones of UP','SW Punjab, Haryana, Rajasthan, and parts of UP','Sundarbans delta of West Bengal','Brahmaputra valley of Assam','B',2,0,0,2),(2780,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','The tree ''Sundri'' gives its name to the Sundarbans mangrove forest. In which state is this forest located?','Odisha','Assam','West Bengal','Bihar','C',2,0,0,2),(2781,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','Dry Tropical Deciduous forests grow in areas receiving 70-100 cm of rainfall. Which trees are characteristic of this sub-type?','Sundri and mangrove species','Teak, sal, shisham, mahua, amla, sandalwood','Babool, ber, khair, neem','Wild date palm and palas only','B',3,0,0,3),(2782,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','Tropical Thorn Forests contain which of the following characteristic trees?','Teak, sal, and shisham','Sundri and mangrove','Babool, ber, wild date palm, khair, neem, khejri, palas','Pine and deodar','C',3,0,0,3),(2783,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','Moist Tropical Deciduous forests receive 100-200 cm of rainfall. Where in the northern plain are they mainly found?','Rajasthan and southwest Punjab','Shiwalik foothills, Tarai, Bhabar, Odisha, and West Bengal','Brahmaputra delta only','Entire Ganga Plain uniformly','B',4,0,0,4),(2784,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','A geographer compares Tropical Thorn Forests and Dry Tropical Deciduous Forests. Which statement correctly distinguishes them?','Both have the same rainfall range; only the species differ','Thorn forests receive less than 70 cm of rain and have thorny drought-adapted species; dry deciduous receive 70-100 cm','Dry deciduous forests are found in wetter areas than thorn forests but have identical species','Thorn forests are found only in the Sundarbans region','B',4,0,0,4),(2785,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','A student claims that mangrove forests grow inland in the Tarai zone. Why is this incorrect?','Mangroves need cold temperatures found only in the Himalayas','Mangroves are coastal or tidal forests growing where seawater and freshwater mix (Sundarbans), not in the inland Tarai zone','Mangroves need sandy desert soil found only in Rajasthan','There is no error; mangroves do grow in the Tarai','B',5,0,0,5),(2786,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Natural Vegetation','Since rainfall decreases from east to west across the northern plain, which sequence of vegetation types (east to west) would you expect to encounter?','Thorn Forests - Dry Deciduous - Moist Deciduous - Mangrove','Mangrove or Moist Deciduous - Dry Deciduous - Thorn Forests','Thorn Forests - Mangrove - Moist Deciduous - Dry Deciduous','Dry Deciduous - Moist Deciduous - Thorn Forests - Mangrove','B',5,0,0,5),(2787,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','Which soil type is the most widespread in the northern plain?','Red soil','Black soil','Alluvial soil','Laterite soil','C',1,0,0,1),(2788,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','Saline soil is found in the Sundarbans delta. What causes it to be saline?','Heavy monsoon rainfall leaching minerals','Seawater intrusion into the delta','Wind blowing salt from the Thar Desert','Underground salt deposits','B',1,0,0,1),(2789,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','Which of the following correctly describes arid soil found in the western areas and Rajasthan?','Dark, rich in humus and highly fertile','Sandy and saline, lacking humus','Waterlogged and rich in organic matter','Red coloured with high iron content','B',2,0,0,2),(2790,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','Peat soil is found in coastal West Bengal. What characteristic distinguishes peat soil from other soils in the region?','It is sandy and dry','It is rich in organic matter formed in waterlogged conditions','It is high in iron oxides giving a red colour','It is deposited by rivers and contains coarse gravel','B',2,0,0,2),(2791,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','Where in the northern plain is red soil found?','Along the Brahmaputra valley','In the Thar Desert','In the southern part of the Middle Ganga Plain','In the Bhabar zone','C',3,0,0,3),(2792,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','Alluvial soils are subdivided into Khadar and Bhangar types. Which statement correctly compares their fertility?','Bhangar is more fertile because it is older and has had more time to develop nutrients','Khadar is more fertile because it is newer and regularly receives fresh alluvial deposits','Both are equally fertile as they are both alluvial','Bhangar is more fertile because it is higher and better drained','B',4,0,0,4),(2793,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','A farmer in coastal West Bengal finds his soil is waterlogged and rich in decomposed organic matter. Which soil type is this, and what is a typical farming challenge?','Arid soil; lack of water','Peat soil; poor drainage and high acidity making crop cultivation difficult','Saline soil; salt toxicity to crops','Red soil; low nutrient content','B',5,0,0,5),(2794,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Soils','The Sundarbans delta has saline soil while the upstream Ganga plain has alluvial Khadar soil. Both are in river delta areas. What additional factor makes Sundarbans soil saline but not the upstream Khadar soil?','The Ganga river itself is salty in its lower reaches','Sea tidal water intrudes into the Sundarbans delta, mixing salt with alluvial deposits, which does not happen in the upstream Khadar areas','Wind carries salt from the Arabian Sea to the Sundarbans','The mangrove trees themselves release salt into the soil','B',5,0,0,5),(2795,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Human Life and Agriculture','The northern plain is called the ''granary of India'' because it produces large quantities of which crops?','Cotton, jute, and tea','Wheat, rice, jute, and sugarcane','Rubber, coffee, and spices','Maize, groundnut, and sunflower','B',1,0,0,1),(2796,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Human Life and Agriculture','Which crop season runs from October to March and includes wheat, gram, mustard, and barley?','Kharif','Zaid','Rabi','Monsoon','C',2,0,0,2),(2797,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Human Life and Agriculture','Approximately what fraction of India''s population lives in the northern plain?','Less than one-quarter','More than half','Exactly one-third','About one-tenth','B',3,0,0,3),(2798,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Human Life and Agriculture','Which of the following is correctly classified as a Zaid season crop (April-June)?','Wheat','Rice','Vegetables and fruits','Barley','C',4,0,0,4),(2799,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Human Life and Agriculture','The northern plain has well-developed roads and railways, but one sub-region is an exception. Which area lacks good transport connectivity?','The Tarai zone','The Thar Desert','The Brahmaputra flood plain','The Sundarbans delta','B',5,0,0,5),(2800,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'2','In the Expansive Plain',28,'Human Life and Agriculture','The northern plain supports more than half of India''s population with rich alluvial soil and three crop seasons. Yet the Thar Desert sub-region remains sparsely populated. Which combination of factors best explains this sparse population?','Rich soil but lack of roads prevents settlement','Arid soil lacking humus, scarce water, extreme heat, and a non-perennial river making sustained agriculture very difficult','Dense mangrove forest blocking settlement','Government policy restricting settlement in the Thar Desert','B',5,0,0,5);
INSERT INTO "Kerala_9_English_Book1_MCQ" ("Id","Syllabus","Grade","Language","Subject","Type","Book#","Chapter#","Chapter","ChapterId","Section","Question","OptionA","OptionB","OptionC","OptionD","Correct","Difficulty","Correct#","Incorrect#","DifficultyNew") VALUES (2801,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Overview and Plateau Types','What is the approximate area of the Peninsular Plateau of India?','10 lakh sq.km','16 lakh sq.km','20 lakh sq.km','25 lakh sq.km','B',1,0,0,1),(2802,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Overview and Plateau Types','Which of the following best describes the shape of the Peninsular Plateau?','Circular','Rectangular','Almost triangular','Oval','C',2,0,0,2),(2803,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Overview and Plateau Types','A plateau enclosed between mountain ranges on all sides is called a:','Continental plateau','Piedmont plateau','Intermontane plateau','Residual plateau','C',3,0,0,3),(2804,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Overview and Plateau Types','The Peninsular Plateau is geologically significant because it is:','Formed entirely by river deposits','One of the oldest landforms on Earth','A recently uplifted sea bed','Formed by glacial action','B',4,0,0,4),(2805,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Overview and Plateau Types','The Peninsular Plateau lies south of the North Indian Plain with an average altitude of 600-900 m. A student claims it is a piedmont plateau because it lies near the Himalayas. Why is this claim incorrect?','It is too large to be a piedmont plateau','It is not at the foot of the Himalayas; it is separated by the plains and belongs to a different ancient geological block','Piedmont plateaus can only form near coastal mountains','The altitude is too high for any piedmont plateau','B',5,0,0,5),(2806,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','The word ''Deccan'' is derived from the Sanskrit word ''Dakshin'', which means:','East','South','West','Highland','B',1,0,0,1),(2807,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','The Deccan Trap is found in which part of the Deccan Plateau?','South-eastern part','North-western part','Central part','Eastern part','B',1,0,0,1),(2808,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','Which type of rock makes up the Deccan Trap?','Sandstone','Limestone','Basalt','Quartzite','C',2,0,0,2),(2809,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','What property of regur soil makes it especially suitable for cotton cultivation?','It drains water very quickly','It has high water retention capacity','It is highly acidic','It is formed from transported alluvium','B',2,0,0,2),(2810,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','The northern boundary of the Deccan Plateau is formed by which hills/ranges?','Aravali and Vindhya','Satpura, Maikala, and Mahadeo Hills','Nilgiris and Anamalai','Javadi and Nallamalai','B',3,0,0,3),(2811,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','The crystalline rocks of the Deccan Plateau include basalt, granite, and gneiss. Which of these is a volcanic rock formed from solidified lava?','Gneiss','Granite','Basalt','Quartzite','C',3,0,0,3),(2812,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','Regur soil is formed from weathered basalt and contains lime, iron, magnesium, and aluminium. Which part of the Deccan Plateau would most likely have the thickest regur soil deposits?','Eastern slopes near the Eastern Ghats','North-western Deccan, where the Deccan Trap basalt is found','Coastal plains of Kerala','Southern tip near Kanyakumari','B',4,0,0,4),(2813,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Deccan Plateau','A student argues that since the Deccan Plateau has very old crystalline rocks like gneiss and granite, its soils should only be red soils, not black soils. However, the NW Deccan has black soil. What best explains this?','Black soil in the NW Deccan formed from weathered basalt of the Deccan Trap, not from gneiss or granite','Red soil and black soil are the same in the Deccan','Black soil forms wherever rainfall is below 50 cm','Gneiss weathers into black soil in all tropical climates','A',5,0,0,5),(2814,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','What is the height of Anamudi, the highest peak in Peninsular India?','2637 m','2695 m','3000 m','2500 m','B',1,0,0,1),(2815,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','The Western Ghats extend from Kanyakumari to which state in the north?','Maharashtra','Goa','Gujarat','Rajasthan','C',1,0,0,1),(2816,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','The Western Ghats are known as Sahyadris in which state?','Karnataka','Tamil Nadu','Kerala','Maharashtra','D',2,0,0,2),(2817,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','In which direction does the height of the Western Ghats generally increase?','From south to north','From west to east','From north to south','From east to west','C',3,0,0,3),(2818,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','Anamudi (2695 m) in Kerala and Dodabetta (2637 m) in Tamil Nadu are both in the southern stretch of the Western Ghats. What does this confirm about the Western Ghats'' height pattern?','The two highest peaks are in the north, confirming height increases northward','The two highest peaks are in the south, confirming height increases from north to south','Height is uniform throughout the Western Ghats','Height increases only from east to west','B',4,0,0,4),(2819,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','Most major peninsular rivers originate in the Western Ghats. The Western Ghats together with the Central Highlands and Aravali form a water divide. Which three drainage systems does this divide separate?','Only Bay of Bengal and Arabian Sea drainage','Bay of Bengal drainage, Arabian Sea drainage, and northward drainage into the Yamuna/Ganga system','Only east-flowing and west-flowing rivers of the Deccan','Rivers of the Himalayan system only','B',4,0,0,4),(2820,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','The Western Ghats are called Anamalai/Elamalai in Kerala, Sahyadris in Maharashtra, and Nilgiris in Karnataka/Tamil Nadu, all part of the same 1600 km chain. A geographer claims these are separate mountain ranges. Using chapter information, which response best refutes this?','They are part of the Eastern Ghats system, not separate ranges','They are the same continuous mountain chain known by different regional names along its 1600 km length','Only the Kerala section is part of the Western Ghats; others are separate','The Sahyadris are fold mountains unlike the rest of the Ghats','B',5,0,0,5),(2821,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Western Ghats','The Western Ghats act as a water divide and most peninsular rivers originate here. A student says the Eastern Ghats must also be an effective water divide since they are on the eastern side. Using chapter facts about the Eastern Ghats, why would they be far less effective as a water divide?','The Eastern Ghats are higher so they block more water','The Eastern Ghats are cut by east-flowing rivers and are lower and discontinuous; they cannot effectively divide drainage the way the continuous, higher Western Ghats can','The Eastern Ghats face the Arabian Sea so they cannot divide drainage','The Eastern Ghats are made of basalt which cannot hold water','B',5,0,0,5),(2822,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Eastern Ghats','The Eastern Ghats extend from the banks of which river in Odisha to the Nilgiri ranges in Tamil Nadu?','Godavari','Mahanadi','Krishna','Kaveri','B',1,0,0,1),(2823,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Eastern Ghats','Which of the following hill ranges forms part of the Eastern Ghats?','Sahyadris','Anamalai Hills','Nallamalai Hills','Palani Hills','C',2,0,0,2),(2824,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Eastern Ghats','The Eastern Ghats are described as discontinuous. What is the main reason for their broken nature?','They were formed by volcanic eruptions at different times','East-flowing rivers have cut through them over time','Glacial action eroded gaps in the ranges','They were never a continuous range','B',3,0,0,3),(2825,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Eastern Ghats','The Eastern Ghats are lower and more discontinuous than the Western Ghats. Which combination of factors best explains why they receive less orographic rainfall?','They are lower in height and face away from the moisture-bearing Arabian Sea winds','They are higher and block all rainfall','They are located entirely in a desert region','They are made of basalt which repels rainfall','A',4,0,0,4),(2826,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Eastern Ghats','A student claims the Eastern Ghats cannot be called a ''mountain range'' because they are lower and discontinuous. Which response best evaluates this claim?','The claim is correct; the Eastern Ghats are just isolated hills with no geological connection','The claim is partially wrong; the Eastern Ghats are a series of hill ranges that collectively form the eastern boundary of the plateau, even though they are cut by rivers','The Eastern Ghats are actually higher than the Western Ghats','The Eastern Ghats were formed recently by human activity','B',5,0,0,5),(2827,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Central Highlands','Which mountain range forms the western margin of the Malwa Plateau?','Vindhya','Satpura','Aravali','Mahadeo Hills','C',1,0,0,1),(2828,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Central Highlands','The Aravali mountains are described as residual mountains. What does this term mean?','Mountains formed recently by volcanic activity','Remnants of very old fold mountains worn down by long-term erosion','Mountains formed by deposition of river sediments','Mountains formed by the folding of sea beds','B',2,0,0,2),(2829,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Central Highlands','The Central Highlands are located to the north of which major range?','Eastern Ghats','Western Ghats','Satpura','Nilgiris','C',3,0,0,3),(2830,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Central Highlands','The Aravali range extends northward to the Delhi ridges and, together with the Western Ghats and Central Highlands, forms a water divide. What does this water divide separate?','Rivers flowing into the Indian Ocean from rivers flowing into the Arabian Sea only','Rivers draining into the Bay of Bengal, the Arabian Sea, and northward into the Yamuna/Ganga system','Rivers of the Deccan Plateau from rivers of the Himalayan system only','Only east-flowing rivers from west-flowing rivers within the Deccan','B',4,0,0,4),(2831,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Central Highlands','Mount Abu is the highest peak in the Malwa Plateau area and a hill station in the Aravali range. A student says it must be part of the Vindhya range because the Vindhya is more famous. What makes this claim incorrect?','Mount Abu is part of the Satpura range','Mount Abu is a peak in the Aravali range, not the Vindhya','Mount Abu is located in the Eastern Ghats','Mount Abu is the highest peak in the Vindhya','B',4,0,0,4),(2832,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Central Highlands','The Chambal River originates in the Malwa Plateau and joins the Ganga system flowing northward. The Chambal Ravines are gullies formed by continuous erosion. A student asks why the Chambal Ravines are more severe than erosion in other river valleys. Which factor from the chapter best explains the intense gully erosion along the Chambal?','The Chambal flows through hard basalt rock that resists all erosion','Continuous river erosion cuts into soft, easily eroded soils of the Malwa Plateau, creating deep gullies over time','The Chambal Ravines are formed by glacial action','The Chambal flows through the Deccan Trap which causes unique erosion','B',5,0,0,5),(2833,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Central Highlands','The Aravali is one of the world''s oldest fold mountain systems, now reduced to residual mountains. A student claims the Central Highlands are younger than the Deccan Plateau because they have more distinct hill ranges. Using information about the Aravali being an ancient fold mountain, evaluate this claim.','The claim is correct; more hill ranges indicate younger formation','The claim is incorrect; the Aravali being an ancient fold mountain system worn down to residual mountains indicates the Central Highlands include some of Earth''s very old landforms','The Central Highlands formed after the Himalayan uplift','The Deccan Plateau is younger than the Central Highlands','B',5,0,0,5),(2834,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Chota Nagpur Plateau','Which nickname is given to the Chota Nagpur Plateau because of its rich mineral deposits?','Mineral belt of India','Heartland of minerals','Gem of the East','Mineral treasury','B',1,0,0,1),(2835,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Chota Nagpur Plateau','The Chota Nagpur Plateau spans parts of which states?','Gujarat, Rajasthan, Madhya Pradesh','Jharkhand, West Bengal, Odisha','Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Kerala','Maharashtra, Goa, Karnataka','B',2,0,0,2),(2836,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Chota Nagpur Plateau','The Chota Nagpur Plateau lies to the south of which hills?','Vindhya Hills','Satpura Hills','Rajmahal Hills','Aravali Hills','C',3,0,0,3),(2837,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Chota Nagpur Plateau','The Chota Nagpur Plateau contains coal, iron ore, manganese, mica, bauxite, and copper. Which two of these minerals are most critical for the iron and steel industry?','Mica and bauxite','Coal and iron ore','Copper and manganese','Bauxite and copper','B',4,0,0,4),(2838,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Chota Nagpur Plateau','The Northeastern mineral zone (Chotanagpur-Odisha) is the largest mineral belt in India. The Central mineral zone covers Chattisgarh, MP, Telangana, AP, and Maharashtra. Which zone covers more states, and does this make it the largest mineral belt?','The Central zone covers more states and is therefore larger','The Central zone covers more states, but the Northeastern zone is still designated the largest mineral belt based on concentration and volume of deposits','Both zones are equally large','The Southern zone is the largest mineral belt','B',4,0,0,4),(2839,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Chota Nagpur Plateau','A student claims that since Rajasthan has minerals like copper, lead, and zinc, the Northwestern mineral zone must be larger than the Northeastern zone. According to the chapter, why is this claim incorrect?','Rajasthan has no minerals at all','The Northeastern zone (Chotanagpur-Odisha) is specifically described as the largest mineral belt in India','The Northwestern zone includes more states than the Northeastern zone','Copper, lead, and zinc are more valuable than coal and iron ore','B',5,0,0,5),(2840,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Nilgiris','Which hill station in the Nilgiris is known as the ''Queen of Hills''?','Kotagiri','Coonor','Ooty (Udhagamandalam)','Munnar','C',1,0,0,1),(2841,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Nilgiris','The Nilgiris form the junction of which three states?','Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu','Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Kerala','Kerala, Tamil Nadu, Goa','Karnataka, Maharashtra, Kerala','B',2,0,0,2),(2842,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Nilgiris','Shola forests found in the Nilgiris, Palani, and Anamalai Hills are classified as:','Tropical dry deciduous forests','Sub-tropical montane vegetation found at higher elevations','Mangrove forests','Tropical thorn forests','B',3,0,0,3),(2843,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Nilgiris','The Nilgiris was declared India''s first Biosphere Reserve and is known for tea plantations. Which combination of factors makes the Nilgiris suitable for both biodiversity conservation and tea cultivation?','High altitude with cool, moist climate supports unique ecosystems and tea plants','Low altitude with hot, dry climate is ideal for tea and wildlife','Sandy soils and minimal rainfall support tea and rare animals','Proximity to the coast provides humidity only for tea','A',4,0,0,4),(2844,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Nilgiris','The Nilgiris form the meeting point of the Western and Eastern Ghats. A student says that since the Nilgiris are in Tamil Nadu, they belong entirely to the Eastern Ghats. Using the fact that the Western Ghats run from Kanyakumari to Gujarat along the western edge of the plateau, why is this claim incorrect?','The Nilgiris are at the southern junction where Western and Eastern Ghats meet; they are part of the Western Ghats system, not exclusively the Eastern Ghats','The Nilgiris are entirely in Karnataka, not Tamil Nadu','The Eastern Ghats end in Andhra Pradesh and never reach Tamil Nadu','The Nilgiris are an independent range unrelated to either Ghats','A',5,0,0,5),(2845,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','What type of climate does the Peninsular Plateau primarily experience?','Tropical desert climate','Tropical monsoon climate','Mediterranean climate','Temperate oceanic climate','B',1,0,0,1),(2846,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','The temperature in the Deccan Plateau can touch approximately how high in March?','25 degrees C','30 degrees C','38 degrees C','45 degrees C','C',1,0,0,1),(2847,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','The windward side of the Western Ghats receives 250-400 cm of rainfall. What is the approximate rainfall received by the rain shadow regions on the eastern slopes?','150-200 cm','100-150 cm','50-100 cm','Less than 50 cm','D',2,0,0,2),(2848,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','The plateau interior experiences a high diurnal temperature range. What does ''diurnal temperature range'' mean?','Difference in temperature between summer and winter','Difference between daytime and nighttime temperatures in a single day','Average temperature recorded over a year','Maximum temperature recorded in the hottest month','B',3,0,0,3),(2849,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','The NE monsoon is dry for the Peninsular Plateau but brings heavy rainfall to Tamil Nadu and Andhra Pradesh''s east coast. What is the primary cause of this difference?','The NE monsoon picks up moisture from the Bay of Bengal before reaching the east coast','The NE monsoon blows from the plateau and loses all moisture before reaching the coast','The Western Ghats block the NE monsoon from reaching Tamil Nadu','Tamil Nadu receives rainfall from the Arabian Sea during winter','A',3,0,0,3),(2850,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','Through which river basins does the South-West monsoon primarily enter the Peninsular Plateau?','Godavari and Krishna basins','Narmada and Tapti basins','Mahanadi and Kaveri basins','Chambal and Betwa basins','B',4,0,0,4),(2851,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','A student claims that because the Deccan Plateau receives the SW monsoon, every part of it gets heavy rainfall of over 100 cm. Using the concept of windward and leeward sides, why is this incorrect?','The SW monsoon does not reach the Deccan Plateau at all','The Western Ghats intercept most SW monsoon rainfall on the windward side; the leeward Deccan interior falls in a rain shadow and gets less than 50 cm','The Deccan Plateau is too flat for any rainfall to occur','The SW monsoon only affects the Northern Plains, not the Peninsular Plateau','B',5,0,0,5),(2852,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Climate','The Western Ghats receive 250-400 cm on the windward side, the Deccan interior gets less than 50 cm, and the eastern coast (Tamil Nadu/AP) gets heavy NE monsoon rain. A student says the entire peninsular region is wet throughout the year. Using all three rainfall patterns, explain why this is incorrect.','The student is correct; all parts of the peninsula receive adequate rainfall year-round','The Deccan interior is dry with less than 50 cm during SW monsoon (rain shadow) and remains dry during NE monsoon; only the windward Western Ghats and east coast get abundant rainfall at different times','The Deccan Plateau receives the NE monsoon directly and is wet throughout the year','Tamil Nadu is dry throughout the year while the Western Ghats are always wet','B',5,0,0,5),(2853,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','Which river is called the ''Dakshin Ganga'' (Ganga of the South)?','Mahanadi','Krishna','Godavari','Kaveri','C',1,0,0,1),(2854,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','Where does the Godavari River originate?','Mahabaleshwar, Maharashtra','Brahmagiri Hills, Karnataka','Nashik, Maharashtra','Sihawa, Chattisgarh','C',1,0,0,1),(2855,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The Hirakud Dam is built on which river?','Godavari','Mahanadi','Krishna','Kaveri','B',1,0,0,1),(2856,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The Kaveri River is perennial, meaning it flows throughout the year. Why does the Kaveri remain perennial when most peninsular rivers are seasonal?','It originates in the Himalayas and gets glacial meltwater','It receives rainfall from both the SW monsoon and the NE monsoon','It is fed by underground springs throughout the year','It flows through a zone receiving over 400 cm rainfall annually','B',2,0,0,2),(2857,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','Which of the following is a tributary of the Krishna River?','Pranhita','Kabani','Tungabhadra','Tel','C',2,0,0,2),(2858,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','According to the Kaveri Water Disputes Tribunal verdict of 2007, which state received the highest allocation of Kaveri waters?','Karnataka (270 TMC)','Kerala (30 TMC)','Tamil Nadu (419 TMC)','Puducherry (7 TMC)','C',2,0,0,2),(2859,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The Godavari is the largest peninsular river with a length of 1465 km. Into which sea does it ultimately drain?','Arabian Sea','Bay of Bengal','Indian Ocean directly','Gulf of Mannar','B',3,0,0,3),(2860,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The Mahanadi originates near Sihawa/Raipur in Chattisgarh, and the Hirakud Dam is built on it in Odisha. What does the fact that the dam is in Odisha while the origin is in Chattisgarh tell us about the Mahanadi?','The Mahanadi flows from Odisha to Chattisgarh','The Mahanadi flows across state boundaries from Chattisgarh through Odisha before draining into the Bay of Bengal','The Hirakud Dam is actually in Chattisgarh, not Odisha','The Mahanadi originates in Odisha and flows to Chattisgarh','B',3,0,0,3),(2861,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The multipurpose projects on peninsular rivers include Hirakud (Mahanadi), Thungabhadra (Karnataka), Nizam Sagar, and Krishna Raja Sagar (Kaveri). Which of these dams is on a tributary of the Godavari?','Hirakud Dam','Krishna Raja Sagar Dam','Nizam Sagar Dam','Thungabhadra Dam','C',4,0,0,4),(2862,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The Godavari (origin: Nashik) has tributaries Pranhita, Indravati, and Sabari. The Krishna (origin: Mahabaleshwar) has tributaries Tungabhadra, Bhima, and Konya. Both originate in Maharashtra. What is a key difference between their tributary systems in terms of the regions they drain?','Godavari tributaries are entirely within Maharashtra; Krishna tributaries span more states','Godavari tributaries like Indravati drain central India (MP/Chattisgarh), while Krishna tributaries like Tungabhadra drain Karnataka','Both rivers have identical tributary systems','Krishna tributaries originate in Tamil Nadu while Godavari tributaries originate in Gujarat','B',4,0,0,4),(2863,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The Kaveri originates in Karnataka yet Tamil Nadu was allocated 419 TMC while Karnataka received 270 TMC in the 2007 tribunal verdict. A politician argues Karnataka should get more because the river originates there. Why is water allocation not simply based on origin state?','Water allocation is based on where the river originates, so Karnataka is correct','River water is shared among all basin states based on dependence, irrigated area, population, and historical use, not just the origin state','Tamil Nadu always gets more water from all peninsular rivers by default','The Bay of Bengal, where the river drains, determines the allocation','B',5,0,0,5),(2864,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - East Flowing','The Godavari is called ''Dakshin Ganga'' and is the largest peninsular river with a catchment of 3.13 lakh sq.km. A student assumes that since the Kaveri is perennial and the Godavari is mainly seasonal, the Kaveri must have a larger catchment. Identify the error in this reasoning.','The Kaveri is not perennial; it flows only in summer','Perennial flow and large catchment area are unrelated; the Godavari has a catchment of 3.13 lakh sq.km while the Kaveri''s is much smaller','The Godavari is also perennial, so there is no error','The Kaveri has a larger catchment area than the Godavari','B',5,0,0,5),(2865,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','Where does the Narmada River originate?','Multai, Madhya Pradesh','Amarkantak, Madhya Pradesh','Nashik, Maharashtra','Mahabaleshwar, Maharashtra','B',1,0,0,1),(2866,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','The Sardar Sarovar Dam is built on which river?','Tapti','Chambal','Narmada','Godavari','C',2,0,0,2),(2867,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','Which of the following is a tributary of the Tapti River?','Hiran','Banjar','Purna','Kabani','C',2,0,0,2),(2868,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','The Narmada passes through marble valleys and has the Dudhsagar Waterfalls near Jabalpur. In which state is this location?','Gujarat','Maharashtra','Madhya Pradesh','Rajasthan','C',3,0,0,3),(2869,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','The Chambal River originates in the Malwa Plateau and joins the Yamuna/Ganga system. What is the key directional difference between the Chambal and the Narmada?','Chambal flows west into the Arabian Sea; Narmada flows east','Chambal flows northward to join the Ganga system; Narmada flows westward into the Arabian Sea','Chambal flows south into the Deccan; Narmada flows north','Both rivers flow into the Bay of Bengal','B',3,0,0,3),(2870,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','Narmada flows through MP, Maharashtra, and Gujarat; Tapti also flows through MP, Maharashtra, and Gujarat. Both drain into the Arabian Sea. What distinguishes their origins?','Narmada originates at Amarkantak (MP); Tapti originates at Multai (MP) - both in Madhya Pradesh but at different locations','Narmada originates in Maharashtra; Tapti originates in Gujarat','Narmada originates in Gujarat; Tapti originates in Rajasthan','Both originate at the same place - Amarkantak','A',4,0,0,4),(2871,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','The Narmada Bachao Andolan (1994-1999) protested the Sardar Sarovar Dam on the Narmada. A student says the dam must be in Madhya Pradesh because the Narmada originates there. Why is this incorrect?','The Sardar Sarovar Dam is in Gujarat, where the Narmada reaches near the Arabian Sea coast, not at its origin in MP','The Sardar Sarovar Dam is in Maharashtra, not Gujarat','The Narmada does not originate in Madhya Pradesh','The Sardar Sarovar Dam is on the Tapti, not the Narmada','A',5,0,0,5),(2872,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Rivers - West Flowing','Most peninsular rivers flow eastward because the Western Ghats act as a water divide. Yet Narmada and Tapti flow west. A student claims this must mean the Narmada and Tapti originate east of the Eastern Ghats. Using chapter content, explain why this reasoning is wrong.','The Narmada and Tapti originate in the Eastern Ghats','The Narmada (Amarkantak, MP) and Tapti (Multai, MP) originate in the Central Highlands, which slope westward; their westward flow is determined by the local gradient, not their position relative to the Eastern Ghats','The Narmada flows east, not west','The Eastern Ghats have no influence on river direction','B',5,0,0,5),(2873,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','Which is the most widespread type of forest found in the Peninsular Plateau?','Tropical Thorn Forest','Tropical Deciduous Forest','Southern Montane Forest','Mangrove Forest','B',1,0,0,1),(2874,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','Which trees are commonly found in Moist Tropical Deciduous Forests (100-200 cm rainfall)?','Acacia, euphorbia, and date palms','Teak, sal, shisham, and sandalwood','Rosewood, axle wood, and bamboos','Mangrove and coconut trees','B',2,0,0,2),(2875,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','Southern Montane Forests found above 1500 m elevation are classified as which forest type?','Tropical','Temperate','Boreal','Sub-tropical thorn','B',2,0,0,2),(2876,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','An area in eastern Maharashtra lies east of the Western Ghats and receives less than 75 cm of annual rainfall. What type of vegetation would you most likely find there?','Moist Tropical Deciduous Forest','Southern Montane Forest','Tropical Thorn Forest','Shola Forest','C',3,0,0,3),(2877,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','Shola forests are found in the Nilgiris, Palani, and Anamalai Hills as Southern Montane Forests. Based on this classification, at what minimum elevation would you expect to find them?','500 m','1000 m','1500 m','2000 m','C',3,0,0,3),(2878,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','Moist Tropical Deciduous Forests (100-200 cm) contain teak and sal; Dry Tropical Deciduous Forests (70-100 cm) contain rosewood and bamboo; Tropical Thorn Forests (under 75 cm) contain acacia and euphorbia. A region receives 80 cm of rainfall. Which vegetation type is most likely?','Only Tropical Thorn Forest because 80 cm is less than 100 cm','Dry Tropical Deciduous Forest is most likely (70-100 cm range), though it borders the Thorn Forest threshold','Moist Tropical Deciduous Forest is most likely','Southern Montane Forest is most likely','B',4,0,0,4),(2879,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','Tropical Thorn vegetation (acacia, euphorbia, date palms) is found in semi-arid Maharashtra/Karnataka east of the Western Ghats. A rainfall map shows a corridor there receiving less than 50 cm. Which two factors from the chapter together explain why this corridor is so dry?','This corridor is dry because of the Himalayan rain shadow and cold winds from the north','This corridor is in the rain shadow of the Western Ghats where descending dry air replaces the moisture lost on the windward side, and the NE monsoon is dry for the plateau interior','This corridor is at high altitude, which reduces rainfall','This corridor is near the coast, which reduces rainfall','B',4,0,0,4),(2880,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Vegetation','The Chota Nagpur Plateau receives 100-200 cm rainfall and has Moist Tropical Deciduous Forests. The rain shadow eastern Deccan gets less than 50 cm. A student claims that the entire Peninsular Plateau must support Moist Tropical Deciduous Forests since they are the most widespread type. Why is this incorrect?','The Deccan Plateau does not have any forests','Most widespread does not mean universal; the rain-shadow Deccan interior with under 75 cm rainfall supports Tropical Thorn vegetation instead of Moist Tropical Deciduous Forests','The Deccan Plateau only supports mangrove forests','All parts of the Deccan Plateau receive 100-200 cm of rainfall','B',5,0,0,5),(2881,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Black soil is also called Regur soil. It is best suited for growing which crop?','Rice','Cotton','Wheat','Jute','B',1,0,0,1),(2882,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Red soil gets its colour from the presence of which element?','Calcium','Magnesium','Iron','Aluminium','C',1,0,0,1),(2883,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Laterite soil is formed by which process?','Deposition of river sediments','Leaching of silica and lime due to alternating heavy rain and drought','Weathering of basalt under tropical conditions','Glacial deposition of minerals','B',2,0,0,2),(2884,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Soils that are formed in the place where the parent rock is found are called:','Transported soils','Alluvial soils','In-situ soils','Aeolian soils','C',2,0,0,2),(2885,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','A farmer in Karnataka finds a red-coloured soil formed from very old crystalline metamorphic rocks. Which soil type is this?','Black soil','Laterite soil','Red soil','Mountain soil','C',3,0,0,3),(2886,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Laterite soil is less fertile in its natural state but can support tea, coffee, rubber, and arecanut with fertilizers. What does this suggest about its natural mineral content?','It is naturally rich in nitrogen and phosphorus','Leaching has removed key nutrients like silica and lime, leaving it nutrient-poor without fertilizers','It has excess iron making it too fertile for delicate crops','It retains too much water reducing fertility','B',3,0,0,3),(2887,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Black soil is an in-situ soil formed from basalt. Alluvial soil is transported by rivers. Mountain soils are found in the Western and Eastern Ghats. If a region has no river transport and sits above 1500 m on the Ghats, which soil type is most likely?','Alluvial soil','Black soil','Mountain soil','Laterite soil','C',4,0,0,4),(2888,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Black soil is mainly found in Maharashtra and MP. Red soil forms over old crystalline metamorphic rocks. Laterite is found in the Western Ghats, Eastern Ghats, Rajmahal, Vindhya, Satpura, and Malwa. Which soil would most likely dominate the north-western Deccan Trap region?','Red soil, because crystalline rocks are common there','Laterite soil, because of high rainfall','Black soil, because basalt weathers into regur in that region','Mountain soil, because the altitude is high','C',4,0,0,4),(2889,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','A geologist finds a Western Ghats soil that supports tea and coffee and is less fertile without fertilizers. She also finds an NW Deccan soil that has high water retention and is rich in lime, iron, and magnesium. Without using their names, identify which is laterite and which is black soil and justify your answer.','The first is black soil (high water retention); the second is laterite (supports tea)','The first is laterite (Western Ghats location, less fertile, supports tea/coffee through fertilization); the second is black soil (NW Deccan, high water retention, rich in lime/iron/magnesium)','Both are red soils formed from crystalline rocks','The first is mountain soil; the second is alluvial soil','B',5,0,0,5),(2890,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Soils','Red soil appears in shades of brown, grey, and yellow in addition to red. Black soil is rich in lime, iron, magnesium, and aluminium. A student concludes that since both contain iron, they must be formed from the same parent rock. Why is this incorrect?','Red soil and black soil both form from basalt, so the student is correct','Red soil forms from very old crystalline metamorphic rocks (iron gives the colour); black soil forms from weathered basalt - different parent rocks, even though both contain iron','Neither soil contains iron','Black soil contains no iron; only red soil does','B',5,0,0,5),(2891,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','Who introduced coffee to India and from where did he bring the seeds?','A British merchant from Sri Lanka','Bababudan, a Muslim priest, who brought 7 seeds from Arabia','A Portuguese trader who brought seeds from Brazil','A Dutch merchant from Java','B',1,0,0,1),(2892,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','Which state is the leading producer of cotton in India?','Maharashtra','Karnataka','Gujarat','Tamil Nadu','C',1,0,0,1),(2893,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','Karnataka accounts for what percentage of India''s coffee production?','22%','44%','59%','71%','D',2,0,0,2),(2894,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','The Northwestern mineral zone (Aravali/Rajasthan and Gujarat) is known for which set of minerals?','Coal, iron ore, manganese','Copper, lead, zinc, uranium, mica','Iron ore, bauxite, lignite','Iron ore and clay','B',2,0,0,2),(2895,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','Cotton is described as a Kharif crop in the Peninsular Plateau. What does being a ''Kharif crop'' typically indicate about its growing season?','It is grown in winter months (October-February)','It is sown at the start of the monsoon season (typically June-July)','It is grown year-round without a fixed season','It is a spring crop sown in March','B',3,0,0,3),(2896,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','Cotton grows best in black soil with 21-30 degrees C temperature and 50-100 cm rainfall. Why does cotton thrive specifically in the NW Deccan Plateau region?','The NW Deccan has alluvial soil which is best for cotton','The NW Deccan has black (regur) soil from basalt, suitable temperature, and adequate rainfall for cotton','Cotton grows best in laterite soil which dominates the NW Deccan','The NW Deccan receives over 200 cm rainfall ideal for cotton','B',3,0,0,3),(2897,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','The Southern mineral zone covers Karnataka Plateau and Tamil Nadu with iron ore, bauxite, and lignite. The Southwestern zone covers western Karnataka and Goa with iron ore and clay. What best distinguishes these two zones?','The Southern zone has lignite and bauxite in addition to iron ore; the Southwestern zone has only iron ore and clay','The Southwestern zone has coal while the Southern zone does not','The Southern zone is in Tamil Nadu only; the Southwestern zone is in Karnataka only','There is no difference; both zones are identical','A',4,0,0,4),(2898,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','Karnataka has 59% of coffee plantations and 71% of production. Tea in the same region has 44% of plantations but only 25% of production. What does the higher production-to-plantation ratio for coffee compared to tea suggest?','Coffee plantations in Karnataka are more productive per unit area than tea plantations','Tea is a more important crop than coffee in the Western Ghats','Kerala produces more coffee than Karnataka','Tea plantations are larger but produce more per hectare','A',4,0,0,4),(2899,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','Sugarcane requires black lava soil, tropical climate, a long crushing season, and high sucrose content. Cotton needs 21-30 degrees C, 50-100 cm rainfall, and 7 frost-free months. Both grow in Gujarat. If a region in Gujarat becomes unusually dry, which crop would be more severely affected?','Cotton, because it needs more than 200 cm of rainfall','Sugarcane, because it requires a long growing/crushing season with sufficient moisture, making it more sensitive to dryness than cotton which can tolerate 50-100 cm','Neither crop is affected as black soil retains all moisture needed','Both crops are equally affected by dryness','B',5,0,0,5),(2900,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'3','Plateau where the Earth''s History Slumbers',29,'Agriculture and Minerals','The Central mineral zone has manganese, bauxite, limestone, marble, coal, mica, iron ore, and graphite across Chattisgarh, MP, Telangana, AP, and Maharashtra. The Northeastern zone (largest mineral belt) has coal, iron ore, manganese, mica, bauxite, and copper across Jharkhand, WB, and Odisha. A policy maker says the Central zone is better for iron and steel because it covers more states. Using the chapter content, evaluate this claim.','The claim is correct; more states means more resources','The claim is misleading; the Northeastern zone is designated the largest mineral belt with major mining and mineral-based industries already established on its vast coal and iron ore reserves','The Central zone has more coal than the Northeastern zone','The Northeastern zone has no iron ore making the Central zone better for iron and steel','B',5,0,0,5),(2901,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','Which factor of production is rewarded with rent?','Labour','Capital','Land','Entrepreneurship','C',1,0,0,1),(2902,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','What reward does the factor of production called entrepreneurship receive?','Rent','Profit','Interest','Wages','B',1,0,0,1),(2903,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','Which of the following best describes capital as a factor of production?','Natural resources used in production','Man-made resources that aid production','Physical and intellectual efforts for economic reward','The ability to combine other factors','B',2,0,0,2),(2904,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','Labour as a factor of production encompasses which types of effort?','Only physical efforts','Only intellectual efforts','Both intellectual and physical efforts for economic reward','Only efforts without any reward','C',2,0,0,2),(2905,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','A farmer allows others to use his land and receives income for it. This income is called:','Wages','Profit','Rent','Interest','C',3,0,0,3),(2906,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','A factory owner borrows money to buy machinery. The reward paid for the use of this borrowed money is:','Rent','Interest','Wages','Profit','B',3,0,0,3),(2907,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','Which of the following correctly pairs each factor of production with its reward?','Land-Wages, Labour-Rent, Capital-Profit, Entrepreneurship-Interest','Land-Rent, Labour-Wages, Capital-Interest, Entrepreneurship-Profit','Land-Interest, Labour-Profit, Capital-Rent, Entrepreneurship-Wages','Land-Profit, Labour-Interest, Capital-Wages, Entrepreneurship-Rent','B',4,0,0,4),(2908,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','What distinguishes entrepreneurship from the other three factors of production?','It is rewarded with wages like labour','It is a natural resource like land','It organises and combines the other factors to produce goods and services','It is a man-made resource like capital','C',4,0,0,4),(2909,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','How many basic factors of production are there, and which one is rewarded with interest?','Three factors; Capital is rewarded with interest','Four factors; Capital is rewarded with interest','Four factors; Labour is rewarded with interest','Five factors; Entrepreneurship is rewarded with interest','B',4,0,0,4),(2910,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','A person invests savings in a business, manages all operations, and bears the risk of loss. Which factor does this person primarily represent, and why?','Labour, because he works in the business','Capital, because he invests money','Entrepreneurship, because he organises resources and bears the risk','Land, because he owns physical assets','C',5,0,0,5),(2911,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','An entrepreneur earns revenue of Rs. 1,00,000 and pays rent Rs. 20,000, wages Rs. 40,000, and interest Rs. 10,000. What is the reward for entrepreneurship?','Rs. 70,000','Rs. 60,000','Rs. 30,000','Rs. 50,000','C',5,0,0,5),(2912,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Factors of Production','Land is rewarded with rent and capital is rewarded with interest. Which statement best explains WHY their rewards differ?','Land is always more valuable than capital, so it earns a higher reward','Capital requires human effort to create and involves a cost of borrowing, while land is a gift of nature commanding a price for its use','The rewards are determined arbitrarily by governments with no economic logic','Land earns interest and capital earns rent in a modern economy','B',5,0,0,5),(2913,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','What is the barter system?','Exchange of goods using money','Direct exchange of goods for goods without money','Exchange of services for money','Trading of goods using gold coins','B',1,0,0,1),(2914,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','Which of the following is the most advanced form of money in the evolution of money?','Metal coins','Paper money','Electronic money','Gold','C',1,0,0,1),(2915,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','Which of the following was used as a barter product in early trade?','Paper currency','Animal skins and crops','Plastic cards','Electronic transfers','B',2,0,0,2),(2916,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','What does ''double coincidence of wants'' mean in the context of the barter system?','Both parties want to use money for exchange','Both parties happen to want exactly what the other has to offer','Both parties agree on the price of goods','Both parties exchange the same type of goods','B',2,0,0,2),(2917,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','A farmer has surplus wheat but needs shoes. The shoemaker needs rice, not wheat. This situation illustrates which problem with the barter system?','Difficulty in storing goods','Lack of double coincidence of wants','High cost of transportation','Absence of a common unit of account','B',3,0,0,3),(2918,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','Which of the following is a major drawback of the barter system?','It requires too many types of money','It is difficult to determine the exchange value of goods','It leads to inflation in prices','It requires a central bank to manage transactions','B',3,0,0,3),(2919,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','Arrange the following in the correct order of evolution of money: (i) Paper money (ii) Gold (iii) Electronic money (iv) Metal coins (v) Barter products','v, ii, iv, i, iii','v, iv, ii, i, iii','ii, v, iv, i, iii','v, ii, i, iv, iii','A',4,0,0,4),(2920,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','Why did humans move from barter products like animal skins and cattle to gold and metal coins?','Animal skins were too valuable to use for exchange','Barter products were difficult to store, divide, and use to determine value for all goods','The government banned the use of animal skins','Gold was easier to grow and produce than crops','B',4,0,0,4),(2921,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','Which statement best explains why money became the basic unit of all economic activities?','Money is made by the government and must be accepted by law','Money solved the problems of barter by providing a common measure of value, store of value, and medium of exchange','Money is more attractive than goods and is preferred by all people','Money is always in limited supply which makes it valuable','B',5,0,0,5),(2922,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Barter System and Evolution of Money','Electronic money and plastic/card money represent the latest stages in the evolution of money. What fundamental problem of the barter system do they most effectively resolve?','They eliminate the need for double coincidence of wants by enabling instant transfer of value across any distance','They make it easier to grow crops and produce agricultural goods','They reduce the role of banks in the economy permanently','They replaced all previous forms of money so older forms no longer exist','A',5,0,0,5),(2923,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','Who are called human resources?','People who own land and capital','People who can work and be used in the production process','Only people with formal education','People who manage businesses only','B',1,0,0,1),(2924,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','What is productivity?','The total number of workers in an economy','The ability of each factor of production to produce goods and services','The amount of money earned by workers','The total output of a country in a year','B',1,0,0,1),(2925,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','How do human resources convert natural resources into useful products?','By using only machines and technology','Using physical power and intelligence','Through the use of money alone','By importing goods from other countries','B',2,0,0,2),(2926,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','What makes human resources different from other factors of production like land and capital?','Human resources are always more expensive to employ','Human resources can think and innovate','Human resources are available in unlimited supply','Human resources do not require any reward','B',2,0,0,2),(2927,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','Why are not all people equally productive as human resources?','Because some people are naturally born more intelligent than others','Because people differ in education, health, skills, and training','Because the government gives some people more resources','Because productivity depends only on age','B',3,0,0,3),(2928,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','A country has vast iron ore deposits but lacks skilled workers to mine and process them. This best illustrates which concept?','Capital is more important than human resources','Human resources are needed to convert natural resources into products','Natural resources automatically become products over time','Money is needed before natural resources can be utilised','B',3,0,0,3),(2929,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','How does increasing the productivity of human resources benefit a nation as a whole?','It reduces the number of workers needed, increasing unemployment','It leads to higher output, higher income, and a better quality of life for the population','It only benefits large corporations and not the general population','It makes the country dependent on fewer resources','B',4,0,0,4),(2930,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Human Resources and Productivity','Country A has a large population with low productivity. Country B has a smaller population with high productivity. Which country is likely to have better economic development, and why?','Country A, because more workers produce more goods in absolute terms','Country B, because higher productivity means each worker creates more value, driving stronger economic growth','Both countries are equal because population and productivity cancel each other out','Country A, because it has more human resources available for future training programmes','B',5,0,0,5),(2931,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','According to the PLFS Report (Feb 2023), what is the minimum age for a person to be part of the labour force?','18 years','21 years','15 years','12 years','C',1,0,0,1),(2932,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','What is human capital?','The money invested in buying machinery','The economic value of human resources through education and job training','The total population of a country','The number of factories in a country','B',1,0,0,1),(2933,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','What is human capital formation?','Decreasing the number of workers in an economy','Additions to the stock of human capital over time','Building physical infrastructure like roads and buildings','The process of recruiting workers for factories','B',2,0,0,2),(2934,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','Which of the following correctly describes the labour force as per the PLFS Report?','All citizens of a country regardless of age','Population aged 15 and above who are willing and able to work','Only those people who are currently employed in formal jobs','People aged 18 and above with formal education','B',2,0,0,2),(2935,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','How does a higher number in the labour force positively influence an economy?','It reduces the need for capital investment in the economy','It provides more workers available for production, contributing to economic growth','It automatically reduces poverty without any other investment','It eliminates the need for entrepreneurship in the economy','B',3,0,0,3),(2936,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','If more young people receive education and job training, what happens to human capital in a country?','Human capital decreases because fewer people are working during study','Human capital formation increases as educated and trained people add to its stock','Human capital remains unchanged because it depends only on physical resources','Human capital decreases because education reduces time available for work','B',3,0,0,3),(2937,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','What is the correct chain of effects when human capital increases?','Higher human capital → lower income → better quality of life','Higher human capital → higher productivity → higher income → better quality of life','Higher human capital → higher unemployment → lower productivity','Higher human capital → more migration → lower income','B',4,0,0,4),(2938,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','Which of the following is NOT a component used to build human capital?','Education','Job training','Construction of roads and bridges','Investment in health','C',4,0,0,4),(2939,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','Two countries have the same population. Country A invests heavily in education and job training; Country B does not. After 20 years, which country will have more human capital and what will be the result?','Country B, because its workers will have more practical work experience','Country A, because investment in education and training increases human capital formation, leading to higher productivity and income','Both countries will be equal, as population size is the only factor in human capital','Country B, because it saved money that can be used for physical capital investment','B',5,0,0,5),(2940,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Labour Force and Human Capital','A 14-year-old student is willing and able to work. According to the PLFS Report definition, is this student part of the labour force? What does this imply?','Yes, the student is in the labour force; child labour is acceptable under this definition','No, the student is below 15 years; the definition intentionally excludes children from the labour force','Yes, the student is in the labour force; age does not matter in the PLFS definition','No, only students aged 18 or above are counted in the PLFS labour force','B',5,0,0,5),(2941,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','What does a knowledge economy primarily produce?','Agricultural goods','Intellectual products','Physical manufactured goods','Raw materials for export','B',1,0,0,1),(2942,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','Which institution is an example of one that supports the knowledge economy in Kerala?','State Bank of India','Technopark','Kerala State Road Transport Corporation','Kerala Tourism Development Corporation','B',2,0,0,2),(2943,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','Which of the following is a characteristic of the knowledge economy?','It relies mainly on agriculture and traditional crafts','It uses intelligence, innovative technology, and information technology','It depends on large quantities of manual labour','It focuses on the extraction of natural resources','B',2,0,0,2),(2944,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','Which of the following workers would typically be part of the knowledge economy?','A farmer harvesting crops','A software developer creating applications','A miner extracting iron ore','A construction worker building roads','B',3,0,0,3),(2945,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','A tax expert, a researcher, and a policymaker are all working to improve the national economy. What type of economy do they primarily contribute to?','Agricultural economy','Knowledge economy','Barter economy','Manufacturing economy','B',3,0,0,3),(2946,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','Which pair of institutions supports the knowledge economy in Kerala?','Kerala Agricultural University and Fisheries Department','Technopark and Infopark','KSRTC and Kerala Tourism','PWD and Kerala Water Authority','B',1,0,0,1),(2947,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','How does the knowledge economy differ from a traditional manufacturing economy?','The knowledge economy uses more physical labour and fewer machines','The knowledge economy creates value through information and intellectual output rather than physical goods','The knowledge economy produces only agricultural goods for export','The knowledge economy does not use any technology or innovation','B',5,0,0,5),(2948,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Knowledge Economy','A country is shifting from producing steel and textiles to producing software and research outputs. What type of economic transition is taking place, and which human resources will be most valued?','Transition to agriculture; farmers will be most valued','Transition to a knowledge economy; scientists, researchers, and software developers will be most valued','Transition to a barter economy; traders will be most valued','Transition to a traditional manufacturing economy; factory workers will be most valued','B',5,0,0,5),(2949,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Education is an investment that contributes to which of the following?','Decreasing national development','Human capital formation','Increasing unemployment','Reducing productivity','B',1,0,0,1),(2950,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which sectors can invest in education for human capital formation?','Only the government sector','Only the private sector','Public, cooperative, and private sectors','Only international organisations','C',1,0,0,1),(2951,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','According to the staircase model, what is the first step that education leads to?','Better income','National development','Increase in ability','Skill development','C',2,0,0,2),(2952,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','According to the staircase model, which step comes immediately after ''Skill Development''?','Technological Knowledge','Better Job','National Development','Better Quality of Life','B',2,0,0,2),(2953,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Using the staircase model, arrange the correct order: (i) Better Job (ii) Skill Development (iii) Technological Knowledge (iv) Better Income (v) Increase in Ability','v, iii, ii, i, iv','iii, v, ii, i, iv','v, ii, iii, i, iv','i, v, iii, ii, iv','A',3,0,0,3),(2954,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which of the following abilities does education create according to the chapter?','Ability to avoid all technological change','Ability to read, write, learn new skills, and adapt to new technology','Ability to work without any training or guidance','Ability to replace machines in all types of work','B',3,0,0,3),(2955,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Why does education enable people to get better jobs?','Education gives people social connections that help them get hired','Education increases ability, technological knowledge, and skill development, making people more employable','Education is required by law before any person can be hired in any sector','Education replaces experience, which is not valued by modern employers','B',4,0,0,4),(2956,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which of the following best explains why education is called an investment rather than a consumption expenditure?','Education money is spent on books which can be resold later','Education leads to higher income and productivity in the future, yielding long-term returns','Education is free in government schools, so it costs nothing to society','Education is compulsory and must be paid for by the government','B',4,0,0,4),(2957,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','According to the staircase model, how does ''Better Quality of Life'' eventually lead to ''National Development''?','Better quality of life reduces the population which leads to development','When individuals earn more and live better, overall productivity and prosperity of the nation increases','National development is achieved by importing goods from developed countries','Better quality of life reduces government spending on welfare programmes','B',4,0,0,4),(2958,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Why should education investment come from public, cooperative, AND private sectors?','Because the government alone can fund all education without any help needed','Because diverse investment sources ensure wider access to education across all sections of society','Because private sector education is always better quality than public sector education','Because cooperative sector investment in education is mandatory under law','B',4,0,0,4),(2959,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','A student argues spending money on education is wasteful because benefits are not immediate. Using the staircase model, which response best refutes this?','Education is not wasteful because school fees are very low','Education builds abilities and skills that lead step-by-step to better jobs, higher income, better quality of life, and ultimately national development','Education is only beneficial for those who complete university degrees','Education spending is wasteful if the student does not get a government job','B',5,0,0,5),(2960,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','In the staircase model, ''Technological Knowledge'' appears after ''Increase in Ability''. What does this sequence suggest about the relationship between general education and technology?','Technology can be learned without any prior general education','General education builds foundational abilities that are a prerequisite for acquiring technological knowledge','Technological knowledge is more important than general ability','Technology replaces the need for general education entirely','B',5,0,0,5),(2961,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Education as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Both formal and informal education contribute to human capital formation. Which example best illustrates informal education contributing to human capital?','Attending a university and earning a degree in engineering','A carpenter learning advanced joinery techniques from a senior craftsman while working','A student passing the Class 10 board examination','A school following the SCERT curriculum for Social Science','B',5,0,0,5),(2962,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','According to the WHO, health is defined as:','The absence of disease and illness','Physical, mental, and social well-being','Physical fitness and strength only','The ability to work without any medical assistance','B',1,0,0,1),(2963,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which state is known as a world model for health outcomes?','Tamil Nadu','Maharashtra','Kerala','Karnataka','C',1,0,0,1),(2964,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which of the following is the correct order of the healthcare hierarchy from the lowest to the highest level?','Taluk hospitals → health sub-centres → district hospitals → medical colleges','Health sub-centres → primary health centres → community health centres → taluk hospitals → district hospitals → medical colleges','Primary health centres → district hospitals → taluk hospitals → medical colleges','Community health centres → health sub-centres → primary health centres → medical colleges','B',2,0,0,2),(2965,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which of the following is NOT listed as an alternative medicine system in the chapter?','Yoga','Homeopathy','Allopathy','Naturopathy','C',2,0,0,2),(2966,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which of the following is a PREVENTIVE health measure?','Surgery to remove a tumour','Immunization against diseases','Hospital treatment after an accident','Medicine prescribed after a diagnosis','B',1,0,0,1),(2967,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','A government builds primary health centres in rural areas, provides clean drinking water, and runs sanitation campaigns. These actions contribute to:','Increasing unemployment in the health sector','Human capital formation through improved health of the population','Reducing the number of medical colleges in the state','Promoting only alternative medicine systems','B',3,0,0,3),(2968,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','According to the WHO definition, a person who is physically strong but suffers from severe anxiety and has no social support is:','Completely healthy because physical well-being is most important','Not fully healthy because mental and social well-being are also required','Healthy because absence of physical disease is the only criterion','Healthy because social support is not part of the WHO definition','B',3,0,0,3),(2969,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Why should health expenditure be considered an investment rather than consumption?','Because health expenditure is always funded by the government','Because spending on health improves productivity and human capital, yielding long-term economic returns','Because hospitals are profitable businesses that earn revenue','Because health expenditure reduces the need for education investment','B',4,0,0,4),(2970,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Kerala is considered a world model for health outcomes. Which combination of factors most likely explains this?','High birth rate and large population','Strong healthcare infrastructure, high health literacy, preventive medicine, and clean environment','Dependence only on alternative medicine systems','High income levels that allow people to afford private healthcare','B',4,0,0,4),(2971,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Which of the following correctly lists the alternative medicine systems practised in India as mentioned in the chapter?','Ayurveda, Yoga, Naturopathy, Unani, Homeopathy','Allopathy, Surgery, Physiotherapy, Naturopathy, Unani','Ayurveda, Chemotherapy, Yoga, Homeopathy, Naturopathy','Unani, Acupuncture, Yoga, Allopathy, Naturopathy','A',4,0,0,4),(2972,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','The WHO definition includes physical, mental, AND social well-being. A critic argues this makes the definition too broad. What is the strongest counter-argument?','Mental and social well-being are easy to measure with standard tests','Without mental and social well-being, a person cannot be fully productive; all three dimensions are necessary for effective human capital','The WHO definition is legally binding and cannot be questioned','Social well-being is the same as physical health and they should not be separated','B',5,0,0,5),(2973,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','In the healthcare hierarchy, why is it important that health sub-centres exist at the lowest level, closest to the community?','Health sub-centres provide the most advanced medical procedures','Health sub-centres provide basic preventive and primary care at the grassroots level, enabling early intervention and reducing the burden on higher-level hospitals','Health sub-centres are less expensive to run than all other health institutions','Health sub-centres can replace district hospitals for all types of medical treatment','B',5,0,0,5),(2974,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Health as Factor in Human Capital Formation','Why is a healthy person more productive than an unhealthy person, and why does this matter for human capital formation?','Healthy people earn more money which lets them buy better equipment for work','Good health enables a person to work efficiently and consistently; higher individual productivity accumulates into human capital that drives national development','Unhealthy people are legally barred from most industries','Health is unrelated to productivity; only education matters for human capital formation','B',5,0,0,5),(2975,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','What is migration?','The exchange of goods between countries','Permanent or temporary movement of people between regions or countries','The movement of money between banks','The transfer of technology from one country to another','B',1,0,0,1),(2976,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','Which profession requires mandatory job training before a person can practice it?','Shopkeeper','Doctor (Medicine)','Farmer','Street vendor','B',1,0,0,1),(2977,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','Access to information in the context of human capital formation covers services in which areas?','Manufacturing, mining, and construction','Education, health, and employment','Agriculture, fisheries, and forestry','Finance, banking, and insurance','B',2,0,0,2),(2978,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','Why is government intervention essential in ensuring access to information?','Private companies can provide all information freely without any cost','Without government intervention, lack of access to information can perpetuate poverty among disadvantaged groups','The government is the only organisation that collects and stores information','Information access is a luxury that only wealthy people need','B',2,0,0,2),(2979,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','How does job training contribute to human capital formation?','Job training reduces the number of people looking for employment','Job training increases the productivity and skills of workers, adding to the stock of human capital','Job training only benefits employers, not the workers themselves','Job training replaces the need for formal education entirely','B',3,0,0,3),(2980,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','When people migrate from rural to urban areas for better job opportunities, what responsibility does the government have?','To stop all migration to prevent overcrowding in cities','To observe regional changes in population and ensure basic needs are met in both areas','To charge migrants a fee for moving to urban areas','To restrict jobs in urban areas to local residents only','B',3,0,0,3),(2981,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','How does lack of access to information contribute to the poverty cycle?','Lack of information makes people save more money and become wealthier','Without information about education, health, and employment opportunities, poor people cannot make decisions that help them escape poverty','Lack of information reduces competition, making it easier for poor people to find jobs','Information access is not related to poverty or economic development','B',4,0,0,4),(2982,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Migration, Job Training and Access to Information','A doctor, engineer, and teacher all require mandatory training before practicing. A vegetable seller does not. What does this reveal about job training and human capital formation?','Only professions requiring formal training contribute to human capital formation','Mandatory professional training creates specialised human capital that delivers complex services critical to society, while informal occupations also build human capital in different ways','Vegetable sellers do not need any training and therefore do not contribute to the economy','Job training is only useful for people who want government jobs','B',5,0,0,5),(2983,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','The poverty cycle is described as:','A one-time event that affects only a few families','A self-reinforcing cycle where poverty leads back to poverty','A government programme to reduce poverty','A phase of economic development that all countries go through','B',1,0,0,1),(2984,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','The poverty cycle is considered the biggest challenge to:','Agricultural development','Human capital formation','Industrial growth','Export earnings','B',1,0,0,1),(2985,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','Which of the following is a direct consequence of poverty in the poverty cycle?','High income and high purchasing power','Malnutrition and lack of education','Better health outcomes','Increased investment in human capital','B',2,0,0,2),(2986,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','Which state is considered a model for poverty alleviation in India?','Bihar','Uttar Pradesh','Kerala','Rajasthan','C',2,0,0,2),(2987,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','In the poverty cycle, how does low income lead to low productivity?','Low income people choose not to work','Low income leads to malnutrition and lack of education, which reduces the capacity to work productively','Low income makes people more creative and efficient through necessity','Low income leads directly to higher productivity','B',3,0,0,3),(2988,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','Why does the poverty cycle result in high infant mortality and increasing dependents?','Poor families prefer to have more children for financial security','Poverty leads to malnutrition, chronic illness, and lack of healthcare, increasing mortality and the number of dependents','Government policies encourage poor families to have more children','High infant mortality is caused only by genetic factors unrelated to poverty','B',3,0,0,3),(2989,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','Which intervention would most effectively break the poverty cycle?','Giving poor families money to buy luxury goods','Investing in education, health, and social services to improve human capital and productivity','Reducing taxes for wealthy people so they create more jobs','Encouraging poor families to migrate to other countries','B',4,0,0,4),(2990,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','Arrange the steps of the poverty cycle in correct order starting from poverty: (i) Low productivity (ii) Poverty (iii) Scarcity of food/malnutrition/lack of education (iv) High infant mortality/increasing dependents (v) Low income/low purchasing power','ii, v, iii, i, iv','ii, iii, v, i, iv','ii, i, v, iii, iv','ii, iv, iii, v, i','A',4,0,0,4),(2991,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','Kerala is a model for poverty alleviation despite not being India''s wealthiest state. Which combination of factors best explains this?','Kerala has the most natural resources, which automatically reduce poverty','Kerala invested heavily in education, health, and social services, breaking the poverty cycle through improved human capital','Kerala received the most central government funds compared to other states','Kerala''s poverty alleviation is due to remittances from abroad only','B',5,0,0,5),(2992,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Poverty Cycle','A person argues the poverty cycle can be broken simply by giving poor people more money. What is the fundamental flaw in this argument?','Money is not useful for poor people','Without simultaneously addressing malnutrition, lack of education, and chronic illness, money alone cannot sustainably improve productivity and break the cycle','Poor people will waste any money they receive','The poverty cycle cannot be broken under any circumstances','B',5,0,0,5),(2993,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','What is open unemployment?','Employment available only in certain seasons','A situation where a person is willing to work but is unable to find any employment','Employment where more workers are hired than needed','Job loss due to introduction of new technology','B',1,0,0,1),(2994,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','Structural unemployment is caused by:','A decrease in population','Introduction of new technology replacing workers','Seasonal variation in demand for goods','Having too many workers in agriculture','B',2,0,0,2),(2995,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','Disguised unemployment is most commonly found in which sector in India?','Information technology','Agriculture','Banking','Tourism','B',2,0,0,2),(2996,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','Five workers are doing a job that actually requires only two. Removing three workers would not reduce total output. This is an example of:','Open unemployment','Structural unemployment','Seasonal unemployment','Disguised unemployment','D',3,0,0,3),(2997,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','An agricultural worker earns income during harvest season but has no work during the off-season. Which type of unemployment does this illustrate?','Disguised unemployment','Structural unemployment','Seasonal unemployment','Open unemployment','C',3,0,0,3),(2998,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','A worker loses his job because the factory installs automated machines. This is an example of:','Open unemployment','Seasonal unemployment','Structural unemployment','Disguised unemployment','C',4,0,0,4),(2999,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','What is the key difference between structural unemployment and seasonal unemployment?','Structural unemployment occurs in agriculture; seasonal unemployment occurs in industry','Structural unemployment is caused by technological change making jobs obsolete; seasonal unemployment is caused by the cyclical nature of certain industries','Structural unemployment is temporary; seasonal unemployment is permanent','Structural unemployment affects only unskilled workers; seasonal unemployment affects only skilled workers','B',4,0,0,4),(3000,'Kerala',9,'English','Social 2','MCQ',1,'4','Human Resources for National Development',30,'Types of Unemployment','In disguised unemployment, workers appear employed and receive income. Why is this still a problem for human capital formation and national development?','Because disguised unemployment increases wages for all workers','Because disguised unemployment means many workers are underutilised, reducing overall productivity and the effective contribution of human capital to the economy','Because disguised unemployment always leads directly to structural unemployment','Because disguised unemployment only affects workers in the knowledge economy','B',5,0,0,5);
